<TEXT>
CHESS
Following his lacklustre 50% score in the Credit Suisse Masters in October,
Gary Kasparov bounced back to win his next tournament, the Intel Rapid Chess
Grand Prix event in Paris (November 9-12). In Paris, Kasparov was devastating.
Although he lost the first game in the final against Vladimir Kramnik, he won
the second game and then the play-off Blitz decider to take first prize both in
this event and the 1995 Grand Prix series as a whole.
Kasparov had some good fortune in the semi-final against Vishy Anand, who
uncharacteristcally defaulted in the first game of the two-game tie. Poor Anand
apparently confused the French for 1pm (treize heures), thinking the tie began
at 3pm. Frantic organisers could not at first track him down in his hotel, as
he had gone out for a pre-game stroll.
The French spectators had plenty to to be proud about. Their top player, Joel
Lautier, also got through to the semi-finals, only to lose 1!s-!s to Kramnik.
But the revelation of the event was the remarkable play of 12-year-old French
junior, Etienne Bacrot. Kramnik had a very hard time defeating him in an
earlier round, and in this tie also conceded one draw.
Rapid Chess is played at a rate of 25 minutes per player per game. Two games
are played at this rate, followed by sudden death Blitz games in the event of a
1-1 tie. In the Blitz games, White gets 5 and Black 4 minutes, with White
having to win and Black only to draw to decide the outcome.
Even the best players make frequent mistakes under this sort of pressure. But
to win requires a great deal of skill. Gary Kasparov was clearly ready for his
opponent in the following game and won superbly.
White: A. Morosevich
Black: G. Kasparov
Intel Rapid Chess Grand Prix, Paris 1995
King's Gambit Accepted
1 e4 e5 2 f4 exf4 3 Nf3 d6
This was Bobby Fischer's famous ``bust'' of the King's Gambit, which he
advocated in an openings article in 1961. The old move, and by no means a bad
alternative, is 3 . . . g5. Fischer called 3 . . . d6 a ``high class waiting
move''. It was aimed primarily at preventing the respected Kieseritzky
Variation (3 . . . g5 4 h4 g4 5 Ne5), Spassky's favourite, with which he beat
Fischer in Mar del Plata in 1960.
4 d4 g5 5 h4 g4 6 Ng5?!
The main line given by Joe Gallagher in his excellent Batsford openings book
Winning with the King's Gambit, is the rather strange retreat 6 Ng1. I doubt
whether this move really gives White anything, but if White can wrest control
of f4, even at the expense of a pawn, he can cause problems resulting from the
weaknesses in the Black kingsde pawn structure (h7, g4 and f7).
6 . . . h6!
Fischer thought Black could refute White's play by 6 . . . f6, and if 7 Nh3
gxh3 8 Qh5+ Kd7 9 Bxf4 Qe8 10 Qf3 Kd8. I expect Morosevich had some new idea in
mind, but Kasparov gets his new move in first.
7 Nxf7
This sacrifice is often dangerous in such positions, but Kasparov appears to
have drawn its sting in this particular line.
7 . . . Kxf7 8 Bxf4 Bg7 9 Bc4+ Ke8 10 0-0 Nc6 11 Be3?!
Possibly better is 11 c3, so that if 11 . . . Qxh4 12 g3 is playable. Now Black
can grab White's h-pawn with impunity.
11 . . . Qxh4 12 Rf7 Rh7!
White may have missed this move, which allows Black to hold on to his extra
piece without compromising the safety of his king. Without any clear target in
Black's position, White is probably already lost.
13 e5 Na5 14 Bd3 Kxf7 15 Qf1+ Ke7 16 Bxh7 Be6 17 Nd2 Rf8 18 exd6+ cxd6 19 Qe2
Kd8 20 c3 Ne7 21 Re1?!
White has a lost game, but this move allows an immediate end.
21 . . . Bc4 22 Bf2
Or if 22 Nxc4 g3 and Black mates on h2.
22 . . . Rxf2 23 Qxf2 g3 White resigns
Once again White faces mate on h2 or hopeless material loss.
CRAIG PRITCHETT
</TEXT>
