<HEADLINE>This sounds alarming</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joe Donnelly</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093762</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY used to have bells, then it was sirens and then electronic wah-wah sound
generators like those in US police car chases. But ambulances, it seems, have a
directional problem. They could be putting people in danger just because while
the driver knows where he happens to be going, the siren sound doesn't let
pedestrians and drivers know where it's coming from.
Dr Deb Withington of Sound Alert in Leeds has a solution to the problem, and
it's almost a silent one at that.
``We can't localise ambulance sounds because there's not enough information in
it for the human's brain to get a directional fix. You get it wrong 56% of the
time, so if you hear an ambulance, it's most likely to be coming in the
opposite direction than you believe. That makes it dangerous at road junctions
when an emergency vehicle is speeding along. Car drivers have a particular
problem in getting a fix on the sound, and it is they who really need to get
out of the way . .  and fast.''
``I work on sound localisation and we've been testing people on the state of
the art driving simulator at Leeds University. You need to test people while
they're driving to replicate as close as possible the normal conditions. We
looked at existing sirens and tried a whole range of noises. Most people get
the direction wrong. We worked out that it was the sound component that is a
problem, so we've altered it.
``We believe our new sound does a better job. A siren must grab your attention.
There's lots of data about what makes an alerting sound. Fire engines
occasionally use an air horn which is better than the normal ambulance sound as
far as pinpointing is concerned.''
The problem so far has been preference . . . for American cop car chase movies.
Withington says: ``People like electronic sounds, but whoever designed them
just didn't have a clue. The makers say it's a big seller in the US and people
think that's fine, believing that what's good for America, must be good for us.
But you still can't tell where the noise is coming from and it's always a good
idea for pedestrians and ambulances to be able to locate a fast-moving
emergency vehicle, to get out of the way, or to ensure they don't impede its
progress.
``We have developed a sound with an alerting tone, like the wah-wah, but that's
followed by a burst of white noise, a bit like sound interference on the
television screen a `sshhh' sound which is a broad band locator, and much
easier for the human ear to pinpoint.
``Our company was set up with DTI money to try to make a better ambulance
siren, and we believe we've got it right. Existing manufacturers are beating a
path to our door, so we know we've succeeded. There are many uses and many
safety applications in having an alarm sound that the human ear can pinpoint.
``We have ambulance, police and fire services on our side. Police forces have
had a play on our simulator and they want the system desperately. It helps them
get to a scene much quicker because traffic gets out of the way. We have
patented the system.''
Strangely, Withington says that as far as emergency sound location is
concerned, the old-fashioned clanging bell was much more efficient on the human
ear than the US import. Now we will have the jarring generator followed by a
pianissimo hush to tell us to get out of the way.
Good for new technology, but we still have a fondness for the old idea, beloved
of primary children, where the young ambulance recruit just yells out of the
window when he's passing his own street: ``It's me, maw . . . me maw . . . me
maw.''
n RUGBY world champions South Africa have been using high technology to keep
them ahead of the game. They've created a new application for the JVC
Professional video system which gives them the edge over the other teams.
The South Africans wanted a minute analysis of the opposing teams and the
formulation of winning game plans. When they ran on to the pitch against
Australia in May, they knew exactly what they were up against, and how to
combat it.
Because they had seen their opponents play over and over again on video. The
JVC Professional system's dynamic variable playback tracking allowed them to
study the way different teams and individual players moved, defended and
attacked. The system's slow-motion capability allowed them to break down the
moves, and the team could even watch the results in their hotel televisions on
the night before the match.
When the Springboks played the All Blacks, they had big Jonah Lomu's moves off
pat, down to which leg he used to start off running, which hand he caught with,
how many strides he took before changing the ball from one hand to the other.
They had him sussed.
Maybe Scotland's team should get in on the hi-tech act. It seems a surer bet
than sending men in bunnets to spy from the sidelines.
n PHILIPS have launched a new VCR range which dispels the user-unfriendly
reputation of players, most of which are unprogrammable by anyone beyond
puberty.
The new four-head VR 757 nicam deck features Videoplus and PDC plus jog shuttle
on both the remote control and front panel.
It's the first to feature Philips EasyLink which the company say makes it the
most user friendly on the market. It's a digital software connection that
automatically downloads channel information from compatible TVs to the video
decks.
The machine comes with a turbo-drive winder which spools an entire 180-minute
tape in just 95 seconds. It also has Videoplus programming and a six-event
memory for up to 15 hours of continuous play. It's selling now at #430.
Sounds simple enough even for adults.
Joe Donnelly  reports
on ambulances with
bells and whistles
</TEXT>
