<TEXT>
ROCKY MOUNTAIN LOWS
n THE 10-hour flight to Denver, plus a few hours stopover, is a bit of a drag.
n Meals are massive and the quality, range, and availability of food excellent.
Be prepared to return with an increased waist measurement.
n The altitude of around 10,000ft can be a problem. You will find yourself out
of puff after walking up stairs, never mind after blasting down a double black
diamond bump run. The benefit is that when you get back to Scotland you can ski
almost all day without getting tired.
As darkening snow clouds over Scotland herald a new ski season, Weekend Extra
presents Ski Special. First
up on the piste is Fergus Wyllie, who travels to
Colorado to discover a world a million miles away
from the snaking queues and monosyllabic lifties
of Europe. Can it really be as good as it sounds?
ROCKY MOUNTAIN HIGHS
n No one thing makes skiing in America so good. It is a combination of varied,
immaculately prepared runs, no lift queues, friendly, efficient staff, and
great food and drink at reasonable prices. The attitude of everyone is such a
refreshing change from Europe.
n All Colorado resorts are terrific but I fell in love with Copper Mountain.
The views and the relaxed atmosphere make it a pleasure to visit.
n Breckenridge is superb for nightlife. It has everything from rough, tough
cowboy saloons to super smooth restaurants.
THE buses said it all about Colorado skiing. To a background of rock music, the
cheerful and friendly drivers talked to passengers over a loudspeaker,
informing them of the next stop, asking who was getting off where, and giving
details about connecting buses. Oh, and they were free.
The service could not be better. Just like the skiing. Whether you like steep
and deep or wide and glide, Colorado has it in spades. It is the equal of
anything Europe can offer but the good old US of A is streets (or should it be
pistes?) ahead on organisation, efficiency, and courtesy.
The nightlife is varied and terrific, food and drink are of a much higher
quality than here (and usually cheaper), and almost everyone is helpful and
friendly. Am I giving the impression that I liked it? Too bloody right. Adored
it more like.
I stayed in the small town of Frisco, a few miles from the ski resorts of
Breckenridge, Keystone, Arapahoe Basin, and Copper Mountain. Across the road
from my hotel was a stop for the Summit Stage buses. Complete with ski racks,
they are operated by the county with financial help from the resorts and make
it very easy and painless to make full use of the Breck lift pass which also
covers Keystone and A-Basin. Check the local patois, dude.
My first stop was Breckenfridge, as it's known locally, and boy did it live up
to its nickname. The cold on the trails (pistes), which rise to nearly
12,000ft, was much worse than anything Scotland has to offer. My face was not
as much pinched by the cold as punched. And that was with hardly any windchill.
After every run, my companions and I checked each others' faces for white
patches of frostnip.
Our faces may have been cold but our welcome was warm. The lifties were
amazingly friendly, helping you on to the chairs, asking how you were, and
encouraging you to ``have a good one''. Obsequious Americans after your cash,
you might say, but they really seemed to mean it. It was definitely altitude
without attitude.
And so well organised, so efficient. Each chair has a rope ``maze'' in which up
to six queues of skiers merge into four, then two, and finally one. At each
junction, the ``Please alternate'' signs are rigorously observed and it is
almost a pleasure to queue. There is a separate queue for single skiers and
even strategically placed boxes of paper hankies with which to wipe damp noses.
Visiting French and Italians must be horrified.
The super quads (four-person chairs) move an amazing amount of people up the
hill very quickly. You progress through what appears to be a huge queue in no
time at all. Our longest wait was an untypical 15 minutes at a quad chair
beside the main ticket office on a very busy Sunday.
But what about the skiing? Awesome just about sums it up. Breck's 126 trails
vary from immaculately groomed, motorway-wide greens to steep, deep, and
mega-bumpy double black diamonds. Whereas European pistes tend to be longer,
fewer, and more crowded, the Americans cut a linked system of runs through the
trees which cover most of the resorts up to almost 12,000ft.
This offers endless options of route and means that, even on a busy day, it is
not unusual to have large sections to yourself. Don't get the idea that the
Breck trails are all short. One of the resort's four peaks claims to have a
three-and-a-half mile run although I suspect this may involve a 40-minute walk
to the summit.
If you are a bump fiend, this is the place for you. They are much more
plentiful than in Europe and it is not uncommon to have one-third of the width
of a run left as moguls while the other two-thirds are groomed. It means you
can bale out of the bumps if the going gets too tough and also that parties of
mixed ability can stay together with some skiing moguls while others cruise the
smooth.
One of my favourite Breck trails was the single black diamond Cimaron, a long,
fast race run which screams down the full length of the mountain. The majority
was groomed but the bumps had been left to grow in one or two places at the
side of the trail. On my third day in Breck, overnight snowfall had left
slightly heavy but very skiable powder on parts of Cimaron and my morning was a
blur of blasting through thigh-deep piles of white delight.
Breck is a beginner's dream. The wide, smooth, easy trails have an amazing
quality of snow and must be the ideal place to learn to ski. The only drawback
is the cost of classes - about #120 for six days. The facilities for children
are excellent.
A fenced-off area not only has safety nets at the end of the short runs but
also conveyor belts to bring the little ones back to the the top of the runs.
When they venture forth on the slopes, the munchkins in each ski class wear
balloons of the same colour tied to their backs, presumably for recognition
rather than elevation. But it's not cheap - #150 for six days including lunch.
Not only do the Americans know how to groom trails, they know how to name them.
Devil's Crotch, High Anxiety, and Sizzler conjure up quite accurate images and
certainly make for an interesting trail map. Goodbye Girl, a short but very
steep double black diamond trail, almost became Goodbye Boy for yours truly
when I picked my way down it through large bumps in deep, heavy snow. Scary or
what.
If I needed a few fingers of red-eye to calm my shattered nerves, Breck was the
place to provide it. The nightlife in what was once a Victorian gold and silver
mining town is just as good as the skiing. Its traditional wooden buildings
house some terrific bars and restaurants and, surprise, surprise, everyone is
really friendly.
Among the best were the Breckenridge Brewery and the Whale's Tail. The Brewery
bar and restaurant makes its own ales right before your eyes. They  bubble away
in 20ft metal vats behind the bar as you stagger your way through the six brews
- ranging from oatmeal stout to the aptly-named Avalanche lager. And the food's
good too.
Mind you, it is even better in the Whale's Tail seafood restaurant. Three
friends and I all had superb mixed grills of salmon, mako shark, and prawns,
plus vegetables, followed by desert, which, washed down with a litre of house
wine, worked out at #20 a head. That was our most expensive meal in Colorado
and, believe me, we ate well.
The excellent quality, even in fast food restaurants, and the enormous helpings
make it much better value than Scotland. Add this to the conspicuous
cleanliness and you wonder what our catering industry is playing at.
A culinary highlight of Frisco was Smithwick's Bar-B-Q Shack, and it was a real
shack, where we ate buffalo in hickory sauce from plastic plates with plastic
knives and forks. The waiter said it had been cooked for 40 hours and I
believed him. It was absolutely gorgeous.
After three days of skiing Breck, we jumped on to the free bus for the short
ride to Copper Mountain. Perhaps it was the glorious sunshine, or the lunchtime
Buds, but the beauty of this resort stole my heart. The towering peaks of the
Rockies were so white and the Colorado sky so brilliantly blue that it almost
hurt.
What definitely did hurt was plunging headfirst down the double black diamond
Triple Zero in Spaulding Bowl after my skis decided to stop dead in a lump of
heavy snow. Luckily, it was my pride that suffered most as I picked my way back
up to give my errant Dynastars a good thrashing.
My reason for attempting this very difficult bump-packed bowl was not bravado
but because it was the only way to reach Crosscut, a single black diamond run
that swooped magnificently through the forest below the bowl. Steep it was but
groomed as smooth as a baby's bottom. Just right for big GS turns and zooming
all the way down.
Although not as big as Breck, Copper Mountain has 98 trails which tend to be
longer and perhaps more scenic. Another of my favourites was Triple Treat, a
black run whose bumps were not too difficult and interspersed with groomed
areas for a quick blast. It led to the bottom of A lift, which must have been
the quietest chair in Colorado when we were there. Mind you, the sun-bathing
lifties did not seem to mind getting up every 20 minutes or so to help us on.
We ate lunch in the Clubhouse, right at the bottom of B lift. The food was
plentiful and cheap, the service excellent, and the only problem was trying to
persuade yourself to stop soaking up rays and Buds and hit the slopes again.
The next day, we moved on to Loveland, a small ski area which does not normally
figure on British holiday itineraries. It is about twice the size of Cairngorm
with a good selection of trails ranging from steep bump runs to smooth
cruisers. It is well worth a visit if you want a change from the big resorts.
And talking of big resorts, there is Vail. With more than 4000 skiable acres
and a lift capacity of 42,720 skiers per hour, it is huge with a capital H. The
121 trails are the usual Colorado mix of easy and difficult but it is the seven
back bowls that set it apart from the other resorts on our tour. They are so
massive that you could share one with 1000 skiers and not be within 100yards of
anyone. The snow was deep and slightly heavy when we were there but the mainly
black runs were still enjoyable. In powder, they must be heaven on earth.
Now the bad news. Although Vail is très chic and classy, it is much more
expensive and not nearly as friendly as Breck. After days of chatting to
lifties, it was quite a shock to be greeted with silence at Vail. Where did
they think they were, for goodness sake, Cairngorm?
Keystone was our next stop. Its 53 trails are full of character and flow over
three heavily wooded peaks. The double black diamond woodland skiing was better
than anything in Europe and I will never forget the thrills and spills when
Timberwolf showed its teeth. Boarders are banned from Keystone which has the
added attraction of floodlit skiing on 13 trails until 9pm. The Outpost Lodge,
12,444ft up on the North Peak, is a great place to eat not only because of the
food. Built of huge pine logs, it has all the atmosphere of a forest cabin
complete with a massive open fire.
A 15-minute bus ride away from Keystone is Arapahoe Basin with 61 trails. The
East Wall area has powder when everywhere else is hard packed and it was
thigh-deep for our visit. A short walk is necessary to get to the best trails
but that was the last thing on my mind as I whooped my way down Corner Chute
and North Pole Plunge leaving billowing clouds of powder in my wake.
The steep mogul runs off the Palivacinni chair are mega difficult and will
satisfy the most demanding bump fiend. I decided discretion was the better part
of valour and left them well alone lest more than my heart was broken at having
to leave Colorado after 12 days of glorious skiing.
There are only two disadvantages about Colorado. One is the long journey -
eight hours from Glasgow to Chicago and two hours to Denver - followed by a
two-hour bus trip to Breckenridge. The other is the fact that you will be
absolutely determined to return, come hell or high dollar against the pound.
Yes, the best skiing in the world is not overpriced, not overrated, and over
there.
</TEXT>
