<HEADLINE>It's one in the eye for authority from Sole</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093764</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was the way David Sole dismissed the Scottish Rugby Union that impressed me.
After his ``tantamount to cheating'' allegation following Edinburgh Accies'
game against Melrose, he first told the SRU that he would not be able to come
and meet them because of ``baby sitting duties,'' and then a statement from
Edinburgh Accies said that it would now be very difficult for David to slot in
time to his schedule to talk to the SRU over the coming weeks because of a
hectic ``social diary.''
Wonderful. Like Sole I have had some real snash from folk at the SRU in my time
- the last one was in Paris when a nobody had a drunken go and to my eternal
relief I didn't punch his lights out - and I have sympathy for David's
predicament.
He was once called ``a cancer in Scottish rugby'' after, you may remember,
captaining a Grand Slam winning team.
David's not the most normal person in the world, but you have to admire the guy
and know that he says what he thinks.
What folk in the public don't realise is that when someone outside the SRU
criticises the set-up, the bearded nobodies take it personally.
You see, many of the blokes in the SRU are on their own personal, one-man
crusade to become the president. Bill Hogg's not.
I like him, but he doesn't like me, which was quite obvious from his early
morning call the other day. Goodness, the man has a strong voice in the early
morning.
I doubt whether David believes that blokes who are on a one-man crusade to be
SRU president have the class to be sitting in judgment of him.
I was at the game when David had his outburst. His side had just lost. The end
of the match had been a farce. Accies were being penalised and then penalised
again as time was running out. In fact time had run out.
As a neutral, and I was a neutral, I thought that something fishy was going on.
Now, I may have been wrong, and I am prepared to accept completely that I am
wrong, but that's what it looked like to me.
A penalty means that time carries on. Anything else stops the game.
The insinuation in David's remarks is that there was cheating going on.
Many thought that was happening, others did not, but only David, as is David's
way, had the guts to say what he thought.
What I'm about to say is probably vastly unfair, but I think it happened in the
past.
I remember going down to the borders to play rugby, and having the incredible
bad luck to have a borders referee on the day.
It seemed to me at that time as a player from Glasgow that the borders referee
would bend over backwards to ignore misdemeanors from the local players, and
keep an extra eye open for our infringements. The local players would bend,
grovel, and handle all day and get off with it. Hey, not that we ever
infringed, you understand.
Now, I am equally sure that borders teams have come up to the cities in the
past, seen a city referee, and then reckoned that they were harshly done by.
David Sole was in a rage after the game. But, it seems to me, nobody has had
the guts to ask the question: Was he right, or was he wrong? The neutrality of
Scottish referees is such a holy subject that you daren't ask the question.
I believe in this case we have to ask that question and find an answer. Maybe
to mollify it we have to ask the question as to whether this was a dreadful
display on the day or not.
OK, David's comments didn't look good in print, but we must surely find out if
he had a case. It was a fraught time.
It is my earnest belief in this one that the SRU have to do the unthinkable,
and examine the game in detail, before they ask Sole in again to ``explain
himself.''
The SRU must launch an investigation into the match to find out if a referee
did become emotionally involved in a game of rugby to the detriment of one of
the teams. Border TV have, I believe, the whole game on video.
For Edinburgh Accies, forty or fifty thousand pounds rode on that game.
That was a big-time game. Sole coaches Edinburgh Accies forwards, their under
21s, and he takes mini rugby on a Sunday. He could and should play a major role
in rugby's future.
He lost his cool on the day. It has now degenerated into posturing. Go on SRU,
ask the unacceptable question.
</TEXT>
