<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000006</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000006</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Silk' can beat the bookies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBIN COOK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093767</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXTRA prize money has ensured that the William Hill Handicap Hurdle at Sandown
this afternoon has a much larger field than last year, and Squire Silk could be
the one to help punters in their struggle with the sponsors.
He was caught for stamina at Chepstow but should have no such problem over this
shorter trip and better going. Andrew Turnell's hurdler beat Bookcase at
Newbury, giving away two stone, and on that form holds Lonesome Train.
Viking Flagship should be favourite for the Tingle Creek Chase on last year's
form. He beat Travado and Nakir when winning this event last year, and the time
of his victory in the Queen Mother Chase was a fraction better than Sound Man
in the ``Arkle'' the previous day.
However, Sound Man comes to the contest fit and showed progression when he won
by a distance at Ascot. I will take a gamble on him taking the measure of his
older rivals.
At Chepstow, Master Oats has the Rehearsal Chase at his mercy. Kim Bailey's
champion won on his reappearance in this event last season and went on to prove
himself the best chaser in training.
Bradbury Star is the only rival in the handicap proper but his disappointing
performance first time out does not suggest he is capable of an upset today.
Mad Thyme won his first two chases last year (General Wolfe well behind at
Uttoxeter), before failing to make the grade in the top class. His early exit
on his reappearance means he starts fresh today, and I will take a sporting bet
on him upsetting Greenhill Tare Away in the Jack Brown Chase.
Beachy Head raced in good company last season and shaped well on his
reappearance. He can land the Emmerdale Chase at Wetherby where he has won over
course and distance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Media quick to put the boot in</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNY LOGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093768</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ the news today. Oh boy. That's how the Beatles put it, and after a week
when I've been mugged in spectacular fashion by certain sections of the media,
I certainly know how they felt.
If you're wise and have restricted your reading habits to sensible papers then
you won't know what I'm talking about.
If not, then you'll know that after my performance against Melrose last
weekend, I got the kind of reviews that are normally reserved for child
molesters or Michael Forsyth. One comic, which masquerades as a middle-market
tabloid, even devoted a double-page spread to my shortcomings.
I wonder if that's what their readers want? Let's get one thing straight. I
played an absolute shocker last weekend and I don't need the media, or
team-mates, or Stirling County ``supporters'' to tell me that.
When the going gets tough you certainly find out who your friends are and over
the past week, I have had to think long and hard about my priorities and my
rugby. The game is moving into fresh pastures and the ground-rules seem to have
changed. As players we are going to have to give serious thought to whom we
talk to and when.
I've always been a media-friendly player. I've never turned down a request for
an interview. Basically, I like a blether and I like speaking about rugby. I've
enjoyed the high profile that goes with being a Scotland player and, although
some might disagree, I think it's good for the game.
There comes a time, though, when you have to be a bit more careful and on your
guard, and that time is now. As rugby moves into the professional era this is a
learning process for all of us involved.
Don't get me wrong, tall trees catch the most wind and if you are a Scottish
internationalist then you have to take the rough with the smooth. If you've
played a stinker then it's the right and the duty of the newspapers to call it
as they see it. We've been lucky in rugby up until now because media treatment
of the game has always steered clear of the kind of personal abuse that crops
up in football.
Constructive criticism is one thing but when it gets to the stage of reporting
the comments of the crowd. Gimme a break.
The media are entitled to write whatever they want, even when they ask loaded
questions with the sole purpose of making money and selling newspapers.
They can be as sensational as they want but, by the same token, those who took
such delight in having a crack at me can't then expect to call me up and carry
on as if nothing has happened.
I've really had my eyes opened over the past six days but I'm a wiser man as a
result. No more Mr Nice Guy.
I take heart from the fact that Gavin Hastings suffered the same kind of
treatment but went on to prove the critics wrong.
I'm not placing myself in the same category as Gavin but, just as he did, I
know that I've still got a lot to offer my club and Scotland, and I'll get it
right not to put one over on the critics but because of the personal
satisfaction that it will give me.
Last weekend against Melrose I was trying too hard. That was a game we should
have won but we know that. Today against Boroughmuir we have the opportunity to
take the premiership challenge right down to the wire. It ain't over until the
fat lady sings, and at the moment she's still warming up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bragg steps down as Border chairman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093769</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MELVYN Bragg, the high-profile chairman of Border Television, is to relinquish
his position at Easter. However, the South Bank Show producer and editor will
remain a non-executive director of Carlisle-based Border.
Referring to Mr Bragg's multitude of other commitments, Border finance director
Peter Brownlow said yesterday: ``The man is just a whirlwind and being chairman
of a public company does demand a fair proportion of time.
``With the additional burdens he is accepting on behalf of independent
television, he probably feels that now is the time to step down from Border,
but still be available.''
Mr Bragg, 56, who reportedly made a seven-figure sum out of share options
issued to him a few years ago to lock him into London Weekend Television, is
likely to represent the interests of the independent television industry when
the long-awaited Broadcasting Bill is going through Parliament.
Mr Brownlow said: ``It is sad that he is stepping down as chairman.'' However,
he was sure Mr Bragg, a native of Cumbria, would continue to make a valuable
contribution as a non-executive director.
The question of who will succeed Mr Bragg as non-executive chairman will be
considered at Border's next board meeting in early February.
Mr Brownlow said he did not yet know whether the successor would be chosen from
Border's non-executive directors or brought in from outside.
Border's shares yesterday lost 2p to 212p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BREWING Sun shines on profits</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093770</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WOLVERHAMPTON &amp; Dudley Breweries basked in City approval yesterday with profit
last year above expectations with the stated pre-tax total up 13.5% to #43.5m.
``The right sort of sun shone in 1995,'' said chairman David Miller.
He added that throughout the summer pubs traded well, take-home trade sales
were buoyant rising by more than 15%, and free-trade business was won back due
in part to problems at one big competitor.
The group boosted its pubs business by building 10 new outlets and buying five
others. There was a strong improvement in margins in the second half as the pub
refurbishment programme bore fruit.
In this financial year, another 15 pubs will be added to the estate, 44 will be
remarketed and another 130 refurbished as part of a capital expenditure
programme costing #45m.
The dividend total has been raised 10.3% to 15p with a 9.9p final. The shares
leapt 21p to 551p.
</TEXT>
