<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kinnock's trouble, which he can never forget, is that he was destined for better things.  Brave face of the becalmed bruiser</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Murray Ritchie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093771</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POOR Neil Kinnock. Even his critics and opponents are beginning to wonder what
he has done to deserve such a bad press. Those days should now be long behind
him.
At first he was portrayed as the Welsh windbag, a political romantic, an
anti-Scottish centralist, a boyo who became distant from the grass roots of the
party. Then they began to call him autocratic, unwilling to listen. After the
election defeat which destroyed his leadership they called him a failure.
This week a new word was added to the lexicon of abuse which Neil Kinnock has
suffered. His boss in the European Commission, Jacques Santer, described him as
weak.
Well, that is the way it was widely reported. In fact Santer did not use the
word ``weak''. But he did - remarkably - suggest that his transport
commissioner had been unable to win an argument in the commission because he
``may not have enough of a strong personality'' to win people over to his cause.
This was immediately interpreted, reasonably enough, as an attack on a ``weak''
Kinnock and as this evidence of disharmony within the commission reverberated
around Europe, Santer quickly began to backtrack. Suddenly, Neil Kinnock was a
``very active, co-operative, efficient commissioner'' with whom Santer looked
forward to working. ``I do not consider, however, that Neil Kinnock has a weak
personality,'' the president added for good measure, shamelessly contradicting
himself.
In retrospect the whole affair was rather ridiculous but probably quite
wounding to Kinnock. To some extent it was caused by the familiar pitfalls when
someone speaks spontaneously in a second or third language and ends up saying
something he did not really mean.
But the damage had been done. Neil Kinnock had been dished again. No-one ever
said politics was supposed to be fair.
In the backrooms of the European Parliament there was fury inside the big
Labour-dominated socialist group with individual British Euro-MPs at each
others' throats. Some, the Kinnock loyalists, expressed outrage at this public
humiliation of a prominent commissioner widely regarded as effortlessly on top
of the job; others argued that he deserved to be slapped down for stepping out
of line.
Kinnock's crime in the eyes of Jacques Santer was to suggest that the king had
no clothes, the king in this case being European economic and monetary union
(Emu). To say such a thing is the ultimate heresy in Brussels these days, at
least inside the commission, where anyone failing to sing from the official
hymn sheet must be struck down. When we talk about Emu we talk about the
European Union's grandest and most ambitious project in decades. Even to hint
publicly that it might be going wrong is treachery.
Kinnock might have got away with it if a French news wire had not picked it up.
His remarks were intended to be personal and private in so far as any speech
made to 200 suits at a business seminar is private. Worse, he then told his
audience that he thought the EU was going about enlargement the wrong way and
that some fresh thinking might be in order.
In these circumstances you might consider that Kinnock, far from being weak and
unable to win arguments, should have been commended for his courage in speaking
up, if not for his carelessness in being reported.
Some commissioners agree with him on both issues. When Bruce Millan, whom
Kinnock replaced, gave up managing the EU's multi-billion pound structural
funds he told reporters as he was leaving that eastwards enlargement of the
community was simply unthinkable in the short term without a major overhaul of
spending. Almost everyone agrees but there are still those who insist that, for
example, the common agricultural policy, accounting for half of all EU
spending, can survive enlargement without major alterations.
No-one outside Kinnock's immediate circle of Eurocrats knows exactly what
happened when Kinnock and Santer met privately on Wednesday afternoon. But it
is significant that Santer's retraction was promptly distributed to Brussels
correspondents by Kinnock's press spokeswoman. Kinnock has remained silent,
with as much dignity as he can muster.
Even without such unforeseen annoyances, life in Brussels was always going to
be difficult for Neil Kinnock and his high-profile wife, Glenys, from the
moment he was chosen to replace Millan as Labour's commissioner and she went on
to win a Welsh Euro-seat with Britain's biggest majority. Her emotional victory
speech in which she bitterly recalled fate's treatment of her husband signalled
the peculiar kind of pressure they would face in Brussels where the knockers
and the merely jealous refer to them sniffily as Labour's royal family.
Obvious efforts have gone into keeping their lifestyle unpretentious in the
face of sniping about their new-found Euro-wealth. Cleverly, they inherited the
tenancy of a modest flat near the commission from a departing Daily Telegraph
reporter. Ostentatious it is not. Thus the tabloids were denied spreads on the
shock-horror scandal of the Kinnocks' continental opulence.
His appearances at cocktail parties are limited and there is no back-slapping
camaraderie with boyos in the pubs around the commission. The Neil Kinnock who
eventually came to power as Labour leader - the former radical with the hippy
hair and extravagant language - is now a slim coffee drinker in a sharp suit
who has the energised look of one who is almost unhealthily healthy.
SOMETIMES, a little of the old Kinnock is allowed out to play. As an
accomplished after-dinner speaker he still has them slapping their thighs and
you can see he is enjoying himself when he slips the leash on his natural
Celtic gift for fun and linguistic histrionics. That is probably why he
sometimes goes on too long: he is a born communicator, a poet.
At work Neil Kinnock showed early on that the job held no daunting challenges.
He brought a briskness to his directorate and a refreshing lack of Eurobabble
to a portfolio which is interesting but limited. Sorting out dodgy ferries,
making Europe's trains run on time, and knocking back airlines chancing their
arm on subsidies is not the stuff of geo-political statesmanship. But he does
the job well, everyone agrees.
Kinnock's trouble, which he will never resolve and can never forget, is that he
was destined for better things, and everyone knows it. The battle-hardened
toughness is no longer needed. Years of experience gained in running a major
European political party goes unwanted. The European Commission with its
flunkeys, limousines, pushy power-dressed women, and subservient bureaucrats is
a long way from the valleys and, in a sense, even further from the bear pit of
the House of Commons. Brussels is not his natural habitat and would never have
been his chosen future.
Kinnock gives the impression of a man carrying a suppressed, agonising
frustration. Underneath the smart suit there is still the bolshy son of a Welsh
miner, still a man of the people, who found the transition to eminence more
difficult to handle than fellow countrymen like Aneurin Bevan, and who,
strangely, attracted more racist criticism than other Welsh politicians in
England.
Yet this is still the man who made Labour electable from nowhere - much thanks
he got - and who handed the job to John Smith for the finishing touches, and
thus to Tony Blair for the ruthless socialist bypass. Kinnock is now the
becalmed bruiser who still loves a political joust and whose eyes light up when
the conversation turns to electoral trends and Labour shoptalk. And then it is
back to the esoterics of trans-European networks and another night of bleak
Eurospeak with commissioners, most of whom have never scaled his heights and
couldn't lace his political boots. No disrespect to Jacques Santer - nice chap
and all that - but to be denounced as a lightweight by Mr Santer is rather like
being criticised by John Major for being colourless.
In his public appearances in Brussels Neil Kinnock puts on a brave face and he
soldiers on. But sometimes, in his darker moments, he must wonder about life's
capricious ways.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
