<DOCNO>GH951202-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TELEVISION OFT investigates BSkyB</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093772</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SATELLITE broadcaster BSkyB's role in the supply of programmes to the cable
television operators is to be investigated by the Office of Fair Trading. This
was announced yesterday by Director General of Fair Trading John Bridgeman who
said the review is expected to last for six months.
It was sparked off by complaints from some cable operators and their request to
the Trade and Industry Secretary Ian Lang for a ministerial reference to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The companies had complained earlier this year and had successfully forced
BSkyB which is 40% owned by Rupert Murdoch's News International to rewrite its
rate card and remove some of the clauses that were thought to be significantly
anti-competitive. Some had said the deal signed with TeleWest Communications
and Nynex Cableomms was unfair.
BSkyB with 4.4 million subscribers is by far the biggest operator in pay-TV. In
addition to the rights to an increasing proportion of premier sports events
being acquired, it has also the rights to a large proportion of Hollywood's
films.
Companies had said that they were being ``bundled'' whereby they had to take
programmes they may not want as part of a package rather than buy just one
individual show.
Mr Bridgeman said the review would be confined to issues relating to the supply
in the UK of programming and related services at the wholesale level. The
investigation will also look into access to encryption, subscriber management
and transponders.
He added that his predecessor, Sir Bryan Carsberg, opted for informal
undertakings because they provided a swift and flexible mechanism to tackle the
practices which he had identified as likely to frustrate competition in this
market. These were to be reviewed by no later than the end of 1996 or earlier
if considered appropriate. He said he had been in recent contact with the DTI
about an appropriate response to continuing complaints from cable operators.
``As the development of this fast-moving market is now at a crucial stage I
have decided to take advantage of the flexibility of informal undertakings to
carry out an early review,'' he added.
Separately, the OFT said that it was evaluating under the Restrictive Trade
Practices Act the terms of various agreements to televise sports. BSkyB shares
saw turnover of almost 30 million and fluctuated heavily during the day,
eventually closing 5!sp lower at 428!sp.
</TEXT>
