<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flaws in community care.  Patients have not been well served</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093775</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CARE in the Community is a good policy for many suffering from poor mental
health. Indeed its advantages are widely recognised, but its implementation has
left much to be desired and there is a widespread unease about its operation.
Many assume that the deficiencies are to be found in the inadequacy of
financial resource, but that, in the main, may not be the case in Scotland,
where the annual report of the Scottish Health Advisory Service has just been
published. The service is no kind of lapdog but a genuinely independent body
with a radical cast of mind. It finds no consistent implementation of policy
and no clear notion of who are responsible for maintaining that policy to
ensure good professional practice.
The drawbacks of care in the community have been exposed in a number of
dramatic cases in England where, for example, several horrific murders have
been attributed to the poor management of schizophrenics. There, lack of
adequate financial resource seems to have been a factor of some importance in
explaining the failures, but here, as the director of the SHAS suggested
yesterday, there has been a simple lack of understanding between social work
departments and health boards, each of which seems to have imagined that the
other was responsible for the oversight of the policy. Conduct seems to have
differed between localities and individual patients have not been well, and
consistently, served. In some ways that is a far more disturbing situation than
a poor outcome because of financial weakness, for that can always be tackled by
an allocation of new funds. Establishing the proper responsibility for the
people concerned, and ensuring they receive the attention they require, is far
more challenging and goes a long way to justifying the widespread sense of
unease which unites many professional workers in the field with popular
observers.
Once established as existing, this situation can be addressed. In fact the new
Secretary of State for Scotland, Mr Forsyth, initiated a thorough review of
Care in the Community on his appointment. For other bodies had expressed doubts
about how the policy was working in fact, no matter how attractive it was in
theory. It should be possible to promote the required reforms by a firm
political judgment, either allocating responsibility generally for implementing
the policy to one body or allocating it to different bodies in different places
but always making the allocation clear. Thereafter, at any rate, seems a
relatively easy matter of administration. This is not the first time Mr Forsyth
has appeared to use his new broom to good effect - and if more money is
required as well, he should get it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chef who always looks for that better way</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093776</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Conrad Wilson compares two very splendid
hotels on the shores
of famous lakes
WHAT the Villa d'Este is to the South-west shore of Lake Como so Cameron House
is to the equivalent portion of Loch Lomond; each seems idyllically situated.
Each, for a price, pampers its guests in the ways they would expect, each is
within reach of a famous major city, each has its own marina, and each serves
uncommonly good food.
The Villa d'Este is the sort of hotel to which opera directors and star singers
retreat for some peace and quiet after they have been booed at La Scala, Milan.
Cameron House, just before I dined there last month, had fed - so they said
with pride - Sir David Frost and Esther Rantzen.
Although Milan and Glasgow have obvious features in common, the smaller towns
of Como and Alexandria, which lie rather closer to their respective grand
hotels, do not. Como has an exquisite cathedral, a fashionable silk industry,
and deservedly plenty of tourists; Alexandria has an air of depression.
On the other hand, the Villa d'Este does cost rather more to stay in. For the
privilege of a view of Lake Como, you will pay something like #280 a night for
one of its 151 rooms, even at the present favourable exchange rate. This makes
Cameron House, at #150, seem relatively cheap, especially as it has just been
named Scottish Hotel of the Year by the AA. Dinner prices are in proportion.
The Villa d'Este's cheapest meal being about the same as Cameron House's
dearest.
Nevertheless, Cameron House is no bargain. Possessor of one of Scotland's few
Michelin stars, its chef, Jeff Bland, is rightly proud of his cuisine, and the
hotel charges for it accordingly. However, although #37.50 per head may seem a
lot, at least in Scotland, for a four-course set dinner on a Saturday night,
nobody could fault the quality of the ingredients or object to the finesse with
which Bland by no means blandly handles them.
Foie gras, langoustine minestronie, fillets of brill and a choice of cheese
formed one permutation of the short menu the night I ate in the so-called
Georgian Room; salmon ravioli, the same soup, fillet of beef, and a hot
chestnut souffle formed another. Although the ingredients themselves were
conspicuously expensive, the expertise of the cooking must have been worth just
as much. This was labour intensiveness on a high and inventive level.
The foie gras, for instance, was served within a ring of roasted cherry
tomatoes - much more interesting that way than raw - along with toasted
brioche. The salmon ravioli turned out to be a single intricate parcel of fish
and shellfish on a bed of thinly sliced asparagus. The clear, keenly flavoured
soup came with ``parma shavings'' (cheese, I would guess, as well as ham) and a
real Marseillaise rouille, its effect an audacious amalgam of France and Italy.
The brill was a brilliant illusion, in which the fish encircled a saffron and
truffle mousse so subtly it was hard to tell which was which. Razor-thin
ribbons of courgette and a dill and vermouth sauce were its accompaniment. The
grilled fillet of beef was no mere fillet of beef, but a fillet of beef stuffed
with wild mushrooms and artichokes with a powerful port wine sauce.
With ingredients such as these, side dishes of vegetables would have been not
only redundant but nonsensical. The chestnut souffle, served with caramel
ice-cream, was a perfect specimen of its kind. The cheese, mostly French and
served from a trolley, was in prime condition.
For those who insist on simple food, Jeff Bland's cooking may seem over-the-top
- the product of a chef already seeking his second Michelin star - but in
almost every respect it carried me with it. Talking to him about it, moreover,
confirmed its seriousness. Whether he has veal or scallops, langoustines or
turnips at his disposal, the questions he invariably asks himself are ``What
are we going to do with them?'' and ``Is there a better way?''.
Originally from Yorkshire, he says he is happy to buy ``everything that's good
in Scotland'', but some things - including chicken, duck, and guinea fowl - he
prefers to import from France. The inference seems obvious. If a product is not
right, he would ``rather scrap it than serve it''. With a background in what
used to be British Transport Hotels - the Queen's in Leeds, the Caledonian in
Edinburgh - he is nothing if not meticulous. But then, with a team of 29
assistant chefs, here is someone who has no need to take short-cuts in his
cooking.
To recoup the cost of such cuisine, the hotel imposes a dismayingly high
mark-up on its otherwise enticing wine list. But the service (except breakfast,
served elsewhere in the building) is immaculate, even though the Georgian Room
- one of several additions to Tobias Smollett's handsome, if somewhat sombre,
birthplace - is a lot less beautiful than the food.
n Cameron House Hotel, Georgian Room, Alexandria, Loch Lomond (Tel:
01389-755565). Dinner for two with a modest bottle of wine #95.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
