<DOCNO>GH951202-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What will the Chancellor's concessions mean to those paying for long-term care? Budgeting for old age</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HELEN PRIDHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093777</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor ack-nowledged in this week's Budget that paying for long-term
care for the elderly is a growing problem for many families. Most people were
disappointed, though, that he did not go further.
The immediate measures he announced were modest. However, he did float a number
of other ideas and will be consulting on proposals to encourage people to make
advance provision for long-term care.
Immediate action includes an easing of the means testing of elderly people who
need to enter long-term nursing or residential care. At present you have to
make a contribution towards this if your savings are more than #3000. If you
have over #8000 you must meet the full cost. Following the Budget you will
qualify for help with fees if you have less than #16,000 and free care when
your assets drop to #10,000.
Age Concern Scotland has welcomed the change but its director, Maureen O'Neill,
points out its limitations: ``The increase in capital limits will help people
with modest savings who need residential or nursing care, but will not prevent
them having to sell their homes to pay for care. The Chancellor's failure to
increase capital limits for means-tested benefits for people living at home,
means the benefit system will continue to penalise older people with savings.''
Providing more free care will involve extra expenditure by local authorities
and the DSS. The Government has said it will provide them with a special grant
to cover this. At the moment, though, according to Age Concern, the amount
allocated for this appears insufficient.
``Church of Scotland homes for the elderly are having to be closed because they
are not receiving enough funding from local authorities and the Church is not
prepared to compromise on quality. Yet they currently provide the lowest cost
care, at under #300 a week, compared to fees of up to #400 to #500 in the
private sector,'' says Liz Mitchell at Age Concern.
As part of this week's Budget package, the Chancellor also announced that
benefits paid out under long-term care insurance policies are to be made tax
free, even where they go direct to the person needing care. Until now, only
payments made straight to care providers have been tax free.
This new provision should make it easier for elderly people to compensate
relatives or friends who give up work to look after them in their own homes.
However, Sandy Johnstone, manager of Commercial Union's long-term care
insurance arm, is somewhat dubious about the possible consequences of this
development.
He explains: ``We see potential problems and abuses. Where we are paying fees
direct to recognised providers, we know there will be some control over the
quality of care given. If payments are made direct to policyholders to purchase
their own care, it is more difficult to check whether they are getting the
standard of care they really need.''
So far, though, relatively few people have taken out long-term care insurance
policies. These come in two main forms. The first involves making advance
payment, either by regular premiums or a lump sum, to cover the cost of care if
the need arises. Policies will normally pay out if the holder becomes incapable
of undertaking two or three ``activities of daily living'', such as bathing,
dressing, or going to the lavatory unassisted.
Under Commercial Union's Well-Being policy, for example, a 61-year-old man
paying a regular premium of #46.20 per month or a single premium of #4616 would
be entitled to #10,000 worth of annual benefit to pay for care for as long as
it was needed.
The second type of policy is available to those with an immediate need for
care. It is an annuity plan which provides enhanced payments in return for a
lump sum investment. Payments will depend on the holder's state of health on
entering care.
The Government would like to encourage more people to make their own provision
for long-term care. Ideas on which it will be consulting include partnership
schemes similar to those which exist in the US, where people who pay for, say,
the first three years of care in a home then receive it free, without a means
test, allowing them to retain any remaining savings.
Another possibility is to enable those with company pension schemes to opt for
a variable pension, taking a small one in the beginning in exchange for a
larger one in later years to help cover the cost of care.
The insurance industry is keen to get involved in this process. Scottish
Mutual's chief executive Andrew Pople says: ``Health care is an area where we
are actively developing our business. We would welcome the opportunity to take
part in the consultation process on long-term care.''
His views are echoed by Britannia Life's Chris Frohlich, who believes the
Government will also have to consider giving people an extra tax incentive
upfront to start planning for long-term care.
For the present, however, according to Age Concern, most retired people feel
betrayed. They believe they have already paid for their care through a lifetime
of taxes and National Insurance contributions and that the state has broken its
promise to look after them.
</TEXT>
