<HEADLINE>Parry's 67 eclipsed by Guepy course record</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093778</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIAN Craig Parry shot a six-under-par 67 for a halfway total of 132 and a
one-shot lead at The Lakes course in Sydney yesterday.
But he was overshadowed by Frenchman Jean-Louis Guepy, who fired a brilliant
course-record 63, 10 under par, to move up to a stroke off the lead.
Greg Norman, the world No.1, stormed to a 67 by picking up six shots in the
first 14 holes to stay in contention for the tournament that bears his name.
Leading scores (Australian unless stated):
132 - C Parry 65, 67.
133 - J L Guepy (France) 70, 63.
134 - M Campbell (New Zealand) 66, 68; F Nobilo (New Zealand) 64, 70.
135 - P Senior 68, 67.
136 - G Waite (New Zealand) 66, 70.
137 - T Price 68, 69.
138 - B Faxon (USA) 68, 70.
139 - G Norman 72, 67.
q LAURA Davies and Mark McCumber say they make a perfect match on the golf
course. It showed yesterday with a six-under-par 67 in the modified alternate
stroke-play second round of the J C Penney Mixed-Team Classic at Tarpon
Springs, Florida.
Davies and McCumber are 14 under for two rounds, one stroke in front of Val
Skinner and Jay Delsing, who also had a 67. Five teams were tied for third,
another stroke back. Of that group, Carin Hjalmarsson and Doug Martin had the
best round yesterday, a 64, while Vicki Goetze and Steve Stricker, and Barb
Thomas and Steve Jones, had 65s.
GREG NORMAN CLASSIC
</TEXT>
