<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Artists in cyberspace</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093780</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n At first glance it looks pretty strange, a new design for some very old
technology. It's the banana chair, and from where your Frontiersman sits
hunched over a smoking keyboard, it looks like the apotheosis of all comfort.
One could go for a snooze given half a chance.
The banana chair is what's known as a dynamic seat which effortlessly tips the
sitter into a series of relaxing positions, the most recumbent of which is the
almost flat- out posture. The makers say it's designed to fit the human form
and sitting in it feels just like floating. It even comes with a relaxation
cassette and a booklet of loosening exercises. Just looking at the picture
makes one's eyelids droop. Originally developed in 1988, a low-down version has
now been raised and made more compact, using adjustable armstraps to alter the
sitting angle. The BC portable folds into a little carry-unit easy to store and
haul out into the garden during the next long-awaited heatwave.
It's selling at #279 from the appropriately named Banana Chair Company on
01773-533626.
The firm have brought out an even more complex version, the Butterfly Recliner
at #495, which looks, to this stressed-out scribbler, the ultimate in induced
lethargy. It's a rocking-chair recliner, guaranteed to paralyse all industry.
Once he is sprawled in one of these, wild horses would be hard put to get this
writer out again.
NIBBLES
n The Society of Scottish Artists have painted themselves into cyberspace with
the launch of the first major British exhibition of artists on the Internet.
Sixty artists and sculptors are now exhibiting more than 100 images on the Net.
The works include pieces by George Wylie, Lesley Banks, Bill Gillon, Lys Hansen
and others.
The SSA web site is: http://www-edin.easynet.co.uk/ssa.
n A NEW home shopping service has been launched for Internet users by the
Innovations Group, offering more than 2500 products on a web site.
The Innovations mall offers gifts and gadgets, home furnishings and a range of
catalogues. Customers can make a selection, complete an order form and give
credit card details which are encrypted before transmission to the Internet
server. The company says it can offer new products every day. Innovations
E-dress is http://www.innovations.co.uk.
n YOUNG women who engage in even moderate exercise may suffer from iron
deficiency that results in anaemia, scientists have found. In the first
long-term study of the effects of exercise on the iron status of women,
researchers found that women who take up exercise can lose enough iron to bring
on feelings of fatigue, a symptom of anaemia. Good diet and possibly iron
supplements could be recommended.
n SCIENTISTS in Oregon are trying to put the pep back into peppermint. The
state is a leading producer of the flavouring, and it's under attack by all
sorts of pests. Now university entomologists have designed a computerised
system known as ``Integrated Pest Management for Peppermint'' which helps
identify pests, diseases and other problems. Our polo mints seem to be getting
the protection they deserve.
n FLOWER power is being used to help the farmed salmon industry in Maine. Like
Scots farms, the US industry is faced with infestations of sea-lice which can
drastically reduce yields. Now scientists at Maine University are using a
treatment made from pyrethroids, a natural derivative of chrysanthemum leaves.
It's already been used as a household insecticide, and it seems to be more than
80% effective against sea-lice. It can be used in very low doses and breaks
down in the environment.
n CLOUDY skies may be gloomy but they're also complicated. Their role in global
warming is still foggy, involving complex interactions with carbon dioxide,
heat, and the sun. This month, scientists are gathering more data on the
situation, using three heavily instrumented aeroplanes that will fly above,
below, and in the clouds over Kansas and Oklahoma. The data from this ``cloud
sandwich'' will show how much of the sun's heat is absorbed by clouds at
different altitudes and will be used to improve computer models that predict
global climate change.
n THE most accurate clock in the universe is a . . . star! It's actually a
collapsed star, squashed by its own gravity with the same mass as the sun, but
only about as wide as Greater Glasgow. It's known as a pulsar, spinning at
colossal speed and emitting a pulse of energy on every turn. Astrophysicists
can use the pulses to check on the accuracy of the most accurate timepieces on
earth, atomic clocks which measure the frequency of radiation produced by the
element caesium.
n TELFORD, birthplace of the Industrial Revolution, will make science history
next year when scientists of all disciplines will gather for Scientific
Computing '96, the first exhibition designed to attract the entire computing
fraternity.
Sponsored by the Institute of Physics, the Royal Society of Chemistry and the
Institute of Biology, the exhibition expects to draw scientists from all over
the UK to test and compare the very latest in soft and hardware. It's being
held at the same time as the Physics World Exhibition and Congress, and will
run for two days in April at Telford International Centre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edna Deane</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093781</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDNA Deane, the world champion ballroom dancer famous for having been the
``girl who danced with the Prince of Wales'', has died at 90.
Deane died at her home in Rottingdean, south of London, where she was confined
by crippling osteoporosis. She was born Edna Morton Sewell in the Orange Free
State - now part of South Africa - in 1905 to British parents. Her family
returned to England in 1907, and she trained in ballet and ballroom dancing.
She found fame in Britain under the stage name Edna Deane in the 1920s.
At one ball in the mid-1920s Prince Edward - later King Edward VIII - asked her
dance nine times. That led Herbert Farjeon to pen the popular music hall number
I've Danced With a Man, Who's Danced with a Girl, Who's Danced with the Prince
of Wales.
Fred Astaire, who saw her at the London Palladium in 1929, called her
``authentic poetry in motion''.In 1933, she and her partner Timothy Palmer won
the British and world ballroom dancing championships. When, upon her first
marriage in 1935, she retired, the Sunday Express mourned, ``The lights of
London have dimmed ..... The divine Edna is lost to us.''
She later became a choreographer and writer on dance. When she turned 90 last
month, she was still receiving birthday cards from fans. She is survived by a
daughter from her second marriage to the late restaurateur John Fuelling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bannocks at dawn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LELIA FARRAH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093782</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Actress Dolina Maclennan plays Ishbel in Machair and Flora in Hamish MacBeth.
She also does television cooking, writes and does storytelling. As she tells
LEILA FARRAH, she runs bed and breakfast at her home in Blair Atholl.
n BREAKFAST is the only meal in the whole day I'm sure of - without it I'm
shaking by 11 o'clock. Mostly porridge with oatmeal from Blair Atholl Mill,
then sometimes fish, bacon and eggs or scrambled eggs, usually the same as what
the guests are having.
Lunch is usually home-made soup left over from the night before. People pop in
all day for numerous cups of tea, the kettle's always on the boil. I don't bake
- apart from bread made with honey and olive oil - or make cakes but love
Selkirk Bannock spread thick with Lockerbie butter.
I cook Scottish food using good fresh ingredients. I grow my own strawberries,
raspberries, gooseberries, lettuce, potatoes, carrot, and beetroot. I get local
pheasant and roe deer - hind - in season from Pitlochry, salmon from Lewis,
trout from Glen Almond, and fresh fish from Buckie. I have nothing frozen or
processed and don't go in for fancy cooking. Game I do in red wine and juniper
berries, fish just in butter and parsley. A wonderful Gaelic expression says
``Everything has its own taste'' so when you come across something like Beef
Collops Culloden or Salmon Killiecrankie you just cringe. If the ingredients
are good, it needs nothing else.
I love cooking with oatmeal and make a wonderful pheasant soup like the
Cormorant Soup I'd eat as a child in Lewis - with onion, fresh sage, pinhead
oatmeal and nutmeg. I don't use recipes but read them avidly.
I love a beautifully set table with polished crystal, silver for dinner, and at
breakfast a plain china just to make people feel they're worthwhile with a
different atmosphere at each meal. My house rule is no hurry - I work very fast
but I don't hurry and that relaxes people which means sometimes people will be
at the breakfast table at midday.
If I'm cooking dinner for six or more, I sometimes forget to eat and by the
time I've cleared up - I'm past it. But as long as I've had breakfast, lunch
and bannock, I'll maybe just eat leftover vegetables. So I just love going out
to dinner and being fed.
As a child from a fishing family in Lewis I'd pick the seafood from the shore,
so my ideal meal would be fresh boiled lobster, sole on the bone with new
potatoes and a salad afterwards, then strawberries and cream fresh from the
garden. I don't like to eat anything that isn't real. And my favourite drink is
the local excellent tapwater with ice - or a good wine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Split over approach to matter of life and death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANTHEA  MASSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093783</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN less than three years the country's largest split-capital investment trust,
the Glasgow-based Scottish National, faces extinction. Yet last week's annual
report made scant mention of this.
Nor is Scottish National the only trust having to face up to decisions about
its future. There are 15, with assets approaching a massive #1750m, due to be
wound up over the next three years. And if the messy way in which Sphere
recently met its end is anything to go by, shareholders may need some
reassurance that the directors are up to looking after their interests during
their remaining life.
Split-capital investment trusts have been around in one form or another since
the sixties. They underwent a great revival in the late eighties and continue
to evolve. There are now nearly 60 which have some form of split capital
structure.
Traditionally, they had two classes of shares: capital and income. The former
benefit from any capital growth in the trust's investments but get no income.
The latter get the dividend income but have no share in any capital growth.
Capital shares are generally a high-risk investment which do well in sharply
rising markets but under-perform when they are falling. Income shares tend to
be much steadier performers.
Most of the newer split-capital investment trusts have adopted a different
structure which involves the issue of zero dividend shares and highly geared
income shares. Zero dividend shares give a predetermined rate of return, paid
when the trust is wound up, and there is no income.
The highly geared income shares get all the income from the trust's investments
and any capital left after repaying the zero dividend shares. Under this
structure, it is the capital shares, the zeros, which offer the lowest risk.
Whatever their structure, all split-capital investment trusts have one thing in
common: a fixed winding-up date. For some investors this is a great help. For
example, many people buy zero dividend shares as a tax efficient way to pay for
things such as school fees. For others, the prospect of being paid a large sum
on a specific date could mean a big bill for capital gains tax.
What happened at Sphere and the proposals which Jupiter is now putting forward
for the winding up of River Plate show that shareholders may end up totally
confused and far from happy.
At Sphere, the management company didn't want to launch a new investment trust,
so shareholders who didn't fancy cash had nowhere to go.
In the end the board told them to take shares in a new trust run by Guinness
Flight. However, Gartmore Shared Equity, one of Gartmore's stable of
split-capital investment trusts, then added to the confusion by putting in a
bid for Sphere which some shareholders accepted.
Jupiter's proposals have pre-empted River Plate's winding-up date by nearly a
year. Shareholders are being offered the choice of going into a new trust,
Jupiter Split, taking cash now, or staying with River Plate until the trust is
wound up next October.
Jupiter's Philip Butt says it decided to make the move now because it was
becoming increasingly difficult to deal in River Plate's shares. However, he
admits shareholders are confused, but adds: ``River Plate income shareholders
who want to carry on getting their high income for another year will be able to
do so."
River Plate can only be extinguished early if more than 90% of shareholders
accept the Jupiter offer and the minority are forced to sell. Mr Butt thinks
this won't happen but admits shareholders who want to stay with River Plate
could lose out in these circumstances.
John Szymanowski of stockbroker Warburgs predicts: ``Most split-capital
investment trusts are managed by large investment management groups and will
come up with proposals which give shareholders the option of taking cash or
shares in a new trust. After all no-one voluntarily watches funds under
management disappear out the door.''
However, investment trusts are run by independent boards of directors and some
of them may ask other groups to put in alternative proposals. And with many
split-capital trusts now standing at a discount to net assets, a spate of
opportunistic takeover bids can't be ruled out. Jupiter Split is hoping to
complete the acquisition of River Plate by the end of the year, but there could
still be a bid from somewhere else.
This could be tough luck on the shareholders who planned to take cash on a
specific date - and the experience at Sphere proves this is what most people
want to do. They may be plunged into uncertainty during the run up to their
trust's winding-up date.
The next trusts to face these problems are Fleming International High Income,
Hong Kong and Rights &amp; Issues, all of which are due to be wound up next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J P Leach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093784</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHY does every day and week and year have to be dedicated to something? Who
decides? Has the UN set up a special committee? (``Hmmm if National Cycling
Awareness Day is in March and 1996 is World Haemorrhoid Year - slogan: Stand Up
For Your Rights - then we should give the International Root Vegetable
Awareness Society the second Tuesday in June.'')
As a generalisation, any issue that needs its own week or month isn't one that
should command our attention. This commemoration gimmick is nothing but a
cynical nineties public relations ploy. This was brought home to me last
Saturday when I caught the televised comedy gig in aid of HIV-related charities
which was set up to mark World AIDS Day.
When I switched on, Phil Kay was just finishing, and after his inspired
improvisation I suppose it could only really be downhill. And boy did it career
downhill fast. In fairness to the other performers, benefit gigs are always a
nightmare. The more serious the cause that is `benefiting'' the more chance
there is that the whole night will involve a major bit of sincerity overload,
and the less likely that a paying audience will allow themselves to be
entertained.
The audience at these things tend to think that, although it's a comedy night,
it's inappropriate to laugh while there are trees to be hugged and dolphins to
be put on re-employment training. The only reason that a comedian might prefer
to do an AIDS benefit is that it provides an opportunity to use his usual
inspiration for material - sex. It's easier to be funny about sex than it is to
be funny about Bosnia or whales. Or Wales. No that's not true, it's always easy
to laugh at the Welsh.
The fact that condoms are such a rich source of laughs should be enough to
rebut the fanciful notion, cruelly put about by AIDS charities, that condoms
are erotic. If condoms were erotic, they wouldn't need TV adverts to tell
teenagers to use them, they'd need to put out adverts telling them to stop
before the world's rubber supplies run out. Maybe the Pope should stop trying
all this moral-high-ground stuff and tell it like it is.
As the competition among fund-raisers hots up they're all having to become more
cynical and manipulative.
In between the comedy segments on Saturday night there were serious
``heart-tugging'' moments, telling us how terrible it is to have AIDS. If
anyone was ever insensitive enough to imagine that having AIDS is a picnic, the
programme was quick to educate them. It did this by interviewing the most TV
friendly, most middle-class AIDS sufferers it could find. From what they told
us we could only surmise that AIDS is much much worse than leukemia, or kidney
failure, or lung cancer.
In some senses they are right: AIDS is a unique illness, but not in the degree
to which it takes young people and breaks them. The programme tried to show a
different image of AIDS, and while challenging people's preconceptions is not
necessarily a bad thing, a denial of the facts (that AIDS affects mostly gay
men and drug addicts) can only serve to stigmatise the disease further. The
only time anyone who looked gay got a word in was if they were doing a turn
on-stage. From their attitude we can assume that it's OK to be gay on a show
like that, but only if it's a sixties-style camp, and only if the person
doesn't look unwell.
Medical science has been able to watch the evolution of AIDS over the past 12
years in an unsurpassed manner. Within five years of its description in the
medical journals we had innumerable programmes featuring ``experts'' who
earnestly told us that AIDS was going to sweep the world, making the bubonic
plague look like last year's chickenpox outbreak. Religious fundamentalists of
all sorts were delighted. Here was proof that God was pretty fed up, and about
to wreak havoc on unbelievers. This always confused me, because by this
implication anyone researching a cure for AIDS would be doing the Devil's work.
What has happened in the past decade? In the UK there is no ``plague''.
Compared with heart disease, cancers, and even car crashes, HIV infection is
still comparatively rare among the general population. From a global
perspective AIDS is rampant in parts of Africa, but it still has a huge way to
go before it catches up with malaria in the continent's death league.
We all know that HIV infection is a tragedy, but if you're an African who's got
malaria, or a middle-aged woman with stomach cancer, that's just as tragic.
Maybe more would be done for them if they had the decency to get themselves a
trendy terminal disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SCOTLAND'S FUTURE.  Calm advice on devolution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093785</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR report on November 28 of Sir Bruce Pattullo's speech at the Glasgow
Chamber of Commerce did no justice to him on the debate on devolution. I say
this as a long-standing supporter of reform who attend the event.
His advice was given added force precisely because he was prepared to set aside
his personal view which he did in a sentence. He went on, at some length, to
suggest that business should engage with the detail of the devolution plans
perhaps on a sector-by-sector basis and that to do otherwise would be some sort
of failure of leadership.
His calm advice had its effect in the chamber but little sense of this was
carried into your over-personalised report.
Here was one of Scotland's leading businessman avoiding shrill comment and
trying to encourage reasoned debate within a business community which, so far
at least, has shown every sign of wishing to duck its responsibilities. One
only needs to look at CBI Scotland which is to give no leadership and do no
homework and in its own quaint phrase ``stick to its knitting.''
I think The Herald's unbalanced report poorly served Sir Bruce, the Chamber,
and Scotland and only confirmed the worst fears of those few people in business
tempted to contribute to the debate: that they had better not.
Nigel R Smith,
Managing Director,
David Auld Valves Limited,
Cowlairs Industrial Estate,
Glasgow.
An insult to the people
SO a majority of Scottish MPs cannot be allowed to determine what happens in
Scotland!
Michael Forsyth insults the people of Scotland.
John Scott Roy,
19 Blenheim Court, Kilsyth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
