<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Music East 17, SECC, Glasgow Rough diamonds are the real thing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jane Graham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093786</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the things that puts East 17 shaved head and hairy shoulders above the
rest of the current boy-group pack is that, in opposition to the dazzling
``shiny teeth and bronzed torsos'' brigade, East 17 look mostly like convicts
on the run after a violent barber attack.
To be this aesthetically challenged and this scary, and still have
pre-pubescent girls scream at you and choose to wear your face on their chests
is a remarkable feat. To come up with the odd pop gem on top of it seems just
like showing off.
The show, as you would expect, is a Big Bucks Extravaganza, complete with a
breathtaking set, a spectacular light show, erotic dancing girls, bad
acoustics, and Georgio Armani boxer shorts (frequently exposed).
However it's a shame that East 17 still feel the need for choreographed dance
routines in their show, a credibility kiss of death.
How can guys like these look cool flying through the air with their ankles
above their heads? They can't. They just look embarrassed, and it doesn't suit
them.
But for the most part this is a wildly exciting show, even for an old woman
like me. All around me, young girls respond with a reverence that reminds me of
an old-fashioned word: swoon.
It can only be a healthy sign that badly shaven rough diamonds still appeal to
teenage girls, especially with Take That getting cleaner and more responsible
at every turn.
Better to scream at something real than to sob for a cardboard cut-out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
