<DOCNO>GH951202-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ebdon again crushes Hicks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093789</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Ebdon gave a superb display as he romped into the Royal Liver Assurance
UK Championship final in Preston last night.
Ebdon had lost the first frame to Andy Hicks during the afternoon but stormed
back to seal a 9-1 triumph.
In tomorrow's final he will meet a Scot - either holder Stephen Hendry or
provisional world No.2 John Higgins, who play their semi-final today.
``I did a thoroughly professional job and felt very good,'' said the
25-year-old Londoner, whose victory took him further than last year, making
amends for his 1994 Guild Hall semi-final defeat by Hendry.
``It didn't matter what Andy did, because I always felt in control of the
match,'' said Ebdon, who will be appearing in his third ranking event final.
``To be honest, I don't think I've peaked yet. I could have played all day
because I was enjoying it so much.''
It was the second time in just over a month he had beaten Hicks following a
success at last month's Skoda Grand Prix - and it avenged a 13-8 drubbing in
the world championship quarter-finals in Sheffield earlier this year.
Hicks, 22, who had beaten world No.5 James Wattana and third seed Ronnie
O'Sullivan in his previous games, claimed the opening frame with an 84 break
before Ebdon bagged the next nine frames.
Frames five and six proved crucial. Ebdon, leading 3-1, fluked a red to start a
clearance of 107. He then doubled the final green after Hicks had missed the
same ball to clear up with 25 for 5-1.
Ebdon finished the session with another vital clearance of 31 and when the
match resumed he required only 39 minutes, firing two half-century breaks, to
wrap up his crushing win.
Hicks picked up a #18,000 consolation prize.
SNOOKER
</TEXT>
</DOC>
