<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheriff Henry Ward Pirie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093790</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HENRY Ward Pirie was educated at George Watson's College and Edinburgh
University, where he graduated MA LLB. He served in the Royal Scots and the
Indian Army during the later war years and left the service with the rank of
lieutenant.
He was called to the Bar in 1947 and in 1954 was elevated to the bench as
Sheriff-Substitute (as the office of Sheriff was then designated) at Airdrie.
He was transferred to Glasgow in the following year and served in the old
Sheriff Court in Ingram Street until his retirement in 1974.
In court, Sheriff Pirie was noted for his quiet courtesy. When it was possible
to dispose of a case summarily he would do so but when the occasion demanded he
could assemble and systematise detailed issues of fact and law with skill and
clarity. His human qualities enabled him to deal with family law cases with
particular sensitivity.
Sheriff Pirie was ready to give his time to the encouragement of young lawyers
and was an active honorary vice-president of the Glasgow Judicial Society.
After retiring he enjoyed writing and broadcasting and gave advice on legal
matters to newspaper readers.
In private life, Harry Pirie was quietly congenial. His prowess at golf was
considerable and his acute mind allowed him to excel at bridge. The same
quality was displayed in his expertise as setter of crossword puzzles for The
Herald, among other publications.
There are now a decreasing number who can remember the Sheriff Court of the
post-war decades. Legal life was, or seemed, less frenetic then than now. To
those who can remember these days, the passing of Harry Pirie will touch a
poignant chord.
Sheriff Pirie leaves four sons. His wife predeceased him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plans promise fairer shares for employees</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN CLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093791</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke's third Budget may not have improved his party's
election prospects to any great degree - although that remains to be seen - but
it did raise a cheer at the offices of ProShare, the organisation which
campaigns for wider share ownership.
ProShare had been upset when, in an ill-judged breakfast-time swoop back in
July, he changed the tax rules on company share options in a way which caught a
whole lot of little kittens as well as the boardroom fat cats who were his real
target. Even when later modified, it looked as though these employee option
schemes would be few and far between in the future.
Now all is forgiven. ProShare greeted the Budget with the comment that it was
``the best in many years for employee share ownership''.
The old Approved Discretionary Share Option Schemes, which gave tax concessions
on options up to a value of #100,000 or four times salary, are to be replaced
with new Company Share Option Plans.
These plans, which have to cover virtually all employees to get the tax
concession, will allow companies to grant options up to a value of #20,000.
These will be at an exercise price equal to the market price at the time of
granting and can be taken up without penalty after three years.
Provided the employee's options do not total more than #20,000, they will
escape the July ruling on discretionary schemes that income tax must be paid on
the difference between the option and market prices when it is exercised even
if the shares are not sold. The concession will also apply to options granted
under the old schemes provided the #20,000 total is not exceeded.
Opponents of the Chancellor's July clampdown had been complaining that levying
income tax in this way meant the employee would have to sell a large number of
the shares.
No chancellor pleases everyone with a concession so there have been a few
rumblings that the #20,000 limit is on the low side. It would be surprising,
however, if he was in any hurry to raise it as, quite apart from political
objections to giving cream to fat cats, the Inland Revenue is anxious to make
sure options do not become a way of giving employees part of their salary tax
free.
Mr Clarke also gave a welcome boost to Save As You Earn option schemes known as
ShareSave. Under these around a million employees have been given options to
buy shares at discounts of up to 20%. They must save with an approved
institution, often a building society, enough money each month for five years
so the total including tax-free interest will be sufficient to acquire these
shares at exercise time. The minimum monthly saving is #10, the maximum #250.
The restrictions on these schemes have been criticised partly because #10 a
month was too much for some employees but mainly because five years was
regarded as to long a commitment. Only about a third of those entitled were
taking them up. Mr Clarke is meeting both criticisms, reducing the minimum
period to three years and the minimum monthly payment to #5.
A pre-Budget poll of companies indicated they would welcome these changes and
continue to support employee share option schemes. The concession on ShareSave
is likely to bring in another 300,000 people.
The new share option plans, which are largely modelled on the old discretionary
ones, are expected to be popular. More than 6000 had been started before the
Chancellor jumped on them in July.
The delight about both ShareSave and Company Share Option Plans is that they
are risk free. The ShareSave employee does not have to exercise the option if
the price is not attractive when it matures. He or she can just view it as a
tax-efficient savings plan. Similarly, those granted options under company
plans will not only get them free but they will be under no compulsion to take
them up.
The Chancellor's other concession to encourage employee share ownership affects
the share-based profit sharing schemes which involve around a million people.
Under these companies can distribute shares worth up to 10% of an employee's
salary each year. The snag has been that income tax must be paid if they are
sold in less than five years. Mr Clarke is now reducing this to three.
No wonder an increasing number of employees are keeping anxious eyes on their
company's share price. Purely from this point of view, ShareSave participants
stand to gain the most as they can be issued options at a discount. The new
company option plan holders should also do well as the share price will have
three years in which to climb, even though the options will not be granted at a
discount.
Research in America suggests firms with such schemes tend to do better than
those without, although there is no proof this is because option holders put in
extra effort.
Provided the schemes keep within the rules, the shares acquired are free of
income tax. Capital gains tax may be paid when they are sold if total gains
exceed the annual limit of #6000. However, anyone seeing gains of more than
that can pass shares to their spouse to double the tax-free allowance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hot pursuit in foreign fields</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093792</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The intrepid Clive James learns to tango and play polo in Buenos Aires. Allan
Laing finds a travel master who is never afraid to step on toes
THEY'RE all at it. A few years ago Michael Palin went around the world in 80
days. Angus Deayton has just circumnavigated the globe in pursuit of that most
elusive of emotions, happiness. And Simon Dring has dusted off the old kaftan
and is currently on the road again, following the hippy trail to Katmandu.
Give a personality a passport and, next thing you know, he will promise you the
Earth. It may have been a hard day on the Planet for some but, for those on a
television company's expense account, life's a beach. I blame Alan Whicker
myself.
The current master, of course, is Clive James. This week, if it's Monday, it
must be Buenos Aires. City of gorgeous women and macho men, both genders
wonderfully unencumbered by political correctness. The last redoubt of the
anti-feminist. Clearly a killing ground for old Clive's witty observational
humour.
So what does the fearless roving reporter do when he secures an exclusive
interview with the President of Argentina? Ask him some deep and penetrating
questions about South American politics? His thoughts on his country's
continuing love-hate relationship with the United Kingdom? The Falklands
perhaps? Well, no, actually. Clive avoids the obvious and goes for the Big One.
He asks Carlos Menem how good he is at the tango. The old paso doble. The
sexiest dance in the world.
Other, more earnest, broadcasters might have taken the opportunity of
conducting The Major Interview. But not Clive. He's been there, seen it, done
it, read the book, bought the t-shirt, and clapped the dog. In his own sweet
way, he is a graduate of the Trivial Pursuits school of television journalism.
If Panorama had asked him and not Martin Bashir to grill the Princess of Wales
then things might have been different. ``There were three people in this
marriage. It only takes two to tango.'' Mind you, it's a task which the balding
Australian would probably have refused. Diana, it is said, is a personal
friend. So perhaps, having made this documentary about Buenos Aires, he
delivered a few wise words of advice to HRH before she em-barked on her tour of
Argen-tina - maybe even a few Latin American dance lessons.
``Buenos Aires is the most romantic city I've ever visited. I'd never been
there - except in my dreams when I would dance the tango with a smouldering
Latin beauty who soldered her body to mine and whispered to me in Spanish as we
moved,'' he says.
But, in his waking hours, Clive could not dance a step. Two left feet. So he
enrolled with an Argentinian dance teacher.
``She was working with unpromising material. The tango is a kind of mobile
embrace but it was about an hour before I got closer to my teacher than the
tips of her fingers. Although her English was almost perfect, she tended to
lapse into Spanish whenever I trod on more than one of her feet at the same
time,'' he confesses.
A woman's place in Argentina is a few dance steps behind her bloke. The men,
explains James, were ``macho to the point of mania''.
``The tango is the supreme example of this. The man can stand there, shooting
his cuffs and being macho. He only has to learn a few steps. The woman will do
the rest, performing wonderful arab-esques around him,'' he adds.
President Men-em can tango, that's for sure. ``He is a man of romance,''
discloses Clive. ``He also has a certain macho directness, a problem you are
stuck with in Buenos Aires.
``The President himself comes from the Sixties, which is my era. As to what he
is thinking - it could be to do with his hairstyle, his sideburns, his stack
heels, and his flared trousers - maybe he has a flared mind.''
But enough tango. Surely there is more to the land of the gaucho? Oh well,
there is the polo. Not the car, not the mint, but the game. Clive found his way
to a ranch on the Pampas where they gave him a pony called Steady Eddie. After
a couple of hours, James had mastered the walk and was making good progress on
the trot. He was ready for a couple of chukkahs.
``Polo is easy,'' he says. ``All you have to do is ride the horse and hit the
ball.'' Easier said than done.
Clive James in Buenos Aires is the first in a series of new travel films which
the globetrotting James has made for ITV. The next stop is Nashville where he
gets to make a country and western record with Mark Knopfler and Chet Atkins.
It's a song called ``Someone Else's Someone'' which he wrote himself.
``If you think that Nashville was a dream come true for me - yes, it was. But
I'd be crazy to think that my record was really any good. There were moments,
though, when I almost got carried away with the dream and thought I was really
something. It was a shock afterwards to hear it coming through all that
equipment,'' he says.
Humorous though his travelogues certainly are, Clive James believes that,
behind the laughs, there is often a serious message trying to get out. ``I
think I do make serious documentaries. The reputation of the programmes is now
such that I don't have to persuade people that, although I'm a joker, I have
serious things to say.
``The programmes have established that these things are possible. But I'm not
the first man in history who thought he was being serious and turned out to be
a very successful clown.''
n.Clive James in Beunos Aires is on ITV on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Honours are even in final</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093793</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETE Sampras and Yevgeny Kafelnikov won their singles matches yesterday to
leave the United States and Russia all square after the first day of the Davis
Cup final.
World No.1 Sampras overcame Andrei Chesnokov in a five-set thriller, then
Kafelnikov put the Russians back in the match by beating Jim Courier in
straight sets.
Wimbledon and US Open champion Sampras defeated world No.90 Chesnokov 3-6, 6-4,
6-3, 6-7, 6-4. After the match and with injured team-mate Andre Agassi among
the specators, Sampras threw his arms in the air to celebrate victory but then
collapsed with cramp and was helped off the court.
Despite Kafelnikov's 7-6, 7-5, 6-3 victory, he and Courier looked evenly
matched - trading powerful shots in a series of long rallies that delighted the
near-capacity crowd in Moscow's Olympic Stadium.
Kafelnikov took time to settle in the first set, double-faulting three times,
before convincingly winning a tie-break 7-1.
The second set went with serve to 6-5 when Courier dropped his service after
the Russian initially squandered two set points.
Courier trailed 3-0 in the third, broke back to 3-2 but eventually lost 6-3.
Kafelnikov and Andrei Olkhovsky face Todd Martin and Richey Reneberg in today's
doubles.
TENNIS
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Love for the unlovely</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093794</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDUARDO MENDOZA'S big novel of the eighties, City of Marvels, established him
as one of Spain's major writers and put Catalonia firmly on the literary map.
Through the maverick and uncompromising rise of its central character - Onofre
Bouvila - Mendoza charted the parallel ascension of Barcelona as it prepared to
become one of the major sources of Spanish wealth and power.
The historical intricacies and dramatic pantheon of characters in City of
Marvels is a vivid portrait of Spanish upheavals early this century. Catalonia
proved to be the perfect focus for an examination of those issues which led to
the first Spanish republic and civil war.
The Year of the Flood takes place some 30 years later, in the fifties, with
Franco firmly in power. It is shorter, quieter and less ambitious. References
to the political climate are kept to a minimum and there are none of the
historical digressions which gave City of Marvels its scope. But the characters
are more fully drawn and the narrative moves with greater pace and precision.
It is the story of a love affair between a nun and the Catalonian landowner to
whom she goes to for help. Sister Consuelo has a plan to build a hospital for
the elderly but all attempts at extracting money from church and state have
failed. So she turns to the disreputable Augusto Aixelà for financial
assistance.
There are two nice, unexpected twists to the way their relationship turns out.
This first occurs with the realisation that it is Sister Consuelo who is
persisting with their business meetings because of a romantic attachment, and
not the other way round. And the second concerns the way in which a sexual
encounter with Augusto precipitates the building of the hospital, precisely at
a moment when his deceit and corruption become apparent.
Sister Consuelo emerges not only as the heroine, but as the most deeply drawn
of all Mendoza's characters. The emotional truth of her predicament is
expressed in a neat but powerful scene which takes place just before the
seduction.
It makes for a good, sad story. The ending is as drab and ironic as real life,
making the constancy of Sister Consuelo's lifelong love for an unlovely man
seem gloomily truthful rather than affirmative.
However this is not enough to fulfil the inherent potential of Mendoza's
narrative. Augusto is a fully committed supporter of Franco; Sister Consuelo is
politically unaware; and the conclusion of the novel comes when we finally meet
the band it named lo coix. But the implications suggested by this trio of
state, church and resistance are not explored.
Even in City of Marvels there is an ironic detachment from the narrative and a
sense that difficult subjects should be cryptically referred to rather than
directly confronted. In The Year of the Flood the story withdraws even further
into the suggestive and the ambiguous.
At a time when Ken Loach's Spanish Civil War film, Land and Freedom, is being
fervently seized upon in Spain for its dramatically charged representation of
the past the critical subtleties of Mendoza's approach seem more impotent than
circumspect.
THE YEAR OF THE FLOOD
Eduardo Mendoza
Harvill, #9.99
FICTION
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nato backs peace force for Bosnia</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093795</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
NATO, signalling the start of its most ambitious military operation, gave the
go-ahead today for 2600 troops to take up position in Bosnia to prepare for the
deployment of a 60,000-strong Alliance-led peace force.
Nato sources said 200 could leave as early as tomorrow from the headquarters of
the ACE Rapid Reaction Corps in Rheindalen, Germany, where they are on 24-hour
standby.
A short Nato statement said the decision to ``deploy theatre-enabling forces
into Croatia and Bosnia-Herzogovina'' was made by Nato ambassadors meeting as
the North Atlantic Council (NAC), the Alliance's top policy-making forum.
Diplomats said the decision followed a formal request from Nato's Supreme
Allied Commander in Europe, General George Joulwan of the United States, who
will be the overall commander of the alliance's peace implementation force.
``I stress these are not combat troops, they are experts in logistics,'' said
one alliance source.
The bulk of the so-called ``enabling force'', which includes 500 Britons and
700 US servicemen, is expected to be in position early next week, a Nato
ambassador said.
``The idea is that they should be in place quickly and complete the enabling
architecture so that the rest . . . can surge in force, that's the concept. The
success of this operation depends on speed,'' another senior Nato diplomat said.
The advance unit will upgrade communications and transport facilities, take
over the running of ports to be used for troop arrivals, and check that roads
and airfields can withstand intensive use.
Alliance sources said the decision to authorise the dispatch of the advance
party was made after a few last-minute hitches on rules of engagement for the
force and the terms of reference for political advisers with the military were
cleared up.
They said the advance unit would have different rules of engagement to the bulk
of the force, which would be covered by a UN Security Council mandate.
Problems over the exact wording had prevented a decision yesterday but the
hitches were quickly resolved after consultations with national capitals.
``There is a can-do air around Nato at the moment,'' said one source.
The NAC is expected to give provisional agreement to the main peace force plan,
which has been meticulously drawn up by the Alliance's military authorities.
It will be endorsed next week at a historic first joint meeting of all 32
Alliance defence and foreign ministers.
The final peace conference in Paris on December 14 will open the way for the
adoption of a UN Security Council resolution handing over the Bosnia dossier to
Nato.
G-day, for Go-day, will then receive final approval and thousands of heavily
armed troops will pour into Bosnia through five entry points.
Alliance defence ministers have been told the rest of the force should arrive
within the first 30 days.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A foretaste of privatisation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093796</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I TRAVELLED back from Paris on Monday, November 27. There was a rail strike in
France, but the Eurostar managed to leave, although slightly late. All troubles
began on arrival in London, where our party discovered that the so-called Link
Train to the North of England and Scotland had departed two minutes before our
arrival.
No-one in authority appeared to deal with the 30 or so passengers (or
customers) who had through tickets and reserved seats on this train which,
presumably, left with no passengers on board!
We were all finally packed into taxis to take us to King's Cross, where we were
left to find any seat that was left on an already busy train. Cross Country
Services took no responsibility in satisfying our needs, as this was a Eurostar
problem.
This break in communication between Eurostar and Cross Country Services, which
runs the Link Train on Eurostar's behalf, has happened before and each seems to
put the blame upon the other. Meanwhile the passenger is caught between the
incompetency of these two businesses.
Is this a clue as to what will be an even more regular occurrence when the
total railway network is privatised?
I also wonder whether Eurostar would quite like to get rid of their northern
connection, and are doing their best to discourage travellers from using the
service.
Irene Rankin,
32 Moncrieff Avenue,
Lenzie.
</TEXT>
