<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093797</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SERIFA is the second in the series Whose Freedom is it Anyway (R4) in which
Vera Frankl looks at how life has changed for women in Eastern Europe. In the
spring of '92, Serifa Halilovic arrived in Zagreb with her nine-year-old
daughter, having left her husband and two older children in her much loved home
town of Sarajevo. Sarajevo, she said was a place with a special atmosphere, a
special smell, where people of different nationalities lived harmoniously, a
place where the tradition of tolerance was strong.
A bridge was blown up, return was impossible, and her lively little girl became
withdrawn. The English teacher who enjoyed her life, her city, who used to sit
in the balcony in the evenings with a glass of wine and enjoy the company of
her friends was now on her way to becoming someone else entirely. We believed
the world would stop the war, she explained, almost incredulous of her former
naivety.
Stranded and without a job, she watched as thousands streamed into Zagreb. She
set up a women's refuge camp, and with the asset of her excellent English, she
travelled overseas to raise funds. Her life was split into before and after
halves, but she did not know which half was the dream - and she carried this
sense of unreality to Brussels, aware that in another life she would have
enjoyed herself, gone shopping, but now inhabiting the ordinary was no longer
an option.
The hopes and experiences of America's black slaves in the light of Abraham
Lincoln's 1863 Emancipation Act was the topic of The Spirit of America (R4),
another illuminating series which will be looking at six historical turning
points of African-American history. This week the British writer Caryl Phillips
talked to Professor John Hope Franklin, who demolished the notion of a
benevolent, straightforward move to grant freedom and guarantee its future with
legislature and state-aided reconstruction.
In fact, the state did nothing to counteract the powerlessness of the people it
had only technically liberated. The euphoria of walking freely off the
plantation, of being allowed to marry, of being allowed to own land was heady,
but it soon became clear that the government actively co-operated in the former
slave owners' accumulation of power; the best next stage for the ex-slaves was
deemed that they become apprentices of their former owners.
The Act was essentially duplicitous, and nugatory in its very conception, for
the preliminary proclamation extended freedom only to Confederacy-held areas,
but not on the Union patch. In other words, freedom was allowed where freedom
was impossible. The Klan was not challenged by the small Union army, and the
handy racist belief that the negro was a helpless child in need of protection,
became a self-fulfilling prophecy as the recently freed were left utterly
exposed to barbarism. ``De facto slavery?'' questioned Phillips. ``That's
pretty strong,'' answered the meticulous expert on oppression, ``but if you
pushed me . . . Yes.''
The corrupt and murderous regime of General Abacha, the Nigerian despot at
whose hands Ken Saro-Wiwa and his eight co-defendants were recently hanged, has
turned the country into a ``kleptocracy of contractors'' where bribery
lubricates every transation. In From Our Own Correspondent (R4) the most
complex and inchoate situations are regularly rendered, if not completely
comprehensible, at least immediate and compelling. John Egan's report from a
terrified Ogoni village bore this out, as did Bridget Kendall's account from
fundamentalist downtown Montana, where the new conspiracy theory gaining wide
appeal seems to be that President Clinton, gays (which equals felons -
homosexuality being illegal) and feminists are plotting to disarm America and
turn it over to the new bogeyman, the United Nations. Well, it is always
disheartening to know that instead of those familiar Reds, there's a foreign,
polyglot and ineffectual body under the bed . . .
</TEXT>
