<HEADLINE>Leon Zitrone</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093798</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRENCH television pioneer Leon Zitrone, a star since the 1960s, died in a Paris
hospital after a brain haemorrhage on the night of his 81st birthday on
Saturday.
Zitrone won the hearts of the nation with sensational commentaries at major
public ceremonies, including the annual Bastille Day parade, the funeral of
President Charles de Gaulle, and the marriage of Prince Charles.
But he also produced gripping commentaries of sports events such as the Tour de
France cycling race, horse racing, and figure skating.
``Leon Zitrone was an extraordinary professional, dear to the hearts of the
French people,'' President Jacques Chirac said. ``Present at all the great
moments of television, his erudition, his rigour, his enthusiasm were
appreciated by all.''
</TEXT>
