<HEADLINE>Gavin Bell discovers Dundee's new award-winning attractions A breath of fresh air</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gavin Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093799</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE jute and the jam may be long gone, but Dundee now has another claim to fame
- the best museums in Scotland. For the second year in succession, the city has
scooped the Scottish Museum of the Year Award sponsored by the Post Office.
Following the 1994 success of Discovery Point, part of the Dundee Heritage
Trust, the #2000 prize went this year to Barrack Street Museum of Natural
History for a display entitled ``Head for the Hills''.
The exhibition focuses on the wildlife of the Scottish Highlands, with
interactive computers explaining the life cycles, of plants, animals and
insects, and audio systems reproducing bird calls.
Originally opened in 1993, the display was destroyed by fire a few months later
and had to be reconstructed at a cost of #50,000. Since reopening last year, it
has attracted 45,000 visitors. The prize money will be spent on another
interactive exhibit on aquatic wildlife.
The award was welcomed by Dundee district councillor Helen Wright, representing
the provost, who said: ``It is a well-deserved tribute to a wonderful project.
When you go in the door it's like a breath of fresh air, it's like stepping
into the country in the middle of the city.''
Announcing the award at Scone Palace, Colin Thompson, the chairman of the
judges, expressed satisfaction at a new innovative approach to museums and
galleries in Scotland, often aimed at younger visitors.
``A significant number of the entries this year were for presentations that
were either designed expressly for children or that kept them firmly in mind,''
he said. ``This signals, thank goodness, the end of the take it or leave it era
of museums when the glass case display was the be all and end all.''
Kenneth Graham, the chairman of the Scottish Post Office Board, welcomed the
increasing popularity of museums and galleries, which he said provided an
opportunity to review the past, better understand the present, and reflect on
the future. He noted that 8.5 million people visited about 300 such
institutions in Scotland last year, which was considerably more than had
attended football or rugby matches.
Sandy Gall, the broadcaster and author who presented the award, provided an
interesting perspective on the ceremony with an anecdote about a museum in
Kabul.
He was making the point that residents of Scotland are fortunate in not being
exposed to daily danger, or having their museums pillaged, as is the case in
other countries. The museum in the Afghan capital was a case in point - when he
visited it last summer he found it an absolute shambles. It had been fought
over and systematically looted of its treasures such as sixth-century ivory
carvings and rare Buddhas.
His audience was left with a greater appreciation of the pleasures of browsing
around a natural history museum without being exposed to artillery fire.
Two other entries were highly commended - the restoration of Abbot House, the
oldest house in Dunfermline, and a new community museum in part of the old fish
market in Newhaven.
The National Museum of Scotland won the publications award for Treasure
Islands, inspired by the work of Robert Louis Stevenson, and the Whithorn
Discovery Centre won the educational award for an archaeological exhibit in the
form of a three-dimensional jigsaw.
Another award went to a scarecrow called Bogle. Created by the Scottish
Agricultural Museum at Ingliston, it comes to life to provide a 12-minute
audio-visual programme for children evoking old ways of life in the country.
</TEXT>
