<HEADLINE>Michael Forsyth deserves gratitude</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093801</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR correspondent William C Wolfe (November 21) appears to be suffering from
that strange affliction which affects SNP supporters, the perpetuating of myths
about Scotland's financial situation within the Union.
He asserts: ``Scottish taxpayers have subsidised other parts of the UK for
generations; ie, taxation spent in Scotland has been far short of a fair share
of what has been raised in Scotland. This has been shown to be the case time
and again since the 1940s''. Eh, no.
The facts are that Scotland contributes around 8% of total taxation revenue
going into the Exchequer, and receives between 10% and 11% of total UK
Government expenditure through the Barnett formula which Michael Forsyth
managed to preserve in the face of Treasury dogma during the latest round of
departmental spending cuts.
Therefore it is quite clear that Scotland receives more than her fair share,
and for that we should be grateful to the Scottish Secretary. And what
``proof'' has there been since the 1940s anyway? Answer - none whatsoever.
Briefly, on a related point, the SNP were reported delighted during the week
when John Major stated that Scotland could survive on her own with five million
people and a steadily improving economy. Alex Salmond took this as proof that
they had finally won the argument, but he was sadly wrong again.
Of course Scotland could survive on her own, a fact which has never been in
doubt. The message that we have given to the electorate for years is that the
Scottish economy would never manage to survive the actual process of
independence, that the effect and the costs would be totally destructive.
It is simply not worth putting the Scottish people through that when we can
stay in a Union which has served us well for just short of three centuries.
Why destroy everything by taking a step into the dark? Why trust our future to
people who, as Mr Wolfe and the SNP's pathetic ``Budget'' showed recently, have
not the faintest idea of how to do a few basic sums and face basic economic
reality, never mind run a country?
Alistair J Craig,
10 Vrackie Place,
Kilmarnock.
</TEXT>
