<DOCNO>GH951202-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No half measures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK McLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093802</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT comes as a surprise to be reminded that of that triumvirate of theatrical
knights who dominated the British theatre for almost half a century, Olivier,
Gielgud and Richardson, the first to be knighted was Ralph Richardson, possibly
the least remembered at the moment of the trio.
He got his knighthood in the 1947 New Year Honours, a deeply jealous Olivier
had to wait six months for the Birthday Honours for his, while Gielgud was out
in the cold until the Coronation list in 1953.
Gielgud is still with us, the theatrical equivalent of the Queen Mother, a
much-loved institution in his own right. As for Olivier, his reputation is
probably at its nadir, and it is currently modish to sneer at his mannerisms
and tricks in performance. But nobody seems to bother about Richardson, who, in
his prime, managed to be what neither of the others succeeded in becoming - a
genuine star in both the cinema and the theatre.
He was a strange man, prone to violent outbursts, and patently haunted by
demons, who disliked directors, and was ruthless with underlings who dared
upstage him. He loved motor bikes, drank gin like water, kept ferrets and had a
Spanish-speaking parrot called Jose, which he treated like a human being.
Audiences loved him, and his colleagues, in spite of all the difficulties of
coping with such an unpredictable man, found him inspiring. John Miller has
turned to many of them in his attempt to analyse what made a Richardson
performance and the result is a fascinating, detailed picture of the actor at
work. Where this admirable, highly readable books falls down is in its portrait
of the private man. We learn very little about Richardson as a husband - he was
married twice, and had a son, Charles, by his second wife, Meriel Forbes.
Charles appears a couple of times and then completely disappears from his
father's life, or so it seems.
The book records Richardson's long pre-war career and the origins of his
lifelong theatrical partnership and friendship with Gielgud. He was one of the
truly great Falstaffs, a wonderful Peer Gynt, a superb Sir Peter Teazle, an
immaculate performer of the plays of J B Priestley, while in the cinema he was
mesmerising in films like The Fallen Idol, The Sound Barrier and The Heiress.
Gielgud, who contributes an admiring preface, recalls how, when he was
directing School for Scandal, Richardson as Sir Peter, worried about how to
make his first entrance, got stuck during rehearsals. ``Should I have a
newspaper in my hand? A walking-stick? Or be taking snuff, perhaps?,'' he would
ask. At last, one morning he walked down to the footlights and announced -
``You know, Johnny, I prayed to God last night to tell me how to come on in
this opening scene, and this morning God answered `Do what it says in the text,
just come on'. ''
WILLIAM RUSSELL
WHISKY
WHAT is now known as ``the licensed trade'' used not to be: it was called, when
I was in it many years back, ``the spirit trade''. And if you see sometimes
some old pub which has a sign on its windows stating ``Wine and Spirits'' you
might well wonder. Back in the nineteenth century the temperance people tried
to close all pubs and taverns, and anywhere which purveyed liquor at all. They
switched eventually to giving licences to beer shops and closing all inns which
sold spirits across a counter. It never worked, and pubs opened everywhere for
the sale of spirits.
Beer is a thin drink, and with licensing laws as draconian as they were it was
small wonder that small beer became relegated to small chasers with large gills
and half gills of spirits. In Scotland, whisky had played a part for centuries
with illicit distilling ending with a genuine retail industry. And of all the
spirits, the one which ended as the biggest seller of them all was . . . the
illicit one. Whisky.
Whisky is now so large and immovable an industry that no other spirit comes
close to it in fame and volume of traffic, and needless to say, the bulk of the
pages of the late Gordon Brown's book on spirits is taken up with Scotch. Brown
died just last year, after a distinguished career as journalistic toper, or
even the other way round. (He wrote a regular column on the old booze for the
Guardian). His book on the geography of the Whisky Trails was a splendid text
for anybody interested in whisky.
And now there is this book on Classic Spirits of the World. Well there aren't
any, in my view, except whisky. I might allow Irish whisk(e)y, but that's about
it. All the others are low young things, with bare feet and ragged dresses,
still too young to put their hair up. What is more they admit it and so does
Gordon Brown.
Scotch has to state its age, and it is the youngest whisky which goes into the
marriage, be they malts, single or vatted, or blends, which is stated on the
label on the bottle. Thus you can find a whisky which describes itself as
five-year-old but which can, and often does, have a 25-year-old and older malt
in it. And every Scotch, even the humblest, has to be at least three years old.
Scotch is unique in that and paying the price for its age and quality for it is
by no means cheap to store all these casks in bond for all these years. It is
not thus with other spirits.
And what a lot of them there are. Brown goes through them. Brandies and
cognacs, gins and genevers. Vodkas and schnappses. Aqua vitae comes out in many
a guise. Sometimes it is next door to poteen or even worse rotgut. The French
marc and the Italian grappa both taste like old raincoats which have been
pissed on for years by elderly wet Airedales. Until recently both drinks were
almost entirely illicit anyway and mightily adulterated by industrial alcohols
when they came to the outlets.
Ironically the now largely prohibitionist Arabs invented spirits and the word
``alcohol'' or alkhul derives from Arabic. This book is not only informative in
every spirit and liqueur you have ever heard of, the pageantry of the
photographs makes it worth buying just as a damned art object. So buy it.
From Canongate we find yet another addition to the genre, The Malt Whisky File.
In much the same format as Wallace Milroy's classic slip-in-the-pocket books it
is equally informative, certainly less subjective, but perhaps not as
entertaining in idiosyncrasy. But no connoisseur of whisky should be without
this well-produced little hardback either for there are some background details
of the distilleries themselves which Milroy (and indeed the other well-known
whisky chronicler Michael Jackson) often left out due to their rather insider
assumption that everybody knows that stuff anyway.
I have often thought that a nice wee play or even novel could be written about
whisky reps. The legendary whisky drummers such as Dougie Renfrew or George
Thompson or Andy . . . I'd better leave his name out for he still supplies me
with some out-of-the way malts. The legendary whisky reps used to drop into
pubs I have known.
``Well Michael, and how is Anna this weather your eldest must just be finishing
at the yooni the wee lassie got into Fernhill did she have a dram yersel wan
fur Jack here and his pal ah'll be getting away . . . '' Then the stop at the
door. ``Ah'll be forgettin' mah name next. Wid ye want an order next week?''.
They always got an order the auld fellows. Like something out of Neil Munro's
Erchie stories, the old whisky reps spread themselves throughout Scotland,
selling their wares with a panache and an impertinence which gladdened the
heart. Today the whisky reps are leggy girls with clipboards who don't sell
anything like as much as the old lags of the whisky circuit.
I looked forward to Malcolm Greenwood's A Nip Around the World; thought it
would be about the whisky lads in their dapper suits and 40 years worth of
selling our most famous product. Well, Greenwood's book isn't. Malcolm is
indeed a whisky salesman but at international level. Somebody told him that his
reminiscences were worth a book. I heard Malcolm on radio last week and he
sounded witty and amusing. Sadly his book of tales of his trade did not meet
that. What makes a damned good anecdote doesn't work, sometimes, in print.
We have a last book on uisge-beatah: Make Your Own Scotch Whisky. Rowland Emmet
did the illustrations and they are a bit thin. Anyway I am not sure this book
is legal. Making your own Scotch most certainly isn't. On the other hand, it
tells you how to make Scotch and is perhaps one of the most informative books
on the water of life (you can call it research when the excisemen catch up with
you), and no imbiber should be without this, just for daftness. Dafter yet: I
was allowed to see an illicit whisky, just for photographic purposes. You
believe that, you'll believe anything. Cheers.
JACK McLEAN
CLASSIC SPIRITS OF THE WORLD: Gordon Brown, Prion, #20.
THE MALT WHISKY FILE: Lamond and Tucek, Canongate, #9.99.
A NIP AROUND THE WORLD: Malcolm Greenwood, Argyll, #7.99.
MAKE YOUR OWN SCOTCH WHISKY: Adam Bergius, Argyll, #7.99
</TEXT>
</DOC>
