<HEADLINE>A cut above the rest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FERGUS WYLLIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093803</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE hills are alive with the sound of the British. The up-market resort of
Courchevel 1850 in the biggest ski area in the world, France's Three Valleys,
has developed a distinct English ring, with not a little twang of Scottish.
Courchevel 1850, and its sister resorts of 1650 and 1550, have always been
popular with Brits inclined towards inclines but now it seems our native tongue
has taken over and is spoken by staff in every bar, restaurant, and shop. By
the way, the numbers refer to the height in metres although it could just as
easily be the price of a meal. Not only the air gets rarer as the altitude
increases.
Obviously, the main attraction is the magnificent skiing but another
contributing factor is the top-class instruction offered by the Scots-run Ski
Masterclass. Kenny Dickson and his wife, Sue, have gathered together a highly
qualified group of British instructors who received nothing but praise from
every pupil I spoke to.
The Dicksons go back to Aviemore every summer where they used to teach skiing
and still have a home. Because of this link, there always seems to be someone
from the Spey valley in Courchevel, either on holiday or working as an
instructor.
Courchevel 1850 is a pleasant mix of modern hotel blocks, traditional mountain
architecture, and sumptuous chalets. It is the nicest of the three Courchevels
and head and shoulders above other Trois Vallee resorts like the bleak Val
Thorens and Les Menuires.
I stayed with Ski Activity in the Ski Lodge in the town centre, three minutes
walk from the slopes and a short stagger from bars and restaurants. Actually,
the nearest bar was only a short fall down the stairs as the lodge had it own
hostelry on the ground floor, Tee-Jays, which had the lowest prices in the
resort.
The Ski Lodge offers basic but comfortable accomodation on a chalet basis.
Activity's main base in the resort is Le Tournier, a chalet hotel close to the
slopes which has a warm, friendly dining room and excellent food and wine.
It is always a good omen when a holiday starts with something going wrong but
turning out to a blessing in disguise. Gils, the geographically challenged
driver of the bus which took us from Geneva to Courchevel, was driving so fast
over a sleeping policeman that the bus's engine hit the concrete, cracking the
sump, and liberating all the oil. Disaster you might think. Not at all. We all
trotted off to a nearby supermarket for beer and nibbles, and spent an
enjoyable hour getting to know our fellow skiers in the warm sunshine. We were
almost disappointed when the replacement bus arrived.
That set the tone for the first three days of our holiday. The sun blazed down
during the day on Les Trois Valles and it snowed at night.
Courchevel valley has 26 green, 27 blue, 36 red, and 11 black runs, and
combined with the other two valleys - Meribel and Beauville - the ski area is
immense. There are almost too many runs to choose from. The Courchevel valley
would be more than enough to satisfy me for one week but because the other two
valleys are just over the hill you feel obliged to ski over and try them out.
On the fourth day of our stay, the weather closed in with rain and cloud
creating poor visibility. It did not seem that bad compared to Scottish skiing
conditions but it prompted the cancellation of an extreme skiing competition in
Courchevel's Grand Couloir, which had attracted skiing notables such as
American Glen Plake, he of the 2ft orange Mohican haircut and star of many ski
videos.
It seemed strange that the world's toughest skiers should be put off by a wee
bit of mist. Perhaps it would have played havoc with Mr Plake's famous tresses.
In a way, that summed up Courchevel. A cut above the rest.
n Fergus Wyllie travelled with Ski Activity, of 23 Blair Street, Edinburgh.
Prices for one week on chalet basis at the Ski Lodge range from #289 to #539
and at Le Tournier from #349 to #609.
</TEXT>
