<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Energy behind the birth of hydro power</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Buie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093804</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Elizabeth Buie looks back over 60 years of a clean and renewable technology
SIXTY years ago, the fishermen, landowners, and councillors were flatly opposed
to Britain's first major hydro-electric power scheme in Galloway.
It would damage the landscape, the fisheries, and mining interests, they said.
But the partners in the Power Traction Finance Company were determined to
succeed in their venture - and they did. In fact, this consortium acted as a
forerunner to the business groupings that are now being formed to develop
projects through the Government's private finance initiative.
In only one of many parallels with similar developments today, this pioneering
company had to appoint a consultant pisciculturist (a specialist in fish
culture) to protect fishing interests. It also had to make compensatory
payments to local landowners, and it had to set up a scenery committee.
Nowadays, hydro power is recognised as probably the cheapest form of energy to
operate, and the least polluting. But if it is to have a future it will be in
the form of small to medium-size generation plants - at least in the developed
world.
Back in 1935, there was just as much opposition to a major new power
development as there would be today.
The Galloway Hydro-Electric Scheme originally comprised five power stations,
together with their associated dams, tunnels, and pipelines. At the time of its
construction, it was the first integrated scheme in Britain designed for the
purposes of public electricity supply. For although hydro-electric generation
existed in the North of Scotland at the time the Galloway scheme was
commissioned, it was aimed specifically at providing electricity for particular
processes, such as the aluminium plant at Foyers.
Plans for the scheme were developed in the 1920s - electricity as a commodity
had grown significantly in popularity in the years following the First World
War.
The proposal to develop Galloway's hydro resources was made in 1923 by three
Kirkcudbrightshire residents - Major Wellwood Maxwell, Captain Scott Elliot,
and Colonel William McLellan, an engineer and partner in the firm Merz and
McLellan.
But their grand plan remained in the back of a drawer until the publication of
the Electricity Supply Act in 1926. The Act created the Central Electricity
Board which was to be responsible for the development of an electricity network
for Britain. Its role was to plan for the creation of a national grid and it
had powers to ``select'' which generating stations would be linked into it. By
the late 1920s it had been decided that the first grid scheme in Scotland would
include a link between Carlisle and Kilmarnock - the green light for power
generated in Galloway to be transmitted into the West of Scotland's population
centres.
Merz and McLellan, in conjunction with civil engineers Sir Alexander Gibb and
Partners, approached the Power Traction Finance Co Ltd to ask for their backing
for a Bill to promote the scheme.
The Power Traction Finance Co, a consortium of engineering companies, plant
manufacturers, and an insurance company - namely Sir William Arrol, Messrs John
Brown, Cammel Laird, English Electric, and the Prudential Insurance Co -
combined engineering expertise with financial power. Its members also had a
successful track record in developing hydro-electricity.
The next stage was to win the hearts and minds of potential objectors to the
scheme.
The provision of a cheap electricity supply to Ayr Town Council in exchange for
their rights to the development of hydro power on Loch Doon, and a promise to
Kirkcudbright County Council to give first priority to the recruitment of local
unemployed during the construction phase secured two important early victories.
But there were objections from local landowners over the impact of the scheme
on the landscape and heritage of the area, and from fisheries boards regarding
the amount of compensation water allocated for the preservation of fisheries.
Then the Mining Association of Great Britain lodged objections on the grounds
that the scheme would have a detrimental effect on the coal industry.
Eventually, the fisheries boards withdrew their protests following the
appointment of a consultant pisciculturist. Landowners accepted significant
financial deals. The mining fraternity's arguments were countered by evidence
that other coal-producing nations had developed hydro-electricity with no
negative effects on mining.
In 1931, the CEB granted all five power stations in the Galloway scheme -
Kendoon, Carsfad, Earlstoun, Glenlee, and Tongland - ``selected'' status. It
was the signal for construction to begin.
The project cost almost #3m to complete and at the height of construction some
2000 men were employed, representing a major boost during the depressed 1930s.
Loch Doon Castle, the finest example of a Norman fortress in Scotland, was
moved, stone by stone, from its original location on an islet to a new site at
the side of the loch.
And to preserve the Doon as a prime salmon water, fish ladders and passes were
constructed to allow salmon to return from the sea to their spawning grounds.
In 1935, Glenlee and Tongland power stations first supplied electricity to the
grid. It cost 0.109d per unit.
Today, on the sixtieth anniversary of the scheme, the original turbines still
generate electricity for the Scottish grid. In fact, the stations' operator
ScottishPower is developing a new control system which will be the first of its
kind in the UK, enabling six power stations (Drumjohn was later added to the
original five) to be controlled out of hours by a computer.
The scheme produces 8% of ScottishPower's output and is its cheapest.
Jack Kelly, manager (Hydros) with ScottishPower, said: ``It is part of our
industrial heritage. It has been there for 60 years and there is no reason why
it should not be there for another 60 years provided we invest in the scheme.''
MOST environmentalists today would not argue with him that hydro power has a
future - provided that any new schemes are small enough in scale not to have
too great an impact on remote areas, habitats, and people's livelihoods.
Some suggest that flow levels have not always been set at the right levels, and
some power generators, such as Hydro-Electric are collaborating in research in
this area. Some fishermen are not convinced that fish ladders eliminate the
problems faced by salmon returning upriver.
But hydro is indisputably one of the cleanest technologies as well as being
renewable. Unlike nuclear and coal-powered generator stations, it has no impact
on global warming.
Nevertheless, the landscape lobby is unlikely ever to permit the construction
of another scheme in Scotland the size of the Galloway scheme. The future for
hydro is likely to be lots of little stations, maybe as small as 2MW to 4MW.
</TEXT>
