<DOCID>GH951202-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rate cut could come in New Year Purchasing managers' index shows a decline for the first time since November 1992</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093805</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CLEAR signal yesterday that manufacturing industry is continuing to weaken
and that price pressures do not pose an inflationary threat added to already
feverish market speculation that the Chancellor would soon slice another half
point off base rates.
It is thought this could even come after his next monthly monetary meeting with
the Governor of the Bank of England on December 13.
The Chancellor, though, with an eye on the pound's vulnerability, may prefer to
leave well alone and it is doubtful if the Governor would support a reduction
at this time, even if the Bank is no longer calling for an increase.
The fresh round of cuts in mortgage rates - others were following suit
yesterday - together with the tax reductions anounced in the Budget could have
taken some of the pressure off the Chancellor, but some market operators
believe that his Budget growth projections are too optimistic without a fillip
from lower rates.
Many economists, including the CBI's who now regard a !s-point reduction as
``sustainable'', are looking for a cut, though a number think not until the New
Year, with Goldman Sachs going for a one-point reduction by mid-1996.
Their case was strengthened with the release of the Purchasing Managers' Index
from the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply which showed a fall in
the index to 49.6 in November from October's 50.5.
Any number below 50 denotes a contraction and this is first time this has
happened since November 1992.
The index has shown a steady downward trend since peaking at 61.6 in mid-1994.
At the same time, the number of companies reporting lower prices exceeded the
number reporting increases for the first time in two years.
The survey echoes the message from other surveys and official data in recent
months that the main risk to growth in the near-term is a period of severe
destocking.
Securities House James Capel's Adam Cole says that while the data clearly
support the case for a near-term reduction in base rates, further evidence that
the Chancellor's growth forecasts are too optimistic is required before rates
come down. This points to early next year as the most likely time for a rate
reduction.
Also released yesterday were figures from the Bank of England showing that net
consumer credit lending rose to #872m in October compared with #640n in
September. This was considerably above market expectations which had centred on
a figure approaching #600m and a large increase over the #430m notched up in
October last year.
Lending by credit card firms rose to #249m from September's #190m. The consumer
credit figures are somewhat at odds with retail spending, with High Street
sales staying flat. Month-on-month sales actually fell 0.1% in October.
However, one month's figures in isolation have to be treated with caution and
while they could be taken to indicate an improvement in consumer confidence,
the credit data have consistently outperformed actual spending in 1995.
One analyst suggested the October rise could be due to either consumer
desperation or optimism, whether people are falling back on credit to maintain
their standards of living or whether they are being adventurous. Certainly, it
in no way dampened market enthusiasm on interest rates, though the Governor of
the Bank of England may look askance.
Mortgage lending data from the Bank shows that the number of loans approved
appears to have firmed in recent months. However, the data also shows that
across the mortgage market as a whole - covering banks, building societies and
other specialist lenders - there were only modest amounts of lending in October.
Gross mortgage lending in October totalled #4650m, almost the same as in
September, but lower than the #4750m in October 1994. Net lending totalled
#925m, a worsening since #1190m, and also lower than the #1540m in October last
year.
However, both the number and value of loan approvals (promises to lend) were
more positive. The value of approvals totalled #4800m compared with #4400m in
September and #4600m in October last year. The number of loan approvals was
78,000 against 73,000 in September and 80,000 a year ago.
Adrian Coles, director-general of the Council of Mortgage Lenders, commented,
``The housing market is not yet out of the woods of recession, but there are
some positive signs. While lenders are cautious of welcoming what could be
another `false dawn', the approvals figures seem to indicate that the housing
market's low point occurred in the summer and that we are now in a period of
fragile equilibrium.''
He added, ``Given that by the middle of next year households will be feeling
the impact not only of the recent mortgage rate reductions but also of the
Budget tax cuts, the hope that confidence can improve seems stronger now than
at any time in the last 12 months.''
Goldman Sachs' economist takes the view that although the mortgage rate cuts
announced by lenders this week will further help, with activity in the rest of
the economy faltering, the housing market is likely to remain weak for a
considerable time to come.
</TEXT>
