<DOCNO>GH951202-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Church role in Ireland is to be envied</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093806</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN his weekly articles, John Macleod has been consistent on two counts: in the
vilification of Roman Catholicism and in his ignorance of that same faith.
His article about the vote on the Divorce Bill in Ireland (November 28) is a
hotch-potch of sarcasm, malevolence, ignorance, and bigotry which, truly, would
not be out of place in a football fanzine.
Eamon de Valera, the Dail, the Irish people (how dare they have a 90% Catholic
population?), Ireland itself (poor and boggy), the Pope, the Roman Catholic
Church, an un-named bishop, and Fr Brendan Smyth all come in for lashings of
abuse from the ``Wee Free'' caped crusader.
It is true that, in the moral dilemmas of recent times such as abortion,
divorce, and contraception, the Catholic Church has maintained a firm,
traditional line whereas Reformed Churches have adopted a more pragmatic
approach.
In both cases, however, memberships are still dropping and it's now time that
we Christians, of all denominations, realise that we have more in common with
each other than that which divides us. We must work and pray together to ensure
that there will be a future of Christianity in the new millennium.
In our increasingly secular society, there are no easy solutions but surely we
should expect something more constructive from a Christian journalist in one of
our ``quality'' newspapers.
The irony of it all is that we in Scotland will never have the chance to
challenge the respective moralities of Church versus State in a referendum
since the Church of Scotland has ceased to be a part of the everyday lives of
most Scots.
The fact that the Catholic Church is still such an integral part of the lives
of many Irish people is to be envied rather than mocked. Wouldn't we Scottish
Christians (of all denominations) be happy to see such vibrant religious and
moral debate in our own country?
John Macleod's article has a coldness about it. He is fond of quoting Holy
Scripture so perhaps he has noticed that Jesus said to his disciples: ``A new
commandment I give to you: to love one another as I have loved you''.
Hugh Phillips,
52 Watson Street,
High Blantyre.
</TEXT>
