<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Britons jailed over cult murder plot</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093807</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Portland
TWO former British disciples of an Indian love cult were jailed for five years
each by a court in Portland Oregon today for conspiring to kill a US federal
prosecutor.
Sally Anne Croft and Susan Hagan were found guilty last July of plotting, with
others, to murder Oregon state attorney Charles Turner in 1985. Sentence had
been deferred until today.
Mr Turner was never assaulted or harmed in any way.
Miss Croft, 45, a former chartered accountant with City auditors Ernst &amp; Young,
and Mrs Hagan, 48, an aromatherapist who devotes much of her life to treating
Aids patients, quit the Bhagwan cult in 1985 in disillusionment.
At the time, the two women were among the top officials at the Oregon commune
founded by followers of the late Indian guru Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh, advocate
of free love and lavish spending.
They had fought a lengthy battle against extradition before being deported to
the US earlier this year.
State attorney Turner, who has since retired, led a grand jury investigation
that resulted in charges of widespread immigration fraud at the cult's vast
commune in central Oregon.
Witnesses said Miss Croft, who was the cult's chief financial officer, provided
funding for gun-buying trips associated with the murder plot, which was never
carried out.
Mrs Hagan was also implicated as a top official in the cult hierarchy.
US District Judge Malcolm Clark said his verdict attempted to balance the
community work of the two women since they fled the United States after the
break-up of the guru's 4000-member cult against the seriousness of their crime.
Lawyers for both women said they would appeal against the sentences although
both had faced possible life terms.
The judge ordered the women to report to federal prison in Washington state on
January 12. They will be eligible for parole after 20 months.
The women were linked to the plot to kill Turner by testimony from five former
commune members, who made deals with the government for their testimony and had
admitted lying in the past.
Defence lawyers tried to discredit the former Rajneesh followers. However, they
called only one witness, another former follower who contradicted a small part
of the prosecutors' case.
Three former commune leaders also have been charged in the plot against Turner,
but remain fugitives.
The Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh became notorious in the early Eighties for his 93
Rolls Royces, #2m watch, and teachings on ``cosmic orgasms''.
He was eventually deported from the United States after pleading guilty to
arranging sham marriages for his followers for immigration purposes.
He died in his native India in 1990, leaving his Oregon community shattered and
many of its members facing legal charges.
State investigators say the sect was responsible, among other things, for the
biggest illegal wire-tapping operation in US history, an arson attack on a
county planning office, an attempt to manipulate local election results, and
the poisoning of a restaurant salad bar that led to an outbreak of
salmonella.-Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Soldier `admitted killing guide'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093808</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Larnaca
A BRITISH soldier accused of killing a Danish tour-guide in Cyprus confessed to
a police officer within hours of his arrest that he bludgeoned her to death
with a spade, a Cyprus court was told.
Chief Inspector Charalambos Argyrou quoted Alan Ford, 27, as saying: ``I killed
the girl. I hit her twice with a spade on the head.''
Argyrou told the court in Larnaca that he had questioned Ford over the
disappearance of 23-year-old Louise Jensen.
Ford and two other British soldiers charged with Jensen's abduction,
manslaughter, and conspiracy to rape have all pleaded not guilty.
The statement took lawyers for both the prosecution and defence by surprise and
the bench ruled it should be ignored.
Ford, face flushed and obviously annoyed, walked over to Argyrou, who was
sitting in the witness box after the judge left the courtroom, and demanded to
know why he had not said anything sooner. Argyrou ignored him.
``He's talking bullshit,'' Ford was overheard saying to his co-defendants Jeff
Pernell, 23, and Justin Fowler, 27.
The court went on to discuss whether an eight-page statement allegedly made by
Ford one day after he was detained was admissible evidence.
The defence says it was not voluntary, but given after police told Ford his two
co-defendants had already incriminated him in their own statements.
Earlier this week the court threw out defence objections to the admissibility
of testimony that Pernell had blamed Ford for what happened to Jensen when he
told a policeman ``Alan did it.''
The three soldiers, stationed at the British base of Dhekelia, are accused of
bundling Jensen into their mini-Moke after knocking her off her boyfriend's
motorcycle near Ayia Napa holiday resort 14 months ago. Her battered body was
found in a shallow roadside grave two days later.
The hearing continues.
q Another court in Larnaca today fined a British soldier #930 for negligent
driving in an accident in which two Pakistani students died earlier this year.
Lance Corporal Gareth Austin, 24, of the Royal Greenjackets, was banned from
driving for two years.-Reuter
</TEXT>
