<HEADLINE>A special kind of magic.  Clinton gives new impetus to push for peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093812</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONNOISSEURS of irony will, as much as optimists, enjoy contemplating President
Clinton's remarkable success in the British Isles. The ironists' pleasure
derives from the way in which Mr Clinton, who promised a near return to
isolationism to win the presidency, has been forced by domestic failure to the
foreign fields which seemed so unappealing when tilled by Mr Bush. Mr Clinton
has, so far, been defeated by domestic problems but has enjoyed a run of
foreign-policy successes whose significance is considerable - the Middle East,
Bosnia, and now, possibly, Ireland. The optimists may not even accept the
qualification: and it is undeniably true that Mr Clinton has neither put a foot
nor a word wrong all week. He has achieved a near miracle, saying what both
Irish traditions wanted to hear. It is possible that he was set up and cleverly
exploited by the Irish-American (shorthand for nationalist) lobby but that
hardly matters when he has managed to cross the traditional Irish divide.
(Perhaps someone has pointed out to him that there are far more Protestant
Irishmen in the US electorate than there are Catholic, though it is the latter
who are organised.)
The President was always on to a good thing. A phenomenon of our times is the
way in which major political figures often carry more clout abroad than at home
- Mrs Thatcher and Mr Gorbachev are quick examples which prove the point; but
Mr Clinton has shown himself to be in the same mould. He went down well here -
deliberately and explicitly reviving the ``special relationship'', to the point
of naming a new powerful US warship after a famous British Premier, the
half-American Churchill. It may be protested that much of his effort, including
the vessel's name, is concerned with mere symbol, but in an Irish context the
symbolic has a contemporary resonance which is rare, possibly even unique. The
significance of Mr Clinton's visit, and its accompanying promises, is all
practical, and designed for today and tomorrow notwithstanding its use of the
past and its ability to deploy symbolic code.
If his imprint was as bold and popular as his appeal, there was little room to
doubt the extent to which the field was prepared. The hunger for peace in
Ireland is as evident as the bankruptcy of the gunmen. At the very least Mr
Clinton's visit must make it harder for the extremists - on both sides - to
resort again to violence. The chance of disarmament has been advanced, though
that does not mean that the hard-line Republicans have been convinced: one
reason for their holding on to the gun is their poor record at the ballot box.
The ability to kill and to terrorise is what makes the IRA a potent force -
that, and not its ability to run up inspiring electoral totals for Sinn Fein
candidates on either side of the border. Whatever the power of the nationalist
tradition in Irish history it is not entirely at the disposal of Sinn Fein,
something which needs re-stating again and again.
Mr Clinton displays a degree of glamour on this side of the Atlantic, where
many Presidents this century have personally come to develop a special
relationship with British and Irish opinion - Wilson, Franklin Roosevelt,
Truman, Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Reagan certainly did so. Mr Clinton may not
have exhibited it before, but something of its magic, the indefinable element
in popular politics, has been discerned this week. And it has been put to good
use. Its real worth may lie in the complicated bargaining which has to take
place in the next three months. It still could be shoved aside brutally - few
gunmen in any situation have much time for effete and imprecise words like
``magic'' any more than they have much time for majority popular opinion, which
has always been hostile to extreme violence in both communities in Northern
Ireland. The IRA might not have the self-confidence to opt for peace, but Mr
Clinton's visit has shown them - what they should anyhow always have known -
just how deep is the longing for it. It is widely shared, being the common
sentiment that united his enthusiastic crowds in London, Belfast, Londonderry,
and Dublin. The reception he received on this side of the Atlantic may, with
his other foreign successes, do Mr Clinton much good in his race for
re-election next year, but its importance here transcends that political
dimension. Though it is too soon to be sure, it is not too soon to hope that he
has delivered a powerful new impetus to the movement for peace.
</TEXT>
