<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Michael the Magician has all the aces</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Smith</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093813</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is a trick that stage magicians do where they dangle some glittering
trinkets in one hand. While your eyes follow their colours and movement the
other hand is stealthily removing your wallet without you knowing.
Scotland's local government leaders were today putting on that wide-eyed look
when they pat their jackets and realise the wallet has gone. The magician is,
of course, Secretary of State Michael Forsyth.
To be fair to Michael the Magician, the local government leaders were willing
victims. While he was working out what constitutional changes to make to
somehow steal the thunder of proposals for a Scottish parliament, on his desk
fortuitously dropped a letter from the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities.
It proposed 52 ways that the Scottish Office could devolve power to the
councils which take over in April. A quick read of the list showed many things
that the Scottish Office could agree with - even the most power-hungry zealot
would not stand in the way of Cosla's wish that pelican crossings could be
erected without the requirement to issue notices and consult the Scottish
Office.
Nor was there much danger of a constitutional crisis if provisions in the Kirk
Dykes Act (1597) requiring councils to maintain churchyard walls were abolished.
The Scottish Office makes much of the fact that only nine of the 52 suggestions
by Cosla have been rejected by Michael Forsyth. The remainder will go out to
public consultation.
But if the 52 were playing cards, Michael the Magician has kept all the aces,
kings and a queen, and thrown all the plain cards back on the table.
Although minor changes concerning kirk walls, traffic regulations, and public
path creation orders may eventually be given to local councils to decide, the
tight grip on the purse strings still remains at the Scottish Office. Mr
Forsyth has rejected claims he should relax the capping powers he has over
councils. He also insists that councils should continue with compulsory
competitive tendering.
Councillor Keith Geddes, Cosla's senior vice-president, was said to have
welcomed the Secretary of State's announcement. He was quoted as saying it was
a step in the right direction.
But he was only being polite. Mr Geddes said yesterday that his complete view
was that yes, it was one step forward, but it was also three steps back, when
other announcements were taken into account.
Earlier in the week Mr Forsyth announced that councils had to spend a quarter
of their receipts from the sale of council houses into servicing council debt -
in other words pay it to the bankers and financial institutions.
Until now it has been used for construction and repair work. At a stroke the
country's construction industry, not in the best of health at present, was
dealt a difficult blow. And as Mr Geddes says: ``This was done without
consulting local authorities or the construction industry about the effects it
will have.
``It is all very well giving us more control in some selective areas, but in
effect it is more control but on a much smaller sum of money.
``The real issue in Scottish local government still remains resources. The
proposed changes would be much more welcome if they came with appropriate
resources.
``The more minor items he has gone along with will simply tidy up some aspects,
but he has held back on the issues which would have given real strategic powers
to the councils.''
One change proposed by Mr Forsyth is that the new councils will be allowed to
make their own bye-laws. The limits though are not spelled out, other than the
relatively non-contentious suggestion of allowing councils to limit the
drinking of alcohol in public places.
Planning applications for fewer than 10 houses would be decided locally without
recourse to the Secretary of State.
Councils may also be allowed to take their own decisions on school closures -
but given the heated arguments they can create, the Scottish Secretary would
probably be quite glad to wash his hands of that one. He can of course allow
any school to opt out, so in a roundabout way he would have a form of final say.
He may also allow councils to take over houses at present owned by Scottish
Homes.
The building of trunk roads may come within the councils' remit. But if there
is not sufficient money coming with the responsibility, then the councils may
be cautious of this expansion.
On allocating resources, there appears to be a significant change in that there
would be only one capital expenditure covering education, social work, roads,
transport, and general services, rather than separate totals. It will allow the
council to decide spending priorities among the different areas.
It sounds like more freedom for the councils. But two key areas are excluded.
Housing will still be a separate total agreed with the Scottish Office. Nor, it
seems, will spending on police and fire services be included.
As John Mullin, chair of finance at Strathclyde region, puts it: ``It's little
more than window-dressing. The financial straitjacket has not been loosened. It
is not so important how you slice the cake up, as the size of the cake in the
first place.''
BUT perhaps they are simply opposition politicians who are unwilling to give Mr
Forsyth his proper credit? So I sought the views of Steven Hamilton, once the
chief executive of Glasgow District Council, but now retired and thus
answerable to no political master.
He also saw the removal of capital receipts from councils as the removal of
freedom to act. And he pointed out that even if councils had freedom within
their capital allocations, they still had to prove to the Scottish Office that
their capital schemes could not have been financed by the Government's Private
Finance Initiative. In other words, the Scottish Office will still be crawling
over the spending plans.
``I don't see where the greater freedom Mr Forsyth is talking about is coming
from. Many of the proposals are very trivial. I find it very difficult to
believe that local authority powers are going to change significantly.''
Mr Forsyth says this will be the first wave in a tide of reform which will
sweep across the shoreline of government and change its shape for ever.
The local councils, though, believe it will hardly get their toes wet.
Although minor changes may eventually be given to local councils to decide, Ken
Smith explains why the tight grip on the purse strings still remains at the
Scottish Office
</TEXT>
