<HEADLINE>Gala out to make the going tough Title now on the menu at Melrose</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093816</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REVENGE is a dish best eaten cold, and after 123 years, the bone of contention
between those old Border rivals, Gala and Melrose, is just right for the
picking.
The issue is the small matter of the Gala goalposts and strips which
disappeared under cover of darkness and ended up five miles away at the
Greenyards, as the Melrose men staged a nocturnal breakaway from their
erstwhile comrades in arms.
That was in 1877 and, in truth, the clubs have long since kissed and made up,
with the purloined goods replaced in kind.
However, against a backdrop of such splendid internecine strife, there is no
way on God's earth that Gala will roll over today and allow their Border
colleagues a clear run at the final championship hurdle.
The SRU Tennents Premiership has maintained its flavour right down to the very
last crunch. Melrose, Stirling County, Boroughmuir, and Watsonians are still in
the hunt. Melrose are in the driving seat and a win for them at the Greenyards
means that Stirling must beat Boroughmuir today and Heriot's FP on December 16.
Then it would come down to points' differential and Stirling must wipe out the
41-point deficit which separates the two sides.
Boroughmuir, who for long enough had the championship and their destiny within
their grasp, now must win against Stirling today and look for Gala to defeat
Melrose. The odds on a Watsonians' triumph are even longer, and if they are to
be champions then they must beat Hawick today and profit from losses by Melrose
and Boroughmuir and by Stirling in the re-arranged game with Heriot's.
If Melrose are successful against Gala today and Stirling lose, then the new
championship trophy will be handed over to captain Bryan Redpath by SRU
president Iain Todd at the close of play. If Boroughmuir beat Stirling and
Melrose lose to Gala, then Todd will hightail it to Meggetland, where he will
present the trophy to Boroughmuir in a 6.30 ceremony once the team have
returned from Bridgehaugh.
But all of that is in the future. Yesterday, Gala coach Peter Dods was
confirming that defeat at the Greenyards is the last thing on their minds.
``We'll not be making it easy for Melrose,'' he said. ``For once we want to
make it easy four ourselves. Last week when we beat Hawick I told the boys that
our season starts now. That win represented our first victory after relegation
and, at last we had started to put things right.
``We're totally relaxed about Melrose. The pressure is all on them and they
certainly won't think that it's a foregone conclusion. The season began badly
for us. We just seemed to crack under pressure. Even yet we haven't really put
our thumb on what went wrong. But there is no pressure on us tomorrow.
``I don't think that Melrose will be playing a fast, furious game. They will
want to keep it tight and it's a game plan they work well. We'll be out to
disrupt that plan. I'm stressing to the boys that we have nothing whatsoever to
fear. We go into the game with that win over Hawick in the bag. I have said all
season that somebody is going to be on the receiving end from us. Hopefully it
will be Melrose tomorrow.
``We're looking at next season now. The premiership is all but over and already
clubs are starting to recruit for next year. We're looking at what we can do
for our players because we have to make sure that we keep as many of the squad
as we can for next season. We have to get the commitment to Gala from the
players now. It's no good waiting until March or April,'' he said.
In the Melrose camp, Doddie Weir, who may well be playing his last league game
for the club he has been with for 10 of his 25 years before enlisting with
Newcastle, harbours no illusions as to how tough it will be today.
``Gala have had a nightmare of a season and there is nothing would please them
more than to beat us tomorrow. I know that because my brother, Tom, has been
telling me so all week.''
Tom Weir, two years Doddie's junior, is at lock today for Gala in direct
opposition to his brother. ``I've been trying to bribe him all week for their
lineout codes but there's nothing doing. He says they played really well
against Hawick last week and that they're all up for it tomorrow.
``It's a great way to end the season, though, a Border derby at the Greenyards.
What more could you ask for. Except a win for Melrose.''
</TEXT>
