<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enigma of the oyster and two the nations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093817</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
READERS of The Pickwick Papers learn that, in Charles Dickens's time, oysters
used to be a poor man's food. The excellent Sam Weller thought indeed that
poverty and oysters went together.
Yet today they are a rich man's food, perhaps becoming a little less so than
truffles or caviar, but still scarcely popular. Even a gastronome in waiting
like myself never tasted oysters till I was 20, and while I now down a few
dozen a year, they are far from a staple of my diet. Yet my consumption must be
well above the average. How do we account for the difference between the age of
Dickens and our own?
The paradox poses itself because we need only go over to France to find oysters
very commonly eaten. In the streets of Paris, there are countless stalls
selling them. You can swallow half a dozen on the spot, or carry them away in a
poke. Yet the French fish the Atlantic waters like ourselves. Why should they
have so many oysters.
Both Britain and France are maritime nations, and have always consumed the
fruits of the sea. Britain is insular, her people free to roam the oceans of
the world, gathering in its produce and sending back her own. She therefore has
a natural bias towards free trade. On the other hand France, attached to the
end of the Eurasian land mass, is open to invasion and has throughout her
history needed a strong state to defend herself. A strong state naturally tends
to intervene in the economy.
By the middle of the nineteenth century, when Neild's story starts, both were
also big nations, with burgeoning urban populations to be fed. Oysters proved
in many ways ideal. Though superabundant, they could not swim away. Once
fishermen found an oyster-bed, all they had to do was scoop the creatures up:
much easier than hunting down and chasing shoals of herring, for example.
What happened then was that British fishermen scooped and scooped till the
oyster-beds were gone. The doctrines of free trade, a religion in themselves
during the Victorian era, made the government wary of intervening. It conducted
inquiries, but ignored the evidence that oysters were being fished to
extinction.
France, however, took the opposite course. There the government was reluctant
to see a cheap source of sustenance vanish. As it became obvious that the old
methods of harvesting natural oysters could not continue, cultivation was
encouraged under strict legal safeguards. Up to this day, coastal communities
make a living from that, and there are oysters in plenty for everybody else.
Each country followed its own instincts but which, Neild prompts the reader to
ask, has come off better?
Interwoven with this narrative are many titbits of oyster lore.  There are
recommendations on how to cook them, though no recipes as such. But you will
not find a clearer explanation of what to do if you want to choose oysters,
take them home, open and eat them for yourself.
Also in my batch this time is the latest edition of Mrs Beeton, thoroughly
modernised since the great lady's time and now put into paperback. ``First
catch a hare'' is out, but there are numerous tips of the kind other cookbooks
omit, such as how to clean a squid, bone a chicken, brand a souffle  or carve a
saddle of venison, all admirably illustrated. Up-to-date methods, including
even the dreaded microwave, are well covered. The text is about evenly divided
between the techniques of every kind and the recipes, the latter oddly
presented in rigid alphabetical order, so that after onion soup comes orange
marmalade, then osso buco, then oxtail and so on. This volume is excellent
value.
There is a similar but more self-conscious old-fashioned look about The Cook's
Scrapbook. Every dish is pictured, and in between there are culinary
reminiscences of days of yore or grainy black-and-white photos of Granny Black
leading her hob and the like. Still, the recipes are good, with all the
standard favourites and an excellent range of specialities from different parts
of Britain, including Scotland. This is obviously aimed at the Christmas market.
Finally, there is another attempt to cash in on the audience for Masterchef,
with a selection of the best recipes from the five years the series has been
running. It is perfectly all right if you like that sort of thing, but I remain
suspicious of virtuosity in the domestic kitchen for its own sake.
n The English, the French and the Oyster: Robert Neild,  Quiller Press, #18.95.
n Mrs Beeton's A-Z of Everyday Cookery: Bridget Jones (ed), Ward Lock, #15.
n The Cook's Scrapbook: John Palmer (ed), Reader's Digest, #24.95.
n The Masterchef Collection: Janet Illsley (ed), Ebury Press, #12.99.
Michael Fry reveals why a staple became a delicacy
</TEXT>
