<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pageantry, drama, but still no crowds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093818</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHILE the draft dodger was in Belfast pouring his sickly syrup over the
medicine hastily concocted for Ulster to ingest, my two American guests
arrived. They, like their President, had come with elections in mind. ``Gee,
this must be so exciting for you Scotch (sic),'' they trumpeted to the man
standing at the bar of the Glasgow pub in which we arranged to meet. He looked
bemused, then, cautiously and silently, began rearranging his hauf-and-a-hauf
on the counter creating a curious pattern with the beer pump, no doubt a secret
symbol to ward off evil spirits or irrepressible Yankies. It didn't work.
``Are you going to a party?'' they asked; somewhat improbably I thought since
his dark uniform below his anorak suggested the only knees-up he experienced
that day was when climbing into the driving seat of his bus. He visibly
brightened, nevertheless, as his interrogators were both attractive young women
in their early twenties, although had overindulged on mom's apple pie.
``No, are you?'' came the reply. I detected an element of hope in his voice.
``It's St Andrew's Day tomorrow,'' they crowed in unison. ``Is it?'' his
expectations sank with his whisky. What I like about Americans is their
inexhaustible optimism. I suppose you must have it to contrive a jigsaw of a
peace plan like that for Bosnia. These ladies, fresh from an east coast
university, were in Scotland to see our own pieces put together, namely, a
Parliament of all the Labour Talents. That it was happening on St Andrew's Day
was ``wonderful'', ``amazing'', ``historic''. I wondered if Canon Kenyon Wright
had written their scripts.
They were anxious to get to Edinburgh, though 24 hours were to elapse before
``festivities'' began. Would there be a parade? Were all the houses decked out
in bunting? Would there be thousands of people out on the streets? Wasn't it
exciting?
Enthusiasm is such a rare quality one is reluctant to dampen it. ``We should
watch it on television,'' I said helpfully. Their faces contorted. ``No, we
want to be out on the streets,'' they pleaded eagerly. This was serious
business. They were writing it up for a magazine so the folks back home could
share our day. They had tape recorders, decorated with all manner of devices,
including a clock which, impressively, told you the time to the exact minute in
places such as Seoul and Peking. For backup there were pads with a rainbow
assortment of coloured pens. Also their cameras had an array of attachments
which would have done credit to Richard Avedon.
They had also been doing their homework. Seventy five to 80% of Scots wanted
constitutional change. The status quo was not an option. Tories faced wipeout.
The Daily Record in audio.
First stop the following day was Calton Hill and the proposed Assembly
building. The Rocky Horror Show in all its grim reality. A balding man from
Stirling was spotted surreptitiously handing out leaflets to press men. We
three created a ``crowd'' on the pavement and, feeling exposed, looked around
for members of the public. Eight or nine were huddled together. We joined them
but they disappeared soon after when their bus arrived.
On to the Mercat Cross in the High Street for real theatre. A proclamation was
read, a pipe band blew, Saltires fluttered, and 100 of the self-appointed,
chests extended, marched to the Assembly hall. Pageantry, drama, but still no
crowds.
None the less, I savoured the pathos. These Modern Anthenians, like their
ancient counterparts who crept out of their city on the way to the ill-fated
Peloponnesian Wars, had set their course to do or die. The Americans, I
discovered, were not big on historical analogies, more on ticker tape. ``Where
is everybody?'' they asked. Which for Labour must surely rank with other
imponderables such as the West Lothian question.
To the rest of us it is transparently obvious. There is no widespread popular
demand. Of course if you ask Scots whether they want their own parliament, the
majority response will be in the affirmative. It is a romantic notion, like
wanting Partick Thistle to win the cup. But few would volunteer to stand on the
terracings to watch them any more than most of us would willingly pay the
Tartan Tax.
Those outwith the chattering classes remotely interested in a parliament have
been suckered into believing that such an institution will have a dramatic
effect on everything from the economy to pensions. When they discover it is no
better than a glorified county council the discontent will manifest itself. It
will, further, spiral out of control if the current generous block grant
formula is revised on the back of objections that the Scots are being treated
favourably. And we are. This is why it makes sense to retain the Union. No-one,
least of all Europe, will give us such a great deal. It is utter folly to throw
it away.
Yet many in Scotland would have us do so, peddling half-truths in TV programmes
like Scotching the Myth. The basis of this argument, which has recently
resurfaced after most of us thought it had been buried five years ago, is that
more public money is spent on a Londoner than on a Scot. What is so surprising
about that? More money is spent per head in Scotland than on a Geordie, a
Welshman, or a Liverpudlian. If you look within Scotland more is spent per
capita in Edinburgh and Glasgow than Pumpherston and Uphall.
If these comparisons mean we can accuse London of having its snout in the
trough, would it not be justifiable for Geordies to accuse we Scots of the
same? Do I see hands raised offering to cut back on public spending to put
Scotland on a par with Newcastle?
Of course it costs more to build in some parts of London than most of Scotland.
It is reflected in prices. Clever, eh?
Propaganda like Scotching the Myth and Labour's hyped claims of what an
Assembly can achieve play into the hands of the separatists. If anyone should
have been dancing in the streets this week it is the Nationalists. At least it
would have made the day for my Americans.
</TEXT>
