<HEADLINE>Pantomime Pinocchio, Citizens' Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093819</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are two kinds of magic and this Pinocchio has them both. There's the kind
of technical whiz-wizardry which makes our little wooden chum's nose grow when
he tells whoppers. And I promise you, it really does get longer and longer
before your very eyes. And even the spoilsport clever-clogs who sit looking for
the tricks and telling everyone else how it's done won't know. Actually it's
done by . . . mmmmm.
Sorry, but the Lady in Blue has sealed my lips. She's the mysterious stranger
who helps everyone see how to make the other kind of magic works. This is the
magic of ordinary things, the magic that we all take for granted. It's to do
with trying your hardest even when things seems impossible, and caring about
others, and having family and friends who care about you. ``You're never alone
if someone is missing you,'' says this marvellously upright, bustled, and
brollied individual in a rig-out that's more be-toqued Queen Mary than token
Mary Poppins.
Does this sound as if writer Myles Rudge hasn't got beyond the ``pi'' in
Pinocchio? Fret not. This is true, bright-eyed, bushy-tailed adventuring - Mr
Fox and Miss Kitty providing a gallus dawd of raffish low life - mixed with
fits of daftness, some sing-alongs, lots of audience participation and just the
right slosh of sentiment.
Really the plot is just a midsummer night's dream where everyone - from
Geppetto the toymaker (Sandy Welch) to Carlo, his flesh and blood son
(Christopher Delaney) - learns the dangers of selfishness. Kathryn Howden's
Frenchified show-off is a cracking oo-la-la-laugh while David McKay's Cricket
so appealed to my own conscience that I simply can't spoil things by telling
you how that nose grows . . .
</TEXT>
