<HEADLINE>Charlie's phantom army</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093820</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HISTORY
THE MYTH OF THE JACOBITE CLANS: Murray Pittock, Edinburgh University Press,
#11.95
THE FORTY-FIVE: Michael Hook and Walter Ross, National Library of
Scotland/HMSO, #12.95
EDINBURGH IN THE '45: John Gibson, Saltire Society, #6.99
FROM REBEL TO HERO: The Image of the Highlander1745-1830: Robert Clyde,
Tuckwell Press, #20
THE flood of Jacobite books marking the 250th anniversary of the '45 swells.
The waters are in some places admirably clear, in others thoroughly muddied.
Murray Pittock has written a bold but in the end, I am obliged to say, a bad
book. I am obliged to say so despite the fact that, as a general principle, I
applaud his quest for a Scottish historiography cleansed of kitsch. In fact,
all historians of the present generation in Scotland are engaged on the same
quest.
This does not mean we must accept the substance of Pittock's argument, that the
Jacobites, so far from being marginal, were and are central to Scottish history
and identity since the Union. His argument proceeds from the notion that they
formed a nationalism in the era after 1707 which, though later suppressed and
distorted, has survived to emerge, perchance to triumph, in our own time.
In a previous book, Pittock's argument rested on the explication of Jacobite or
quasi-Jacobite texts, in the present work, he at least looks to a real world
beyond texts. He even wrestles with statistics. No doubt to his own
satisfaction he wins the bout, but I have to disqualify him on grounds of
cheating.
The central point which Pittock seeks to establish is that Highlanders did not,
as myth tells us, make up the bulk of the armed strength which Prince Charles
Edward Stuart was able to call forth from Scotland. On the contrary, they
contributed only half of it, if that. It follows that the rest must have been
Lowlanders. The prince therefore united Highland and Lowlands: he led a
national, indeed nationalist, uprising. This was not the dying jerk of a doomed
Gaelic civilisation, but Scotland striking for freedom. The main evidence
adduced is that, when Charles marched off in November 1745 with 6000 clansmen
into England, he left behind a ``northern army'', composed of Lowlanders, to
hold the territory of Scotland. It did not do very well, for English troops at
once re-occupied Edinburgh.
Maybe it was a matter of the northern army's organisation. Pittock stresses
that the prince's invading force was not a tribal rabble, but a modern military
corps with a proper command structure.
But who were the generals, brigadiers and colonels of the northern army?
Pittock does not tell us. What, come to that, were its units? At the Battle of
Falkirk in January 1746 the only Scottish additions to the Jacobite host,
meanwhile back from England were three regiments of Farquharsons, Mackenzies
and Frasers - Highlanders, not Lowlanders.
Indeed at the Battle of Culloden in April the only further additions were one
regiment of mixed clans and two of Gordons (though some of the latter, raised
on Speyside, might just about count as Lowlanders). But why did the rest of the
northern army not show up at this supreme crisis of Jacobitism? No doubt, with
the holding of all that territory, it had better things to do.
One might begin to suspect that the northern army was a phantom, a figment of
Pittock's imagination. The suspicion will be confirmed on examination of how he
came to believe that it existed at all. The authority on which he most relies
is a doctoral thesis of 1963 by a Miss McCann, who put the number of fighting
Jacobites at 12,470 to 14,140. Subtract the 5000 who marched into England and,
hey presto, the northern army appears.
I have not had the pleasure of reading Miss McCann's thesis, so I cannot tell
how she arrived at her figures. What I wonder is why, for a piece of evidence
crucial to his case, Pittock again does not tell us. He diligently computes
recruitment in various bits of the Lowlands, but omits to add them up. A glance
will show that they come nowhere near covering the gap between 5000 and 14,000.
Hanoverian spies reckoned the Jacobites raised no more than 3450 extra men
while the prince was dashing to Derby, but many of these must have had second
thoughts when before long they faced the prospect of encounter with the
bayonets of the British army. In any event, why should the spies have lied?
It is easy to lie with statistics, or at least to accept consistently the
estimates most favourable to a preconceived purpose. This is not good
historical method, though. It may be quite all right for a literary critic, as
Pittock is, to draw out of texts an individual interpretation which opens up
original insights to himself and others: I dare say that is his job.
A historian, on the other hand, is stuck with facts, which often refuse to
gell. But he is never entitled to ignore or wish away those that will not fit
the framework he would like to find. And in this instance, Pittock has failed
to disprove the myth of the Jacobite clans. The rest of his argument falls.
Not all Jacobite books in this anniversary year are bad. The one by Michael
Hook and Walter Ross, which presumably counts as the official publication on
the '45, is exceptionally good: rapid narrative, skilful deployment of detail,
sound judgment right through and excellent illustrations. John Gibson, whose
monographs have so expanded our understanding of Jacobitism, gives sterling
service again with a vivid book on Edinburgh's uneasy experience of the Stuart
homecoming. Robert Clyde mainly surveys printed literature on the Highlands
after it was all over, but the theme of rebel-to-hero is well sustained.
MICHAEL FRY
n Read Michael Fry's latest instalment of the '45 on page 49
</TEXT>
