<HEADLINE>Records are broken in Rio</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093821</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SWIMMING
TWO world records went tumbling at the world short-course swimming
championships in Rio de Janeiro yesterday while China's Le Jingyi won her
second gold medal.
Claudia Poll, of Costa Rica, and Australian Samantha Riley broke world records
as they won gold medals in the women's 200 metres free-style and 200m
breast-stroke respectively.
China's Le, a double gold medallist at last year's world championships in Rome,
added the women's 50m free-style title to the 100m free-style gold she won on
Thursday. Le won in 24.62sec.
Poll won her final in a time of 1min 55.42sec, bettering the mark of 1-55.84
set by Germany's Franziska van Almsick in Beijing nearly three years ago.
Brisbane's Riley demolished the opposition in her final, finishing in 2min
20.85sec to knock more than one second off the record.
Van Almsick, in addition to losing her 200m record, pulled out of the
confrontation with Le when she failed to start in the morning's qualifiers, her
coach Achim Jedamsky saying she had a bout of flu.
Australia won two more golds, taking their total to six, when defending
champion Daniel Kowalski won the men's 400m free-style, and the men's relay
team won the 4 x 200m free-style. Kowalski swam the last leg to take his second
gold of the day.
Britain's Sarah Hardcastle won her first world title when she won the women's
800m free-style in 8-26.46.
</TEXT>
