<DOCNO>GH951202-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Not in the running</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093822</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALNWICK Castle is used to rebellious Scots - the fortress owes the existence to
their unwelcome attentions.
Scots again are girding themselves for battle beneath its ramparts - not
because they will be competing for Britain today in the European Cross-country
Championships, but because they are not.
The failure to include any Scot has provoked anger among those who believe the
performances of Kilbarchan's Robert Quinn and Cambuslang's Steven Wylie,
respectively third and fourth in the final trial, warranted more than reserve
status.
British Athletic Federation secretary Matt Fraser, also secretary of the UK
cross-country commission, said: ``There was no trial as such, because this is
so early in the season. We just stipulated four races to be taken into
consideration. But we acknowledge the discontent, and we'll review it for next
year.''
Fraser warns Glasgow, who want the 1997 championships but have yet to lodge a
formal application, that they have a rival. ``Portugal have already made a
bid,'' said Fraser.
Quinn, first reserve today and is optimistic of a place: ``usually one person
gets injured or has flu,'' is himself that victim. Wylie is on standby, hoping
to be given the chance to flourish. However, with a clean bill of health
reported last night, that prospect seems remote.
Andrew Pearson is the Briton most likely to challenge Portugal's defending
champion, Paulo Guerra. ``I will be disappointed if I don't take a medal, and
also if the British team does not get one,'' he said.
Pearson spent last summer in Kenya, but it was a disaster: ``I proved allergic
to malaria tablets, and was ill for months.''
With women's world 10,000 metres champion Fernando Ribiero, and defending
champion Catherina McKiernan sidelined, the world junior champion, Anne-Marie
Sandell, of Finland, could make a speedy impact on the senior ranks.
Wylie's absence on international duty will weaken Cambuslang's team for the TSB
West cross-country championships today at Stepps, where the Lanarkshire club
will be under strong pressure from Shettleston.
Dave Cavers (Teviotdale) chases retention of the East title at Edinburgh's Jack
Kane Centre, but Glen Stewart should lead Leslie Deans Racing Club to the team
title.
ATHLETICS
</TEXT>
