<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093823</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOAN McFADDEN visits a show for parents-to-be and young families
THE Baby and Toddler Show at the SECC, in Glasgow, is designed especially for
parents-to-be and young families, and aims to provide an enjoyable day out
coupled with the chance to buy anything and everything you might need for your
children.
Anyone who is pregnant and revelling in it will find themselves thoroughly at
home, while those who are already baby bores can indulge themselves and their
offspring.
Begin with the stand representing the Queen Mother's Hospital, where the staff
midwife has the knack of making every pregnant woman feel cherished and
special; move on to the fashion show where the models look hugely pregnant yet
very elegant; and test drive the huge range of baby equipment on display.
Throughout the day there is non-stop entertainment for children, which includes
favourites such as Fireman Sam and Rupert the Bear. Santa is welcoming guests
into his grotto - a bit early but welcome - and there are free balloons and
goodies galore for all the tinies. There is also excellent provision for all
the practical needs of the under-fives, including a play area, feeding and
breast feeding areas, nappy changing areas, and a restaurant.
Life assurance, pain relief in labour, and safety in the home are just some of
the services on offer, and although there are certainly some predictable toys
such as the ubiquitous Mr Blobby there is also a wide variety of rather more
unusual goods. One stand features hard- wearing and very attractive reversible
clothing, while another sells beautiful wooden toys, which include a unique
nativity scene.
The drawback to all the more individual clothes and toys is the price, as the
sellers are clearly aiming at higher income families. Some of the parents I
spoke to felt the entrance fee of #6 per adult was extortionate, and that the
bulk of the goods available were out of the question for anyone on a tight
budget. Since financial constraints usually go hand in hand with children, some
exhibitors appear to be simply pricing themselves out of the market.
Some of the most popular stands are those featuring specialist magazines, such
as First Steps, which are tailored for pregnancy through to toddlers. These
magazines provide a wealth of information on subjects such as baby equipment,
ante-natal care, and children's fashion, and they are well worth looking at
before you start forking out hundreds of pounds on the latest trend.
It is very pleasant to be able to take small children into a show which happily
caters for them and doesn't leave you feeling that pushing a buggy
automatically alienates you from the rest of the human race.
If you're looking for a special present, one to try before you buy, or just
like the feeling that everytime a tantrum threatens you can divert your toddler
with a passing clown or reindeer then this is for you. The big plus for me is
no-one attempted any hard sell, but the big minus has to be all the people
ignoring the No Smoking signs. With so many small children around there are too
many tiny faces at just the wrong height.
n The Baby and Toddler Show at the SECC, Glasgow, today 10am-6pm and tomorrow
10am-5pm.
</TEXT>
