<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Detectives probe shooting of envoy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093826</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nairobi
BRITISH detectives are in Nairobi to investigate the shooting of British
diplomat Graeme Gibson, 43, who is paralysed after being shot in the neck on
November 24 by a three-man gang driving a stolen car.
Two detectives from Scotland Yard flew to Nairobi at the Kenyan Government's
request this week.
Police believed the attackers were thieves after Mr Gibson's car, but Kenyan
Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka now says it could be an attempt to undermine
the government and give the impression of insecurity.
Mr Gibson and his wife Pam left for Britain today, leaving a note to say they
were sad to leave. ``We will be flying to Britain where Graeme will be
continuing treatment for the terrible injuries he suffered,'' they said.
Attacks on expatriates in Kenya have risen in the last few years and political
analysts said the government's decision to bring in Scotland Yard was meant to
show it was seriously concerned.
Next week, prosecution and defence lawyers will present final submissions in
the trial of three men charged with the rape and murder last year of British
housewife Caron Winter.
Kenya called in Scotland Yard to investigate the 1988 murder in a game reserve
of British tourist Julie Ward. That murder was never solved and a Kenyan judge
accused local police of attempting a cover-up.
In February 1990, President Daniel arap Moi brought in Scotland Yard again to
investigate the murder of populist Foreign Minister Robert Ouko, after his
charred remains were found in a bush near his rural home in Western Kenya.
The detectives were sent home before completing the work.
In another sign that the Kenyan Government was taking attacks on visitors
seriously, it announced the formation of a Tourism Protection Unit (TPU)
designed to end attacks on tourists and win back confidence in the country's
top foreign exchange earning industry.
</TEXT>
