<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TRAPPED ON  THE SIDELINE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sue Innes</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>herald essay</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093827</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN A FIT of misplaced vanity the day after my book, Making It Work*, on the
challenges facing women in the nineties, was published (but after all, no-one
knew me there), I went into Dillon's bookshop near London University to see if
they'd got it and whether they'd displayed it decently. I couldn't see it but
checked with an assistant. ``About women? That'll be under gender studies which
is under sociology on the third floor.'' It was a long climb - up the main
staircase, then up another much narrower one to the most obscure and distant
corner of the shop. It wasn't there either, and since it's written in plain
English wouldn't really have fitted.
Coming downstairs I paused by a table at the main door. NEW THIS WEEK! Peter
Ackroyd on Blake, Robert Harris's Enigma, a novel about clever but crusty (in
the old sense) bachelors, Anthony Quinn on himself, Michael Barrymore on
himself and booze, another chap on Andre Malraux. Men on men, but no-one calls
it ``men's studies''.
This is not just a story of how pride comes before a crestfallen exit, but I
think illustrates a dilemma facing feminism today. It is no longer the case
that women's voices go unheard, or women are not present as writers and
broadcasters and filmmakers, in law, in unions, in decision-making (though
there are many areas still wholly male). What's much harder is getting women's
views to count as mainstream. The very emphasis we have fought for to stop
women's specific interests (as practitioners and audience, representatives and
voters) being obscured and overlooked, has turned back on us to create a kind
of trap, another excuse for marginalisation.
The book is about the things that shape women's lives and options in the 1990s:
work, kids, grannies, the CSA, politics, sex, self-esteem . . . obscure things
like that. Writing about changing families and demographic change - the ageing
population, why fewer women are having children; about an ill-divided ``60-40
society'', long hours and competitive pressures at work, and insecurity; about
legal reform of divorce and child maintenance - these seem to me questions of
current affairs as well as central to contemporary feminism. Of interest to
men, even.
Flag up ``women'', though, and you can be tucked away under a category of
special interest and at the back of the shop. As one woman councillor put it:
women's issues are people's issues, only most people in decision-making roles
ignore them. Women politicans have for years faced this dilemma, but it comes
in several guises: the distinction between ``soft'' and ``hard'' news, for
example, though family policy matters as much to most of us as economics, and
indeed the two cannot be understood separately.
Pursue ``women's issues'' and you risk being marginalised; determinedly eschew
them in the hope of being taken more seriously and you reinforce an ascription
of value which underpins sex discrimination. Mrs Thatcher is the pre-eminent
example of the latter strategy, famously described as the best man in Cabinet.
Yet she was both praised and reviled in ways permeated with sexual imagery,
from Alan Clark's flirtatious talk of slim ankles to the slogan ``Ditch the
Bitch''. I never thought of myself as a woman politican, she said. But can you
avoid it?
Fiona Mackay at Edinburgh University, in a study of women politicians in local
authorities, found most were deeply ambivalent about ``women's issues'' - seen
as a way of sidelining concerns which should be in the mainstream, but
recognising the risk of those issues being lost there. Most agreed in practice
a list of interests which should be shared, but aren't usually: childcare and
other caring responsibilities, women's health, violence, equal opportunities,
part-time working, low pay, and the low level of women in decision-making.
The processes of agreeing the Platform for Action at Beijing and, although
closer to home, drawing up a parallel Agenda for Action (which the Women's
National Commission and Equal Opportunities Commission did earlier this year)
can feel remote from our everyday and local concerns, but when you look at the
details, reflect them. Again they raise political, social, and economic issues
which concern everyone.
It is a long and scarcely visible battle for political legitimacy, not just for
women but a ``women's agenda''; not just a place on the
board/committee/executive, but a role in reshaping its priorities.
Engaging with and challenging national and international politics - for example
taking forward the resolutions of the UN Women's Conference at Beijing - is one
of two clear priorities in women's politics in the 1990s. (The other is sexual
and domestic volence.)
But ``mainstreaming'' is also a demand for a different focus: that gender is
taken account of across all policy-making. For example, understanding that care
is an economic, not just a family, issue; and that the impact on most women of
most policies is different than it is for men. For example housing (women are
more likely to live in social housing), transport (women are much less likely
to have a car); the consequences of austerity programmes in the Third World
(women fill the gaps when health and social programmes are cut back), and types
of aid. But it means making very careful arguments when integration - not so
very different a concept on the face of it - has become code for quietly
dropping these awkward besoms off the bottom of the agenda. A current example
of this is the sidelining of the world of women's units and committees in some
new local authorities.
If integration risks invisibility, intervention to increase women's role means
political trouble - and leaves many women wondering whether the battle is worth
it. The front-running example is women-only short lists in the Labour Party:
the policy has generated a great deal of heat (and a false but general public
impression that no Labour men can stand anywhere) but, in Scotland anyway, a
very mixed outcome: of the six seats where the policy applied, the three least
winnable have gone to women. The policy is called diversionary and
undemocratic, even anti-equality, in the case of the London would-be candidate
who is suing under the sex discrimination legislation. Yet male-only short
lists go unremarked, as does the Tory party's failure, so far, to pick a woman
candidate to fight any safe seat in the UK.
When I interviewed feminist writer and researcher Cynthia Cockburn she argued
that managing both to keep a specific focus on women and on discrimination and
to insist that women and women's issues had a central place in the mainstream
would be difficult. ``We've made a huge climb and we've reached a plateau and
it seems now almost inconceivable that we can make the next step. The demands
have become less legitimate because we already have some representation.''
When I talked to her she was doing research on the presence of women and
women's interests in the social dialogue (between government, trade unions, and
employers) in the European Union. ``It's not a negative story. There are women
present and women's interests are acknowledged and there are women's committees
which are considered legitimate. At the same time there's a huge step still
needed to get real parity, or to have a women's vision of the future of Europe
in any way central to what happens.''
Because more women are in decision-making roles, and often forcefully so, it
obscures how small their number is: 9% at Westminster - an increase of 2% on
the 1987 election, and at a time when there was a lot of lobbying on the issue.
Similarly the elections to the shadow unitary authorities returned 22.4% women,
a stunning increase of 0.5%. If the argument for a gradualist, evolutionary
approach was plausible in 1928, it isn't any longer. Yet action to ensure women
have an equal part is seen as reverse discrimination - a quasi-liberal argument
which only makes sense if you assume the same starting point. We need to
recognise that most of our institutions still run positive action programmes
for men.
Structures and intervention to address women's lack of involvement are still
needed, not so much to provide a springboard as information, research back-up,
and political analysis, to make possible the evaluation of all policies in
terms of how they support, or erode, equality. And to enable women to argue
more successfully that women's interests are people's interests. And that we
all need a different political settlement.
The second, allied, dilemma is summed up in feminist shorthand as
``difference''. Women's politics have been dogged by oversimplistic assumptions
of women's commonalities. No - read on - this really doesn't contradict what
I've been arguing about a women's agenda, though it is a tightrope to be walked
with care.
If sisterhood was powerful once, it has not been enough for a long time. Tenets
of shared oppression and solidarity defined women without their consent;
women's liberation asserted a stereotype of women almost as narrow as those it
overthrew. The astonishing amount of comment generated by the spat between
Suzanne Moore and Germaine Greer earlier in the year and the recent more
serious public disagreement between Angela Neustatter, Maureen Freely, and
Naomi Wolf about Wolf's views on abortion are telling - and not only that the
women's movement is sexy when it's angry. Both glee (in the media) and dismay
(some feminists) at such discord reveals a lot about ideas of feminist
solidarity.
This has long been a paralysis and unrealistic expectation. Yes
From an acknowledgement of diverse inequalities and conflicting priorities has
followed the difficulty on developing a single feminist politics - but the
world still expects us to. The idea that the women's movement could be more
formal than a loose network of groups and campaigns is, I think, unrealistic.
Although it would be easier to relate to existing political structures if it
were, and mean interventions could be more powerful. (Better communication
between groups would help a lot.) But gender does not provide that sort of
organising principle.
A DIFFERENCE which has come more into the frame in recent years is between the
Scottish women's movement and the rest of the UK. Interviewing women in England
I asked them whether they saw themselves as part of the women's movement and an
awful lot said ``what women's movement?'' No-one says that in Scotland: you may
have reservations about its role and effectiveness but not its reality.
Defining it is harder. Without even trying to go beyond recent contacts and
events I can think of the women drummers Sheboom (now the largest drumming
group in Europe, I'm told), women weaving webs in endangered trees, the new
lesbian health clinic in Glasgow, the latest stage of Zero Tolerance, Meridian
(the centre for black and ethnic minority women), Engender's Gender Audit, the
STUC's women's conference, the Lanarkshire 16-day campaign against violence.
The image of feminism is problematic: still dungarees and shoulder pads (though
rarely worn together); its practice, though, is widespread and diverse.
``Front-line'' organisations like Women's Aid and Rape Crisis add another
dimension, as do specific professional and interest groups, like women in
social work or women planners, and student groups and academic courses. At a
recent conference for the Clackmannan Women and Girls Project the topics
engaged with (on my count anyway) included homelessness, political
participation, women and technology, unplanned pregnancy, relationship
problems, the social dimensions of health, employment rights, and the Beijing
conference. Organising and creating consensus across such a range of interests
is difficult: which is a lesser priority, not relevant, not political? Perhaps
the only thing all the Scottish women's groups have in common is lack of money.
Knowing about the range of organisations rather than a narrower focus is an
advantage of a small country. Something else that seems to me different is
consciousness of poverty as the most fundamental inequality, and one which can
co-exist with equality of opportunity for some women. The widening gap in
income and life chances between different women is one of the negative changes
of the past 25 years.
If the revived Scottish women's movement since the 1970s has much in common
with the rest of Britain, since around the mid-1980s it has become more
separate and consciously Scottish: arguments about gender and nationhood and
``the double knot in the peeny'' have been important, as has women's political
response to Conservative rule, and the way women have participated in building
a distinctive political culture. Disgruntlement with the ``double democratic
deficit'' has brought women actively into the process of constitutional reform.
As Isobel Lindsay from the Campaign for a Scottish Parliament and Alice Brown
at Edinburgh University, among others, have observed, this has been a catalyst
for a radical and assertive response to women's limited representation.
The prospect of a new legislature has galvanised interest and brought women
together from all sorts of political backgrounds and none. Arguments about a
different electoral system, sensible and ``family friendly'' parliamentary
procedures, authentic consultation, and the role of civic society have been as
important as 50/50 representation. Gender equality has become the cornerstone
of a vision of a Scottish parliament as more participatory and responsive; an
intrinsic part of the debates on access, accountability, and democracy.
Less commented on is how this has led to a wider stage for women's politics and
a different kind of dialogue with other players on it - a conversation which
has been perhaps a little more equal, with more real communication than in the
past. Rather than a women's movement which is wholly oppositional its voice is
now acknowledged, if still often misunderstood and talked over.
It is when women within and outwith traditional political structures have
worked, if not in clear accord, then at least in parallel and with some
communication and mutual respect, that most has been achieved. This was true
for the British legislation of the 1970s; it is also true of the quite rapid
porgress made on key women's issues in the Republic of Ireland in the 1980s and
1990s.
In Scotland, such a useful convergence, allied to a more pragmatic feminism, is
reason for cautious optimism. And reason to believe that interests and
approaches defined as ``women's'' are more and more part of a shared vision of
the kind of political future we want.
n Sue Innes is author of Making It Work, Women, Change and Challenge in the
90s, Chatto &amp; Windus.
Women's voices no longer go unheard, but the problem now is getting their views
to count as mainstream, argues Sue Innes
