<TEXT>
SKIERS are a faithful lot. Come budget or bank rates, inflation or skidding
currency, the addicts are now anxiously awaiting the first snowfalls, searching
out bargains and new areas, where their francs, schillings, pounds or lire can
go furthest.
So what's on the ski map for 1995/96?
In headline terms, the snow-sure resorts of the US and Canadian Rockies are
being strongly featured in the tour operators' brochures, since our two main
skiing countries, Austria and France, have pretentious currencies (15
schillings for a pound in Austria, and about seven francs in France) that have
made them expensive for British skiers.
Thomsons, the largest tour operator, have reintroduced four Rocky Mountain
resorts. In the US, the British beginners' favourite of Breckenridge, smart
Vail and Beaver Creek, and Winter Park, the nearest major resort to Denver,
offer flights from Manchester and Gatwick, with prices starting at #406 a week,
for flights and room only.
In lesser-known Canada, they're offering Banff and Lake Louise, both beautiful
areas with a good variety of skiing, Jasper, most suitable for beginners to
intermediates, and the highly challenging Whistler. Prices here start at #415
from Heathrow.
The debate about North America v Europe continues to run; certainly standards
of transatlantic safety are almost obsessional, while maintenance of the skis
and lifts is unbeatable, as are the standards of tuition and fun in the ski
schools, as well as the friendliness and welcome often missing in sometimes
surly France and Switzerland, though rarely in Austria.
There are more holidays on offer this year in tax-free Andorra, in the nearby
French Pyrenees and in Italy, particularly Livigno, where costs of extras,
passes, equipment hire and tuition are half of most other parts of Europe.
The black run bashers maintain that the Alps still have the most challenging
skiing, and that the vast connected areas such as the Val d'Isère/Tignes
circuit and the Trois Vallees in France, the huge St Anton-Lech region in
Austria and the Sella Ronda in Italy, have this as well as the cosiness, the
rustic huts and mountain restaurants of the traditional Alpine resorts.
WHETHER the beginners are children or adults, the choice of the ski resort is
critical. Few resorts are really suitable for experienced skiers and total
beginners, and certainly in year one it is best to compromise by choosing a
resort for the least experienced in the party, perhaps with classier resorts
nearby.
What are the special needs for a total learner?
It all starts with the ski school; English-language tuition is a must, as is an
understanding of how bad we Brits can be.
Cheap equipment hire and limited ski passes (which beginners may not need in
the early days) are sensible; there's no point in paying for the latest
equipment, or expensive passes covering miles of hillside.
The nursery slopes should be near the village centre, avoiding the need to lug
cumbersome equipment all over the hillside. Gentle, wide and easy slopes should
also be accessible, for the blissful time the learners move from the painful
snowplough to piste skiing.
Finally, there should be plenty of life and lots to do in the village or
resort, in case the beginner decides to drop out - this happens to about a
quarter of first-time skiers.
The best skiing country for beginners is still Austria - the natives are
welcoming, tuition is excellent and standardised throughout the country. Most
resorts have plenty of après ski activities.
Alpbach is a friendly and picturesque mountain village, with good nursery
slopes near the village, swimming, sleigh rides, tobogganing, indoor tennis, as
well as bars and cafes to keep holidaymakers happy off the slopes.
Obergurgl, only discovered in 1931 is high enough to have snow over a long
season - which means it is above the treeline and can be a bit bleak in
January. There's a good ski school that meets near the hotels, cosy apres ski,
plus two nearby resorts for more advanced skiers.
Skiing in France is superb, but by no means always for the beginners, and ski
classes tend to be large. There are miles of runs of most grades - but many are
too difficult for all but budding geniuses for the first few years.
La Plagne is a large, modern purpose-built resort, and like most of these, a
little light on atmosphere. The accommodation is largely in concrete towers,
but the ski schools are good, and nursery slopes excellent and well maintained.
Flaine is somewhat smaller, very popular with the British; not too far from the
airport, with good kindergarten and children's beginners classes - though the
après ski is a bit thin on the ground.
The United States is having a revival on the British ski market. The advantages
are the language, and excellent ski facilities, the disadvantages the long
flight and transfers, a problem with young children.
Breckenridge is a Colorado resort, an old silver mining town with lots of
restaurants and nightlife (although remember, those under 21 cannot get
alcoholic drinks) has excellent skiing, good facilities for beginners, while
the more expert skiers have decent skiing of their own.
Other resorts that are suitable for total beginners, but which aren't death to
skiers in the party; Westendorf, Igls, Soll and Niederau in Austria; Les Arcs,
Avoriaz, Courchevel, La Clusaz and Valmorel in France; Saas in Switzerland.
DON'T believe the hoary old chestnut that all you have to do with the very
young is to strap skis to their feet, and they'll be off down the slopes,
fearless, fully in control. It's a legend that insurance claims are made of.
Couples who have been skiing for blissful childless years think they can take
junior to their favourite (lots of black runs) resort, put him or her into ski
class and that's it - maybe by day three they'll be skiing together. Ha Ha!
Apart from the distance of the resort from the airport (the nearer the better),
it once again all starts with the ski school. I remember my first born lining
up, as a minority of one in a French class, falling over and so knocking down
half the class, with the pigeon English speaking instructor not very amused.
Tears - and total refusal to return on that trip.
British, or largely British classes, with English speaking instructors is an
absolute essential, as is the proximity of the class to your accommodation;
it's not fun walking for miles four times a day (or at least twice) delivering
or collecting junior, carrying his equipment before he causes serious injury to
others within ski-pole distance.
Choose a resort with plenty of non-skiing activities, in case the child drops
out. And of course if the kids are say under six, then an excellent nursery (or
obliging Granny) are vital.
Mayrhofen in Austria actually breaks the basic rule of the proximity of the
nursery slopes to the village - but since they collect children from the foot
of the cable car which is in the centre, keep them all day and deliver them
back to the village, it is my number one choice anywhere in the world.
THE ski school is a family affair, run by the Spiess family, started by Riki
Spiess, a former Olympic ski medallist, her grown up children and even
grandchildren - plus a cosy heated hut where the young skiers are made to relax
over lunch and a couple of cartoon films.
Hinterglemm is another village where learners have their own hillside, away
from the queues and traffic. Within a few days of tuition, children can usually
join one of the easy blue runs and maybe even undertake a seven kilometre run
back to the village - a triumph indeed.
The skiing is too good in many of the best French resorts to spend money on
extensive ski passes for beginners. The largest nursery slopes are probably at
Isola 2000, developed and built by a British company. As long as you stay at
the top end of the resort, the rather untidy Alpe d'Huez offers both a large
range of creches for pre-ski children, and British owned ski school for those
learning to ski.
Other resorts with excellent facilities for children include Flaine, Avoriaz
and La Plagne in France, Wengen and Saas Fee in Switzerland.
To entice families on to the slopes together, and reasonably economically,
Thomsons have chosen 16 resorts which offer savings on child prices,
supervision, free children's ski school, and some free lift passes.
Their Polar Bear Ski Club in five resorts provides children between four and
eight years old with mornings or afternoons on the slopes or fun and games for
non-skiing children, organised by NNEB trained representatives. The cost is
between #40-#90 a week.
Family ski specialists Ski Esprit (01252 616789) run half-day Snow Clubs on six
days every week at four French resorts, with horse-drawn rides, tobogganing,
nature trails, picnics and snow art, and some baby sitting - this costs #89 per
week, including lunches.
THERE'S no such thing as cheap skiing - but there are ways of making the whole
business less expensive.
Dates are crucial - avoid the high seasons, which include the Christmas and New
Year holidays and school half term. The best reductions are in January, after
New Year celebrations, and after Easter - when you have to go high to be sure
of snow.
If there are three or four of you, take a car package, offered by various tour
operators. A car is also very useful in the resort. You can reach most of the
French skiing areas in a very long day's driving with a change of driver, but
budget for an overnight stop for Austria and Switzerland.
Coach skiing holidays are the cheapest way to get to the snow - although not
suitable for small children, most coaches these days offer videos, reclining
seats and toilets.
Look out for last-minute bargains - companies offer real discounts of between
#50-#60, if you specify the resort, and they pick the accommodation.
Take advantage of the ski companies' special money-saving holidays - Thomsons
for example offer Learn to Ski Weeks in a couple of dozen resorts, where the
price includes equipment hire, English speaking instructors, discounts on ski
passes, clubs for children and even free babysitting.
Andorra, tucked away in the Pyrenees between France and Spain is the tax-free
country with friendly instructors, mainly British and Australian instructors,
perhaps missing the most challenging skiing, but with plenty to do off as well
as on the slopes. Arinsal and Soldev with wide, open runs are its best resorts
for beginners and intermediates, while advanced skiers will find more challenge
at Pas de la Casa, Andorra's highest resort. Boot and ski hire costs under #40
a week, with passes just over #50 - about half of what you can pay in France
and Austria.
Bulgaria is another budget choice, lacking perhaps the charm and après ski
options of the Alpine resorts, but what you miss in character, you'll make up
by real money savings.
In Pamporovo, there are 14 runs suitable for beginners, and at Borovets the
slopes are gentle and sunny. Cost of equipment hire is similar to that in
Andorra, but ski school is even cheaper, while a lift pass will be around of
#35.
Italy too has its advantages, and disadvantages for the budget skier. It is too
far to drive, and some of the distances from the airport can be horrific. But
equipment hire is even cheaper than in Andorra and Bulgaria (#28 for six days),
though lift passes cost more than in those countries.
Livigno is one of the most popular resorts, though the five hours plus drive
from the airport make it unsuitable for families with children. But there's
plenty of skiing, and the resorts of Bormio and Santa Caterina are on the same
pass. The village of Livigno is somewhat chaotic, but like much of Italy great
fun - with the added advantage that drinks are below the supposed duty-free
airport prices.
Cauterets and Barège in the French Pyrenees are just about accessible by car,
and much cheaper than some French Alpine resorts - though you'll have to pay
#60 or more for ski hire, and lift passes can cost from #100 upwards for six
days.
IF resorts for non-skiers seems like a contradiction, it refers to those who've
tried it and hated it, to those non-sporting partners or appendages who like
the scenery but not the scene, and to pregnant women decent enough to indulge
their partners by going along. As one who came under the latter heading on
several occasions, my own requirements have been those traffic free resorts
with lots of walks (usually with cross country Langlauf skiing) - Saas Fee in
Switzerland being a perfect example, and Australian resorts within easy reach
of Innsbruck or Salzburg, with good public transport. The lack of charm and
activities in Flaine and Les Menuires in France were two that nearly caused
serious domestic friction.
Choose a resort where there are lots of shops, perhaps a swimming pool, sleigh
transport and a lift system which allows you to go up to the mountain and
admire the scenery, and enjoy the huts and restaurants - returning to base by
cable car.
For the non-pregnant non-skiers, look out for skating, perhaps riding, good
places nearby for excursions and lots of activity, with the larger Austrian and
Swiss resorts being the most suitable.
Switzerland's Pearl of the Alps, Saas Fee deserves its title - a genuine
Valaisanne village, guarded by a glacier, quaint wooden cuckoo clock chalets
with logs stacked outside for the winter, no cars, no sky scrapers, outstanding
shopping, so what more can a non skier ask for?
Excellent school for beginners, and most important this - the slopes converge
in the heart of the village near the cafes, so that it's easy to meet up with
the rest of the party.
For the non-skiers, or those who want a day off, there's a really fine leisure
centre which they call a resort in a resort, with pools, saunas, gymnasium,
Turkish bath, plus a centre for cross country skiing and walking.
Fine shopping - look closely at some of the oldest chalets, half of which are
shops selling jewellery, watches, designer wear and other high quality goods
for a high quality resort.
IF you can, avoid January, when the sun never seems to top the mountains bowl,
and it's cold. In Austria, more than half of Seffield's winter holidaymakers
never set foot on skis - they spend their time . . . eating in some of the 70
or so restaurants, they play tennis on stupendous indoor courts, or try their
hand at bowling. In between, as with most Alpine resorts, there are delightful
walks in the woods on prepared paths.
Seffield is also one of Austria's largest cross-country centres, with more than
120 miles of prepared track. Cross-country is much cheaper than downhill
skiing, and even a beginner can lope off into the woods to enjoy the peace and
silence.
Innsbruck, the capital of the Austrian Tyrol, and not itself a ski resort,
seems to have found the ideal compromise - packaging five surrounding ski
resorts, while being based in the city itself.
All are linked from Innsbruck by a bus service, with the same ski pass serving
the entire region, offering a great variety of skiing (and sometimes snow
conditions) plus the advantage of a sophisticated city.
For those who will not go near anything resembling a ski, Innsbruck is a
delightful city with its echoes of grandeur of the Austro-Hungarian Empire,
combining with the quaintness of the Tyrol - usually traffic free streets of
arcades, rococo houses, baroque churches, shops selling high quality loden
clothes, plus more than 80 bars, restaurants and cafes.
Other resorts for non-skiers: Grindelwald, Wengen and Murren in Switzerland;
Soll and Kitzbuhel in Austria and Chamonix in France.
THERE can be few holiday situations as disastrous as heading off for the annual
ski pilgrimage and finding . . . no snow. And its arrival is totally and
horribly unpredictable.
Last year, from December onwards it lay deep and crisp and even over most
European ski resorts from December onwards. Yet for several years beforehand
the season has been starting later and later, with the best snows not arriving
until late February and March.
The package holidays tend to start in the second week of December, when many
``ski bargains'' can be found. But be warned, the height of the resort above
sea level is critical; generally you must be above 1400 metres before mid
January, or find a resort near a glacier. These include Kaprun, Zell am See,
Hintertux, Obergurgl, Lech and Stubai Valley, all in Austria; Saas Fee, St
Moritz, Zermatt and Verbier in Switzerland; Livigno, Cortina and Courmayeur in
Italy and Les Arcs, La Plagne, Chamonix, Tignes, Val Thorens and Meribel in
France.
The American and Canadian resorts probably have the longest season, from quite
early December to well into March.
It is also worth checking with the National Tourist Offices on the availability
of snow-making machinery. It does not provide snow for long runs, but it can
repair worn out bottlenecks and help to keep the runs down to the village open.
The Consumer Association's (#15.99) includes information on snowmaking, as well
as good early or late skiing.
THE prices quoted are for seven nights, per person, self catering (S/C), half
board (HB) or bed and breakfast (b&amp;b).
n Alpbach, Austria. Gasthof Post - HB. #338-#447 plus #30 Glasgow departure.
Thomsons.
n Breckenridge, USA. Liftside Inn - S/C. #446-#583 plus #35-#48 Manchester
departure. Thomsons
n Mayrhofen, Austria. Hotel Obermair - b&amp;b. #306-#396 plus #30 Glasgow
departure. Thomsons.
n La Plagne, France. Belle Plagne Apartments - S/C. #282-#337 plus #30 Glasgow
departure. Polar Bear Club for children. Ski School 4-8's morning #59. Polar
Bear Club 3-8's all day #89. Mornings/Afternoons only #49. Optional lunches
#3-#7 per day. Creche for 18 months-3 years all day #78. Thomsons.
n Andorra, Arinsal. Poblado Apartments S/C. #219-#279 plus #17 Manchester
departure. Panorama.
n Borovets, Bulgaria. Rila Apartments S/C. #249-#359 plus #17 Manchester
departure. Crystal.
n Saas Fee, Switzerland. Saas Fee Apartments S/C. #319-#399 plus #35 Glasgow
departure. Crystal.
As sticks and boots are hauled out again from the
jumble in the attic, Jill Crawshaw offers a
comprehensive guide to the best of the slopes
