<TEXT>
Celebrity surfers
Andi Robertson examines the
rehabilitation of snow bums as skibiz recognises potentially lucrative
new markets
EXPERIENCING near exponential growth currently, snowboarding is the
mid-nineties boom winter sport. Only a couple of years ago, the struggle was to
gain acceptance on the slopes of some of the more conservative resorts. Now
there's a realisation that this is not just a short-term youth fad, complete
with a bad attitude, but it could in fact become a worthwhile profit centre.
Significantly perhaps, this coincided with a projection that 4.8 million
snowboarders will be on the slopes worldwide by the year 2000 - which would
equate to roughly one in three piste users being on a board, not skis.
It has doubled its number of participants each year, a trend unlikely to be
broken as the marketeers and hype merchants seize snowboarding's potential for
the consumer advertising world to sell everything from energy drinks to
breakfast cereal.
Add to that the growing number of celebrity boarders: Sting, Peter Gabriel,
Jamiroquai, Seal, Paula Abdul, Uma Thurman, Daryl Hannah, Eddie Vedder and
Stone Gossard of Pearl Jam, and Adam Yauch of the Beastie Boys, and there's
little wonder that every resort that can, is opening its arms and welcoming the
prodigal sport as it inexorably heads mainstream.
Although its roots in the USA date back to the late sixties with Tom Sims
regarded as one of the founding fathers, latterly along with Sherwin Popper,
Dimitre Milovich and Jake Burton Carpenter who have all contributed to varying
degrees. It is undoubtedly the latter whose company, Burton, has popularised
many of the technological developments which have ultimately made the sport
all-mountain and all-terrain.
The majority of today's boarders still come from a surfing, windsurfing or
skateboarding background, with a small, but growing percentage completely
abandoning skis in favour of a board. Skateboarding has left the strongest
imprint, while the obvious common manoeuvres and tricks are readily translated
from street to slope - or indeed icy half pipe - with no separate phrase-book
needed for their cryptic descriptions.
``The average board buyer is still very much in the 17 to 29-year-old age
bracket,'' confirms Andy Groom of Glasgow snowboard shop Mach, ``but it's
really only recently that we've started to see more families, for example, come
in and hire a board to try for the first time. As well as the exposure it's
enjoying I'm sure that word is starting to filter through that it's actually
easier to learn than skiing.''
The British Snowboard Association now has a recognised three-level teaching
qualification which is highly regarded around the world; and it is now working
closely alongside BASI, the British Association of Ski Instructors, in its
ongoing tuition developments.
All the Scottish resorts now have some level of qualified teaching on their
hills, and boards can be hired on the hill, or from most specialist retailers.
Aviemore snowboard shop Boardwiser reckon to have hired to more than 9000
customers last season and this year will have rental equipment for children as
young as seven or eight: ``Currently boards must be one of the main presents on
loads of children's Christmas lists, because we're inundated at the moment with
parents looking to find out what's best for their kids,'' says Boardwiser's
Justin.
The competition scene equally owes much to surfing and skateboarding. While
there is a mainly alpine-based circuit run by skiing's governing body, the
Federation Internationale de Ski (FIS), who currently hold the keys of the door
to the Olympics (where the sport will feature in the Japan games of 1998);
snowboarding's own international body, the ISF, runs a flourishing circuit of
its own which is well supported by the trade and runs the full range of
freestyle and boardercross plus gate events.
The hard-core ISF members take exception to being described by the FIS as
merely a discipline of skiing and are campaigning for Olympic status in their
own right. Meanwhile riders who compete in FIS-sanctioned events cannot go on
to race at ISF events.
Boardercross is the latest contest to capture the boarders' competitive zeal.
It is a mass start downhill race which takes in jumps and tricks en route and
was the most popular event at last year's well-supported British Championships
in Val d'Isere.
A full calendar of competitions is already planned for next year in Scotland,
ranging from the Scottish Championships which will be a mainly freestyle
contest and a boardercross, to a fun weekend at Cairngorm sponsored by clothing
company Westbeach.
Typifying the moves by UK resorts to accommodate the unique needs of the
snowboarder, Cairngorm will have a custom-built snowboard fun park in
operation. Free to users, it will be designed and maintained by Boardwiser and
situated on the Fiacaill Ridge. It will include big quarter-pipe jumps, table
tops and railslides with at least half a dozen exciting ``toys'' according to
the shop's staff.
As much as anything it is the level of technology - which has stayed abreast,
at least, of what the leading edge exponents are doing - which has meant that
riders have continued to enjoy the sport, making progress. Time was, when
powder snow was the snowboarder's raison d'etre, but now with the advances in
board construction, making them stiffer and lighter, even old hard packed snow
can be enjoyed.
There are four main types of board. Freeride boards cover all types of terrain
and conditions, and along with freestyle boards - used for tricks and spins -
should be the first purchase of the newcomer. JIB boards are for more advanced
skate style tricks and fun-park riding while freecarve boards are for
alpine-style riding with hard boots.
A specialist retailer is undoubtedly the best first stop for the newcomer. Most
have been around since the sport started in Scotland and will give good advice
on where to go and learn - and what to hire or buy.
</TEXT>
