<HEADLINE>Start to feel the heat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lady Claire Macdonald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093831</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOUP, that most versatile of all dishes, comes in many differing guises. As a
family we eat soup as the standard Macdonald family lunch throughout the
autumn, winter and spring.
Early in the new year I intend to give some thought to main-course soups, as I
think of them. Today my attention is focused upon an altogether more elegant
aspect - soup as a first course. I feel that soup as a first course has been
forgotten. We have all tended towards the knife-and-fork type of first course,
imagining it to be more impressive. We are wrong! With one or two provisos, few
first courses can beat a good soup in our lengthy cold weather months.
These provisos are the soup shouldn't be too thick, which is not only inelegant
but makes it far too filling when followed by a main course and pudding, and
that great care is taken in its making.
To explain myself on this last point, the most vital prerequisite for
first-class soup is really good stock. I tend to use chicken stock for pretty
well all my soups, but if you don't eat meat, make vegetable stock, which takes
10 minutes in a microwave oven, and 40-45 minutes on a conventional cooker.
All homemade stock is better by far than a cube and water, and better, too,
than ready-made bought stock. Good stock makes all the difference not only to
the taste of soup but also to its texture.
Before I turn to the variety of soups which make suitable first course
subjects, there are a number of ways to dress up a good soup - I hesitate to
use the word garnish. One of the most obvious garnishes are croutons. These
shouldn't be deep fried because that renders them saturated with fat, but an
even golden brown colour is easily reached if you bake your croutons. Brush the
slices of bread on each side with melted butter, cut off the crusts, and slice
into fine and neat cubes.
Brush a baking tray with melted butter and spread the bread over the tray. Bake
till the depth of colour is reached - open the oven and shake the contents of
the tray a couple of times as they bake. You can flavour croutons with curry
powder or bashed cumin seeds, or sprinkle them with freshly grated Parmesan
cheese halfway through baking.
Croutons render serving bread or rolls unnecessary and should be handed round
in a bowl with a spoon - this prevents them from becoming soggy as they sit in
the hot soup.
Herbs make a good garnish: not chopped parsley, but a leaf of flat-leaved
parsley, or a sprig of dill - good on leek and potato soup. Other garnishes can
be a fine chopping of a relevant ingredient of the soup - finely diced apples
in the soup recipe today. Or skinned, diced and deseeded tomatoes chopped
finely or sliced into slivers in a smooth tomato and carrot soup.
Which brings me to the content of smart soups - for my taste, beetroot makes
one of the very best. Not only does it taste so good but it looks positively
beautiful, with its richly ecclesiastical purple hue. I always feel a twinge of
guilt when I serve Bortsch because I have always understood true Bortsch to be
made with duck stock. I never make duck stock, only chicken.
To make Bortsch thin enough for a dinner party two large or three smaller
beetroot cooked in 1!s pints of stock give the right texture.
Carrot soups, flavoured with ginger and garlic, liquidised and sieved when
cooked to get the desired smoothness of texture, make  memorable eating. The
quantity of  garlic and ginger needn't be feared; the result, if both are well
cooked, is a very pleasing glow of flavour.
Lady Claire Macdonald praises the          oft-neglected culinary virtues of
soup
</TEXT>
