<HEADLINE>Spaniard picked to head Nato.  Choice of Solana ends weeks of Alliance crisis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093832</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
NATO ambassadors unanimously picked Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana as
the new head of the Alliance today, ending six weeks of often bitter
transatlantic arguments.
``Ambassadors have agreed by consensus to propose Javier Solana, currently
Spanish Minister of Foreign Affairs, as Secretary-General of Nato and chairman
of the North Atlantic Council,'' the Alliance announced.
The choice of the 53-year-old Spaniard will be formally endorsed at a meeting
of Nato foreign ministers in Brussels on Tuesday.
The Spaniard will replace Belgium's Willy Claes, who was forced to quit on
October 20 after being implicated in a bribery scandal involving his party in
the late 1980s.
Nato had desperately wanted to resolve the succession before it sends a
60,000-strong force to police the peace in Bosnia. The first elements may leave
for Bosnia as early as tomorrow.
It will be the first time the Alliance has had a secretary-general from a
country whose armed forces are not fully part of Nato's integrated military
structure.
Diplomats stressed that Spain, unlike France, was a member of the Alliance's
nuclear planning group and participated in military planning.
However, Solana must be the first Nato chief to have campaigned actively
against his country joining the Alliance.
The Spanish Socialist Party swept to power in 1982 on a ticket that promised to
tke the country out of Nato if the people voted for such a move in a
referendum, and Solana used the issue as part of his platform.
He became the Minister of Culture in the first post-Franco Socialist government
and remains the only member of the Spanish Cabinet to have served alongside
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez throughout his 13 years in power.
Carlos Miranda, Spain's ambassador to Nato, who as Dean of the North Atlantic
Council chaired today's informal meeting, welcomed the choice.
``This is a very good and important day for Spain,'' he told reporters in
Madrid, adding that the appointment was ``a great recognition of Spain's
contribution to the Alliance''.
Britain said Solana had the right attributes for a tough job. ``We are
confident he has the right qualities and experience to take on this demanding
post,'' said Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind.
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel commented: ``Javier Solana is a
first-class choice. (He) combines a European outlook and a commitment to
transatlanticism with the ability to lead. He has demonstrated this clearly
during the Spanish presidency of the European Union, which is just ending.''
The news came as Danish Foreign Minister Uffe Ellemann-Jensen announced in
Copenhagen that he was withdrawing his candidacy for the top Nato job.
``I congratulate my former Spanish colleague,'' he said in a statement. ``I
express the hope that he will use it to work for a strengthening of the
transatlantic ties as well as a strengthening of the European pillar of Nato.''
Solana emerged as a clear favourite for the post after the United States vetoed
former Dutch Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers, the European candidate, on November
10 and the French refused to agree to Ellemann-Jensen, who was Washington's
choice.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
