<HEADLINE>Stilton, apple &amp; celery soup</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093833</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Serves 6-8
1!s pints good chicken or vegetable stock
2oz butter
2 onions, skinned and chopped
2 good eating apples, eg Cox's, cored, skins left on and chopped
3 washed sticks of celery, trimmed and chopped
6oz Stilton, or other blue cheese, well crumbled
A grating of nutmeg, pepper - taste to see if salt is needed and add salt
accordingly.
Melt the butter in a saucepan and cook the chopped onion for several minutes,
until it is really soft and just beginning to turn colour. Add the chopped
celery and cook for a further couple of minutes. Stir in the chopped apples and
don't worry about the skins - the soup will be sieved later on) and pour in the
stock.
Simmer gently till the celery is soft. Cool, liquidise, adding the cheese to
the liquidiser. You can use any good blue cheese in this recipe. Season with
nutmeg and pepper, and salt if it is needed. Sieve the soup. Reheat carefully,
in a clean saucepan, and taking care not to let the soup boil, which will make
the texture granular. If you like, stir a couple of tablespoons of chopped
flat-leaved parsley through the soup just before serving.
</TEXT>
