<HEADLINE>Cracking the Stone Age code</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LORN MacINTYRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093834</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Walking in all of
the squares
Archibald S Thom
Argyll Publishing, #16.99
HISTORY
HELPING to build a bridge over the Salmon River in Ontario in 1913, Sandy Thom
saw one of the Red Indian squad throwing his sledge- hammer into the water far
below. Several other Indians scrambled down into the river to retrieve the
hammer which hadn't been thrown in a temper, as Thom thought. The Indians
brought up the pike that the thrower had seen from the heights.
It was a lesson for Alexander Thom. Ancient practices can survive in a modern
context. He was to use this insight when he came to study standing stones and
circles in Scotland and beyond. Had they been thrown together, or raised to a
design?
Thom was the classic lad o' parts: from a Carradale, Argyll, farm (born 1894)
to Oxford as professor of civil engineering, via a teaching post at Glasgow
university and important work on gun ships, flying boats and Spitfires in two
world wars. Retirement is a restriction of cerebral function for many people,
but Thom had a new career in the sights of his theodolite.
A superb sailor and navigator, he had entered the quiet anchorage of East Loch
Roag on Lewis on a summer evening in 1933 to see the rising moon with the
stones of Callanish, the ``Stonehenge of Scotland,'' silhouetted against it.
``After dinner we went ashore to explore. I saw by looking at the Pole star
that a north-south line existed in the complex. This fascinated me, as I knew
that when the site was built no star of any magnitude had been at, or near the
celestial pole.
``Precession had not yet brought Polaris as near to the celestial pole as it is
now. I wondered whether the alignment was a chance occurrence or whether it had
been deliberately built that way.''
Thom had found a subject to which he was to devote most of his time and
creative brilliance on his retirement from Oxford in 1961. He collected
information on as many megalithic sites as possible, as far apart as the Orkney
and Brittany, arguing (as Magnus Magnusson stated in the Chronicle television
programme he made with Thom) that ``Stone Age people were not just simple
primitives. They could be intelligent and sophisticated mathematicians and
astronomers to whom time was an exercise in science, using stones as calendars
and clocks; men who could measure and survey with the accuracy of a modern
theodolite.''
At Kintraw there is a standing stone, a large ruined cairn, a deep gully and on
the far side of the gully, 20 feet further up, a large boulder on a ledge like
a platform. Thom was convinced that a Stone Age man, standing on the platform,
made his first observation of the winter solstitial sun setting in the Paps of
Jura behind Ben Shianti 30 miles away.
Thom's book Megalithic Sites in Britain (1967) caused much controversy and
scepticism, but he was a man sure in his opinions and in his mathematics. The
appeal of this biography by his son and collaborator Archibald is not only the
great affection and respect he had for his father, but because of its wandering
narrative.
The Thoms lived at The Hill Farm, Dunlop, Ayrshire, where Alexander built his
own house, Thalassa, in 80 days. How invigorating it is to read the story of a
man of independent mind who seems to have cracked ``the Stone Age code,''
whatever the sceptics say.
LORN MacINTYRE
</TEXT>
