<HEADLINE>Shadow of 1968 falls over France paralysed by public sector strike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicholas Powell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>Paris diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093835</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Jacques Chirac must be seeking posthumous guidance this weekend from
the spirit of General de Gaulle, the man he claims to follow, as the nationwide
public sector strike in France gets even worse.
There are already no trains and no public transport. Half the country's postal
sorting offices have stopped work and many universities are closed. Electricity
and gas workers have gone on strike and teachers have voted for a stoppage next
week.
Air traffic at Orly Airport was disturbed yesterday when maintenance workers
occupied the runways. Last night, two of the main unions, CGT and FO, pushed
for the strike to be extended to other public sector branches and announce they
are ready to continue their action until December 12.
The student riots and general strike of May 1968 which almost toppled General
de Gaulle has become a nervous topic of conversation in government circles as
France slithers further towards economic paralysis this weekend. On Thursday,
France's Prefets, the regional representatives of central government, had talks
with Prime Minister Alain Juppe about alternative means of transport and
requisitioning the army.
Mr Juppe has even been said to have had television facilities installed in his
Paris offices in order to address the nation in case of extreme difficulty.
President Chirac, meanwhile, who kept cautiously in the wings last week,
leaving his ministers to stand front stage and face the abuse, is going to have
to take firm action of some sort.
For the government has dug in, repeating it will not go back on welfare reform,
waiting to see which way public opinion will turn, and hoping, unrealistically,
that disagreements will weaken the unions. Already at a historically low
popularity level, Mr Juppe, ``a man so wounded that he can no longer feel
pain'' as one commentator put it, dare not change tack. To do so at such an
early stage of Mr Chirac's presidency would deprive the latter of credibility
for the rest of his seven-year mandate.
Dissolving the National Assembly and calling a General Election, as did
President Chirac's role model, General de Gaulle, in 1968, appears futile,
given the huge majority he already enjoys. A national referendum on the welfare
reforms which provoked the strikes is an increasing possibility.
President Chirac's Gaullist RPR party, meanwhile, is organising a demonstration
by its supporters in Paris on Thursday - exactly as the general's followers
staged a giant march on the Champs Elysee in 1968 to help extinguish the May
riots. To add to the government's pain, meanwhile, seven by-elections are being
held in the Paris region tomorrow.
The strikes have scuppered all hopes of increased pre-Christmas spending. As if
the economic consequences were not dire enough, figures published last week
have brought even deeper gloom: consumer spending is down, unemployment has
increased for the third consecutive month, and France is heading for zero
growth in 1996.
It is not only the extent of the strikes, and the discomfort they entail, but
also the violence of the protests that has proved a shock. One hundred thousand
students and workers took part in demonstrations in 12 towns and cities on
Thursday. The marches in Paris and Nantes in Britanny ended in violence,
apparently committed by outside elements, who ransacked a university cafeteria
and library and looted shops. They destroyed bus shelters and telephone kiosks
and set alight cars and buses.
Physical destruction was met yesterday with verbal violence when the government
accused unions of lying about their plans concerning the state-controlled
sector.
Even supporters of the government are dismayed by the tactlessness with which
Mr Juppe, after doing little during his first months in power to honaour
President Chirac's spectacular election promises on unemployment and
relaunching the economy, has piled reform upon reform within a very short
period, without consulting unions or explaining his intentions properly.
Changes to France's deeply indebted welfare state have been introduced at the
same time as reforms of the country's equally overdrawn rail service and the
pension schemes of public employees. The abolition of certain tax allowances
affecting all salaried workers have also been put forward without proper
explanation. To cap it all, Mr Juppe announced he would push his measures
through by decree, to avoid debate in the National Assembly.
</TEXT>
