<TEXT>
n You, the vast majority - Protestants and Catholics alike - must not allow the
ship of peace to sink on the rock of old habits and hard grudges - Bill Clinton.
n My Christmas wish is that peace and love will last in Ireland forever -
Catherine Hamill (9) to Bill Clinton.
n The most ultimate human being is a woman who likes football. You know,
someone who lies back and thinks of England and who knows who's in the team -
Craig Charles.
n Judges still seem to think that any woman who goes to a man's home is
``asking for it'' and so does not deserve the full protection of the law -
Helena Kennedy QC.
n You are Queenie! Queenie! - Silvana Ashby to her husband, David Ashby MP and
his friend Edward O'Byrne.
n Is this the Secretary of State's big idea: weekend breaks for the Cabinet?
After all the hype, all the publicity, is this the best he could come up with?
- George Robertson MP on Michael Forsyth's new vision for the treatment of
Scottish politics.
n Mummy, what's a mystery lover? - Nathalie Faldo (9) to her mother Gill,
estranged wife of Nick.
n The Lewisham education deputy hails from south of the Thames, where most
persons of colour live - The guide, issued by the US Embassy in London, on why
Sarah Ebjana had been invited to Hillary Clinton's coffee morning to
``interface'' with some of Britain's most distinguished women.
n What had they done to her? The men with the mind-machines have captured her
at last, sucked the life and guts out of her, fashioned her into the only
acceptable model - a fully-fledged First Stepford Wife. She sits stiffly like a
mannequin, her head nodding up and down mechanically, her expression glazed,
half smiling, hardly changing, her views anodyne, her words as carefully
manicured as the lawns outside the window. What have they done to the woman who
was one of the brightest lawyers of her generation? - Polly Toynbee on Hillary
Clinton.
n It is both the best of times and the worst of times to be a woman - Hillary
Clinton.
n John (Lennon) was the one I admired most. He was so witty . . . It was the
wit that appealed to me, but I suppose he was a bit too unconventional for my
personal life. But, then again, I don't know. I was a bit of a raver - Joan
Bakewell on the Beatles.
n They say there hasn't been a war for 50 years. The truth is World War Three
has been going on and nobody's twigged it - Peter McDougall, writing in The
Herald after being attacked at the weekend.
</TEXT>
