<HEADLINE>Music Teenage Fanclub and the Pastels, Barrowland, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Williamson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093838</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF the Pastels are the most obvious support act for Teenage Fanclub,
particularly in Glasgow, then they are also the most apt. Only a few songs into
their set, remarkably their first Barrowland show in their 12-year existence,
they shared aesthetic and songwriting values. In short, the two bands listen to
the same kind of records: the right ones.
In spite of the self-mocking references to ``our usual lack of
professionalism'', this is one of the Pastels' most cohesive sets for some
time. With flute and an additional guitar augmenting the three permanent band
members who share lead vocal duties, the set mixes the best of Mobile Safari
(Coolport, Basement Scam, and Token Collecting) with a knowing cover version,
an offshoot project song and a nod to the past in Truck, Train, Tractor.
It is also quite obvious why Teenage Fanclub, and not the Pastels, are
headlining. Where the latter's excellence is studied and sporadic, the
Fanclub's comes in sackloads and is made all the more remarkable by its
apparent ease of execution.
Where most other homecoming shows by established acts rely on crowd-pleasing,
watered down, souped-up versions of their best songs with a great light show,
the Fanclub delve into the back catalogue and recorded highlight, Grand Prix,
with only the warmth of the songs to call on.
Such is the charm, self-assurance, and unassuming nature of both the band and
the songs that to succeed in this manner makes for a much greater triumph. Star
Sign, The Concept, Radio, and Sparky's Dream played back to back make for a
great quartet of intelligent and timeless pop songs while 120 Minutes and
Versimilitude show the qualitative depths of the band.
</TEXT>
