<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Tracey Craik produced a final-round 75 yesterday to win the American
Express Tour qualifying school tournament at the La Manga Club, Spain.
With a level-par aggregate of 288, Craik finished two strokes ahead of
Australian Anne-Marie Knight, with Tracy Loveys one stroke further behind.
There were 41 players who earned exempt places on the Tour next season,
including Myra McKinlay, who had a closing-round 74 to finish on 298, and Morag
Wright, whose 78 enabled her to qualify with one stroke to spare.
``It wasn't very good today,'' said Craik. ``I missed a short putt on the
eighth and that seemed to put me out of my stride, but the cheque will help to
pay for the week.''
The winner had started the final round four strokes ahead of Loveys, who
birdied two of her first three holes, while Craik drove into rough to drop an
early shot at the second.
She redeemed this with a birdie at the third, where she hit a  No. 9-iron to
eight feet before finding sand to take 4 at the short fifth, then missed a putt
of 18 inches for another 4 at the eighth.
Craik then pulled her No. 3-iron into sand to drop another shot at the ninth
and, out in 39, was now only one stroke clear of Loveys and two ahead of
Knight, the losing finalist in this year's US amateur championship.
A birdie at the eleventh from 20ft steadied Craik who came home in 36, with
Knight moving into second place with a birdie at the last to creep past Loveys.
