<HEADLINE>God answered: `Do what it says in the text'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093840</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEATRE
RALPH RICHARDSON: The Authorised Biography
John Miller
Sidgwick and Jackson, #16.99
IT comes as a surprise to be reminded that of that triumvirate of theatrical
knights who dominated the British theatre for almost half a century, Olivier,
Gielgud and Richardson, the first to be knighted was Ralph Richardson, possibly
the least remembered at the moment of the trio.
He got his knighthood in the 1947 New Year Honours, a deeply jealous Olivier
had to wait six months for the Birthday Honours for his, while Gielgud was out
in the cold until the Coronation list in 1953.
Gielgud is still with us, the theatrical equivalent of the Queen Mother, a
much-loved institution in his own right. As for Olivier, his reputation is
probably at its nadir, and it is currently modish to sneer at his mannerisms
and tricks in performance. But nobody seems to bother about Richardson, who, in
his prime, managed to be what neither of the others succeeded in becoming - a
genuine star in both the cinema and the theatre.
He was a strange man, prone to violent outbursts, and patently haunted by
demons, who disliked directors, and was ruthless with underlings who dared
upstage him. He loved motor bikes, drank gin like water, kept ferrets and had a
Spanish-speaking parrot called Jose, which he treated like a human being.
Audiences loved him, and his colleagues, in spite of all the difficulties of
coping with such an unpredictable man, found him inspiring. John Miller has
turned to many of them in his attempt to analyse what made a Richardson
performance and the result is a fascinating, detailed picture of the actor at
work. Where this admirable, highly readable books falls down is in its portrait
of the private man. We learn very little about Richardson as a husband - he was
married twice, and had a son, Charles, by his second wife, Meriel Forbes.
Charles appears a couple of times and then completely disappears from his
father's life, or so it seems.
The book records Richardson's long pre-war career and the origins of his
lifelong theatrical partnership and friendship with Gielgud. He was one of the
truly great Falstaffs, a wonderful Peer Gynt, a superb Sir Peter Teazle, an
immaculate performer of the plays of J B Priestley, while in the cinema he was
mesmerising in films like The Fallen Idol, The Sound Barrier and The Heiress.
Gielgud, who contributes an admiring preface, recalls how, when he was
directing School for Scandal, Richardson as Sir Peter, worried about how to
make his first entrance, got stuck during rehearsals. ``Should I have a
newspaper in my hand? A walking-stick? Or be taking snuff, perhaps?,'' he would
ask. At last, one morning he walked down to the footlights and announced -
``You know, Johnny, I prayed to God last night to tell me how to come on in
this opening scene, and this morning God answered `Do what it says in the text,
just come on'. ''
WILLIAM RUSSELL
</TEXT>
