<HEADLINE>Thirsts and the thistle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW  MACKAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093841</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT seemed not so long ago that Tennents at its Wellpark brewery in Glasgow
introduced two new beers to the Scottish market. At that time Tennent's
70/-Velvet Ale, a 3.5% ABV keg beer, and Aitken's 80/-cask ale, with an ABV of
4.2%, have gained wide ground across the country.
Perhaps heartened by a degree of success in these products, the brewers at
Wellpark have had the recipe books out again and this time their ingenuity has
created two new beers; Tennent's White Thistle, a cask-conditioned ale, and SD
Premium Lager, believed to be the first mixed-gas dispense draught lager.
Born out of Tennent's association in sponsorship of Scottish rugby, White
Thistle stems from the emblem that is woven on to the internationalists'
jerseys. Indeed, it has become the official beer of the Scottish Rugby Union.
Tennents has certainly a creditable performance in past sports sponsorship and
the SRU will surely benefit from the brewer's association with the league and
the new 1556 Cup.
White Thistle is certainly worth a try. It is dark in colour with good malt and
hop flavour, and with an ABV of 3.7% it has an acceptable session-drinking
strength. In a market area where uniqueness of flavour and individuality are
the hallmarks of many beers, White Thistle will certainly not disgrace itself.
It will certainly be the cause of a number of conversions.
The other product from Wellpark is Tennent's SD Premium Lager. Its name has
been derived from the genius of Bass Brewing's marketing department who after
many months of meetings and mind exercises drew up a short list from the draff
and whittled this down to the moniker, SD.
However, as a brew SD is totally different. Dispensed at a temperature of 2¡C
it is four degrees colder than the normal serving temperature of lager. It is
also dispensed using mixed gas which gives the beer a tight creamy head. At 5%
ABV it is in the premium class and a new design of bar font and tall glass give
it a kind of princely status. Indeed, its appearance is also supported with a
range of point-of-sale items such as T-shirts and holdalls.
When Cellarman first sampled SD it was a struggle to find taste. The head
created by the mixed gas overwhelmed the beer and those extra degrees of chill
almost called for gloves to prevent frostbite in the fingers. But just the way
that food can be served too hot to appreciate its taste then so too beer can be
served too cold to capture those tiny, delicate darts of flavour.
As the beer warmed more to my palate then so too did better flavour come
through. The mixed gas head hung on determinedly, however, and was more of an
intrusion than it is in stout.
Apart from the premium status as a beer, SD will be sold at a premium price
which is expected to be about 25p a pint more than ``lesser'' lagers. But
taking the ABV of 5% apart, for lager drinkers SD will be quite a different
experience. Unlike Tennent's lager or Carlsberg lager, SD is not the owner of a
particularly distinctive flavour and it may have more appeal with the drinker
who enjoys beer such as Caffrey's and who dislikes the high fizz factor found
in lager.
SD is certainly different but so too was Ken Brooker of Harviestoun's
Schiehallion, a pioneering cask-conditioned lager which when introduced had a
certain gamble factor attached but which has gone on to be a huge success.
Maclay followed and in the summer 1314, a cask-conditioned seasonal lager,
flowed forth.
But perhaps SD needs a second chance, this time with the gloves off and not at
1100 hours.
ANDREW MACKAY
</TEXT>
