<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trade gap narrows to #972m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093843</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S visible trade gap with the rest of the world narrowed to a better
than expected #972m in September from August's revised #1258m as exports rose
faster than imports.
However, the whole of the change in the overall deficit comes from the
previously reported deficit with with non-EU countries which fell from #1000m
to #702m, largely reflecting a rise in exports to North America. This was later
reversed in the October non-EU trade outcome.
For September the deficit on trade with the EU (the new component in the
figures) was little changed at #270m against August's #248m.
After stripping out oil (a surplus of #403m against #292m in August) and
erratic items defined as ships, aircraft, precious stones and silver, the
underlying gap improved slightly over the month from #1586m to #1402m.
The Central Statistical Office said that despite the improvement in the deficit
in September the latest estimate of trend suggests that the whole world visible
deficit is widening.
Analysts considered that the October global data will probably show the
improvement in the deficit between August and September more than reversed
given the non-EU figures for that month.
In terms of both value and volume with the latter excluding oil and erratics,
the visible trend is for is for imports to rise slightly faster than exports so
the gap is likely to deteriorate moderately in the months ahead.
However, when overseas economic activity begins to stengthen, there could be
some improvement from next spring, according to some sector analysts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
