<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Last verse from RLS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093845</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN AT this, the eighth and last volume, it all seems incomplete. Perhaps
that's as it should be. It was not a life to be done up in ribbons as a gift to
posterity.
Besides, the story has been told well enough and often. Stevenson guessed most
of it himself, with the tainted percipience that comes from constant,
hag-ridden infirmity. He intimated his own mortality, cool as you like, writing
jovially to Edmund Gosse, just days before death arrived, ``I was not born for
age''.
A book such as this, the final instalment of the yarn and an exemplary piece of
scholarship in its own right, might seem to call for some sort of definitive
statement. The truth is there have been too many valedictory speeches made over
Robert Louis Balfour Stevenson. It is as though all the scholars and
biographers and journalists have conspired. We saw, or imagined, criminal
neglect while succumbing to that implausible charm. It may not have been the
best of combinations.
Now, with RLS restored and his reputation as secure as any can be, there is a
chance to conclude the puerile debate between the ``debunkers'', who got their
revenge in early, and the restorers who have been at work in the 40-some years
since J C Furnas and David Daiches began to bring the real Stevenson to light.
With these letters finally in print we can stop treating the writer as a piece
of his own fiction, cease the vicarious adventuring, and consider the artist,
meaning the work.
Stevenson's prose remains a thing of wonder, as people as diverse as Graham
Greene and Jorge Louis Borges have testified. Its punctiliousness owes a
little, perhaps, to his legal training and a good deal, I think, to the
Enlightenment stylists like Hume whose anglicised (Hume would have said
``purified'') Scottish diction was still evident, even in polite society, when
Louis was a boy.
Then there was his auto-didacticism, the apprenticeship of the ``sedulous ape''
mimicking Addison and Steele. Stevenson's paragraphs are like complicated
Victorian instruments, the clauses cogs and spinning gears, the whole
brass-bound with semantic rigour. He is, in all things - politics, family
crises, literary criticism, descriptions of nature - precise.
But then add the metaphorical glitter of Stevenson's Francophilia, nowhere more
evident than in these (generally casual) letters. It gave him his romantic
streak, his panache, and invigorated, perhaps even at an unconscious level, his
storyteller's gift. Thus, even in notes dashed off or dictated it is, always,
the sheer vivacity of the writing that entertains, no matter how grim the
subject. So the veteran of sickness could write to a seriously ill J M Barrie
in July, 1894: ``No, Barrie, 'tis in vain they try to alarm me with their
bulletins.
``No doubt you're ill and unco ill I believe; but I have been so often in the
same case that I know pleurisy and pneumonia are in vain against Scotsmen who
can write. (I once could.) You cannot imagine probably how near me this common
calamity brings you. Ce que j'ai tousse dans ma vie!'' As the world knows, he
packed an amazing amount into these last two years, ``up to the knees in one
novel, up to the waist in another, and over head and ears in verses''. When not
writing he was planning to write; when not toiling he was itching to toil.
In addition to paying work there were the 300 or so letters preserved here,
sometimes very long ones; a publicity campaign in defence of Samoa's natives
(Lord Rosebery, then Foreign Secretary and another correspondent, eventually
warned local officials to leave RLS be) and the aftermath of his wife Fanny's
mental breakdown (still a source of controversy).
There are meditations on his lineage (here he writes to Samuel Smiles, no less,
inquiring after a connection between George Stephenson and his own tribe); an
estate to run, family to feed, thoughts of home (``I wished this morning to see
the hills of Fife in their winter hap . . .''), bills to pay and, always, the
shadow of illness.
RLS was a curious combination of happy charm and pessimism; it may have been
the key to the man. Here he writes to his old friend and lawyer Charles Baxter,
with a native rebellion going on, after fretting over royalties (``Suppose we
got 1000 from the magazines . . .'') and his will:
``It is strange; I must seem to you to blaze in a Birmingham prosperity and
happiness; and to myself, I seem a failure. The truth is, I have never got over
the last influenza yet, and am miserably out of heart and out of kilter. Lungs
pretty right, stomach nowhere, spirits a good deal overshadowed; but we'll come
through it yet, and cock our bonnets. I confess with sorrow that I am not yet
quite sure about the intellects; but I hope it is only one of my usual periods
of non-work. They are more unbearable now, because I cannot rest. No rest but
the grave for Sir Walter! O, the words ring in a man's head.''
The strangest thing about these letters is that they can read almost as a
narrative in their own right, yet it will be a rare reader who does not know
how the story ends, with that famous, brutal, near-mythical suddenness.
The last, self-deprecating words of the final letter read simply: ``(Matter
petered out). Yours ever R L Stevenson''.
Add only that this volume is the magnificent conclusion to a magnificent
enterprise. Bradford Booth, who began it, died in 1968; Ernest Mehew has worked
on it for 25 years. They deserve the highest praise.
Meanwhile, a paperback selection (at the very least) should be published
forthwith.
IAN BELL
LETTERS
THE LETTERS OF ROBERT LOUIS STEVENSON. Volume Eight: January 1893 - December
1894
Bradford A Booth &amp; Ernest Mehew, editors
Yale, #29.95
</TEXT>
</DOC>
