<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>Foreign Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093846</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Envoy rebuked
in China row
THE Foreign Office summoned the Chinese charge d'affaires yesterday after a
senior Chinese official accused Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten of behaving
like a ``big dictator''.
Wang Qiliang was told that the comments by Chen Zuo'er, a Chinese
representative on the Hong Kong Joint Liaison Group, were ``unacceptable'',
particularly as the handover of the colony to China is only 18 months away.
Volcano threat
PLYMOUTH: Montserrat's Governor Frank Savage has declared a state of emergency
and ordered a second evacuation of thousands of residents as the Caribbean
island's volcano, Chances Peak, rumbled anew. The volcano roared to life in
July and forced half the island's 11,000 residents to flee a month later.
Guevara found
VALLEGRANDE: Bolivian authorities believe they have found the burial site of
legendary leftist revolutionary Ernesto Che Guevara, 28 years after the
military killed him. The remains will be exhumed and given a Roman Catholic
burial.
15 held in raid
BUENOS AIRES: Authorities raided Argentina's largest military barracks and
arrested 15 people, including several soldiers, in connection with last year's
attack on a Jewish cultural centre that killed 86 people.
Leader `stable'
ATHENS: Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou remained in stable condition on
life support machines in hospital yesterday.
Malan in court
DURBAN: Former South African Defence Minister Magnus Malan and 19 other
officers appeared in court yesterday to hear an indictment accusing them of
plotting operations against the ANC and its supporters in the 1980s. The 20 are
to stand trial in March in the massacre of 13 people in 1987.
Body found
VERONA: Italian police investigating a ``House of Horror'' case have found a
third female corpse in the grounds of an abandoned villa linked to Gianfranco
Stevanin, a 35-year-old farmer convicted of sexual assault.
Ship in peril
HALIFAX: A Maltese freighter with 29 people aboard was listing badly and in
danger of breaking up in gale-force winds 890 nautical miles off the coast of
Nova Scotia last night. The Canadian navy frigate Calgary was heading for the
Mount Olympus in the hope that a rescue helicopter could airlift the crew to
safety.
Charge dropped
MONTREAL: French singer and actress Vanessa Paradis, 22, who was arrested at
Montreal's airport in February, has had hashish possession charges against her
dropped ahead of a scheduled trial.
Stone steps in
UNITED NATIONS: Film star Sharon Stone yesterday replaced Elizabeth Taylor as
chief fund-raiser for the American Foundation for Aids Research. Stone, who
will be asked to raise $76m (#50m) over four years, told reporters: ``This
sounds like an awful lot of money until you realise that one movie may cost
$50m.''
Teenager cured
CHARLOTTESVILLE: A British boy who holds the world record for receiving
get-well cards - he reckons about 200 million of them - has been declared cured
of a brain cancer which doctors originally said was inoperable. ``I feel great,
fantastic,'' said 16-year-old Craig Shergold, who had an egg-sized tumour
removed from his brain by a Virginia surgeon in March 1991.
</TEXT>
