<HEADLINE>Dane steps into Wayne's world</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WAYNE McCullough brings his world crown home to Ireland tonight - and can
increase the clamour for a showdown with ``Prince'' Naseem Hamed.
The WBC bantamweight champion's three-fight deal worth more than #700,000 with
ITV will increase the public's awareness of him, starting with his first title
defence against unbeaten Dane Johnny Bredahl in the special big-fight
atmosphere of the King's Hall, Belfast.
If the non-stop Ulsterman hits peak form against Bredahl - a former WBO
super-flyweight champion - there will be more talk of a Hamed fight, especially
as McCullough is thinking of moving up two more categories to featherweight,
the same division.
McCullough said: ``I'd like to shut Hamed up for once and for good. He hasn't
fought anybody; let him fight somebody first.
``The fact is he's unknown in America and I think that makes him jealous. I'm
popular over there and here.''
After winning the silver medal in the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, McCullough moved
to the States under the managership of Matt Tinley, a Denver-based television
executive - and the 25-year-old from the Shankill Road journeyed to Japan in
July to win his title the hard way.
Meanwhile, McCullough was shocked when his American boxing mate, Justo Sanchez,
due to meet Belfast's Paul Ireland, had to withdraw from his scheduled fight
with Paul Ireland because of a mugging incident.
BOXING
</TEXT>
