<HEADLINE>Shame of inquisition then second-class wedding</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart Lamont</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975093848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE bride is drunk. Very drunk. She giggles her way through the vows, and on
her way to sign the marriage schedule sprawls all her length on the chancel
steps. What should the clergyman do? He has just read a passage in which he
declared that marriage is ``not to be entered lightly or inadvisedly but
thoughtfully, reverently . . .'' That clearly is not the case in this instance.
Is the bride sober enough to be responsible for her answers? And who is to
decide - in the absence of a Breathalyser in the vestry?
These are not simply hypothetical questions. The incident described actually
occurred recently within a church in the West of Scotland. Certainly the
incident is not unique (although it is usually the bridgroom who is the worse
for wear).
On hearing the story of the tipsy bride I asked a group of senior Kirk clerics
what they would have done. Would they have called the wedding off? Certainly
not, replied my first sage, who has hundreds of weddings (and wedding meals)
under his belt and is the minister of one of the big surburban charges.
``Would you take the responsibility of telling the relatives that they had to
send everyone home and cancel the reception?''
What about the charge of marrying while under the influence of drink?
``Not your problem. I take the view that once the marriage schedule has been
issued by the Registrar the wedding has been legally sanctioned. As long as it
doesn't turn into a mockery you have done your duty in blessing it.''
At this my second sage, who has been involved in more legal wrangles than most
people have had steak-pie dinners, grew restive. ``Notwithstanding this,'' he
began, showing his legal background, ``if there is a subsequent legal challenge
to the marriage - that it was undertaken while not of sound mind, you're on a
sticky wicket, especially if you had evidence of that in front of you.''
However, to demonstrate that he did not always follow this counsel himself, he
followed this ruling with a number of amazing tales of marriages he had
conducted 50 years ago.
I was left without a definite answer to my question and hoping fervently that
the situation never came my way. The fact that the problem arises in the first
place is a consequence of the role that the Kirk plays as a national church.
Its ministers are pledged to marry and baptise those who live within the parish
in which they serve, and once they have opened their church doors, all sorts of
people may enter therein. That is why the fuss this week about the report of
the Church of England on co-habitation is not simply an instance of the church
moralising from a distance about those who have little to do with them. This is
a real issue both for the churches and for society.
Many of the couples who present themselves to book their church wedding are
already living together and/or one (or both) has been divorced. This presents
ministers with several choices, and the wide and contradictory way in which
they make them has created a very real dilemma.
One response is to welcome the couple, perhaps encourage them to become
attached to the church and even become members. The fact that they share the
same address is glossed over. After all, it is what they are promising in the
future that is to be blessed, not anything that has gone before. As for the
divorce, Protestant marriage is not technically a sacrament and therefore the
covenant which is to be made is not invalidating anything which went before,
only recognising that the previous covenant has failed and hoping for a lasting
one.
The alternative is to refuse the wedding or to impose conditions (such as one
partner moving out until the wedding). This might be accompanied by probing
questions about the sleeping arrangements or whether the bride is a virgin. You
think I'm making this up? Well I'm sorry to say that several of my colleagues
in the Glasgow area are adopting this kind of attitude. One even offers a
second-class wedding service for non-virgins. Others point blank refuse if the
couple, although resident in the parish, are not members of their church (which
is contrary to Kirk regulations, but most who take this stance can usually cite
conscientious objection, which is allowed in the case of remarrying divorcees).
If I thought it might shame my colleagues into a more tolerant attitude I would
name them and their parishes, but it would only distract for the real issue -
that there are now diverse and contradictory views within our churches on
divorce and co-habitation. It is too easy to polarise them into fundamentalist
and liberal. Those who think the Catholic position is clear on this question
should also think again. Their very clarity and orthodoxy is - as is so often
the case with fundamentalists (both Catholic and Protestant) - lacking in
kindness and compassion. As for church reports on this question, they help
clarify the issue but they should be noted, not voted. That way lies sectarian
sacraments - only avalailable to those who say the right creed, sleep in the
right bed, and don't have a bad marriage behind them.
Pastoral problems, as my sages illustrated, are often best dealt with by a
mixture of compassion and common sense. You can call that a ``fudge'' if you
like, but if a fudge can bring peace in Ireland, it must surely have God on its
side.
</TEXT>
