<HEADLINE>Whippets up a storm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNETH WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLASSIC SPIRITS OF THE WORLD: Gordon Brown, Prion, #20.
THE MALT WHISKY FILE: Lamond and Tucek, Canongate, #9.99.
A NIP AROUND THE WORLD: Malcolm Greenwood, Argyll, #7.99.
MAKE YOUR OWN SCOTCH WHISKY: Adam Bergius, Argyll, #7.99
PAPERBACKS
Up North: Travels Beyond the Watford Gap, Charles Jennings, Abacus, #6.99.
ALTHOUGH it's impossible to love a travel writer who doesn't love Blackpool,
and difficult to take seriously a cosmopolitan sophisticate who says he
couldn't live anywhere but the suburbs of London, Charles Jennings's engagingly
written and cheerfully abusive tour of the land of whippets and brown ale is a
droll and cheeky read.
His knockabout insults are defused by their wild exaggeration of stereotypes
and his evident fondness for the innocently ludicrous (it made my day to know
that there's a Sooty Museum at Shipley, near Bradford). All very unfair, of
course, but what's funny that isn't? Last (aggrieved) word goes to Blackpool's
director of tourism: What on earth did he expect a town like Blackpool to smell
like?
Cycle Of Violence, Colin Bateman, Harper Collins, #4.99.
NOT since Evelyn Waugh's Scoop has there been as good a novel about a
journalist as this insouciant black comedy-thriller of the Troubles, written by
a young man who rejoices in the noble title of deputy editor of the County Down
Spectator and shares with Flann O'Brien a keen interest in the comic potential
of the bicycle. His hero is Miller, a too-smart young hack exiled from the
safety of Belfast to bandit country and the Crossmyheart Chronicle, where he
proceeds to get into more trouble than you can shake an Armalite at. Apart from
the ceasefire, this is the best thing out of Ulster for years.
Brando, Peter Manso, Orion, #8.99.
ELEVEN hundred pages, distilled out of 750 interviews, may just smack slightly
of overkill for the biography of a film star. As a document of the movie biz
and its mores from the 1950s to the 1980s, however, it's intriguing in moderate
doses, stuffed with more scandal than Kenneth Anger's Hollywood Babylon, and
Marlon Brando emerges almost incidentally as one of the great sacred monsters
of Hollywood.
Scottish Dates, Brian D Osborne and Ronald Armstrong, Birlinn, #6.99. Scottish
Proverbs Colin S K Walker, Birlinn, #5.99. Scottish Customs, Sheila
Livingstone, Birlinn, #6.99.
LEFT by your bedside for a month or two and subjected to regular offhand
dipping, these excellent little books will gradually and painlessly furnish
your mind with a useful quantity of the lore, language, and history of Scotland
- which is something a Scottish school education never did for most of us.
Sheila Livingstone's Scottish Customs, a treasury of folkways linked to all
aspects and occasions of life, is particularly evocative, reminding the reader
of the few old customs that still survive and the many that only very recently
faded away.
The Guinness Encyclopaedia of Television, Jeff Evans (ed), Guinness, #14.99.
PUFFED as a reference book but really aimed at TV trivia fans, this is the kind
of book that its purchasers will look up from every couple of minutes to regale
their helpless partners with a fascinating remark like ``Here! Did you know
there used to be three Cartwright brothers in Bonanza?''
KENNETH WRIGHT
</TEXT>
