<HEADLINE>Chill out and warm to that winter blunderland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Paul Welsh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WATCH out, here it comes! After record-breaking summer '95, the most inclement
months of the year have finally arrived - a time of howling winds, horizontal
rain, and ``crunch, slither, slip'' on ice-bound roads from Lerwick to Berwick.
When the shivers hit San Andreas proportions in January, the realisation should
have finally soaked in, writes PAUL WELSH.
Short of boarding the first steamer  for Panama and forgetting Scotland from
November to April, this is a heavyweight contest that always goes the full
distance. It is Us versus Winter again, and like any fight, tactics are
essential if you want to survive the contest intact. Throwing your hands in the
air and cursing this particular season is not good enough - it will land the
punches anyway.
Read on, then, and defend yourself.
STEP 1
Performing Ablutions
n A plunge in the Kelvin might work, but without an ice-bound loch it is hard
to appreciate the full impact of a sauna in winter. On a weekly basis, however,
saunas help to keep you healthy, and a level of Scandinavian rigour can be
attained using a cold shower. As long as high blood pressure is not a problem,
go and sweat.
Saunas stimulate the immune system (something you will hear about) and, if
rheumatism or arthritis are unwelcome visitors during winter, a session at the
local leisure centre should help to chase them away as well. For those who have
never tried one, imagine a mini tropical paradise that can cost less than #3
per hour. Now imagine a typical day in February. . . enough said.
n Allander Sports Centre, Glasgow - 0141 942 2233 (#2.90 per hour, swim
included); Perth Leisure Pool - 01738 635454 (#4 per hour, swim included,
reopening mid-December); Commonwealth Pool, Edinburgh - 0131 667 7211 (#5.60
for maximum of two hours, no swim).
STEP 2
Choosing Underwear
n Standing in your birthday suit, your body will feel relaxed and invigorated
after a sauna. You will be positively glowing with good health, so if you want
to stay that way, think ``warm layer close to the skin'' before getting
dressed. Call me old-fashioned, but wearing a pair of long johns is the single
major difference between smiling and grimacing all the way to next summer; and
here, at least, the wearer has some tactical options. Sparks will fly with
top-of-the-range Damart - long-lasting, toasty-hot, but man-made - whereas
Marks and Spencer do a fine cotton line - cosy, comfortable but liable to leave
you looking like a nineteenth-century gold prospector. After intensive use, the
crotch will head for the knee, the knee for the ankle, and all elastics will
declare unilateral independence. But the best thermals of all are army surplus.
Cheap and rugged, find a rare wool mix and you will absolutely never go to war
(or is that work?) chilly.
n Damart Thermawear - 0141 332 2586 (ladies from #12.99, men from #16.99);
Marks &amp; Spencer - 0141 552 4546 (ladies from #9, men from #10); Army surplus -
0141 337 2550 (unisex cotton mix from #1.50)
STEP 3
Wrapping Up
n To declare a wind and waterproof outer-shell essential from now till the
Scottish Cup Final is worse than stating the obvious - it is rubbing salt in a
frost-bitten wound. Nevertheless, it might stop some people going out
underpressed and under-gunned in midwinter. Cappuccinos and croissants may
induce a continental spirit in Princes Square, but that wind-tunnel also known
as Buchanan Street will quickly disperse the feeling in March. Button-up before
leaving any building, or body heat will be replaced by an unforgiving arctic
jet stream. From that point on, common sense should prevail. Hat, gloves, and a
chest/throat-protecting scarf are de rigueur (thermal insoles would be also, if
imagination could only stretch that far). It may sound like the kit-list for an
OAP coach excursion, but the experience of 65 winters soon puts fashion sense
where it belongs; out in the cold.
STEP 4
Eating well (or not, as the case may be)
n Regardless of clothing, every wizened parent still swears by one fundamental
maxim: you are what you eat. Unfortunately, Christmas and New Year are often an
excuse for eating and drinking too much. For many, the rest of winter is spent
covering up the depressing result with over-size woolly jumpers and old jogging
pants. Pampering that constant winter companion, comfort eating, will not
preserve your hour-glass shape or honed physique but plenty of fresh fruit and
vegetables will. Up your carbohydrate intake with pasta, potatoes, etc, if you
feel cold. Avoid fatty foods as ever. This will curb some of the food-related
winter blues, and, although many of the survival steps encourage an appetite,
that is OK. Burn-up energy with exercise, not brooding over unwanted weight.
STEP 5
Swallowing Supplements
n Remember, a continental breakfast doesn't do anything for a cold but vitamin
C will. Take the case of Dr Linus Pauling, the Nobel prize-winner in Medicine.
He died recently but not for lack of this supplement, because he swore by it.
Pauling advocated a level of consumption which exceeds government
recommendations by over 1000%, and developed a mega-dose regime of vitamin C
that apparently counters severe ailments including cancer. A vastly increased
resistance to the common cold, flu, etc, is also possible using the same
tactic. A dose of between one and three grams per day is reasonable but have no
fear about quantity, it is impossible to overdose on vitamin C. Things can get
a little loose down below, though, so if they do, cut down to bowel tolerance
because you have had quite enough.
Combined with vitamin B - the great stress buster - the effect of vitamin C is
further enhanced, and apocryphal stories abound regarding these vitamins'
life-enhancing properties. Both are widely available.
STEP 6
Staying Happy
n Are you sad or what? Yes, Glasgow parlance is rough, but Seasonal Affected
Disorder (SAD) is always rougher. C
n SAD Helpline - 0800 45 43 45; Full-Spectrum Lighting - 0141 944 2647
STEP 7
Exercising The Body
n They say: ``Winter does not rot in the sky!'' But you might, if you don't
flex your muscles now and again. In fact, a minimum of two or three times a
week for 20 minutes, according to Nicola Forrest-Brawley, ex-British champion
mogul-skier and now a lecturer in health and fitness in Glasgow. If you want to
cover all the bases, ie stretching, the cardiovascular system (heart and
lungs), and muscular strength/endurance, an exercise regime of 25-plus sit-ups,
press-ups, and squats per day is a start for enthusiastic men and women.
``This will help maintain good body compostion,'' says Forrest-Brawley, ``and
sustain summertime fitness levels.'' An additional bonus is the buzz of
endorphins, the natural opiate released into the bloodstream during exercise.
The potential for a healthy addiction is there, and these hormones also
neutralise pent-up aggression, tension, and the ``winter blues''. If you want
to feel good and stay on the right side of the law, start by touching your toes.
STEP 8
Exercising The Mind
n Some folk deny they have a body. Some folk deny they have a mind. In both
cases, the results are usually far from attractive. But don't worry, winter is
the perfect time to do something about brain fitness as well. Blown back
indoors, Scots are left with plenty of time to read interesting books, learn a
second language, ditto musical instrument, or write a story. In fact, do
whatever takes their intellectual fancy.
A holistic view of human life rates creativity right up there with vitamins and
regular physical exercise, and it has been shown that active use of the brain
helps to slow its physical degeneration in older people. Bucking the winter
trend of limited mental activity also has its social rewards. Next summer's
trip to Spain will be enhanced by a regular language class during the winter.
Pick up a guitar at the same time, and you could serenade a potential lover
with the poetry of Lorca. As you stroll through Granada discussing the finer
points of Moorish architecture, the personal reward for visiting Partick
Library in December could be more abundant than the orange groves of Andalucia.
STEP 9
Scaling The Heights
n Winter sports have annoyed people for years. Groan at ``bare-your-chest and
howl'' climbers flawed by gaudy colours, gizmos, and real ale. Guffaw at the
body-hugging jumpsuits of hopeless skiers piste-bound by social obligation
rather than inclination. Grimace with Captain Courageous as he is winched to
safety in a force nine gale. Yes, they all deserve to be gently knocked, but
there is one thing that cannot be denied. They have all turned the tables on
winter, harnessing wind, snow, and ice for excitement and pleasure, as each
weekend blast of do-or-die adventure carries them through the dull days (and
nights) that stretch till spring. Be careful, of course, but get out there and
try one nevertheless. What could compete with that heady mix of adrenalin and a
savage, elemental world?
STEP 10
Supping Ancient Brews (of course)
n Winter is synonymous with feelings of fatigue, low energy, and sluggishness,
all signs of a body conserving heat by slowing down blood circulation.
Unfortunately, this lowers our natural immunity to coughs and colds, so a
downward spiral of infection and tiredness is also possible.
For centuries, our wily ancestors have experimented with herbs and plants that
tackle this problem, and many of their tonics and natural medicines are still
available today. Taken in tincture form (a teaspoonful a day), the herb
Echinacea increases the body's immunity and, according to Jackie Hazzard of
Napiers Medical Herbalists, ``it makes people feel vital, energised and
alive''. This is the number-one herbal response to winter, but combinations of
ginger, cloves, thyme, cinnamon, and chilli in remedies such as Napiers
Composition Essence and Remedy No 7, will also chase away respiratory problems
and warm cold hands and feet by increasing the rate of circulation and
generating a feeling of warmth. Although herbal medicines work for all, they
are especially effective with older people of low mobility.
n Napiers Help-Line - 0141 334 0705.
</TEXT>
