<HEADLINE>A BOOK AT BEDTIME</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN DONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093851</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Siobhan Redmond - actress tells ANN DONALD about her nighttime reading
n I'M a bit of a fiend for the printed word. I'm always buying books,
newspapers and magazines. In fact in the boot of my very old Volkswagen Beetle
I still have bundles of old Vogue magazines that I can't bear to throw out. I
don't read them, just look at the pictures. Very occasionally I'll read the New
Yorker because I've never been to New York and I'd like to go, but the nearest
I get to it is buying the New Yorker and having a bagel.
I've also just read Deborah Tannen's book You Just Don't Understand which is
about the conversational differences between men and women and what really
underlies the text. Obviously I can't precis the book for you as Tannen is a
highly intelligent woman who has managed to write a whole book about it so I
can't sum her up in a few sentences.
I do like short stories and I find them perfect for times such as when I'm
rehearsing and I don't have a lot of time at my disposal. I've just finished
Alice Munro's latest book Open Secrets which is wonderful. I promised myself
I'd learn 10 pages of lines then read one short story but they're so morish
that I gorged to bits on them.
I'm also leafing through anything with kitchens in them as I've just moved
house. The trouble is I'm spending so much money on buying the magazines that
I'll never have enough money left to buy the kitchen stuff. I'll probably end
up papering the walls with cuttings instead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Best actresses in the world</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE working prostitute has a degree in hypocrisy, the man who pays her can also
preach against her, and it happens. But if you cannot understand the need for
prostitution then you don't understand sex.
If a man sleeps with a woman who is willing, he can kid himself he's not using
her, but if money changes hands he can't. Men are at their most honest when
they kerb-crawl. It is more cost-effective to buy the services of a prostitute,
than it is to wine and dine a hopeful. As one male source put it, at the end of
the night, a date might say no.
The prostitute triggers different reactions in both sexes. Some women hate her
because she supplies cold what they need to be warmed up for hours to do. Other
women secretly admire her, because she makes men pay for what is provided for
free in a relationship or in the name of a one-night stand. Straight, honest
payment is more respectful a response than the token promise of love and
affection. A man, however, does not hate the prostitute, he can't dislike what
is available to accommodate his desire. Men and prostitutes are in league with
each other. And women know it.
Sex is supposed to be romantic, an expression of emotion rather than a quirk of
market forces. If you sell it you're turning pink-rosed connotations around and
dumping on them. But the prostitute's clients remain uncriticised. This
illustrates the prejudice society has. Blaming a prostitute for providing sex
that people buy is like blaming a baker for making people fat.
There is, although many would not admit it, a huge element of free will in
prostitution. You don't have to sell your body and no-one has to buy it. Like
men, prostitutes can disassociate sex from emotion. To some this seems
merciless, but it is not morally wrong.
Edinburgh has many prostitutes, and their health and welfare, and that of their
clients, is kept under a semblance of control by Scot-pep, a society set up and
run by working and ex-prostitutes. Project workers supply condoms, HIV
counselling, talk to the girls about welfare rights and give them legal advice.
The aim of Scot-pep, subsidised by Lothian Health Board, is to ``promote health
and dignity in prostitution by empowerment, support and peer and client
education''.
The group recently took part in a European Symposium on health in the sex
industry. Other ``twinset and pearls'' societies which aim to ``help'' working
girls, have God on their side, which is nice but somewhat impractical, their
purpose to convince women to abandon their ``wicked ways''.
Rose is 39 and has been working for five years, as has Amanda, 23, a single
parent, currently on what she jokingly refers to as ``maternity-leave''.
Jennifer, 35, (not her real name) has worked on and off for 15 years. She is
sonsie, smiling and assertive, with a face from the past. She's the snub-nosed
madam in a Toulouse-Lautrec poster, with a mothering chest.
Amanda looks much more contemporary with a nose-ring, black DMs and T-shirt,
but Rose looks as if she's had a harder time. If Jennifer represents the
gallusness of the oldest profession in the world, then Rose represents its
distress. The women say it's amazing how many ``brain surgeons with brickie's
hands'' pick them up, how many 20-stone footballers. Some guys who pay to have
sex with a prostitute want her to enjoy it. ``I had my first orgasm with a
client,'' says Amanda. Jennifer adds: ``You get some very talented men.''
If you remove subjective opinions about the morality of prostitution then she
is allowed not to be a victim, but a businesswoman. And her clients are allowed
to be well-balanced husbands and fathers, not raging psychos. But some might
prefer the prostitute and the client to make a tragic case, for if using a
prostitute is regarded as normal, rather than a perversion, then there is no
reason of principle for soliciting to be illegal, and the bellowing moral
guardian is stumped.
The insistence to portray the prostitute as victim is a convenient mechanism to
avoid the truth that some of the women enjoy their job. Amanda comments that
it's nice to work in a situation where you can have a laugh with your
colleagues. Compare working long shifts in a factory to make up a decent wage
and you find out why women sell sex. You are untaxed and self-employed, you
have a control over your hours not afforded to wage slaves, and there is no
ageist glass-ceiling. Unlike food or pieces of technology, nothing can replace
the demand for sex.
Some female prostitutes, however, only earn enough to pay the bills. The
``Quarterly Group,'' as professional prostitutes call them, are women who take
to the streets every three months when the gas, telephone and electricity bills
come in. Whenever Edinburgh is injected with disposable income during the
Festival, the Tattoo or any political or religious conference, there's work.
There is also a constant support of local clients who prefer to come out in the
dark. It's not worth starting on the streets before 9.30pm in the summer, or
6pm during the winter.
To be specific, prostitution itself is not illegal in Scotland, but soliciting
- that is, loitering with intent - is. Interestingly, here, pimps are
non-existent. ``This is a matriarchal society,'' says Jennifer, ``and Scottish
women don't bend to the will of men.''
Some might say that prostitution is synonymous with the abuse of women, that's
why it's so hard for a prostitute to file for rape. ``I really do believe that
prostitutes prevent a portion of sexual offences,'' insists Jennifer. ``If you
can pay for sexual favours then you won't abuse somebody.'' So a man will
assault if he's broke? Prostitutes say, by way of illustration of their theory
that all men are potential rapists, that they get every profession and class,
but the common denominator is probably sexual immaturity. In Hollywood, as the
arrest of Heidi Fleiss exposed, groupies are so easy, that paying for it is the
only way a rich, famous guy can get his kicks. Sometimes prostitution is not a
social service, but an outlet for sexual hedonism. What prostitutes really do,
is help other relationships along. They are paid mistresses.
``Prostitutes are the best actresses in the world,'' says Rose. She claims a
hundred different roles, from sex therapist, to nurse, to psychiatrist, but she
says nothing about the abuse of an innocent victim having more to do with the
pursuit of power. Talk about abuse and the subject of S&amp;M is raised, quite
naively. Sado-masochism is theatre between adults, mere titillation. If a man
wants to rape he will.
``If you have someone who wants to pay a lot of money for you to take the belt,
you lay down rules,'' says Jennifer. ``My life isn't worth an extra #20. You
agree on a cut-off word and the activity ceases. Clients know the rules and
abide by them. A lot of people think that who pays the piper calls the tune,
but you are in control.''
In Scotland you need two witnesses to corroborate that you are actually
committing an offence by loitering with intent. After a third caution you go to
court for a #40 fine. Rose, Amanda and Jennifer say they've never had any
trouble with the Scottish police. It's more of a hassle to be a prostitute down
south, they say, as you only need one witness for a conviction, and determinant
on how many condoms you have on you, the law can insist that you are soliciting.
The media fuss over the recent granting of licenses to several saunas is
unwarranted. Apres Debra Scanlon, the Leith woman who won a battle to prevent a
sauna opening near her home, Edinburgh's prostitutes feared that licences would
be revoked, leaving 200 women on the streets. But the first sauna licence was
granted 17 years ago. Prostitution will carry on regardless of legislation, an
underground organisation run mostly by women, who have to look out and after
themselves.
``The majority of clients are trustworthy,'' says Rose, ``but you don't know
how drunk a client is until you're already in the car. The worst I've ever had
is someone asking for their money back.'' Little things hurt, such as small
boys, maybe punters of the future, throwing eggs, and passers-by spitting on
you.
Prostitutes carry mobile phones or ask clients if they can take down their
number plate. When I ask the three how much they earn, one of their pals looks
at me and says: ``More than you.'' In terms of being a professional, she's
convinced a prostitute earns more.
A girl in a sauna earns the same as the girl on the street, but in a sauna you
have to pay desk money or ``rent'', and this is a consistent percentage figure
of what you earn. Rose prefers working the street, regardless of the danger,
because she wants every penny she earns to be hers. But she curses the fact she
has to take clients to dark alleys. Jennifer prefers the sauna, saying:
``You're a bolt away from help''. They all agree, that by working in a sauna
you can disguise the job better, because you work shifts, the way you would in
McDonald's.
In a sauna, the minimum charge is #25, on the streets, #20. All three women
went into prostitution for the money. ``I was doing cleaning jobs, the DSS
found out and I had to pay them #500. I was living on #36 a week, I couldn't do
it,'' says Rose; Amanda was caught out when the Government withdrew benefits
for 16 and 17-year-olds; Jennifer was working as a lab technician when she
encountered financial problems. ``You can make a very healthy living out of
prostitution,'' she says. ``If you work every day you earn #30,000 to #40,000 a
year. You get used to the standard of living, when you stop work it's difficult
to adjust.''
Prostitution is a mindset. Jennifer, for example, has had trouble with her car
this morning. The discussion turns to how much it will cost her to fix it.
``Two punters,'' she says. Fifty quid.
It is impossible to gauge the number of men who use Edinburgh's prostitutes.
Jennifer asks me to multiply three punters a night over five years, times the
number of women working in what they charmingly call the ``outdoor industry''.
``There is no such thing as a standard client,'' says Jennifer, ``human beings
are very complicated. Some relationships are sad, people who have been together
for a long time and who can't experiment sexually, and the man can't ask for
what he wants because the woman can't hear him. I have a regular, middle-aged
client, and the only reason he comes to me is because his wife won't give him
oral sex and he enjoys it. He tells me that a man has two choices; to go with a
prostitute or have an affair. The woman involved might tell the wife, but the
prostitute won't.''
There is an underlying contempt for women who are sexually inhibited. The three
prostitutes I interviewed, seemed genuinely disgusted at the fact that men had
to come to them at all. In their world, they provide a sexual menu because the
person the man really wants to be with, isn't co-operating.
``Sometimes you get widowers, sometimes clients just want a cuddle, some miss
physical contact with a woman,'' Jennifer adds.
Although 35, she advertises herself as 40. ``Some men prefer a younger lassie
because that's their fantasy; some men look for an older woman who knows where
she's at and doesn't have any hang-ups.''
It may seem daft, but I ask what qualities you need to be a prostitute.
Everyone howls with laughter. ``Do not be a virgin,'' screeches Rose. ``Wait a
minute, you'd get quite a lot of money for that!'' shouts Jennifer. ``Aye,''
Rose retorts, ``but you could only sell it the once.'' They're chewing the sofa
in merriment.
``It's a job you can or can't do,'' says Jennifer, when it calms, ``it's about
attitude. You have to put up with bullshit, and be sympathetic and patient.''
``Prostitutes do not receive much understanding,'' says Rose. ``But we are very
tolerant. What we don't like to take, we don't like to dish out.'' Jennifer,
Rose and Amanda say they are actresses, but they have no pretence. Just the
compassion any underdog has for downtrodden others, a category which they
believe includes frustrated men.
