<HEADLINE>Moods, Will Downing (4th and Broadway)</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>51</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>home entertainment weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q WILL is the effortless master of the creamy-smooth love-groove, and we relax
into the mellifluous folds of his voice. He can be readily located somewhere
between old-time cocktail-jazz and nu-style R&amp;B, in a penthouse suite adjacent
to those occupied by Barry White and George Benson. Will Downing croons
butterily, like a butterfly with satin wings. Yeah, as you might have guessed,
we like Will Downing at Belcher Towers. Even when his songs are a bit on the
bland side. Like they are here. Drat it.
Your Little Secret, Melissa Etheridge (Island)
q MS Etheridge's slow, subversive ascent to all-American post-grunge rock
superstardom takes a nasty turn as she mutates into Bryan Adams. Strained vox;
ploddy drums; cliched gewtar.
Mixmag Live Volume 20, Richie Hawtin (DMC)
q STEP it out this way for yon driving, mutated electronic soundscapes, chuck.
If you missed Richie Hawtin guest-starring with the Slam laddies into the early
hours of the morning in Glasgow, you'll be able to sample his sonic sculptures
in the privy of your own home early in the new year upon the release of this
seamless 22-track, 56 minute set recorded on Hawtin's home nightclubbing turf
in Windsor, Ontario. As well as a couple of blasts created by young Hawtin
under his Plastikman alter ego, you get a wheen of politely uninsistent techno
recorded by sundry chaps for the Ferox label. Ah me; after hip hop, trip hop,
and loop bop, how about a spot of nimble, fleet-footed skip lope?
Trance Atlantic 2, Various (Trance Atlantic)
q A FURTHER instalment of digitalised transatlantic trance-ambience from the
folk behind the Volume compilation series, which means that in addition to two
75-minute CDs, you get a fat, glossy, full-colour CD-sized brochure explaining
exactly where in the US of A all these plangent sound-washes and percussive
pumpings are coming from. From suburban bedrooms in towns and cities coast to
coast, actually, wherein computer-literate young music-boffins are having fun
igoring all the rules.
Essential Mix: Tong, Cox, Sasha, Oakenfold, Various (ffrr)
q DJ superstars Tong (Pete), Cox (Carl), Oakenfold (Paul) and Sasha (just
Sasha, OK?) offer propulsive insights into the healthily diverse state of this
nation's dancefloors. Radio 1 top dog Tong favours songs (eg Kelli Rich's
Hide-A-Way); clubland favourite Cox opts for a harder-edged, more relentless
groove, courtesy of such dancemeisters as Laurent Garnier and Dave Clarke.
Sasha prefers squittery bloops; Mr Oakenfold revisits the scenes of old crimes
with Utah Saints and the Prodigy. All in all, a moderately good time is had.
</TEXT>
