<PAGE>51</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>home entertainment weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093855</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q IT has been clear for many years, to those who have heard her music in
concert, that Aberdeen-born Judith Weir is one of the most individual and
distinctive composers around.
There is a compact quality to her language, technique and style; and a ready
accessibility. Weir's is a pared-down music, no excess baggage, entirely
fat-free. Now, for the first time, in a collection of her chamber works, there
is an opportunity to assess and survey that style at breadth.
Performed by two groups that have tirelessly championed her music - Domus, and
the Schubert Ensemble of London - this is a superb collection, containing a
broad range of Weir's music, from the stellar piano work, The Art of Touching
the Keyboard, to the instrumental mini-opera, The Bagpiper's String Trio.
Prince of the collection, which also includes the atmospheric El Rey de Francia
and Ardnamurchan Point, is the masterpiece, Distance and Enchantment, inspired
by Brahms, and a wondrously evocative piece in its own right as well as a
compendium of Weir's techniques, from mind-boggling echo effects to soaring
lyricism.
</TEXT>
