<HEADLINE>Now, one more time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>51</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT frequently happens that jazz musicians become trapped within their chosen
style, still able to improvise of course, but limited to a stylistic approach
or a repertoire of songs with which the public associate them.
In his touring years with the All Stars even the majestic Louis Armstrong
produced a set menu of tunes night after night, rarely changing them because
the trumpeter believed he knew what his public wanted.
Duke Ellington was lumbered with the ``medley'', that group of his most famous
tunes which he ran through thousands of times on tour after tour.
Similarly, the pianist Ralph Sutton, was long identified with Fats Waller who
was his inspiration and a major influence on his playing. But in recent years
Sutton has been playing with a new authority, breaking free of the programme
which had become overly familiar even to his most devoted followers.
Waller songs still form a part of any of his sets and he remains the finest
interpreter of the impressionistic pieces written by Willie ``The Lion'' Smith
but Sutton has moved into other areas showing a new assertiveness and authority
as he does so.
Three CDs which have been issued in the past few months underline that trend
which was first demonstrated on a Sackville recording Live At the Cafe des
Copains where Sutton played such songs as Laugh Clown Laugh, Poor Butterfly,
This Is All I Ask, and Russian Lullaby among others.
On a follow-up to that recording Sackville have pieced together a second
helping from Sutton's Toronto appearances. And, once more, we hear the pianist
stretch out on Winter Weather, You Turned The Tables On Me, Willow Weep For Me,
I've Got a Crush On You and the wonderful Worryin' The Life Out of Me, written
by the trombonist Miff Mole.
On yet another Sackville offering Sutton renews his partnership with the
Australian trumpeter Bob Barnard. Using a Steinway Model D instrument Sutton is
at his very best.
The third CD finds Sutton teaming up with the Japanese trumpeter Yoshio Toyama
in a series of duets interrupted by a solo track from Sutton on Shine. Again
the programme is a varied one. There are certainly two from the Waller songbook
but otherwise the music is as varied and imaginative as on the other recordings.
There is Hoagy Carmichael's Lazy River, and Moonglow and One Hour. The two men
spark fresh ideas off each other and the results are fascinating and hugely
enjoyable.
At the time of writing, Ralph is playing a lengthy engagement in Berne before
moving on to Switzerland and then returning to his Colorado home just before
Christmas.
At the start of the year the grind of touring will begin again and, hopefully,
it will include a visit to Britain, and, more especially, a return to Glasgow.
Last summer he starred at Nairn demonstrating the newer facets of his work as
well as reworking the Lion's delicate but difficult pieces. A Glasgow
appearance sometime next year would confirm his stature for all of and redefine
his place in the jazz world's piano playhouse for his supporters in the city.
In the meantime the new CDs are available to underline the still growing
talents of the man from Hamburg, Missouri, who was discovered by Jack Teagarden
in the forties and who continues to travel the world proving that stride piano
is alive and well in his massive hands.
</TEXT>
