<HEADLINE>Forget the sanity clause</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNETH WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>51</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>video weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093857</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIRACLE ON 34TH STREET
(retail, #14.99; also available to rent; cert U).
Desperate goodwill addicts such as Couch Potato, who likes to get a seasonal
fix around this time of year to put him in the mood for Christmas, are not
inclined to be too picky about the quality of their supply - as long as it's
not Dudley Moore in 1985's Santa Claus: The Movie, any one reel of which would
have made the reformed Scrooge sack Bob Cratchit and break up Tiny Tim's crutch
for firewood. Like realistic-minded children on Christmas morning, we take
what's under the tree with as grateful a heart as we can muster.
Which is just as well for the new Miracle On 34th Street, Les Mayfield's 1994
remake of George Seaton's 1947 Christmas classic. What's wrong with this is not
that it doesn't live up to the original - it really would be a miracle if it
did - but that it doesn't live up to its own tantalising possibilities.
On the credit side, Richard Attenborough gives a lovely performance, artfully
underplayed but wonderfully warm and gentle, as Kriss Kringle, the
department-store Santa who believes he's the real McClaus and ends up having to
prove it - both to a New York insanity hearing and to a little girl who wants
something very special for Christmas. Mara Wilson is both sweet and wholesome
as the little girl, and Dylan McDermott twinkles pleasantly against type as her
mum's boyfriend and Kriss's lawyer.
Elizabeth Perkins, contrariwise, is pretty flat as Momma - but we could ignore
that if it weren't for the general lack of zip and zing in direction,
photography, and editing; the corporate blandness of tone that discards the
original's sharp but genial satire; and the way the soundtrack neglects its
beautiful orchestral theme in favour of naff pop covers of Christmas standards.
Despite all that, the story and four solid performances - we forgot to mention
old-timer Sam Prosky as the Judge - just about save the day, and if you watch
this Miracle in the right spirit, it'll produce the desired effect. In the
spirit of Christmas, we'll give it two Ho!s out of three.
THE MADNESS OF KING GEORGE (rental, cert PG).
Its title shortened by one word from the stage play - for fear that American
audiences would think it the third film in a series - Alan Bennett's witty and
sympathetic account of the mental, political, and familial light of the first
(but probably not the last) British monarch to talk to the trees makes an
agreeable but essentially uncinematic talk piece whose main purpose is as a
substitute for the play.
Nigel Hawthorne is heartbreakingly good as the king, seizing every opportunity
for pathos and barnstorming bravura, while Rupert Everett makes an almost too
convincing figure as that heartless fop, the Prince Regent; but purely as a
film, the production suffers from the British carriage-trade curse of gentility
and decorum.
This doesn't extend to the sleeve blurb, however, which reads ``The King was
all powerful and all knowing. But he wasn't quite all there.'' What are they
trying to sell us - Carry On Up The Nuthouse? If only Frankie Howerd and
Kenneth Williams were still here to play the King and Prinny . . . now, that
would be a movie.
</TEXT>
