<HEADLINE>Inside the bungalow from Atlantis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Donald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra Home is where the art is</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAN this really be the shy, retiring Glasgow suburb of Clarkston? Where are the
ubiquitous, nice, neat hedgerows, the orderly grey, paved garden paths, the
perfect window frames and all the other necessary architectural accoutrements
of suburban living? Why is it that instead of the collective utilitarian spirit
of DIY heaven, it is the collective magical spirit of Turkish Delight,
Tutenkhamun and Grimms' Fairy tales that is invoked by one peek over the garden
wall at a certain unsung designer craftsman's home/workshop?
The subversive in suburbia is Michael Gallacher. For here in ``conservative''
Clarkston, the 38-year-old amateur craftsman has endowed the art and
architecture of the area with more than a hint of Eastern promise and gothic
fantasy in products that vary from one-off interior design features and
cabinets to rocking horses and gigantic flying dolphins on rockers, all
hand-carved from wood.
One need only glance up the muddy path to the customised front door and sitting
room window to realise that here is a man who took those summer holiday trips
to Cyprus, Greece and Turkey that little bit further, in actually attempting to
reproduce back in Blighty the architectural wonders captured in holiday snaps.
The overhang of the window is composed of semi-circles of plate (hand-carved by
Gallacher) as one would see on Islamic temples, while the latticed wood door
frame recalls the window design of any conventional Eastern building.
It is only recently, however, that the self-effacing craftsman has ``gone
public and professional'' with his work, For the past 10 years he has worked in
the theatre at Ross Hall Hospital, with his craft skills taking a back seat.
Despite coming from an artistic lineage - his mother Nita Begg is a painter as
was his father William Gallacher, who also lectured in architecture at Glasgow
School of Art - the young Gallacher has never been formally trained, other than
a three-year Scotvec evening course in joinery and carpentry.
Sitting in the small front room swamped by two very adult-sized rocking
dolphins on one side of Gallacher's settee, and two traditional styled wooden
rocking horses on the other, he explains why it has taken nearly 20 years to
finally recognise his inherited artistic blood.
``Ever since I was a boy and given paints, pens and crayons I've loved making
things,'' he says with a grin. ``However, I think that I took my skills for
granted, in that I have learnt them subconsciously in the same way as being
able to see or walk and so I never really saw the advantage of formal
training.''
Although he opted for ``artistic civvy street'' rather than attend art college,
Gallacher continued to work away independently after hours. These projects
involved everything from renovating his father's former garret of a studio in
Sauchiehall Street into an imaginative and valuable house to building sunken
bathrooms for friends and one-off Arabic cabinets for work colleagues.
The influence of his deceased father is not only visible on the walls of
Gallacher's house, which almost disappear behind the series of vast
self-portraits that hang throughout the small house, but is obviously in his
son's latent enthusiasm for architecture. ``There were always my dad's
architectural drawings around the house when I was young,'' he recalls, ``and
I've always been the guy who wanders around Bath Street and West Regent Street
gazing at all the intricate architectural detail or running up closes to get a
better look at a particular carving.''
This enthusiasm is supplemented by an impressive library of architectural books
that echo his love of the Islamic style. ``I've got everything from World of
Interiors to imported American books on architecture and construction.
Everything in here,'' he says leafing through a particularly heavy tome, ``is
where I get my ideas from.'' That, of course, and the numerous scrapbooks of
hundreds of photographs he and his wife compile when they sojourn to places
like Cyprus and Turkey. ``Oh yeh, I definitely get a huge buzz out of seeing
these incredible tombs or stone labyrinths or columns and thinking `Right, that
will look really good in a sunken swimming pool or bath'.''
Expanding on his own personal taste, Gallacher is patently not a clean-cut
minimalist man. ``I have very strong opinions on styles and Minimalism or
Charles Rennie Mackintosh aren't really me at all,'' he states. ``I love that
whole image of fanciful that mixes the epic nature of films like Ben Hur with
the lost city of Atlantis!'' he grins broadly.
And it is fittingly in Gallacher's own bathroom / showroom where the ``epic
meets the watery''. This is clearly the designer craftsman's labour of love,
having devoted two years of his time and coupled his interior eye with
carpentry and joinery skills to fashion everything by hand. We enter what
appears to be a fourteenth - century Turkish bath chamber, replete with
eight-sided Islamic star carved into the former window frame, sunken bath,
soaring gold embossed pillars and perfectly replicated mini temple that doubles
as a bathroom cabinet.
Artistic licence and liberty have been thoroughly embraced with a scoot through
the centuries and styles, with one half of the room opting for the Turkish look
and the other half for the Egyptian.
The surprising influence for this original bathroom is slightly closer to home,
as Gallacher explains. ``It's actually inspired by the fantastic architecture
of the Acropolis, Glasgow,'' he says. ``It really is an architectural
historian's paradise because these Victorian bigshots built themselves
incredible tombs that were influenced by architectural styles from all over the
world.''
Gazing at his handiwork, Gallacher notes with a dissatisfied sigh that his
artistic vision is not appreciated by everyone. ``I think that people are a bit
wary of my style,'' he says, ``which is why I have to temper the `oddities'
like the temples and cabinets with the traditional crafts like dolphins and
rocking horses.''
With plans to go full-time into the designer craft business, Gallacher is
hoping that his ``oddities'' will appeal to those who don't run with the
conventional interior pack and who appreciate a hint of Eastern promise in
their household. Who knows, he may even succeed in transforming conservative
Clarkston into a hotbed of Turkish baths. Michael Gallacher can be contacted on
0141-644 2644.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
