<HEADLINE>Dublin greets man of peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Simpson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AND then there was Dublin . . . a day like this is a rare occurrence, but when
it happens one day after the other then you know that times can change and that
humanity has already overtaken hatred.
Dublin's day with the Big Feller sought no competition with the Belfast or
Derry visits of President Clinton. Those momentous events truly broke new
ground, moving Northern Ireland closer to that moment in the Nobel poet Seamus
Heaney's dream when ``hope and harmony rhyme''.
The Republic's offering was a partnership in welcome for an extraordinary
peace-broker, a man who in one year of gambles in foreign policy has pulled off
the Arab-Israeli accord, the Bosnian peace agreement, and now is articulating
with such potency the ordinary people's desire for a settlement in Northern
Ireland. It cannot be disregarded by those who hesitate and see it as the
opportunism of an upstart outsider.
What President Clinton is doing is nudging the key political players, north,
south, and over the water, towards a permanent and stable peace, stripped of
triumphalism for anyone. To view his actions simply as an exercise in gathering
votes back home recklessly misreads the dynamics of what is happening.
Not since 1990 had Dublin's College Green been so thronged with bellowing good
nature as yesterday when the third American President to become a Freeman of
the city spoke of his pride in feeling like ``a real Dub''.
Five years ago Jack Charlton had delivered a similar message to 100,000 people
when he brought home the ``lads'' after the quarter-finals in Italy's World
Cup. Yesterday the lunchtime crowd reached 80,000 but for security reasons
space had been reduced since that sunny evening of Jacko's time on the
municipal podium.
In a day of salty air and pearly light the Bank of Ireland's eighteenth century
elegance was at its best. This was the site of the original Irish Parliament
and before its colonnades Bill Clinton, his voice strained now from three days
of garrulous diplomacy, reinforced his peace-making role with some of the
phrases we had heard before.
The reason was not idleness or lack of attention - this has been one of his
most eloquent journeys abroad - but merely because the essential message does
not alter: those who now take imaginative risks for peace will find America
morally, politically, and financially supportive: ``We want to walk together.''
But from his Northern visits he was clearly affected by the urgent aspirations
of the young. And in the Republic, too, where the majority of the population is
below the age of 35, his message again to any of those who remain reluctant to
seize the new momentum was this: ``I want more than anything for the young
people of Ireland, wherever they live on this island, to be able to grow up and
live out their dreams close to their roots in peace and honour and freedom and
equality.''
As is the way of presidential voyages yesterday's was wrapped around with
formalities and official functions: a trip down the formal corridors of
President Robinson's residence, an address to the Dail at Leinster House, and
finally a state banquet hosted by Taoiseach John Bruton at Dublin Castle.
And as this is a man of spontaneous walk-abouts and impromptu one-to-one
briefings, and this is Ireland, land of flexible time, everything ran late.
Added to this, Dublin's own irrepressible informality was in cracking form.
Glued to a classical pillar on College Green, was an emergency notice written
in a hasty hand: Whitehouse toilets, O'Neills's Pub round the corner.
On the matter of pubs President Clinton himself paid homage to that Dubliner
incarnate, the bar-fly, by visiting Cassidy's in Camden Street, the den where
the Special Branch drink and where market traders roar out the price of fruit
and vegetables on the pavement outside, their voices loud as America.
In the back snug the President raised a glass or two of the black stuff
(even-handedly, as ever on this trip, he sipped both Guinness and Murphy's)
with the Cassidy clan. Their ancestors were shared by his late mother, also a
gambler whom, he said, would have loved Ireland because ``you have nearly 300
racing days a year''.
Everyone has a Christmas they remember above all others and this may be the one
which Northern and Southern Ireland never forget. But if peace is really to
grow stronger it is vital to ensure the memory of every victim of the Troubles
also remains alive.
But the overwhelming message for everyone from the past two days is that this
is a different Ireland than even 15 months ago and anyone of rabid politics
must ask themselves now just who do they represent? On this island, north and
south, a softer wind is blowing.
</TEXT>
