<HEADLINE>Every frog has its day</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Fay Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra green fingers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093861</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MATT Smith once woke to find a heron investigating the pond in his back garden
but otherwise - barring the odd road accident - his frogs live a fairly charmed
life. Neighbours in the flats above know to rescue any strays found hopping
towards the traffic at the front. At the last count there were 60 frogs and an
uncertain number of newts.
The garden at 60 Cleveden Drive in the West End of Glasgow is a world of its
own. Six young robins were reared in the wall above Smith's collection of
ornamental grasses from the southern hemisphere. Wrens flit through the
Australian eucalyptus and Chilean Fire Bush. Young frogs try out their legs
among naturalised snakes head fritillaries and oxslips in the wild flower
strip. Edible grapes grow among passion flowers on the patio. All within a
shortish walk from the Great Western Road.
Native birds will take whatever shelter and food they find in the city but
exotic tender plants are flourishing in what used to be a common-or-garden back
green only because the gardener goes to great lengths to seek them out and grow
them. ``A garden is a very artifical environment,'' says Smith who grows many
of his plants from seed and traces others through plant exchanges organised by
the National Council for Conservation of Plants and Gardens (NCCPG).
With the help of the Plant Finder, he beats a track to small specialist
nurseries in the nooks and crannies of Scotland. If he wins the Lottery he will
buy a piece of land somewhere in the Central Belt and start his own nursery to
produce the rare plants he finds round Inverness-shire or Dumfries and Galloway.
Let's hope he does. The plantsman's approach challenges the ``subtle
brain-washing'' of commercialised gardening. ``We don't need to spend a fortune
on expensively packaged seed. Smith either collects seed from his own plants or
orders from ``no-frills'' suppliers like Chiltern Seeds. Like most of us he
bought his first plants from garden centres. ``They're fine when you are
starting out but after a while you realise that they are very limited,
over-priced and they all stock the same things whether they are at Wick or
Land's End.''
You may not need rolling acres to create a unique garden but it helps to have
nerve, know-how and imagination. Matt Smith seems to have it all. At the age of
30, he is not only treasurer of Glasgow and District branch of Scotland's
Gardens Scheme, and a keen member of NCCPG, he is also assistant horticultural
officer (``a charge hand'') for East Kilbride responsible for developing Calder
Park's new winter garden glasshouse collection which attracted 100,000 visitors
this year.
But all this has happened almost by accident. When Smith moved to Cleveden
Drive around nine years ago the garden was little more than a few narrow
borders of Michaelmas daisies set in grass. At that time he had just asked to
be moved from his job as accounts clerk (``I hated it, absolutely hated it'')
to the parks department. He took a horticulture course at Auchincruive College
and never looked back. ``I might be earning more money if I had stayed where I
was but I never wake up in the morning and wish I didn't have to go work.''
Meanwhile the garden in Kelvinside has been transformed with full support and
some help from the neighbours. John Kinloch built stone paths and dry stone
walls which provide the structure. Wendy Henry, in the garden flat, helps with
cultivation, Ian Butler's garage is crammed with sands of pots and bags and
Ross Graham provides ground space for tubs and cold frames where hundreds of
seedlings lie wait to be potted on. ``They're screaming for attention,'' says
Smith, shutting the lid on them firmly. ``They'll have to wait.''
Smith filled the borders and dug the ponds then rescued the frogs and newts
from underneath old carpets and corrugated iron on a piece of wasteland
destined to be cleared for luxury flats. He also commissioned the wooden bridge
he was featured leaning on in The Beechgrove Garden. This summer 200 visitors
came when he opened to the public under the garden's scheme.
Of course I should have seen it then when the meconopsis, grown from seed, were
in bloom. In fact any time but now when the leaves are lying on the grass and
only a few grapes cling to the vine. ``It's the usual story. Gardeners always
say, `if only you had come last week you would have seen . . . '''
That hint of self-mockery seems characteristic. Smith, aware there is still
plenty to see, alternates between infectious enthusiasm, and ironic
self-consciousness. He scatters botanical names with such bewildering speed
neither my Latin nor ageing shorthand can keep up. What is the Pitman's
shortform for Lippia citriodora? Let's say lemon scented verbena.
Smith uses Latin terms for accuracy - ``common names are only common to where
you live, if you want to find something at a nursery it is useful to know even
just a bit of the Latin name.'' But he has no time for horticultural fads. ``I
hate to think I'm becoming a plant snob. I really loathe people who look down
on plants just because they are common. But I want to grow things you don't
find anywhere. If I want to see a berberis I can look over the garden wall, I
want the space for magnolias and eucalyptus - I suppose that makes me a plant
snob.''
Despite this morning's autumn rain, the garden has a lush sub-tropical look.
Smith's favourite garden is Logan, near Stranraer, where he once found a
gardener hoeing a bed and muttering, ``Bloody cordylines, they get
everywhere.'' From Logan come the echiums, from Inverewe the bromeliads. An
Australian holiday last year has strengthened his passion for plants from down
under: note the white flowering eucryphia and aromatic Australian mint bush.
``I was hanging over walls photographing people's gardens and then I discover
they really envy our cottage gardens and plants like delphiniums and aquilegia
which they can't grow.''
You will find some of those at 60 Cleveden Drive, too, along with alpines,
hostas, rhododendrons and spring bulbs. But the flowering currant is white and
the gardener manipulates the shades he wants from self-spreading plants like
Indian Balsam (``Policeman's Helmets'') by weeding out anything other than pale
and more interesting forms. ``In the ideal world there would be room for
everything.''
Faced with the reality of a six-month winter the ``plantaholic'' makes sure
colour and scent from September to April. The winter flowering cherry, Prunas
subhirtella ``Autumnalis'', will bloom from November; the striking foliage of a
variegated Lords and Ladies, Arum italiacum ``Pictum'', now catches the eye;
spring snowflakes, Leucojum vernum, appear in February, and nearing Christmas
the Chinese witch hazel, Hamamelis mollis, puts on a spectacular scented
display. The first real sign of spring is when the frogs start croaking.
</TEXT>
