<HEADLINE>What a gift</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Liz Taylor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra under the hammer</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BONANZA of books that would make good Christmas presents have appeared on the
market in the past few weeks and a round-up of some of them might make useful
reading.
Leading the field because of the sheer scale of its scope and the information
it provides is the 1996 edition of Miller's Antiques Price Guide, subtitled ``a
Professional Handbook''. Now in its seventeenth edition, it codifies and lists
more than 10,000 different antiques, ranging from corkscrews to Chippendale
furniture, which have been sold through auction houses, antique shops, markets
and fairs during the past year. All the entries are accompanied by photographs,
many of them in colour.
In the past, Miller's Guide, and others like it, have been included little
information about individual items but this year the consultants Judith and
Martin Miller have incorporated features throughout the text discussing such
diverse subjects as collecting early oak furniture or the state of the market
for silver.
The price of this authoritative and weighty tome is #21.99 and it is published
by Reed Consumer Books Ltd.
Miller's closest rival in the collectors' handbook class is Lyle Publications
who have also brought out their Antiques Price Guide for 1996.
The emphasis in Lyle books, especially in the Price Guide which is reputed to
have a good sale to the inmates of HM prisons, is on finding bargains and
making money. Apart from a foreword discussing the state of what to look for in
any specific area.
As with Miller's the items listed in the guide have been taken from past sale
returns and 7500 of them are illustrated with photographs. This book is also a
weighty hardback and sells for #17.95.
In their series Cash In On Collecting, Lyle's have also brought out other
useful handbooks - There's a Fortune in your Attic; Antique Dealers Pocket
Guide and 1001 Antiques Worth a Fortune (which not a lot of people know
about!). These are all thick paperbacks with a cover price of #7.95 and the
emphasis is on finding unlikely or unsuspected bargains.
Buyers are urged on by anecdotes such as the one about the man who bought an
oddly shaped walking-stick for #4.50 from a junk shop which was subsequently
discovered to be a Hawaiian godstick worth #47,000. What ``not a lot of people
Know'', of course, is how rarely this sort of thing happens.
A more seriously informative book from Lyle is their Price Guide To Silver
which contains more than 3000 descriptions and illustrations of pieces of
silver - with prices. Very useful sections include a glossary of names and
terms and a list of silver marks. Unfortunately not many Scottish marks have
been included, only Edinburgh and Glasgow. The silver price guide costs #14.95
and all the Lyle books are published by Lyle Publications, Glenmayne,
Galashiels.
A book where pecuniary profit is not offered as the main temptation to buyers
is A Guide to the Antique Shops of Britain 1995-96, published by the Antique
Collectors' Club at #14.95.
It has a section on antique shops in Scotland, dividing the country into
Scotland north and Scotland south, and the list of shops given is fairly
comprehensive although there are some omissions. Information appended to each
entry details opening hours, half closing days and the availability of parking,
as well as describing the stock and giving some idea of the range of prices to
be expected.
There is also a list of auction houses throughout the country, maps, a list of
specialist dealers and an index of all shops mentioned in the text. It would be
the perfect book to take on a touring holiday.
Last of all is a book for the specialist numismatist, Coincraft's Standard
Catalogue of English and UK Coins 1066 to Date. It contains 600 pages with 5000
photographs and prices. The publishers make the claim that it is the first new
catalogue of British coins since 1929.
Although my knowledge of coin collecting is next to nil, I found this a good
book to browse through because the pages are frequently enlivened by little
boxes of information entitled Collecting Hints. The headings to the various
sections also give a mass of interesting information, mystifying Latin
abbreviations on coins are explained, and a history of British coinage is
included, as well as a chart of monarchs to lead the reader through history.
I found myself following the history of the mint at Berwick-on-Tweed, which
only operated when things were quiet on the Border and the coinage from which
was often very coarsely cast. The book is produced by     a panel of specialist
editors and published by Coincraft at #19.95.
n Christmas is coming and the salerooms are bringing out their seasonal
offerings. On December 8, Christie's in South Kensington are offering a
selection of dolls and Christmas decorations including a six foot tall
composition figure of Santa Claus holding an empty sack.
In the 1930s, this figure used to stand at the entrance of Trinity Arcade, a
very up-market store in Nottingham. Children used to climb on to his feet in
order to whisper their requests for presents and as a result the toes of his
boots are all worn away. The estimate for the shoddily shod Santa is between
#1000 and #1500.
An unexpectedly high price of around #500 is also quoted for a set of eight
large German-made coloured glass balls for hanging on Christmas trees and
dating from the 1950s. There must be many of those coloured baubles still lying
around in family attics or boxrooms. Worth having a look anyway.
</TEXT>
