<HEADLINE>In a twinkling of the winter sky</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Fowler</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>50</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093865</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DECEMBER skies are empty of planets, save for surly Saturn hanging low towards
the south-west. No matter. Who needs planets? Let's cast an eager eye on the
winter stars.
Making a slow entrance from the south-east comes the aptly named Winter
Triangle, a trio of biggies called Sirius, Procyon and Betelgeuse. Sirius,
alias the dog star, is the brightest in our whole firmament. The others are
pretty good shiners too - with Procyon the eighth brightest in the sky and
Betelgeuse the tenth.
Also clearly visible is Capella, the sixth brightest. Look almost directly
overhead and you'll find it in the constellation Auriga. Having located Auriga,
pan a little southwards and you can lock on to the constellation Taurus in
which there are two easily identifiable star clusters.
Swimming strongly into vision come the Pleiades, a glorious sight, the famous
Seven Sisters lightly veiled in mistiness. No need to remove the binoculars and
rub your eyes, however - that blurry effect is caused by the swirls of spare
gas left over when the sisters were born, a kind of inter-stellar soft focus.
The gas glows with a luminosity reflected from these young and hot lovelies,
which is why the Pleiades are classed as a reflection nebula.
The sisters are mere infants in the cosmic time scale, having been formed just
a few million years ago.
According to ancient myth, they represent the daughters of Atlas who were swept
up into the sky when they pleaded to be saved from the clutches of the hunter
Orion. The seven may be the brightest luminaries in the cluster, but there are
fainter stars galore alongside them. Altogether there are about 400 stars in
the Pleiades - some sorority!
Also in Taurus is the Hyades star cluster, which is grouped round Aldebaran.
But since Aldebaran, a red giant, is the brightest star in the whole
constellation, the Hyades are rather outfaced by their companion.
Keep with Taurus. Within it you will find the nebula known prosaically as M1
and more picturesquely as the Crab. The origin of the Crab is far different
from that of a nebula such as the Pleiades. The Crab - which in fact is a great
cloud of gas - is all that remains of an old star which expanded in old age
until it exploded (the phenomenon known as a supernova). The cataclysm was seen
as a bright light in the sky by earthlings in the year 1054, though of course
it happened much earlier in time.
Once a supernova takes place, the neutrons created by the gravitational
collapse form a rapidly spinning, highly condensed core or neutron star which
sends out radio signals or pulses at regular intervals - hence the name pulsar.
The Crab is one of only two pulsars which transmit light as well as radio waves.
On the whole, 1995 has been a poor year for viewing meteor showers, due to
their occurrence at times of fairly bright moonlight. December is no exception.
However the Geminid shower, due on the 14th, are prominent and should be worth
seeing. Look towards the south-east and locate the constellation Gemini - the
stars Castor and Pollux are good markers.
</TEXT>
