<HEADLINE>Waughs are in control</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARK Waugh abandoned his trademark cavalier approach to wreck Pakistan's hopes
of a substantial first-innings lead in the third and final Test in Sydney
yesterday.
The Australia batsman defended resolutely to compile a patient unbeaten
half-century on the second day at the Sydney Cricket Ground.
Batting at No.4, Waugh's 54 not out steered Australia to 151 for three from 57
overs in reply to Pakistan's first innings 299 before bad light stopped play 30
minutes before the scheduled close.
Waugh gained valuable support from twin brother Steve, who finished on 26 not
out, in adding 60 runs in an unbroken fourth-wicket partnership.
Pakistan No.3 batsman Ijaz Ahmed had earlier lifted his side to a respectable
total with a fine 137, his highest score in test cricket.
But the tourists failed to capitalise on his marathon performance by losing
their last six wickets for 36 runs after resuming on 231 for four.
AUSTRALIA v PAKISTAN
</TEXT>
