<HEADLINE>Smith's hit not enough for England</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093868</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DEFIANT 52 from South African-born Robin Smith was not enough to save his
adopted England on the second day of the second Test against South Africa in
Johannesburg yesterday.
Replying to the home team's total of 332, England slumped to 200 all out in
just 68.3 overs. South Africa were five without loss in their second innings at
the close.
Left-arm spinner Clive Eksteen claimed three for 12 to destroy the middle
order, while paceman Shaun Pollock mopped up the tail to return figures of
three for 44.
Smith hit a steepling uppercut 6 in his 109-ball stay, which also included
eight 4s, but apart from Graham Thorpe, England's batsmen had only themselves
to blame for not keeping Smith company.
Thorpe was horrified to be given out caught at short leg, off Eksteen's first
delivery, and his ire seemed vindicated when television replays showed neither
bat nor gloves within touching distance of the ball.
But there was no doubt about Eksteen's next two victims. Graeme Hick struck a
powerful return catch soon after tea on six, and Jack Russell was caught at
mid-wicket for 12 following a mistimed sweep.
Alec Stewart earlier clipped swing bowler Meyrick Pringle straight into
Kirsten's hands at short mid-wicket in the last over before tea to depart for
45 as England slumped from 109 for two to 116 for four.
Stewart and Thorpe had added 64 to repair the early damage inflicted by Allan
Donald who bowled Mike Atherton for nine with a beautiful off-cutter and Mark
Ramprakash for four with a full delivery that ripped out the middle stump.
Stewart had enjoyed a remarkable piece of luck on 26 when he was beaten for
pace by a Donald bouncer. His attempted hook lobbed gently to mid-wicket where
Shaun Pollock dropped a simple catch.
Pollock, who endured a day of fluctuating fortunes, had fared much better
earlier when South Africa added a further 54 runs to their overnight 278 for
seven thanks largely to his brisk innings of 33.
Eksteen was delighted to have made a significant contribution on his home
ground.
``We've had a very good day but there are still three hard days to go before
the Test is ours,'' he said.
Coach Bob Woolmer also sounded a warning note. ``Plenty of Tests have been lost
from similar positions to this. We have to put a really big score on the board
to make sure it doesn't happen to us.''
After a disastrous second day for England, William Hill quote South Africa as
1-2 favourites to win the second Test, with the tourists at 5-1 and the draw at
5-2. Scoreboard:
