<HEADLINE>Duffy is still the key to takeover</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE vice-chairman Malcolm Reid admitted last night that the proposed
management take-over of the club  will hinge around Jim Duffy.
It emerged yesterday that Canadian millionaire Ron Dixon had jumped the gun on
Thursday by announcing that a #3m deal had been concluded which would put Reid
and player-manager Duffy in control at Dens Park.
Reid, who would succeed the Canadian as chairman with Duffy taking a seat on
the board, said: ``I am fairly confident the deal we have been offered will be
completed.
``But Jim Duffy's final decision will be a key to the whole thing.
``If he were to turn down what is on offer then I would not be interested in
playing my proposed part in the take-over.''
But last night, Duffy was making it clear there would be no comment from him on
the matter. ``Right now I am prepared to talk about football at the club and
nothing else,'' he said.
Reid also conceded that negotiations are on-going on the plan Dixon put
forward. He said: ``There is a lot of work still to be done. We have still to
look at the legal angles involving the movement of shares in the club. And we
are still talking about the final price although Ron is not putting any
pressure on us in that regard.''
The vice-chairman also made it clear he is also still looking for financial
backing to complete the take-over. He said: ``Things have now been spelled out
to the other members of the board and other          people are also showing an
interest.
``We believe there will be backing because this move would put the club into
the local ownership of people determined to fulfil Dundee's ambitions.''
Reid hopes that the whole thing can fall into place to the satisfaction of
Dixon and those taking charge at Dens in time for Christmas.
</TEXT>
