<HEADLINE>Dynasty was once a great power in Europe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BARINGS was described in 1818 by French statesman Duc de Richelieu as the sixth
great power in Europe, alongside England, France, Russia, Austria and Prussia.
q The first Baring, Johann, arrived in Britain in 1717 from Bremen in northern
Germany.
q Two of his sons, John and Francis, started the bank in London in 1762.
q Baring credit re-opened trade with the United States after the American War
of Independence and helped finance Britain's wars against Napoleon.
q The Barings invested heavily in land to hedge against disaster should the
bank fail. When Francis died in 1810 he had just #68,000 in the bank but
#400,000 in land holdings.
q The so-called Baring Crisis of 1890 rocked the City. It was sparked by a
default on Argentinian loans worth about #250 million in today's terms.
q Edward Baring, Lord Revelstoke - who had a gambling instinct - had to sell
houses, paintings and furniture to pay off his debts and his wife was said to
have died of shame.
q But the bank survived as the dynastic family rallied around.
q In 1969, control was passed to a charity which held the share capital.
</TEXT>
