<HEADLINE>Bankies out to break three-year sequence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Hugh McKinlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093871</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIRST DIVISION
\IT was a shock at the time, but neither Morton nor Clydebank can remember the
exact season. ``Approximately three years ago,'' seems to be the general
consensus from manager Allan McGraw and Kilbowie secretary Ian Steedman. The
Bankies travelled to Cappielow never having defeated the home side on the south
banks of the Clyde. The men from across the water, formed in the mid-60s, won
7-1. They have not tasted victory there since.
The two sides meet again today. Morton, in second place in the first division,
naturally are favourites. The fact that Clydebank have lost only four league
games this season - twice each to Dunfermline and Dundee United - would suggest
caution in any forecast of what will happen.
Much will depend from Morton's point of view whether or not Alan Mahood can
shake off an injury, while Bankies must wait for fitness tests on Tom Currie,
Davie Nicholls, and Colin Sutherland.
Leaders Dunfermline, meanwhile, can still look down on the other teams despite
having lost three of their past five matches. And, as far as their long list of
injuries is concerned, there's good news for them, and possibly bad news for
the opposition who have failed to take advantage.
Hamilton are the visitors to East End Park today, and the Fifers will welcome
back Stewart Petrie and Greg Shaw. Injuries, however, still will rule out Brian
Rice, David Bingham, Neale Cooper, Andy Smith, and Kenny Ward.
Accies manager Iain Munro will miss the injured Michael Geraghty and Scott
McCulloch.
Dundee coach John McCormack is in no doubt that his club - despite their
Coca-Cola Cup defeat by Aberdeen last week, and the boardroom wrangles in
midweek - will not only come back strongly against St Mirren at Love Street,
but also win against Dumbarton in midweek to go top of the league. Winger Neil
McCann may miss today's match.
Airdrie have striker Steve Cooper suspended for their home clash against St
Johnstone at Broadwood.
St Johnstone have John O'Neill, Andy Whiteford, and Danny Griffin doubtful.
Dundee United take on struggling Dumbarton at Tannadice.
HUGH McKINLAY
</TEXT>
