<HEADLINE>No longer sisters under the skins</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093872</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEAUTY BOX
I would call it a debate if it was intelligent enough, but nothing
intellectually smart comes from the fashion industry. Designers, style gurus,
PRs and models, have decided that the PC mob have had it too good. The fur
coat, they claim, is back.
Last year, Sophia Loren agreed to advertise fur. She was approached because she
is old, and has the stage-managed tartiness of the fabulously rich and
self-obsessed. In Italy, 7.5 million women own real fur coats, and if I was
prepared to be nice, I'd say that the star is deluded by a cultural and genetic
disposition to flaunting vulgar items of wealth. In America, too, the fur
industry is still worth $1.5 billion. Think of their weather, it's glorious.
Wearing fur in Italy and America can't be explained away in terms of
practicality.
There are women like Sophia, who think that wearing mink and fox is glamorous.
They are conditioned by avarice into believing that real fur is sensual. But
women like Sophia Loren are dinosaurs for they have no spiritual involvement in
modern-day society.
Implementing the idea in the public consciousness that it is OK to wear real
fur, is designed, literally, to redress the zeitgeist. If the stigma attached
to wearing fur recedes, sales increase. Statistics show that the number of fur
farms in Britain has decreased from 50 in 1989 to 13 today, and it's a fact to
be proud of.
Marketing men and women, however, are working overtime to convince people that
it is socially acceptable to return to wearing real fur. The Fur Education
Council (FEC) who speak for the Fur Traders Association, say that in Britain
during 1993/94, sales were up from #3.7m to #10m. What is significant is that
the FEC was set up to counteract anti-fur campaigns by Greenpeace and Lynx. The
FEC say their figures are supplied by the Department of Trade and Industry, who
in turn, say they were supplied by the Central Statistical Office, who, in
turn, have admitted that they don't know where the figures came from.
The underlying presumption in the fur debate, is that people are ready and
willing to abandon principle for the sake of being in fashion. The lives of the
truly superficial are a series of gestures, and if a woman is heard to declare
that she has no problem with wearing mink or snow leopard or alligator or
domestic cat (they use cat fur to make coats in Italy), then she will parade
the streets in defiance of public disapproval, wrapped up in her own personal
crusade.
Women who wear real fur coats scare me, they are dangerously pathetic. They
think they're so brave for stepping out in one too. But they are not Marie
Antoinette, there is no rabble, no crescendo of revolution at their front
porch. In the street they are usually eyed with a mute disbelief, their tragedy
the fact that they think the murder of 40 joyful, vulnerable, intelligent
creatures could possibly be flattering to wear.
Another tack adopted by spin doctors for the fur trade is that the popularity
of fake fur is responsible for the return of real fur. I have several fake
furs, which are made of the same material as a teddy bear, in blue, red, and
speckled like snow after a dose of road grit. No effort has been made to
simulate the skin of any species. If I thought their appearance would propel
women to a furrier, I would burn them.
The older women who wear fur have a different mindset. They would never wear a
fake, too cheap. Just as girls of my generation, would never dream of doing it
for real.
</TEXT>
