<TEXT>
MILLION DOLLAR CHALLENGE
NICK Faldo shot his worst round of the year as he struggled to a 78 at the Sun
City Million Dollar Challenge in South Africa yesterday.
The former world No.1's second round was one of the most remarkable of his
career as he went out in nine-over-par 45 - but came back in three under.
Faldo's troubles began when he dumped two balls in the greenside lake at the
par-3 fourth hole to record a quad-ruple bogey 7. Then he took a 7 at the par-4
eighth.
``The strange thing is that I did not hit the ball that badly,'' said Faldo,
who lies 12 shots behind leader Nick Price. ``But the rough is so bad this week
that if you're 10 feet off line you have no shot.''
Price, of Zimbabwe, shot the best round of the day - a 67 to lead at the
halfway stage.
Scotland's Sam Torrance, joint overnight leader with American Corey Pavin,
dropped back after a 73 to be four shots behind Price.
Pavin carded a 72 which left him sharing second place with Germany's Bernhard
Langer and fellow American Tom Lehman, three behind Price who bogeyed the first
hole but made no further mistakes.
He went out in level par but stormed home in 31 with five birdies, including
three in the last four holes.
Torrance spoiled his round with a 7 at the par-5 ninth - the hole he eagled on
his way to the joint lead yesterday.
After a 69, the second-best round of the day, Langer said he did not think
Price's three-shot lead was significant.
``You can lose three shots at one hole the way the course is set up,'' he said.
Colin Montgomerie continued his woeful time at the event, adding a 76 to his
opening 79 which left him detached from the rest of the 12-man field and 17
shots behind Price.
Local favourite Ernie Els remained in contention after a second successive 72,
six behind Price. He was critical of difficult pin positions. ``With the rough
up they should put the pins in easier places. The crowd does not want to see us
struggling out there,'' he said. Scores:
