<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A great city falls,  but a crisis looms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>49</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093875</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MACCLESFIELD, December 2 - A deadly game of cat-and-mouse is being played in
the tranquil English countryside of Cheshire as the Jacobite and the British
Government's armies try to outmanoeuvre each other.
Prince Charles Edward Stuart and his 4500 clansmen, their numbers now swelled
by about 300 English supporters, mean to continue their headlong advance, which
has brought them from Carlisle in 10 days. Their momentum has baffled all
resistance. There were hopes of intercepting them at the River Mersey, which
runs just south of Manchester. But without opposition they crossed it yesterday
and covered another 10 miles to arrive at this little town, famous for its
button-making.
Here the prince learned that the Duke of Cumberland, now in charge of all royal
forces in England, is moving towards him with 8000 troops. Formerly under Sir
John Ligonier, these have been encamped in Staffordshire for a fortnight,
barring one of the main routes south but otherwise making no attempt to meet
the Jacobite invasion while they awaited their new commander. The duke has
galvanised them into action and obviously intends to join battle at the first
opportunity. His forward outposts are now at Newcastle-under-Lyme, fewer than
20 miles away.
The Jacobite leaders held a council of war last night. They decided to split
their army, not for the first time, to keep the other side guessing and exploit
their advantages of greater speed and flexibility over a more conventional
force.
At daybreak, the Jacobite general, Lord George Murray, moved 1200 soldiers five
miles south-west to Congleton. From there a road leads into Wales, where he
might get the chance to recruit more men. Cumberland really has no choice but
to turn and follow him. The danger is that this will leave the rest of the
clansmen, still standing to arms at Macclesfield, with an open road through
Derby towards London. There are no other loyal forces between here and the
capital.
The Jacobite leaders maintain in public a united front of support for Prince
Charles's strategy of striking straight at London. But the anxieties of the
Scots are never far away. Most would have preferred to remain in their homeland
and defend its independence under the restored Stuarts against any Hanoverian
attack. They went along with the invasion of England against their better
judgment, but they are becoming pessimistic.
This is because so few Englishmen have joined them. They expected their
fortunes to look up after they reached the prosperous textile town of Preston
on November 26, in the heart of the traditionally Jacobite North-west of
England. There and at every place where they have stopped since Carlisle, they
held a ceremony proclaiming King James III and VIII in an effort to stir the
local people. But the response was minimal.
Prince Charles then forecast he would raise at least 1500 men in Manchester,
which he entered on November 29. He was encouraged by the fact that, like other
towns, it fell to him with ridiculous ease. People said afterwards:
``Manchester was taken by a sergeant, a drummer and a woman.''
The sergeant was James Dickson, a Scot formerly serving in the British army who
opted to change sides after being captured at Prestonpans. He marched out in
front of the main body of the Jacobites with his mistress and a drummer-boy.
They got to Manchester well ahead of the rest, to be surrounded by a crowd
which was first curious then hostile. He defended himself with a blunderbuss,
and this was the signal for the 500 or 600 local Jacobites to show themselves
and come to his rescue. They then occupied the streets.
When the army arrived, church-bells rang out and bonfires were lit. Many people
illuminated their windows, while civic leaders came to kiss the prince's hand.
Another crowd gathered outside his lodgings, where some were allowed to watch
him dine. At the table, according to an eye-witness, Lord Elcho, Charles was
exhilarated, and asked his officers ``in what manner he should enter London, on
horseback or afoot, and in what dress''.
But the town may have put on its show of enthusiasm only to humour the
Highlanders and prevent any looting. In any case, when it came to recruitment
Manchester was little better than smaller places. About 300 men volunteered,
most of them unemployed, and several admitting that they would have joined
whichever came first.
There are still enough of them to form a Manchester Regiment, the only one to
be mustered so far by the Jacobites on English soil. It has been put under the
command of Francis Townley, of Townley Hall, Burnley, a Roman Catholic whose
father joined the rising of 1715 but was afterwards acquitted of treason. The
younger Townley has served as an officer in the French army.
None of this was enough to impress the Scots, who while in Manchester held
private meetings to go over the situation. The English people were obviously
cool towards them and, as Lord Elcho puts it, they have ``received not the
least encouragement from any person of distinction''. Nor have the French shown
much sign of mounting the promised invasion across the Channel. The Scots
reckon they have proved their own loyalty to the Stuarts, and never meant to
force the deposed dynasty on England.
When the clan chieftains then gathered at a highly charged council of war on St
Andrew's Day, November 30, they told the prince he should go back to Scotland.
But he differed and again got his way. The Scots agreed at least to march on to
Derby so that, in Elcho's words, ``neither the French nor the English might
have it to say, the army had not marched far enough into England to give the
one encouragement to land and the other to join''. The next day the Jacobite
army left Manchester, but with its leaders clearly sensing the approach of a
crisis.
n Another dispatch next week.
</TEXT>
