<DOCID>GH951202-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man who broke the bank</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093876</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICK LEESON's deal with the Singapore authorities may not mean that others
involved in the Barings scandal will walk away scot-free, but the fact he was
not cross-examined in court meant that he would not be publicly naming names.
What happened next depended on whether the Singapore authorities, as Finance
Minister Richard Hu indicated in October they intended to, pursue charges
against those Barings executives alleged to have taken part in a cover up.
Leeson's immediate staff in Singapore are unlikely to interest the Singapore
authorities. They are more interested in the man he reported to in London, Mr
Peter Norris, and the two regional bosses, Mr James Bax and Mr Simon Jones.
Singapore's official report into the Barings debacle, published in October,
said other Barings officials had concealed Leeson's unauthorised trades and
that there was ``a strong inference that key individuals of the Barings group
management were grossly negligent, or wilfully blind and reckless with the
truth''.
After the collapse in February, Barings was bought by the Dutch financial
conglomerate, ING, and, while most of the 2000 Barings staff in London were
kept on, 21 of the senior staff were either sacked or resigned. The ING
decision was clearly taken on the basis of what it found when it took over. The
Singapore report found the fall of Barings Futures to have been caused by
``institutional incompetence, a lack of understanding of the future business
among senior executives, and a total failure of internal controls''. Some of
those who left voluntarily, or were dismissed, must have borne some
responsibilty for that situation.
The two names which crop up repeatedly are those of 40-year-old Mr Norris, who
was head of the investment banking arm, and now lives in Hertfordshire, and
42-year-old Mr James Bax, who was south east Asia regional manager, and still
lives in Singapore. The auditors, Price Waterhouse, in their report to the
Singapore authorities, alleged the two men had ignored warning signs, provided
Leeson with more and more money for his losing bets, and later tried to cover
up his losses.
They were said to have played down a #50m discrepancy in Leeson's books,
discovered by the auditors in January, which would have served as a warning
that things were going wrong. There were other warning signs about that time
which were also ignored, including two from Simex, the Singapore International
Monetary Exchange.
The Bank of England, whose Board of Banking Supervision published its report on
the affair in July, is examining whether it was misled by Mr Norris in the
account he furnished of the events leading to the collapse. There are
discrepancies between what he told the Bank, and what is contained in the
Singapore inspectors' report, and he has discussed them with the Bank's
investigators, Mr Brian Quinn, head of banking supervision, and Mr Ian West,
head of special investigations.
Although criticised by the Board of Banking Supervision report published for
failing to prevent the collapse, it is only in the Singapore report Mr Norris
is accused of participating in a cover up. Mr Bax has not been interviewed by
the Bank officials. He has, however, been interviewed by the CAD, as has Mr
Simon Jones, operations manager for the region when Leeson was dealing. The
Singapore report also named Mr Anthony Hawes, the group treasurer, as having
been involved in the concealment.
Mr Norris has dismissed the Singapore conclusions as having no basis in fact,
and, to be fair, the report's conclusion that there was a cover up appears
based on conflicting testimony from former Barings executives, rather than
conclusive proof. The man who might be able to furnish that proof is Mr Leeson.
Since he is not now going to undergo cross examination in public about his
crimes, if no further action is taken by the Singpore authorities, that may be
the last to be heard. While what has happened is clearly in Mr Leeson's
interests, from the point of view of the British investors, who trusted
Barings, as well the matter of public trust in the Bank of England's ability to
supervise the activities of such banks, it is bad news.
Other Barings executives criticised by the Board of Banking Supervision for
their part in the affair include Mr Ron Baker, head of the financial products
group, was found to have no real understanding of the nature of Baring Futures
Singapore and to have failed to familiarise himself with what Mr Leeson was
doing, and the former Bank supervisor, Mr Chris Thompson. Although the
chairman, Mr Peter Baring, and the deputy chairman, Mr Andrew Tickey, emerged
relatively unscathed, they, too, had to take responsibilty for the fact that
senior management was so ill-informed.
Mr Leeson's lawyers have all along claimed he was being made a scapegoat for
``a wide circle of people''. This magic circle may well, because of the deal,
simply vanish. It is no longer operating, its members are no longer working for
Barings, and the supervisory authorities have learned the lessons of the
Barings affair.
Mr Bax and Mr Jones have so far not commented on either report, but in a letter
to the Singapore Times in March, claimed that Mr Leeson reported directly to
London.
The Serious Fraud Office said last night it had not uncovered any evidence of
criminal actions by London-based Barings staff, but it would be taking a keen
interest in developments in Singapore. The SFO investigation into Barings would
be reactivated in the event that information were to come to light which
warranted it pursuing any actions in Britain, he added.
</TEXT>
