<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Referee supervisors to continue as normal SFA refuse to bow to demands for change</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093879</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DESPITE criticism from Rangers and Scottish Professional Footballers'
Association secretary Tony Higgins, the SFA have no intention of altering its
use of referee supervisor reports in disciplinary cases.
Chief executive Jim Farry made it clear yesterday that, under the current
rules, the committee is entitled to conduct an inquiry into any player
misbehaviour from wherever the information comes.
``We have a good relationship with the member clubs who agree to the articles
and rules that allow the disciplinary committee to investigate any reports of
misconduct.'' said Farry. ``All reports are examined and passed on to the
relevant body. It is up to them if any inquiry is instigated, wherever the
report comes from. We once received one from the Lord Provost of Glasgow.''
The SFA case, disputed by Rangers, is based on the articles and standing orders
which refer to the council having the right to discipline any player or
official who brings the game into disrepute . . . and the committee's
entitlement to ``deal with all reports in connection with field offences or
misconduct . . .''
The chief executive also insisted that the role of the referee supervisor is as
it has always been. ``His mission is to construct a report for the association
on the pre-prepared form that he fills in after the game. It is then up to the
SFA to pass on any relevant matters to the respective department.
``Contrary to opinion, the supervisor is not there to pick up on the referee's
mistakes but if there is a clear indication in his report that there is a
disciplinary matter which needs investigation then it is passed on.''
Farry said that the meeting on Thursday, during which two Rangers players, Paul
Gascoigne and John Brown, were suspended for one game as a result of incidents
not reported by the referee in the game against Aberdeen at Ibrox, had been
conducted fairly.
``Every player had his chance to state his case, there was time for the
reporter of the incidents (the supervisor) to be questioned and to question the
players and then a decision was reached.''
He also pointed out that the punishment handed out matched the suspension which
would have ensued had the players concerned been shown a red card by the
referee.
Two players also involved in controversy at Ibrox, Rangers' Alan McLaren and
Billy Dodds, of Aberdeen, had their cases deferred in order to allow police
investigations in which they had been questioned, to be completed.
However, that does not mean the others, Gascoigne and Brown, will be excluded
from any action taken by the procurator fiscal who has asked for the
investigation.
Meanwhile, Gascoigne was in his usual place in the squad announced by manager
Walter Smith for the trip to Edinburgh to meet Hearts at Tynecastle, but the
manager left his listeners intrigued by saying that Brian McGinty, who played
in the side that was successful in last week's visit to the capital, when they
beat Hibs 4-1, will keep his place.
With Stuart McCall and Brian Laudrup fit again, there seems to be a
well-stocked midfield, especially as Charlie Miller has also to be accommodated
but perhaps McCall will be used in a different role.
McGinty, who did well last week, will be 19 shortly and may be about ready to
stake his claim for a regular spot in the pool. In any case, Smith would be
pleased to see a repeat of the form his team showed at Easter Road where
Gascoigne received some of his best notices since he arrived from Lazio.
``Hearts have had something of a revival in recent weeks,'' said the manager,
``and although they were dented at Parkhead last week they will be a different
team from the one we beat at Ibrox.''
The Tynecastle side would be all the more formidable if they have striker John
Robertson in his place but, although he will have a fitness test on the injured
hamstring which kept him out last week, he may be odds against making it. Alan
Lawrence is standing by to take his place.
q DUMBARTON are set to appeal over the five-match ban imposed by the SFA on
goalkeeper Ian McFarlane on Thursday.
McFarlane was called in front of the disciplinary committee after being
red-carded twice for the one incident when a linesman said he had both
head-butted and punched Airdrie's Jim McIntyre.
McIntyre described the incident as ``handbags at 10 paces'' and Dumbarton
manager Jim Fallon said yesterday: ``Our directors will meet over the weekend
to decide whether they will make an appeal.''
Meantime, with 17-year-old Peter Dennison the only other keeper on the books,
Dumbarton last night signed the former Clydebank keeper Ken Meechan, from
Greenock Juniors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
