<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fifers out to improve their home record</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Sutherland</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093880</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECOND/THIRD DIVISIONS
IF ASKED to pick out a team who have failed to win any one of their past four
home games, you would not immediately think of East Fife, leaders of the second
division. Curiously, that indeed is the Fifers' record over the past two months.
Player-manager Steve Archibald, however, will not be too hard on his men for a
number of reasons. They would have been bound to lose momentum sooner or later,
they do still lead the division by six points, and they can boast seven wins
from eight away matches.
Today's visitors are Berwick Rangers, who share second place with Stirling
Albion, and Tom Hendrie's injury-hit Borderers have been boosted by the return
to the squad of striker Paul Rutherford, who is available for selection after a
long time out through injury.
The result at Methil will be noted with interest at Forthbank, where Stirling
will hope to extend their 12-game unbeaten league run. Out-of-form Forfar are
the visitors.
Like the leaders, Clyde fare better away from home than in front of their own
support but they will find it hard to take points from Stranraer's Stair Park.
Stenhousemuir will hope to make up for last week's home defeat - at the hands
of Clyde - by collecting the points at lowly Montrose, whose manager, Andy
Dornan, has been trying to recruit from the Highland League. Gordon Dalziel
will expect his Ayr United team to climb out of the bottom two by defeating,
and leapfrogging over, Queen of the South.
The highest attendance in the third division assuredly will be at Livingston,
where second-placed Ross County will hope to deny Jim Leishman's team a first
victory at their new Almondvale Stadium. Caledonian Thistle will do well not to
understimate East Stirlingshire, while Cowdenbeath's revival will be tested at
Arbroath.
Brechin City ought to be too strong for Albion Rovers at Cliftonhill, while the
visit of Queen's Park to Alloa takes Spiders' manager Hugh McCann back to a
ground where he once had charge. One man who was there at that time, the home
side's long-serving defender Willie Newbigging, has come off the transfer list
and will be fighting to win back a first-team place.
BILL SUTHERLAND
</TEXT>
