<TEXT>
n I LOVE beautifully dressed toddlers, velvets and muffs flatter the demon
underneath. Girls are great when they're wee; well-dressed and badly behaved,
and some of them don't grow out if it.
These children, however, aged between nine months and 10 years, are in
sartorial chains. They were photographed outside Stratford-Upon-Avon where, the
adults say, ``they had lots of fun'' carol-singing Deck The Halls With Boughs
of Holly, We Wish You A Merry Christmas and On Christmas Day In The Morning.
The whole scenario smells of bossy parents, for only a starstruck mum would
bother disciplining a toddler to learn the words to Good King Wenceslas.
Other instances of human cruelty on the photo shoot include a spot of
gardening. Yes, they were indeed ``gathering winter fuel". The girls picked
``pine cones and twigs'' in their floral dresses, while the boys ``pushed the
wheelbarrows'' in Venetian trousers and white shirts. What a lot of work to
portray a picture of gentrified countryside indolence.
