<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Radical chic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andi Robertson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093883</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OVER the course of a dozen years, Edinburgh-born skier John Vaitkus has slowly
become one of skiing's more familiar faces. Captured in spectacular action for
the pages of ski magazines and videos across the world, his profile is
instantly recognisable. His neat, technically precise skiing mixes control with
absurd dynamics and at 37 he remains in demand as one of an elite breed of
international skier.
Paradoxically for all his globe-spanning exposure to ski enthusiasts of all
standards, he remains almost entirely anonymous. Vaitkus has lived in Chamonix
for more than 10 years and has the unmatched snowfields, challenging couloirs
and cornices as his daily ``office'' routine, making his living as one of
Europe's leading ski models.
It's a remarkable existence and a success story which has outlasted the
hundreds of pretty-boy rich-kid Europeans, Antipodeans and Americans who
gravitate to photographic meccas such as Chamonix for a post-ski racing
pre-college rite of passage - if they're lucky earning beer money and perhaps a
few glossy enlargements of a once-in-a-lifetime leap.
``Over the past few years it has become crazy out here. There are kids who are
prepared to fling themselves off anything without a second thought just to get
themselves on to film. It's amazing that, as yet, there's been no real tragedy,
but it's waiting to happen,'' says Vaitkus, who has worked with most of
Europe's top photographers, but now chooses only to work mostly as a close-knit
team, with those who sympathise with his working methods and ethics.
``It's come to the stage where photographers demand more and more, not because
they've shot it all perfectly before, but because they want to make up for
their technical shortcomings by getting kids to do bigger more radical jumps
and that's stupid.''
Vaitkus points to the exploits of the mohawk-styled American stunt skier Glen
Plake and Scott Schmidt; and also producer Greg Stump whose enormous video
sales have made them ski-household names. Their exploits become simply
run-of-the-mill, swelling this lemming-like exodus to the mountains to jump
higher and further in pursuit of celluloid glory.
His stock in trade has been stills and video work in advertisements and
promotions for leading worldwide manufacturers such as Salomon and Tenson,
while in the UK one of the most comprehensive annual collections of Vaitkus in
action is featured in the retail chain Ellis Brigham's weighty, glossy
mail-order bible The White Book in which he has starred for a number of years.
The world recession in the ski market coupled with the fast-growing influx of
do-it-for-nothing thrill seekers has made it all the tougher. He reflects that
five years ago a mere 20 days of work early in the season was more than enough
to keep body and soul intact for the year. Now now he is increasingly being
forced to exploit other avenues in paragliding and climbing.
Those who hire him rank him among only a handful of successful, totally
dedicated European ski-action models. While his contemporaries have almost
universally Alpine or Scandinavian backgrounds, born in the mountains,
Vaitkus's enduring passion for the sport started on the dry-slope matting of
Hillend as one of the first Edinburgh comprehensive school kids taught to ski
as part of the curriculum.
He too may have served his apprenticeship on the race circuits in the winter,
but he also bummed in the summer skiing resorts, living in a beaten-up Renault
6 for three months just to ski every day.
His teenage potential was rewarded as one of the first recipients of the Boyd
Anderson scholarship, which was awarded by the benefactor who granted much of
the land Hillend is sited on. It was for less privileged kids who needed to get
racing and training on snow. He went on to become a respected coach to British
Alpine Racing Clubs but gave up when, he says, he really felt he couldn't look
British children in the eye and tell them they really could go on to win World
Cups.
``Racing's a vital background for what I do now. It requires at least
centimetre if not millimetre precision every time, just as it's needed when you
make a turn for a top photographer who expects you to keep the skis' logos
perfectly framed - even when you're dropping in on a big cornice -- so I guess
all those wet nights at Hillend must be worth something now!''
Most of all he feels the new crop of bone-headed daredevils are simply missing
the point, trading only on the freefalling seconds of big air - not that he
doesn't still yearn for the same regular adrenalin fix and will take the
scariest of drops in his stride, but his is a craft which has been honed
through winter and summer months in Chamonix.
``Now I always know the risks exactly, intuitively. I'll have flown the slopes
through the summer paragliding, or climbed them, and know the likely conditions
for any given weather pattern. We set out to minimise the risks. I want to do
this for a lifetime, not to have to give it up tomorrow. What most of these
kids are losing out on is the whole mountain experience.''
Vaitkus has turned director, teaming up with fellow skier Roger Lambert and
Swedish cameraman Lars Pykto to make their second film over a six-week period
last spring. The Long Way Down records an inspirational descent from a 4000m
peak above Chamonix dropping 6000ft of vertical, down through the tree line
towards the valley floor.
Avoiding the cliches of endless cliff jumps and wipeouts, it concentrates
instead on stunning scenery and dangerous descents in areas never skied before.
With a budget of around #15,000 it reputedly challenges even the multi-million
dollar productions of Warren Miller.
At one point in shooting Vaitkus dropped on to a 45-degree untouched face only
to find the six inches of new snow slide away from underneath him to reveal a
sheer wall of glacial blue ice.
``My first thought was that my only means of survival, my ice axe, was on my
pack but fortunately I had brand new skis on and the razor sharp edges gripped
until I managed to get my pack off and sort myself out.''
In the immediate future the trio will be skiing to earn their keep but looking
for funding for their next film project. A job which, says Vaitkus, is a much
more daunting mountain to conquer
.
n  Jill Crawshow offers a comprehensive guide to the best in skiing -- pages 42
and 43.
</TEXT>
