<HEADLINE>Additives approved</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093884</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE United Kingdom Agricultural Supply Trade Association has approved 69 forage
additives which are recognised as being capable of improving at least one
aspect of UK silage making. The scheme sets out in which of nine separate
categories silage additives are approved.
Mr Tony Baldry, Minister of State for Agriculture, has welcomed the creation of
a UK-wide register of products which gives livestock farmers up-to-date,
independent information on approved additives.
``The silage additives industry has become increasingly important,'' he said.
``Far more sophisticated products have been developed, which allow not only for
a high degree of control over the fermentation process but also other benefits
such as increased liveweight gain for beef cattle and improved milk output for
dairy cows.''
He praised the UKASTA scheme as a good example of self-regulation by industry.
</TEXT>
