<DOCNO>GH951202-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Panel of judges overturn  1949 fair trial ruling Lawyers'  bungling  grounds for appeal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN, Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PANEL of five judges ruled yesterday that incompetent legal representation
can amount to a miscarriage of justice in Scots law.
In a landmark decision, the Court of Criminal Appeal brought the Scottish law
into line with legal systems in a number of other countries and overruled a
previous case which is nearly 50 years old.
The judges made it clear, however, that they were not opening the floodgates
and that an appeal over incompetence would succeed only where it had led to the
denial of a fair trial and a miscarriage of justice.
The appeal was brought by James Anderson, 44, who was jailed for three years
and nine months at the High Court in Glasgow for a serious assault and a Bail
Act offence.
He alleged that his solicitor-advocate had changed previously agreed tactics
without consultation and ignored instructions to attack the character of the
victim in the assault charge.
Lord Hope, the Lord Justice General, who heard the appeal with Lord Justice
Clerk Ross, Lords Sutherland, Cameron and Johnston, said that in the case of
McCarroll in 1949 it had been decided that lack of skill or diligence in the
preparation or conduct of a defence could not be pleaded as a miscarriage of
justice.
Both the Lord Advocate and defence counsel for Anderson agreed that McCarroll
should now be overruled.
Lord Hope said the starting point for an examination of the whole issue was the
right to a fair trial - an essential principle for any system of criminal
justice. Part of that was that an accused should have his defence presented to
the court.
The right to a fair trial should not be viewed as involving a right to a
retrial simply because things might have been done differently by an accused's
counsel or his solicitor.
However, the decision in McCaroll's case seemed to mean that even if the
conduct of counsel or the solicitor deprived the accused of the right to a fair
trial by not presenting his defence, the court could not interfere on the
ground that there had been a miscarriage of justice.
``We regard that proposition as unacceptable,'' Lord Hope said.
The court was referred to cases from England, New Zealand, South Africa, The
USA, Canada and Australia, countries which all recognise the right of the court
to intervene if a fair trial has been denied by the incompetency of counsel.
Lord Hope said counsel's independence must be preserved if he was to fulfil his
duty to the court and act in the public interest. He could not disregard his
client's instructions, but the way in which he conducted the defence within
those instructions was a matter for him.
Therefore, the circumstances in which an appeal would be allowed on the grounds
of inept legal representation must be narrowly defined.
``The conduct must be such as to have resulted in a miscarriage of justice. It
can only be said to have resulted in a miscarriage of justice if it has
deprived the accused of his right to a fair trial.
``That can only be said to have occurred when the conduct was such that the
accused's defence was not presented to the court.''
In Anderson's case, the appeal court ruled that there had been no miscarriage
of justice and his appeal must be refused.
Lord Hope said the solicitor-advocate who conducted the defence at the trial
had been fully justified in not attacking the character of the victim in the
assault charge.
Lord Hope added: ``The criticisms which have been made of the
solicitor-advocate in this case fall far short of an allegation that he
deprived Anderson of his right to a fair trial.''
Mr Alan Boyd, President of the Law Society of Scotland, commented: ``Legal
representation must be of an acceptable standard, particularly where an
individual's liberty is at stake.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Six years for armed robber</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN armed robber who staged a hold-up at an off-licence weeks after his release
from prison was jailed for six years yesterday.
Brian Dick, 28, managed to get #209 cash from a woman employee by threatening
her with a wine bottle.
However, Dick, of Crewe Road Gardens in Edinburgh, did not escape from the
premises and was still there when police arrived to answer an alert.
The High Court in Edinburgh heard that the raider had been given separate
sentences of three and five years for armed robbery. He had only been freed
from his last prison term weeks before he staged the robbery at Victoria Wine,
in Dalry Road, Edinburgh, on October 26 this year.
The Lord Justice Clerk, Lord Ross, told him he had to take account of his
previous record and added: ``My principle concern must be the protection of the
public.''
Dick admitted assaulting the woman employee by threatening her with a bottle
and robbing her of the money.
He also pled guilty to resisting arrest and struggling violently with police
and was given a further three months in prison.
Advocate depute James Campbell said that after browsing in the shop, Dick
picked up a wine bottle and told the employee: ``All the money out of the
till.''
After he was handed the cash he demanded tape from a security camera.
But other customers arrived at the store and the shopworker managed to press a
panic button.
His defence, solicitor-advocate Ray Megson said that Dick had committed the
offence on ``the spur of the moment''.
He said Dick could give no real explanation for failing to escape from the shop
after he was given the money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
