<HEADLINE>The artist as a young fogey</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN BOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093887</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROY FULLER: Writer and Society
Neil Powell
Carcanet, #25. SOME poets live dangerously and we love them for it, love Burns
for his boozing and Byron for his battling and Berryman for his battling and
boozing. These reckless, self-sacrificial poets seem authentic to a reading
public suspicious of the creative credentials of Wallace Stevens who became
vice-president of the Hartford Accident and Indemnity Company; and Roy Fuller
who became vice-president of the Building Societies Association and a governor
of the BBC.
In 1968 I was one of those foolish enough to run against Fuller in the election
for the post of Oxford Professor of Poetry. Fuller, who described himself as
the Conservative candidate, was the obvious man for the establishment.
Nominated by Auden and Day Lewis - old leftists who had left old beliefs behind
as they lurched to the right - he had impeccable social credentials as the
senior solicitor of the Woolwich Equitable Building Society. Fuller was duly
elected, easily beating Enid Starkie, Yevtushenko, Al Alvarez, Kathleen Raine
and yours truly.
Recalling this event, Neil Powell notes: ``Oxford's academic establishment
breathed an almost unanimous sigh of relief on finding that its most public
literary honour had landed in such capably safe hands''.
Although he flirted with Marxism and sold the Daily Worker on the streets of
Blackpool in the 1930s, Fuller was always a safety-firster. It was fashionable
for English poets - Auden and Day Lewis and Spender - to make Marxist noises in
the 1930s and Fuller simply followed the fashion. After Margaret Thatcher made
her marks on British society, Fuller described himself as ``an old bull of the
right''. He took pride in meeting Her Majesty and when the Queen asked him what
he thought of Ted Hughes (destined to become Poet Laureate) he replied: ``Well,
he certainly looks like a poet.''
Fuller himself looked like a safety-firster although he attempted to add a dash
of danger when describing himself in his novel Image of a Society (1956): ``His
face was very smooth, his pallor had an orange tinge: against it the moustache
seemed incongruously luxuriant and brown.'' Smooth is the essential epithet.
After a stretch in a private practice as a solicitor, Fuller joined the
Woolwich in 1938. The year after that he established himself as an acolyte of
Auden in his first collection, Poems; and the year after that he prepared to go
to the war in which he served as a radar mechanic in East Africa then as a
radio and radar officer at the Admiralty in London. In 1942 he published his
second collection, The Middle of a War, and this remains the most impressive
artistic achievement of all his slim volumes and 10 novels.
The title poem of The Middle of a War is a self-portrait of the artist as a
young fogey: ``My photograph already looks historic./The promising youthful
face, the matelot's collar,/Say `This one is remembered for a lyric./His place
and period - nothing could be duller'. '' Fuller roughly rhymes with ``duller''
and knew he could not equal the intensity of the Great War Poets of the past,
Owen and others who died in action. Fuller was, however, good enough to win the
approval of safe old Spender who favourably reviewed The Middle of a War and
wrote of its author as ``the only poet who has given us as clear a picture of
the life of the Forces as some of the war artists have done in painting''.
Surviving the war - ``Incredibly I lasted out a war,/Survived the unnatural,
enormous danger'' claimed the poet, though Powell claims ``given the cushy good
fortune of his wartime career his survival was not really incredible at all'' -
Fuller returned to his safe job with the Woolwich and Powell points out that he
carefully avoided contact with the literary louts of London. He continued to
write poems, of course, but he also displayed his professional expertise in
Questions and Answers in Building Society Law and Practices (1949).
Powell sees Fuller as a man who carefully cultivated the two contrasting
aspects of his personality - a bit of a professional bore yet also a practising
bard who reached ``greatness'' in his poem The Ides of March, from Brutus's
Orchard (1957). The Ides of March is a statement of Fuller's paradoxical
position, his ``romantic, classic situation''.
Fuller's poems always define his existence as a dilemma, a matter of living
with classy (rather than classic) comforts while longing for some meaningful
romantic quest. He is always writing about himself, even when assuming roles as
in Translation from Counterparts (1954). Supposedly speaking as Cinna, the poet
from Julius Caesar, Fuller sticks to the same old subject of himself: ``I will
stop expressing my belief in the rosy/Future of man . . . When they call me
reactionary I shall smile,/Secure in another dimension . . . The ruling class
will think I am on their side/And make friendly overtures, but I shall retire/."
The fiction of Fuller is similarly autobiographical. Having read Counterparts,
Robert Graves wrote to Fuller: ``But what a world you live in! . . . Your
solicitor's job doesn't sound very thrilling.'' Fuller responded by writing a
novel, Image of a Society, about life as lived in a building society in a plot
that turns upon the overvaluing of a property and the casual construction of a
mortgage document.
Featured in the novel is Fuller himself in the image of Philip Witt, a building
society solicitor who writes on the side. Witt, as Powell accurately puts it,
is ``a self divided between a career which he despises and a literary ambition
in which he lacks confidence''. The Woolwich was not amused and Fuller was told
to hold his tongue on the subject of building societies. He did as he was told.
``I would like to renounce the waking rational life,'' wrote Fuller in
Counterparts: ``I would like to resolve to live fully/In the barbarous world of
sympathy and fear.'' He never did. He did his professional duty and he died, in
Powell's opinion, as an unfairly neglected poet. Powell is an admirer of Fuller
but aware of his flaws and his ``divided self's wishful thinking, inventing a
purely hypothetical alter ego''. Powell is to be applauded for his controlled
enthusiasm and for describing one man's struggle to reconcile creativity with
careerism. Career, in this case, came first.
</TEXT>
