<HEADLINE>Call off the battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jim Hewitson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra Scotching the myths</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093888</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jim Hewitson recalls how a fair maid's
name got in the way
of a good battle
DRUMS were beating, banners flying in the breeze and everything was set for the
Battle of Falkirk, 1578 vintage. But you'll search the histories in vain for
details of this stramash because it's one of the very few battles I can trace
in the history of Scotland which was called off at the eleventh hour - with the
teams lined up and the referee's whistle to his lips, if you'll pardon the
Brockville analogy.
So many dire conflicts and so much bloodshed permeate the pages of Scottish
history that it's a delight to come across a battle which was abandoned with
opposing armies squaring up to each other on the field, a day which ended not
with a roll-call of the dead and maimed but with troops trudging home to the
wife and weans and their ain fireside. Surely, only the psychopaths were
disappointed.
Although on July 25, 1578, the young King James VI had taken the reins of
government, the former Regent, the Earl of Morton, was still effectively
running the show. He had been throwing his weight around to such an extent (for
example, persuading the King to switch a meeting of parliament to Stirling from
Edinburgh where he felt safer) that he had angered a large section of the
Scottish nobility including Argyle, Athole, Montrose, Lyndsay, Ogilvie,
Maxwell, and Herries.
Licking their wounds in Edinburgh this disaffected crew latched on to (or
possibly originated) a story which was certainly doing the rounds (although
later publicly denied by James) suggesting that the King wished to be freed
from the clutches of Morton. Many of Edinburgh's citizens were irked at the
removal of the parliament to Stirling and so there was no difficulty getting
together a force which, commanded by the Earls of Athole and Argyle, left the
capital on August 11 and was supplemented on its arrival at Falkirk until it
was 7000-strong.
Some nice historical detail is available. We learn that among their banners was
a silk affair displayed by the men of Merse and Teviotdale on which was painted
a boy ahint bars with the motto - ``Liberty I crave, and cannot it have'' and
beneath it the answer of the soldiers that they would die to set him free.
In the crazy politics of the time Morton's party, of course, also claimed to be
acting both in the King's name and for his welfare and had gathered a force of
some 5000 men which although outnumbered had superiority in cavalry and a host
of experienced soldiers.
Drawn up to face each other at Falkirk, a desperate conflict looked on the
cards. However, a brief delay occurred when a Teviotdale man called Tait
challenged anyone in the Morton camp to ``break a lance with him'' in honour of
his mistress. The call was taken up by one James Johnston, a retainer of the
Master of Glamis. On a little plain beside the River Carron the joust took
place with all due ceremony. In the first tilt, Tait was run through by his
adversary's lance and fell dead from his horse.
However, this chivalrous hiatus had allowed Sir Robert Bowes, the English
ambassador, and two Edinburgh ministers, to pass between the armies and after
frenzied discussion a basis for a truce was identified and the forces
dispersed, at least for a wee while.
Just for the record, the two bona fide Battles of Falkirk were in 1298 (defeat
for William Wallace) and 1746 (victory for Bonnie Prince Charlie). One each -
extra time still being played.
</TEXT>
