<DOCNO>GH951202-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP tells court of economy in sharing beds</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MPS sometimes sleep together on foreign trips to save money, Tory David Ashby
told the High Court yesterday.
Mr Ashby told the eighth day of his libel action against the Sunday Times it
was ``unimportant'' whether he had slept with a man or not and there had been
other times when he had had to share a bed with fellow MPs.
He said the fees office, which controls expenditure, will allow an MP only so
much and that as a consequence an MP may have to share with another member.
Mr Richard Hartley QC, for the Sunday Times, asked him to name the other MPs he
had slept with. Mr Ashby replied: ``I can't do that.''
He said, however, he would write down the names for the judge and jury.
Mr Ashby is claiming damages over an article published in the Sunday Times on
January 16, 1994, which said he shared a double bed with a male friend during a
holiday in Goa at the end of 1993.
He says it alleged that he was a homosexual who had misled his wife about the
nature of his sexuality; that he had lied to the public about having an affair
during a French holiday with a Dr Ciaran Kilduff; and that he was a hypocrite
in having emphasised the importance of the family in his last election address.
Times Newspapers Ltd and former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil deny libel,
although they accept that Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa. They
assert that the MP was, and is, having an affair with 32-year-old Dr Kilduff.
Mr Ashby denied grabbing a carving knife or threatening to kill his wife during
a row at his constituency home in Ravenstone in June when she found him in the
company of a friend, retired civil servant Edward O'Byrne.
The jury watched extracts from a video tape of Mr Ashby arriving at and leaving
Dr Kilduff's flat in Westleigh Avenue, Putney, last August Bank Holiday.
The newspaper claims he stayed overnight while Mr Ashby says he left late on
the Monday and returned early on the Tuesday, but that was not recorded on
video.
Mr Ashby said the extracts showed him wearing different clothes and his car
parked in a different position.
Mr Hartley read out a letter from Mr Ashby to his wife, written some months
before the hearing in response to a letter from her warning that she would be
giving evidence for the newspaper if he persisted with the action.
Mr Ashby wrote that she was being ``taken for a ride'' by the Sunday Times.
He wrote that if he lost the case, he would be destroyed as a barrister and MP
and his means of keeping her would be gone.
Mr Ashby angrily told Mr Hartley that the letter was not an attempt to stop his
wife from giving evidence, but a bid to get some dignity back and give her some
respect amongst her fellows.
``Alastair Brett (Times Newspapers' in-house lawyer) was trying desperately to
break and has succeeded in breaking up what remains of my relationship with my
wife,'' Mr Ashby said.
``How dare you suggest otherwise. How dare you.''
The court adjourned briefly as Mr Ashby broke down.
Re-examining, Mr Ashby's counsel, Mr Geoffrey Shaw QC, asked if the five days
he had spent in the witness box had been a strain.
Mr Ashby responded, ``I can't say how much of a strain they have been. I think
the whole litigation, everything that has happened, I'll never forget it. I'll
live with it for the rest of my life. It's going to haunt me.''
``Do you relish speaking of these private matters?'' asked Mr Shaw.
``I've hated every moment,'' Mr Ashby replied.
Asked if he had been feeling unwell some of the time, Mr Ashby, who is diabetic
and has a heart condition, said it had been very difficult.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
