<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coal and candlelight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH OUSTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra birdwatch</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n MIDWINTER on the Ythan, and a shocking pink dawn over the black dunes. Ice
floes hush against the banks, borne inland on a rising tide. Long-tailed ducks
flight in from their roosts offshore, laying the arctic sky on to the river
where they settle.
They make vees on the moving water, then dive, then flight again, calling out
the winter's necessities in a romantic yodel: ``Coal and Candlelight''. Of all
the transliterations of their call, this old name evokes most strongly the
frosty northern coasts where they winter.
It is only since the 1970s that we have found out how many ``Caloos'', as they
are known in the northern isles, winter with us. A great roost was found off
Burghead, ten or 15 thousand strong, too far out to be seen from land. In Scapa
Flow they roost likewise in the centre, where the German sailors must have
heard them in winter of 1919. By day they scatter in little parties off the
coast, diving for molluscs longer and deeper than any other duck: a minute at a
time and well over a hundred feet down.
Off any sandy shore from Barra round to Bellhaven you could pick out twos and
fours through binoculars. They look white against a blue sea, but closer you
see a patchwork pattern of browns and blacks. In flight the long, pointed
tailfeathers show which give them the fowler's name ``sea-pheasant''. By April
you will see bigger parties on the lochs and bays of Orkney, now moulted to a
darker brown with white cheeks. By the Churchill Barriers they perform a rich
repertoire of bowing, stretching, twisting, splashing displays, pairing for the
long flight to the arctic. They look like a different species then, until you
hear that unforgettable, musical cry.
As a child, on first looking into the Observer's Book of Birds, the prints of
the long-tailed ducks, with a wild northern shore behind, held me spellbound.
Every time I see them again, or hear their ``Coal and Candlelight'', the spell
is woven anew.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Five children and mother died in blaze after quarrel, trial jury told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093892</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN murdered a mother and her five young children in a fire which engulfed
the bedroom they were sharing, a court heard yesterday.
Mr Scott Vowls, 24, had quarrelled with the woman's brother with whom he had
earlier shared the flat, alleged Mr David Calvert-Smith, prosecuting at the Old
Bailey.
He returned to his former flat, took hold of a double mattress, and left it
``outside what he thought was the man's bedroom. He deliberately set fire to
it,'' Mr Calvert-Smith said.
``The result is hard to contemplate. It was a single, terrifying and terrible
incident.''
Mr Vowls, a barman, of Bermondsey, south London, has denied murdering Mrs Judy
Newell, 35, and her five children, aged between one and seven years, at the
flat on the Longfield Estate, Bermondsey, in January.
The prosecution alleged that Mr Vowls had moved into the flat in July, 1994,
with Mrs Newell's brother and another man, but in January moved out after a
quarrel with the brother. Mr Calvert-Smith said: ``We say Vowls kept his key.''
He left a mattress and a bag containing some clothes in his room. Less than
three weeks later Mrs Newell moved in with her five children, Nathan, seven,
Cassandra, six, Ashley, four, Courtnay, three, and Curtis, one.
Mr Calvert-Smith said the brother moved out to accommodate them. ``The family
slept in his bedroom.
``Vowls returned at midnight two days later, retrieved his clothes and left
them on an outside balcony.''
He then went back inside and ``deliberately set fire to the double mattress'',
alleged Mr Calvert-Smith.
A man sleeping in the lounge was able to escape by climbing over a balcony. The
father of Mrs Newell's children, who had recently separated from her, was first
suspected of starting the blaze.
``There were allegations that he had ill-treated her. But as investigations
progressed it became clear from circumstantial evidence surrounding the case
that Vowls and he alone must have been responsible for the killings.''
Mr Vowls was a loner who often drank in a local pub, Mr Calvert-Smith said.
He had left the flat after arguing with Mrs Newell's brother.
``It was the sort of argument people in flats have - about untidiness and
making a proper contribution to the electricity bill,'' Mr Calvert-Smith said.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
