<DOCNO>GH951202-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hearts' Italian import is more than just a hit-man Bruno is tackling hard-man problem</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Paul</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>this sporting life</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE ARRIVED in Scotland with a reputation that suggested he was only marginally
less menacing than Don Corleone, a football hit-man whose temper was as short
as his closely cropped hair, yet Pasquale Bruno exudes Mediterranean charm, not
to mention dark looks, which, I hear tell, has ladies buckling at the knees.
Bruno, who has quickly established himself as a favourite with Hearts fans, is
disarmingly frank about his image as a hard man, just as he quite freely talks
about his observations of Scotland, Edinburgh, and football in this country.
The fact that, in the main, he is complimentary ought not to be taken as too
significant, either, because the impression this hardened, experience but
likeable pro gives is of a man who would not hesitate with a criticism, just as
he doesn't hang about with his tackles.
So far, the new man likes much of what he has seen and has had no problems at
all in fitting in with the capital lifestyle. Partly, this is due to his
discovery that Scotland is predominantly a wintry but welcoming extension of
the old country itself. ``There are so many Italians here,'' he says, with the
expressive gesture that has not fooled a referee for years. ``Restaurant owners
and waiters and people like that - it is not so different.''
Bruno, who has two cousins in Hamilton, a privlege he probably shares with much
of the Italian population, was born in Lecce on the Mediterranean coast, where
he learned and began his pro football career with the local Serie B team.
A four-year spell with Lecce was followed by four at Como in Serie A, then
Juventus for three years, Torino for three years, and finally Fiorentina for
the past couple of seasons.
It is a career that was signposted with major successes, particularly for
Juventus in the UEFA Cup of 1991, when they also won the Italian Cup, and city
rivals Torino, where the club were to reach the final of the same competition
but lost to Ajax. There were other winning medals but also a perceived
toughness that earned him a much larger collection of yellow and red cards.
Ask him how many and he will shrug and say: ``I do not know, honestly.'' Press
him a little and he will confess that he did miss a total of 50 games because
of suspension. When I responded in astonishment, the old Latin humour surfaced
as he put his head in hands in mock shame.
Bruno, none the less, seriously refutes the hard-man charge, insisting that
there are far tougher characters in the Italian game. ``The problem for me,''
he says in English that may not be perfect but is creditable - ``I want to
learn it better here'' - ``was that I had become known as a tough guy. Referees
knew who I was and if I fouled someone I could be sent off, when another player
could do the same foul and nothing happen.'' All of these remarks are
accompanied by expressive hand movements that leaves the interviewer astounded
that he didn't convince any referee that canonisation was imminent.
``They call me ``The Animal' but this is not true. There are many harder
players than me in Italy. `The Animal' stays with me and referees get to know,
and they see me make fouls, but not others.''
Pasquale's popularity with the Gorgie Road aficionados has not been based on
the macho image, more on the Italian's ability to read games, allied to an
incisive and accurate tackling skill. There are not too many ordinary players
in Serie A and certainly not one who survived so many years in its heat. Bruno
can play. That is for sure.
In Scotland to date he has still managed to pick up two yellow cards and it
would be a brave man who would predict he will steer clear of Park Gardens
during his 18-month contract with Hearts. However, the man himself has been
comfortable with many aspects of the Scottish game. ``Here, if I tackle a
player and he goes down, he gets up again right away. In Italy he rolls around
and around for minutes. That is why I like it here.
``The game here is tough and strong, but fair. People are not diving or
pretending. I like that. Also, the game is on for 90 minutes, not like Italy,
where there is so much time lost for injuries and other time-wasting. In Italy
a game lasts one hour.''
This is not to say he is uncritical of the game he has joined. ``Sometimes the
long ball is a good idea but other times you have to pass the ball about from
the back.''
He arrived at Tynecastle aware of Hearts' contribution to the Scottish game.
Joe Jordan, who seems to be universally popular in Italy, told him all about
the Edinburgh club, as well as the delights of the city. ``Edinburgh is a
beautiful place. My wife Marcella and I like it very much.'' His older
daughter, 11-year-old Sandra, has stayed with his sister in Florence ``because
she likes the school'' but young Marta, who is five, is in Scotland.
``The Scottish people are different from the English. They are very friendly,
warm, like the people in the Mediterranean where I come from. The fans have
been good to me. They are passionate, like the Torino and Fiorentina supporters.
``I want also to help the young players at Hearts to develop. Scottish football
must improve its organisation and skills because you saw the different class
when Juventus met Rangers. It is maybe not so bad when teams from abroad come
to Scotland but when they go to Italy, say, the teams there have so many
top-class players and technique that it is difficult.
``I think British football could become leaders again and I hope so, because it
is so important for the people here.''
Perhaps his remarks about the English would have been readjusted if he had
moved to Manchester City a few years ago, when they were keen to bring him from
Italy. ``It was always my dream to play in British football one day but it
didn't happen with Manchester City or Crystal Palace, who also had been
interested. The problem then was that I was earning too much money and they
could not pay so much.'' It was at that time he spoke to Paul Gascoigne, then
with Lazio, to get the Manchester City picture, but he also played against him,
and knows and admires the Rangers player's talent.
``I also played against Laudrup and Mikhailichenko when they were in Italy.''
He will meet two or maybe three of them again this afternoon at Tynecastle when
he knows his side are in for a hard afternoon. ``Rangers are rich and can get
the top players but in football you never know. I think we can do a good
result.''
The fact that he has scarcely had an injury in his 16 years as a professional
has meant that this 33-year-old may have more miles on the clock left than most
of his contemporaries. He is not sure what will happen when his contract runs
out. ``I know that Jim Jefferies and the chairman want to build a good team and
if that happens, I may stay a long time. Who knows?'' The shoulders shrug
again. ``I don't want to be a coach when I finish playing, maybe a general
manager.''
In the meantime, the old Med charmer will get on with his business, proving
that he has a lot of talent still going for him. He wouldn't deny he likes the
going when it gets tough, which might be reflected in the player has most
admired. ``Gentile was my favourite.'' If memory serves me right, that old
Italian star turn was able to look after himself, too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for action on BSE regulations</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093895</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AGRICULTURE Minister Douglas Hogg was last night coming under increasing
pressure to tighten ``mad cow disease'' regulations after a leading brain
scientist warned that humans could be at risk.
Shadow Agriculture Minister Gavin Strang echoed Professor Sir Bernard
Tomlinson's call for beef offals to be banned from the food chain.
Earlier Sir Bernard, a neuropathologist and medical adviser to the Government,
warned that ``mad cow disease'' - bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) -
could be transmitted to humans. His warning came after reports at least three
farmers and three teenagers have been struck down by the human equivalent of
BSE - Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD).
And Mr Strang says many people, who might not have been worried about BSE in
the past, will have been alarmed by a warning from a scientist of Sir Bernard's
standing.
``A lot of people are going to listen to him,'' said Mr Strang. ``Up to now the
Government has been saying that any possible link between the two diseases is
remote. I don't think that description can be justified any more.''
The Government continues to stress that there is no proven link between BSE and
CJD and says the numbers of cases of BSE are falling year on year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major expects Budget before next election</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter, Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By Our Political Correspondent
THE Prime Minister said last night that he fully anticipated there would be
another Budget before the next General Election - and that he looked forward to
several more years in power.
``This Parliament can go on towards the middle of 1997. I see no reason for it
to be foreshortened, so I would expect another Budget next November,'' he told
Channel 4 News.
Asked about the prospect of another five years in office, he replied: ``I very
much hope so. Yes, indeed.''
Earlier, when he addressed the Tory women's conference in London, Mr Major said
he was ``proud'' of this week's Budget.
He said that he and Chancellor Kenneth Clarke had resisted calls to take risks
or bribe the electorate because that would have been wrong for Britain.
``The British people have worked too hard, sacrificed too much to achieve the
excellent prospects that lie ahead for us to even consider putting it at risk.
We are not that sort of Government,'' he said.
However, he forecast: ``In time 20p will become the basic rate''.
Many Tories are now pinning their hopes on the Chancellor getting close to that
target next year in another Budget
At the women's conference, Mr Clarke made a robust defence of his Budget,
promising that the tax cuts would not be reversed and that there were more to
come.
After a muted reaction from voters and business to what he himself has called a
prudent rather than an exciting Budget, Mr Clarke was out to convince that it
was just the first step in a tax and interest rate-cutting year to come.
Mr Clarke said his Budget would help win the next election because it was ``a
platform for lasting prosperity for individuals, their families and business''.
Referring to the criticism of the Budget, he said he stood accused this week of
the ``dreadful crime'' of honesty, responsibility and financial rectitude.
However, he insisted: ``The British people would not have been much impressed
by unsustainable tax cuts that were not affordable, or were branded as some
kind of electoral bribe.
``As a Conservative Chancellor, I don't believe in some mythical money tree
from which I can pick imaginary fivers and tenners.''
However, Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown, speaking in his Dunfermline
constituency, claimed that the Budget was ``unravelling with every day that
passes''.
He listed hidden charges coming into force which would wipe out the effect of
the tax cut ``almost before it has come into peoples's hands''.
Mr Brown cited the council tax, postal charges, increased TV licences, rail and
London Underground fare increases, school meals, milk rises, higher dental and
NHS charges, with raised prescription charges to come, the petrol rise and the
road tax increase.
Far from being prudent, he said, Mr Clarke was ``prisoner of failure, now
paralysed into inaction hoping something will turn up''.
Mr Brown indicated that Labour was considering subjecting the privatised
utilities not just to a windfall tax when it came to power but to compulsory
rebates to consumers.
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown, speaking in Bristol , called the Budget
``a smoke and mirrors con trick.''
The Government was borrowing to fund tax cuts to try to save their skins and
the next election, he said.
The promised extra money for education did not even cover rising pupil numbers,
the cost of inflation and pay rises for teachers.
Mr Ashdown again challenged Labour to join his party in voting against the
income tax cuts in the Commons on Tuesday at the end of the Budget debate.
</TEXT>
