<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Councils warn of building cuts. Spending curbs `will hit jobs and construction projects'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORBURGH, Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093897</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH local authority leaders meeting in Stirling yesterday warned that the
Government's clampdown on capital spending announced in the Budget would have a
devastating impact on their building programmes and on jobs in the construction
industry.
The Convention of Scottish Local Authorities has estimated that the new
restrictions will mean the loss of #100m of potential capital investment for
schools and road-building in Scotland next year.
Cosla's Labour vice-president Councillor Keith Geddes, who leads the new City
of Edinburgh Council, said he very much doubted that if the new rules had been
in force projects like the Edinburgh Festival Theatre and the new Edinburgh
International Conference Centre could have been undertaken.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth has told the new single-tier councils that
next year they will have to use 25% of their capital receipts to pay off their
growing capital debt. That sum is due to double the following year and could
increase even further if debt totals are not reduced greatly
In addition, he intends to severely reduce the amount of current revenue
councils can spend on capital projects.
Councillor Geddes said it was no use Mr Forsyth offering councils more freedom
over their capital spending priorities on the one hand - as also announced this
week - while at the same time imposing such draconian curbs on the amount which
could be invested .
The powers Mr Forsyth was planning to return to councils in some areas paled
into insignificance compared with the new powers he had taken over capital
spending, he said.
Council leaders now intend to have discussions with construction industry heads
and trade unions.
Councillor Geddes said he believed they were also genuinely concerned that the
clampdown would lead to huge reductions in new building programmes by councils
alone or in partnership with others and, therefore, to job losses.
The Scottish Secretary has said if councils were prepared to enter into
partnerships with the private sector on more capital projects this should more
than offset the effects of the changes he was imposing.
However, Councillor Geddes said it had to be recognised that joint ventures
under the Private Finance Initiative still had to be paid for from somewhere.
Council leaders also are ``gravely concerned'' at the effect of the tight
capping limits imposed on Scottish local authorities in the budget settlement
for next year.
At yesterday's meeting, they warned that if they only increased spending by
0.8% over what the Government believed they should be spending the public would
face service cuts and increases in charges. Council jobs also could go.
Between now and Cosla's next meeting with the Scottish Secretary on January 19,
the new councils have been asked to produce figures showing by just how much
they will have to cut spending to reach their capping limit and what sort of
services are likely to be hit.
The Convention also decided yesterday to press ahead with its plan to set up an
independent commission to examine the future of local government finance.
Cosla vice-president Councillor Peter Peacock, convener of the new Highland
Council, said he hoped the Scottish Office would decide to co-operate with the
setting up of a commission.
The Convention now plans to look for people prepared to serve on the proposed
body.
Councillor Peacock said it was time to recognise that the council tax was
inadequate as a means of financing local authority spending. He said the
commission would prepare a report which would be presented to the Scottish
Grand Committee and/or a Scottish parliament.
</TEXT>
