<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Children worked 12-hour shifts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BUSINESSMAN who employed children as young as 14 to work 12-hour shifts in
his bread-making factory was yesterday ordered to pay a total of #40,500 in
fines and costs.
Managing director William Eid employed two 14-year-old boys and one 15-year-old
to work in his Leicester factory, which manufactured speciality breads for
large companies.
One child was told to use the dough-cutting machine without the guard down,
exposing him to the blades, because it increased productivity, Leicester Crown
Court heard.
``All employees, including the children, were exposed to electric hazards in
the building which could have led them to receive lethal shocks,'' said Miss
Caroline Knight, prosecuting.
Eid, 31, of West Heath Gardens, Hampstead, London, was also disqualified for
three years from being a director of his firm, Balaika Ltd, of Chartwell Drive,
Wigston, Leicestershire, which used to trade as Honeytop Foods.
He admitted three charges of employing under-age children and eight breaches of
Health and Safety regulations concerning an unsafe electrical system and
unguarded machinery.
Eid was fined #7500 and ordered to pay #5000 costs. On behalf of the company he
was fined #18,000 and ordered to pay #10,000 costs for the Health and Safety
breaches.
Mr Simon Readhead, defending, said Eid was not a man who couldn't care less
about his workforce.
He blamed a female supervisor for employing the children to work in the factory.
``His plea is based on his failure to intervene or double check for himself the
ages of these children,'' said Mr Readhead.
Judge Christopher Young told Eid that the Victorian days when young children
could be exploited had long since gone.
</TEXT>
