<HEADLINE>Switched-on engineer who loves being in control</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>trailblazers</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW Circuit Engineering has come a long way in 10 years. In 1985 John Kirkwood
was in his garage, identifying faults and adapting standard socket switch units
which welders were having difficulties with. (They were always short-circuiting
and exploding.) Now he is the managing director and driving force behind a
company with an annual turnover of #2.5m, a workforce of 43 and a 25,000 sq ft
factory in Maryhill, Glasgow.
New Circuit Engineering specialises in the design, manufacture, installation
and com- missioning of automatic control system and distribution switchgear. As
the larger of only two independent switchgear companies in Scotland, it has
bucked the economic trend to take an ever-increasing share of a shrinking
market.
Kirkwood believes an important reason for this it that its independence has
allowed it to be flexible in looking at customers' requirements. It aims to
offer a high-quality total solution to their problems, and to remain
competitive at the same time.
Kirkwood had been an electrical engineer with a large Japanese company. It was
his experience there that led him to see a gap in the market for a company
which could produce switchgear designed to meet customers' specific needs.
Having solved the welders' problems by re-designing and adapting their
mass-produced switchgear, he decided to launch NCE to manufacture switchgear to
the optimum specification for every customer. He moved into a unit in Yoker in
Glasgow with a colleague and two electrical wiremen.
Since then the company has grown steadily. Kirkwood maintains his approach to
the control of the business has been central to this. The management team keeps
a very close eye on every aspect - design of the equipment, production methods,
administration and, most significant, finance.
Right from the start, he saw the importance of making NCE a ``one-stop shop''.
This meant early investment in a facility to fabricate control panels as well
as building the casing and designing and manufacturing the electrical
switchgear.
Over the 10 years since, NCE has continued to invest in new plant and
equipment. Most recently the metalwork fabrication machines were linked to an
integrated CAD/CAM facility, while a sophisticated new paint plant enables it
to tackle almost any finish.
NCE's expansion has also been helped by taking over of a number of small
companies which were specialists in their own fields - metalwork fabricators,
painters and CNC engineers. The most recent acquisition was in 1994, when it
bought Harper Hillington Controls, which had a skilled team with experience in
sewage, water treatment, marine and other specialised areas.
Unusually, this steady expansion and solid capital investment has been funded
out of profits. Kirkwood believes this moderate approach to growth is one of
the key factors behind the company's strong position.
NCE has never borrowed and, as a result, can ride out dips in demand in a way
debtors cannot. Too many companies, he says, grow too big too quickly, build up
debt which has to be serviced, regardless of business cycles, and then collapse.
In fact, the management team has been very successful in spreading its market
base so slumps in demand do not occur. Its customers range from multi-national
chemical corporations, oil companies, offshore operators and the semi-conductor
industry, to regional and district councils, specialist water and sewage firms,
hospitals, the whisky industry and ScottishPower.
So, while NEC blazes a very successful trail in the UK, the future should see
its steady expansion into the direct export market, particularly to the Far and
Middle East.
The award and entry
The scheme is a joint initiative of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young, business and
financial advisers, to recognise organisations which demonstrate innovation and
ingenuity in their operations and procedures. Forms can be obtained by sending
in the coupon below.
Entries should be based on one or a combination of:
innovation/ingenuity
business performance
product/service quality
management calibre
marketing flair
contribution to the local/Scottish economy
Rewards
The monthly winner  of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young Trailblazer award will be
presented with a certificate and will be featured in an article. The overall
TrailBlazer of the Year will send a company specialist on an agreed specialist
management training course at the renowned Harvard Business School.
</TEXT>
