<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clinton toasts his vision for a new Ireland Visit puts hope in the front line</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093900</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT BILL Clinton set out his vision for a new Ireland last night, and won
praise from all sides for giving a massive boost to the peace process. In
Dublin, he drew 80,000 cheering people on to the streets to hear a passionate
plea for a lasting solution to the Troubles and an end to bloodshed.
He called on them to stand firm alongside Premier John Bruton as he took the
necessary risks in the search for peace.
And he won warm praise from Mr Major and Mr Bruton for his commitment to peace
in Ireland and received a standing ovation in the Irish parliament.
The first tangible signs of progress came with the despatch of invitations from
the British and Irish governments to Ulster's political parties to join
preliminary discussions aimed at leading to inclusive negotiations on the
future of the province.
Mr Clinton toasted his success with a glass of Irish stout in a Dublin pub
bearing his mother's maiden name, Cassidy. It was the high emotion of the
public rally in the city centre which encapsulated the mood of his historic
three-day visit to Britain and Ireland that forced a breakthrough in the
stalled peace talks.
Having received the freedom of the city, the President set out his vision for
the future and a new Ireland.
``I know well that the immigration from your country to the shores of mine
helped to make America great,'' he said.
``But I want more than anything for the young people of Ireland, wherever they
live on this island, to be able to live out their dreams close to their roots
in peace and honour and freedom and equality.''
His address was repeatedly interrupted by rousing cheers from the crowd, waving
US and Irish flags.
In a heartfelt plea to the Irish people, he said: ``The most important thing is
that we have more in common with people who appear on the surface to be
different from us than most of us know. And we have more to gain by reaching
out in a spirit of brotherhood
Cand sisterhood. That is the challenge the young people of this generation
face.''
Mr Clinton's deft path through the minefield of Irish politics was saluted by
the British and Irish leaders.
Mr Major said the cause of peace had received a ``huge boost'' from the first
trip by a serving US President to Northern Ireland.
In a keynote speech to the Tory Women's Conference in London, the Prime
Minister delivered a blunt message to the paramilitaries: ``People who mean
peace don't need guns.'' He said the time had come for paramilitaries to
``start ridding themselves of guns and explosives'' so all-party talks could
start.
Mr Clinton's key political engagement during his 24-hour stay in Ireland was a
private 40-minute meeting with Mr Bruton.
Mr Bruton openly admitted that the President's visit created the opportunity
for London and Dublin to reach a breakthrough agreement over the peace process.
``The ingredients for the agreement have been there for some time,'' he said.
``We both recognised that the President's visit was an opportunity for both of
us to launch in the best possible circumstances an initiative we were both
going to have to agree to shortly anyway.''
Later last night Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams was sitting down to dine with Mr
Clinton. Mr Adams was among 300 people at a banquet hosted by Mr Bruton in
honour of the President at Dublin Castle.
Mr Major last night told Channel 4 News he was confident that the preparatory
talks with the parties would now go ahead following the issuing of formal
invitations by the two governments.9
</TEXT>
