<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for fast action on care in the community Alarming failures in health policy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093901</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALARMING failures in community care for people with serious mental health
problems were revealed yesterday by an independent health watchdog.
Three years after health boards and social work departments in Scotland were
instructed to implement a care programme approach there is no evidence that the
policy has been implemented.
The findings in the annual report of the Scottish Health Advisory Service were
revealed at a conference in Edinburgh, where Health Minister Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton announced a series of measures to answer the criticisms.
The policy was drawn up to ensure individual planned care and adequate back-up
facilities in the community for those with serious long-term mental illness,
including dementia, leaving hospital or already living outside.
It was also designed to avoid the horrific incidents in England where
schizophrenic patients had been discharged only to kill themselves or others.
SHAS director Donald Rankin said: ``This is a very worrying situation and
people have got to do something about it now.''
Although the absence of written individual care plans did not mean services
were shoddy, these were an essential discipline to ensure effective care and
support were actually delivered.
The SHAS conducted a survey of staff throughout the country but found a
worrying inconsistency in arrangements between boards and local authorities and
poor implementation in most areas of the whole care programme approach.
Dr Rankin said the problem was not financial but a failure to take on the
policy and implement it.
``My impression is that health boards have been waiting for social work to act
and social work has been waiting for the health boards to act,'' he said.
``The result is that after three years nothing has actually happened, but there
is now a very clear view from the Scottish Office that this has to get done.''
The SHAS findings come in the wake of earlier disquiet expressed by the
Scottish Association for Mental Health, the Mental Welfare Commission and the
Scottish Office social work group.
A review of community care policy was instigated by Mr Michael Forsyth after
his appointment as Scottish Secretary.
Lord James said the policy of caution over the introduction of community care
in Scotland had served the country well and would continue but at a more
measured pace.
``We have agreed that no hospital will close without agreed replacement
facilities and services being in place and properly resourced, and that no
person should be discharged from long-stay care without an agreed care plan
setting out arrangements for their support, care and accommodation,'' he said.
Lord James said the operation of the care programme approach would be assisted
by the experience of two pilot schemes now under way in Stirling and Glasgow.
``These will ensure that authorities do keep in touch with mentally ill people
and that services develop to provide necessary back-up, such as community
mental health teams and the availability of 24-hour on-call support,'' he added.
Lord James said the Government had long recognised community care was not a
cheap option.
``This scheme has been a valuable means of providing momentum for community
care, but now that momentum is established we want the emphasis to be on
achieving sound local agreements,'' he added.
Mr Robin Laing, director of the Scottish Association for Mental Health, gave a
broad welcome to the Minister's comments, but he said there was one glaring
flaw: he said the Scottish Office had, without consultation, frozen next year's
grant at #18m to provide community facilities and support for people with
mental illness.
``This grant has risen substantially in recent years to meet demand. Now it has
been frozen at a time when mental health has been declared a priority area.
With no increase, there will be no new developments at a time when they are
most needed,'' he said.
The SHAS report also criticises hospital discharge procedures for the elderly
and calls for a radical re-appraisal of design of psychiatric hospital wards
and the need for choice of single sex accommodation.
