<HEADLINE>Copenhagen 96. Cultural capital of Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL over Copenhagen buildings are being built, renovated or tarted up. So much
so that a month ago the city ran out of scaffolding because the entire supply
was being used - by private house-holders as well as by the authorities. The
reason for the sprucing up of an entire city? Copenhagen is the European City
of Culture for 1996.
In the four years since Copenhagen won the title, over 50,000 Danes, 42 local
authorities and three regional authorities have been involved in deciding how
to spend the #99.3m budget. Like Glasgow, holder of the prestigious title only
five years ago and one of the two role models for Copenhagen 96, the Danish
capital has opted to celebrate the accolade with a year-long festival.
Given its budget and the significance the Danes are attaching to the tourism
value of 1996, the festival is vast: 100 international programmes involving 500
contemporary visual artists and more than 200 international theatre, opera,
music, dance and ballet companies. Not to mention the hundreds of local
community projects (another leaf from the Glaswegian book) which go unlisted in
the official brochure.
The Glaswegian influence is most apparent in the philosophy behind the 1996
celebrations. Copenhagen 96 is hoping to rejuvenate the city by generating
creativity and by encouraging the people to take an active interest in cultural
events. The theme ``rediscovering the city'' has been incorporated into the
curriculum of schools all over the Copenhagen region.
The Danes are also following the Glaswegian example of renovating old buildings
and finding new uses for disused, often industrial, buildings. Under the banner
The Changing City, at least 40 such projects are in progress, one of the most
interesting being a 1960s-built former power station which is being converted
into a site for youth events, and which will include a hip hop centre for
children. Similarly, the nucleus of the year's activity is the Kronborg, a car
ferry from the 1970s, which has been transformed into ``a sea-going house of
the arts'', complete with exhibition and conference areas, a concert room, and
a cafe bar. The Kronborg has already functioned as a kind of ambassador of the
arts: when Lisbon was city of culture last year, the Kronborg sailed to visit
her.
Each day during Copenhagen's reign as city of culture, there will be at least
nine, and at most 140, events and activities on offer. These range from the
sublime to the ridiculous. Many are sublimely ridiculous: there's none o' yer
Frank Sinatra or yer Pavarotti here; in fact there's not a great deal of
popular culture in the Danish programme. They take their culture very
seriously, and define it very broadly. Among the more bizarre projects is
Smells of the City: a team of Japanese fragrance artists have been commissioned
to come up with a smell for each season. Their incense pads will be used on
buses, trains, in city squares and at the openings of events during the year.
In a similar vein, Sounds of the City will be an evolving work by the leading
``acoustic sound artist'', Klaus Schonning (from Germany), and will be made up
of sounds recorded by microphones placed in gaps between the paving stones in
the Town Square.
In addition to the 21 orchestras, 11 string quartets, 15 solo classical
pianists, and festivals of jazz, world music, Nordic Women's music, baroque
music, and choral music, there is a fascinating venture called Art Projekt 96,
scheduled to take place in September. First launched in Munich last year, the
idea is to invite a prominent musical figure to organise a day of concerts
representing the entire scope of their interest. The finale of each day will be
a concert involving the celebrity him/herself. Among those who have been asked
to participate are composer Steve Reich and the Kronos Quartet, saxophonist
Branford Marsalis and pop star Bjork, who has agreed to put on a pop-art
concert.
Even more ambitious, however, is the Copenhagen 96 visual art programme. While
the city's museums were planning exhibitions celebrating Denmark's ``Golden
Age'' (1800-1850), video art, Nordic art , Islamic and Byzantine art, 14
artists from all over the world were despatched to the Arctic where they spent
a month in isolation considering how they would interpret the experience for
Copenhagen 96. Even more artists, 96 to be precise, will be participating in
Container 96 - Art Across Oceans. The museums of ports around the world chose
artists to represent their cities by creating art installations to be
transported to the port of Copenhagen in seven-metre long shipping containers.
Everything from paintings, graphics, sculptures, photographs, and computer art
will feature, and the containers will be displayed on the main pier of
Copenhagen's harbour from May until August.
Factfile
The brochure for Copenhagen 96 is free, and obtainable from the Danish embassy
in London, offices of the Danish tourist board or by writing to Copenhagen 96,
Information Department, Amagertorv 21, DK-1160 Copenhagen K (telephone: 00 45
33 77 96 33, fax: 0045 33 77 96 01). Information on the year of culture is also
available on the Internet - on http://info.denet.dk/cph96.
</TEXT>
