<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rescuers praised as three die in crash</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR fire officer praised the bravery of passers-by who dragged six
Aberdeen University students from their car after it struck a wall and burst
into flames early yesterday.
Three of the students died and the three others were badly injured in the
accident outside the College of Agriculture, in King Street, Aberdeen.
Passing drivers and people attending a ceilidh in the college rushed to the aid
of the victims in the north-bound F-registered Audi. A passing nurse stopped to
help.
Divisional fire officer John Sangster said: ``When we arrived all six had been
removed from the vehicle and were lying on the pavement at the rear of the car.
``It is very brave for an untrained person to drag someone from a burning car.
The firemaster intends obtaining their names from the police so they can be
asked if they would be prepared to accept a commendation.
``We were there before the ambulance and we carried out first aid and heart
massage until they arrived. Two of our officers then went with the ambulance to
Aberdeen Royal Infirmary and continued to attempt resuscitation until they
reached the hospital.''
The three who died were the driver, Mr Raymond Hessey, 30, of Livingstone Road,
Thornton Heath, Surrey; Mr Anthony Oxborough, 23, of Lansdonne Close, Baildon,
West Yorkshire, and Taryn Elder, 20, from the US.
The injured are Mr Russell Betney, 19, of Millfield Close, Farndon, Chester, Mr
Darren Stonard, 21, of Newry Road, Wyken, Coventry, and Mr Ian Holmes, 18, of
Lanburgh Road, Hutton Rudby, Cleveland. They have been detained in hospital but
their conditions were not giving cause for concern.
Aberdeen University principal Professor Maxwell Irvine said: ``The entire
university community is shocked and deeply saddened by this terrible tragedy
and is giving all the assistance it can.''
Professor Irvine said that Mr Holmes and Mr Betney were both BSc freshers, and
Mr Stonard was in the final year of BSc geography. Mr Oxborough was an MSc
graduate at last week's ceremony.
q A soldier from Scotland died and another was seriously injured when they were
thrown from a car early yesterday at Weyhill, in Hampshire. Police named the
dead man as Mr Brian Allan Longmuir, 21, from Irvine.
The injured man, who is in hospital at Winchester, was named as Mr Brian
Fisher, 29, of Dinnington, Sheffield.
The men were both based at Tidworth, Hampshire.
Police said it was not certain who had been driving, and appealed for witnesses.
</TEXT>
