<DOCID>GH951202-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>With its MBO finally achieved, carrier Currie Line is shipshape once more Voyage of recovery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf  Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093905</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRANGEMOUTH-based Currie Line celebrates its 200th birthday next year. Last
February it was bought by its management for #6.7m, after what adviser Andrew
Godfrey of Grant Thornton calls ``the longest running MBO I've ever been
involved in''.
Some MBOs are over in weeks. Some take a few months of nail-biting haggling.
Others, like Currie Line's, persist, in on-off convoluted fashion, for years.
Nearly four years, as far as Mike John and his six-strong Currie Line
management team are concerned.
This story really started in April 1991. Currie was originally the Leith,
Hamburgh &amp; Hull Steam Packet Company, trading from the Baltic to the
Mediterranean. In 1940, because of that word Hamburgh, the censor started
holding up its mail.
So it changed its name to Currie Line. By 1968 the freighter business was
running out of ideas and was bought by another powerful Scottish shipping
family, the Runcimans.
``I don't think they could believe their luck,'' says Mike John. ``There was
#3m in the bank and a large estate in central Edinburgh where the Currie
directors had lived and the gardeners' bill alone was #8000 a year.'' Within
the Runciman Group, Currie became part of the Anchor Line. In 1972, Runciman
added another east coast shipping line, George Gibson, a specialist in gas
carriers.
At the time Anchor itself was still offering transatlantic services and
sailings to India. So Currie, with its short sea services, and Gibson looked
like natural additions. But, when the managing director left in the early
eighties, responsibility for the subsidiaries was spread across several pairs
of management hands. It just wasn't working.
Mike John joined in 1987. A student apprentice with Stewart &amp; Lloyds in South
Wales in the early sixties, he was a qualified metallurgist and fuel
technologist, a natural choice for the new markets which were opening up in the
North Sea in the seventies. He worked on platform construction for a subsidiary
of British Steel's tubes division, latterly as operations manager, responsible
for some 500 people.
In 1978, he decided to move into the private sector and took a job with diving
specialist Wharton Williams. By the early eighties he had moved to Oceaneering
International, a NASDAQ-quoted, Aberdeen-based service company with a turnover
of #50m.
Then the Oceaneering president was killed in a flying accident and a new CEO
moved in, determined to appoint his own team. ``Within a year there had been a
50% turnover in senior executives. I was halfway down the list and the North
Sea was in a mess,'' he recalls. ``Runciman happened to be looking for someone
to put the pieces of Currie Line back together again.''
So he moved. But, within a year, Runciman was the target of a hostile takeover
bid from the Leeds-based mini-conglomerate Telfos. The bid failed but Telfos
was left with nearly 30% of the Runciman stock. Then Telfos got into trouble
and that stake was sold to Swedish group Avena.
Little more than a year later, a larger Swedish consortium was back with an
aggressive bid for the rest of Runciman, which finally succeeded in May 1990.
Avena was interested in Runciman's property and engineering interests. Two
other consortium members were attracted by the shipping side.
Within a year the new owner was struggling to justify its purchase price. So
John and his team broached the idea of a buy-out. A colleague who had been
finance director at Oceaneering when he had been MD had since joined Grant
Thornton. He introduced John to his corporate finance colleagues. Partner Jim
Borrows became the group's principal adviser.
Initially the plan was to test the MBO bid against a trade alternative. Bids
went in that summer. But majority parent Avena went bust and a bank emerged as
the majority holder of the Runciman group assets. All talk of an MBO went on to
the back burner.
Other assets, such as the Duncan Adams haulage subsidiary were sold off. But
Currie, under John's management, was cash generative. Turnover, which had been
#3m in 1987, reached #17m by 1994.
There was talk of trade sales but, eventually, in early 1994 John and the
management were invited to renew their interest. By this time Grant Thornton's
Jim Borrows had another big deal in hand. So head of corporate finance Andrew
Godfrey stepped in.
The team had a price on the table within two days. But, again within days, they
were told it was too low. Outside advisers were appointed to find a trade
buyer. For months the business was hawked around. But eventually, after more
nail biting, an offer from the MBO team, backed by 3i and Bank of Scotland, was
accepted.
``We're rolling now,'' says John. The greatest challenge since completing the
deal has been investing in new equipment - trailers, containers and side
loaders - to enhance Currie's position as a carrier by sea and land with a
distinctive Scottish hub.
The three-vessel short-sea container service, operated by its Rotterdam-based
Macvan subsidiary, offers four sailings a week out of Grangemouth, three out of
Antwerp, two out of Rotterdam and two out of Felixstowe. ``We carry
petrochemicals, whisky, electronic goods, paper, rubber and plastics for all
the majors,'' says John.
Currie's shipping side is complemented by extensive ware- housing, including
bonds, at Grangemouth and a road haulage fleet of 29 tractors and 160 trailers,
assembled from a standing start. There is also a ships agency.
``We are very much in balance in terms of trade in and out. And the more you
are in balance, the more profitable you can be.'' At present Currie commands
12% of all unit loads moving out of Scotland.
``We can see how to grow that,'' says the man who waited long and patiently to
get to make the decisions for himself and his team.
</TEXT>
