<HEADLINE>Curtain down on panto writer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MacKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RON MacKENNA
EXCLUSIVE
ONE of Scotland's best known theatre companies was forced into hastily
rewriting its Christmas pantomime last night after paying off its artistic
director on the eve of the show's opening.
The board of Borderline Theatre Company unceremoniously made award-winning
director Mr John Murtagh redundant on Thursday - without apparently taking into
account that he had written, was directing and was due to star in the panto.
Mr Murtagh refused to take rehearsals yesterday and, through his lawyers,
issued a statement to Borderline, exercising his copyright over Babes in the
Wood, which had been due to open at the Magnum Theatre in Irvine on Monday.
The move, which is already being construed in theatre circles as an
embarrassing own-goal, also resulted in the resignation of the board's
vice-chair, Mrs Catherine Czerkawska.
``I am disgusted by the way this whole thing has been engineered. There is no
other word for it,'' Mrs Czerkawska said yesterday.
``Papers were timetabled 30 seconds before the meeting, and the redundancy was
handled in a heartless manner. John had given a lot to this company and was
popular and respected. My phone has not stopped ringing with people horrified
at this decision.''
Borderline announced yesterday that it is to cancel the first three nights of
the show while a new version is written and the cast learn their lines.
Councillor Bobby Campbell, chairman of the theatre board, who personally told
Mr Murtagh of his redundancy, confirmed that the theatre had not expected the
pantomime to be hit.
``I understand he walked out and took his script with him today. It was clear
last night that he wasn't happy, but I have been made redundant myself and I
didn't go in the huff about it. Anyway, that's his decision at the end of the
day.''
Councillor Campbell confirmed that no warning of impending redundancy had been
given to Mr Murtagh, but said that it would have been impossible to do so. The
decision had been made only at Thursday night's board meeting into the
company's financial crisis.
``The financial problems for the company are being caused by the reorganisation
of local government,'' he added. ``Strathclyde region have given Borderline
considerable grants in the past, but they are not going to be there next year.
``Already one local authority has said it will only give limited support. A
report was produced into the various financial options, and it was decided that
the job of artistic director should go.
``Nothing was mentioned before because the decision was only made at the board
meeting, and there could have been another outcome. After that it was decided
that he should go forthwith, because that was the best financial option for
him.''
Mr Murtagh said he was ``simply shocked'' by the decision. ``I have been with
this company for almost five years and had recently been praised by the Arts
Council for what I was doing. Their only comment was that I was overworked.''
He added: ``I was playing the Dame in the pantomime, as well as writing. They
just expected me to turn up for work this morning, directing the cast as
normal.''
Equity, the actors' union, yesterday described the decision to make Mr Murtagh
redundant as ``shabby'' and said it would be supporting him in legal action on
his behalf.
Scottish Organiser Mr Drew McFarlane said: ``Put crudely, the board have been
inept. This is the crassest piece of management I have ever come across in my
industrial relations experience.''
</TEXT>
