<HEADLINE>Twelve face charges after Customs and Excise raid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093907</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CUSTOMS officers last night charged 12 people after Britain's largest operation
on untaxed wines, spirits, and beers.
Customs and Excise investigators raided addresses and seized alcohol worth
several million pounds in Operation Barlow last Thursday.
Officers charged Alan Carlton, the director of Carlton Transport, based in
Fraser Road, Erith, Kent, his wife and co-director Carol, and their son Steven,
the company manager, all from Slade Green, Erith, Kent.
They will appear before magistrates at Birmingham later today together with
Alan Brown of Burnham-on-Crouch, Essex; William Beale, an importer from
Tatworth, Somerset; Francis Savage, 58, of Parsonage Street, London and Anthony
Lacey, 41, from Bexhill-on-Sea, East Sussex.
Five others will appear at Warley Magistrates Court, in Oldbury, West Midlands,
tomorrow.
They are Mark Nixon, a 41-year-old owner of a haulage firm based in West
Bromwich; Sukhdev Shergill, 26, of Bescott, Walsall; Ramjet Paul, 31, of Castle
Bromwich; Delveear Sagu, 33, from Smethwick and Edward Bacon, from Perry Barr
in Birmingham.
All are charged with evading excise duty on goods between November 1994 and
November 1995.
Others including nine from the Leeds area, have been bailed until a later date.
Investigators also found Ecstasy tablets worth #130,000 at a commercial address
in Kent, a investigators said.
Many of the goods recovered were marked as tax free exports but had been
diverted within the United Kingdom or re-imported without taxes being paid.
</TEXT>
