<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#900,000 damages</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093908</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE were yesterday awarded a total of nearly #900,000 damages for their
severely handicapped daughter by a High Court judge who criticised the legal
delays the pair had faced in their battle for compensation.
Anne and Keith Jewitt have been fighting in the courts for nine years for money
to help them provide special care at home for their daughter, Michelle, 13, who
is paralysed, incontinent, and knows only 12 words following difficulties at
her birth.
Mr Justice Holland, who was giving his judgment in London after hearing the
case in Newcastle upon Tyne, said it should have been possible to bring the
case to court faster. Meanwhile, a crash victim whose face and skull were
reconstructed by pioneering computer-based plastic surgery using photographs
from the family album won #956,303 damages in the High Court yesterday.
Mr Maurice Bell, 48, of Thornby, Cumbria, is blind as a result of the injuries
he suffered when a defective lorry jack-knifed and hit his car five years ago.
He also has no sense of smell, is deaf without hearing aids and has a severely
restricted sense of taste. Even his sense of touch is affected.
</TEXT>
