<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Judge recommends deportation for HIV sufferer who stabbed her lover with syringe  Parting `present' leads to jail</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093909</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN who injected her boyfriend with her own HIV-infected blood as a parting
``present'' collapsed in the dock at the Old Bailey yesterday - World Aids Day
- as she was jailed for two years.
Rhena Ndagga slumped to the floor as Mrs Justice Steel passed sentence,
describing her crime as ``deliberate, calculating and cruel''. She also
recommended Ndagga for deportation, saying her continued presence in this
country was detrimental to the public and there was ``a real risk she might
commit a similar offence''.
Ndagga was treated by the court matron before being helped to the cells.
The judge said Ndagga's former boyfriend, David Kabagwire, has spent the months
since her attack in ``constant fear and distress'' that she had infected him.
He has had several blood tests which ``mercifully'', added the judge, have
proved negative. But he faces more before the final prognosis is known.
At an earlier hearing the judge told Ndagga: ``There can be nobody in this
court who can fail to have sympathy for you, your condition and your ultimate
future. Equally there is nobody in this court who can fail to be horrified by
what you did to David Kabagwire.''
``For whatever motive, maybe your own unhappiness, you quite deliberately and
calculatingly injected him with your own blood.''
Mr Kabagwire knew Ndagga from her native Uganda but he did not become her lover
until they met again as students in the UK. He was not in court for the
sentence.
Prosecutor Garrett Byrne had told the court Ndagga began an affair with Mr
Kabagwire soon after she arrived in late 1993.
``As she had recently come from abroad and despite the fact they had protected
sex, he thought it prudent they should both attend hospital to be tested for
the Aids virus.''
Mr Kabagwire's tests were negative, but hers were positive.
``However, they continued to see each other and have protected sex. She
insisted the tests must be wrong.''
Then he began a relationship with another woman and told her he did not want to
continue seeing her. ``She said she did not care and wanted to carry on having
sexual relations,'' Mr Byrne said.
In May this year, Ndagga told her 28-year-old lover she had been ordered to
leave the country and was returning to Uganda.
``She said she had a present for him and she was sure he would like it.''
In bed that night he felt a sudden pain in his shoulder and saw Ndagga turning
away from him.
The following day, after she insisted again the HIV tests on her must be wrong,
they agreed to return to the hospital for further tests.
They stopped at the home they shared in Gurney Close, Barking, Essex, on the
way. As he bent down to recover a briefcase ``he felt a sharp pain in one of
his buttocks.
``He stood up and saw the defendant in front of him. On the carpet was a needle
attached to a syringe with what seemed to be blood inside.
``She said she had injected him earlier on the arm, but had only put in a
quarter of the blood. She said he would now be ill as well as her.''
She added she was leaving the country the next day and did not care what
happened to him.
``She said this was the present she had promised.''
Mr Kabagwire called the police and she was arrested. A small syringe containing
blood was found in her pocket, said Mr Byrne.
Mr Kabagwire told the jury that when he asked Ndagga why she had done it she
said she wanted to satisfy herself. ``I did not know what to do - I felt
upset.'' He said he received counselling afterwards and still had more tests to
take.
Ndagga was cleared of causing a noxious thing, her blood, to be administered
with intent to endanger life, but was convicted of causing grievous bodily harm
with intent.
The judge said it had not been possible to test the blood found in the syringe
for HIV.
Ndagga, who now claimed she did not have the Aids virus, refused to take
further tests.
But the court had heard from Mr Kabagwire that he and Ndagga had had tests in
two separate clinics and on each occasion hers had been positive and she was
very upset about it.
Mr Serugo Lugo, defending, said Ndagga's present condition was unknown.
He said if she was sent back to Uganda where her experiences had been
``harrowing'' she would not get the assistance she would in this country. ``She
needs assistance rather than punishment.''
</TEXT>
