<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major attacks `stupid' plans on devolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>Conservative women's conference</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093910</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister insisted yesterday that the tax-raising Scottish parliament
Labour was proposing ``to outflank the SNP'' would prove a mechanism ``to
maximise conflict and wreck the Union.''
Mr Major told the Tory women's conference in London that Labour's plans could
do what Britain's enemies had never achieved, ``split our island apart and set
one people against another. What stupidity.''
He accepted that changes were due in Scotland, but said that those proposed by
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth would improve the government of Scotland
without endangering the Union.
Would the Scots feel the Union gave them a better deal, he asked, if they had
to pay an extra tartan tax on Scottish jobs, investment and prosperity?
He said Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson had made it clear that he
believed the Government majority in Westminster should not have the final say
on the laws of Scotland but must defer to the majority party in Scotland.
He asked if Mr Robertson would apply the same proposition to England. ``For on
that basis, few past Labour governments could have governed England - they had
no majority in England. What sort of perversion of our constitution are they
prepared to tolerate?
``Either they fail to grasp the dangers of such devolution or they are prepared
to sell the crown jewels of our political heritage in a desperate bid for
votes.
``They are putting the whole constitution of our country in question. As they
plan that, how dare they talk of the national interest.''
</TEXT>
