<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lucrative deals see Evans brush up cash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093913</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TV star Chris Evans announced new deals with the BBC and Channel 4 yesterday.
His hit television game show Don't Forget Your Toothbrush will move from
Channel 4 to BBC1 - but without him as host.
Media pundits speculated that Evans would defect to BBC TV, because he already
works for the BBC as Radio 1's breakfast time disc jockey. But they thought
Channel 4 would assert its rights over the Toothbrush format.
Instead, Toothbrush will go to the BBC, which will pay Channel 4 for the format
rights. Evans will stay with Channel 4, creating and presenting a 26-part
entertainment and music show.
He is also discussing ``new projects'' for BBC1 and BBC2 with entertainment
head Chris Pye, which are thought to include late night Friday music shows.
No-one would put a price on his latest deals. But Evans, 29, has already become
a multi-millionaire from his company Ginger Productions. His three-year deal
with Radio 1 alone is rumoured to be worth #3m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ScotRail under fire as fares are increased</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093914</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTRAIL yesterday announced that fares will increase by an average of 3.5% in
the new year. A Glasgow-Edinburgh standard return will go up by 4% to #13.
Labour and the Federation of Small Businesses in Scotland expressed
disappointment at the increases.
Shadow Transport spokesman Brian Wilson said: ``Even if many of these increases
are above the rate of inflation, this is still the quiet before the storm.
``If the Tories succeed in privatising, then all the indications are that fares
would rise sharply. There is also a lot of hidden increases going on from the
removal of special fares.''
A spokesman for the FSB said ScotRail should have made an effort to freeze all
fares given the problems it encountered in the past year. He added: ``This move
is hardly going to encourage people to leave their cars at home and travel by
train.''
The Government announced earlier this year that some fares would be capped and
would not exceed the inflation rate.
However, ScotRail's are based on the retail price index for July, 1995 - when
inflation was 3.5% compared with the current rate of 3.2%. The increases will
take effect on Sunday, January 7.
It is expected that fares within Strathclyde - some 60% of rail services in
Scotland - will be held at least until April by Strathclyde Passenger Transport
Executive. From then, a new PTE, comprising of members from the new unitary
local authorities, will assume control of local transport budgets.
ScotRail said its fares would increase by an average of 3.5% in line with
national policy, which regulates increases in key fares to the rate of
inflation for three years from next year and at 1% below for the following four
years. Similar fares changes are being applied by other train operating units
across Britain.
There will be no change in the fares for passengers purchasing advance tickets
for the long distance routes from Glasgow or Edinburgh to London. This includes
the Fort William sleeper service which was reprieved earlier this year.
Examples of ScotRail increases include: a 3.1% increase in the
Edinburgh-Glasgow standard single fare, up from #6.50 to #6.70; a standard day
return on the same route is up 4% from #12.50 to #13. A standard single from
Edinburgh to Aberdeen is up 3.5% from #28.50 to #29.50, while an Edinburgh to
Aberdeen supersaver return is up 3.1% from #32 to #33.
ScotRail said some short journey fares will increase by slightly more than 3.5%
and some slightly less because minimum fares would be rounded to the nearest
10p. Apex fares, booked 48 hours in advance of travel, have not been increased.
Inter-City West Coast, which runs Anglo-Scottish services to and from London
Euston, including overnight sleeper trains, said there would be no increases
for tickets purchased in advance. The same will apply to Inter-City East Coast
Anglo-Scottish services to and from London King's Cross.
Inter-City Cross Country, which runs Anglo-Scottish services not going to
London, including Aberdeen-Plymouth, Edinburgh-Manchester, and Glasgow
Birmingham, said it would continue its ``fares freeze.''
Labour's transport campaigns co-ordinator, Ms Glenda Jackson, said the
increases demonstrated that the Government's fare capping was nothing more than
deception. ``The reality for many rail passengers is that their fares will
again be rising by well above the rate of inflation.''
STRATHCLYDE Police yesterday urged the public to consider using public
transport or park-and-ride facilities as an alternative to their vehicles to
cut down on the amount of traffic in Glasgow city centre in the run-up to
Christmas.
Police appealed to drivers who must use their cars to plan their journeys
carefully, making use of multi-storey car parking, and advised against
continuously driving around the city centre looking for a parking place.
They also warned that vehicles which were illegally parked or were causing an
obstruction, endangering the safety of motorists and pedestrians, would be
removed.
</TEXT>
