<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shortage of fertiliser and feed despite price rises</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FERTILISER and feed prices are rising, and some farmers may find it difficult
to find supplies of fertilisers unless they had already booked their orders
with merchants.
The sales director of Montrose-based Angus Fertilizers , Alistair Ballantyne
outlined the situation this week when he said: ``Prices are anything up to #18
per tonne higher than last year and the supply situation is tight.
``I can see problems ahead for some farmers who think all they have to do is to
pick up the telephone and expect the fertiliser to arrive the next day. Often
it will not.''
The most acute shortage is of ammonium nitrate and it is reckoned within the
trade that virtually all the UK manufactured product is sold at prices around
#140 per tonne. Imported fertilisers from the former Eastern Bloc countries
have, in recent years, offered farmers a lower cost option, but often with
lower quality.
Now countries such as Lithuania are finding it more attractive to divert their
exports to the world market rather than just within the EU.
Commenting on that aspect, Mr Ballantyne said: ``Countries in South America for
example which, in the past, have used relatively little fertiliser are now
active in the market as a result of high grain prices.''
Sources in the trade say that has probably been more fertiliser purchased
forward this year than for some time. This is reckoned to be a direct
consequence of most farmers having had an excellent harvest.
At the same time world grain prices have rocketed with wheat having risen from
#89 to #137 per tonne in the past six months, although there are indications
that the market is falling back slightly. In effect, world prices are at least
on a par with those in the EU, hence the Commission's decision to halt export
restitutions apart from on a limited tonnage of malting barley.
q The National Farmers' Union of Scotland has appealed to the Government for
action to restore confidence in the pig industry. Speaking after a meeting with
Scottish Office and Ministry of Agriculture officials in London, the union's
pig convener, David Whiteford, said that despite improved prices margins were
being badly squeezed by the high cost of cereals.
``Brussels must improve its management of the cereals regime and make even more
radical cuts in arable set-aside rates,'' he said. ``This will help get feed
prices down towards the level promised under reform of the CAP.
``We also told the Government how disappointed we are that it has again failed
to offset trade distortions caused by unilateral UK welfare legislation. It
must now honour its commitment to encourage retails to buy only from sources
which match our welfare standards.''
</TEXT>
