<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unchanged land of Finbarr</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE SANDISON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>ways and means weekend extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Map</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOT many people know that Noah knew the Macneill of Barra. But he did, because
prior to the Great Flood, Noah sent the Macneill a message, telling him that he
had reserved a place in the Ark for him and for his wife. The Macneill replied,
with typical Highland courtesy, thanking Noah for his trouble, but saying that
he already had a perfectly good boat of his own.
Barra is the largest of the southern isles of the Outer Hebrides. The other,
smaller islands, are Vatersay, Muldoanich, Sandray, Foldday, Lingay, Pabbay,
Mingulay and Bernery. These islands are uninhabited, other than Vatersay, which
is now joined to Barra by a grand new causeway, completed in 1994.
Climb to the top of Barra's highest peak, Heaval (383m),  past the Carrara
marble statue of the Madonna and Child to enjoy the view. A comfortable half
hour will see you up and from the summit you will be rewarded with an
unforgettable vista which encompasses most of the Hebrides; the mountains of
South Uist and Harris in the north, the lazy spread of the southern isles; the
misty island of Skye, hazily to the east.
In 1839 when the last of the main line of Macneill chiefs, General Roderick
Macneill, was declared bankrupt, Barra was bought by the infamous Colonel
Gordon of Cluny. The new laird presided over decades of brutal eviction and the
enforced emigration of his tenants. Against their will, the people were shipped
to Canada and their land was given over to sheep farmers.
Robert Lister MacNeil, a Canadian architect and descendent of a dispossessed
Barra man, successfully proved his claim to the chieftainship and became the
45th Chief in 1915, restoring and living in Kisimul Castle in Castle Bay.
Robert Lister is buried in Kisimul Castle and his son, the 46th Chief, now
cares for the ancient clan home of the Macneills.
Another more recent famous Barra resident, was Compton MacKenzie, the author of
Whisky Galore, who recounts the story of the SS Politician which ran aground
off the Island of Eriskay, her holds packed with thousands of cases of whisky,
many of them being ``liberated'' by local people.
The film of the book was shot on Barra with Compton MacKenzie himself playing
the part of the captain of the island ferry. MacKenzie, who came to live on
Barra in 1928, was a founder member of the Scottish Nationalist Party and he
built himself a fine house on the north coast of the island; overlooking the
white sands of Traigh Mhor, cockle strand, where Loganair land their
aeroplanes, weather and tide permitting.
Compton MacKenzie lies in the graveyard of Cille Bharra, one of the oldest
places of Christian worship in Scotland and perhaps dating back as far as the
early years of the seventh century.
The chapel was founded, tradition has it, by St Finnbarr, patron saint of
Barra, whose dramatic statue dominates an outcrop in the sea at Northbay.
The ``Aberdeen Breviary'', from the sixteenth century, tells us that Finnbarr
was born in Caithness, was ordained a priest in Rome, then returned to Scotland
where he ``converted many to the faith of Christ''.
Cille Bharra is the starting point for a super Barra walk. Park near the chapel
(OS Map 31, Barra, Gd Ref 31/70407) and climb south to the top of Ben Eoligarry
(102m). Look north east to the island of Eriskay and the Princes Strand, where
Bonnie Prince Charlie first set foot on Scottish soil in 1745. In fact, BPC had
made a prior call at Kisimul Castle, but the Macneill diplomatically and
happily, given the horrendous aftermath of the uprising, was ``not at home.''
Descend south, on to the white sand and golden green-marram-grass spiked dunes
of Traigh Eais. Three thousand mile old, huge, blue, foam-crested, Atlantic
waves crowd the shore and dash in fury against the black crags of Ben Erival
(200m). The landscape lies essentially unchanged, as awe-inspiring today as it
must have been in the days when Finnbarr's monks trembled and prayed before
their mysterious maker.
At the end of the beach, cross the narrow neck east to reach the road near the
cement-block factory, the offices of which are Compton MacKenzie's old house
(31/695056). Walk north now over Traigh Mhor, keeping a weather-eye open for
incoming Loganair flights, back to the eternal peace and calm of Cille Bharra.
</TEXT>
