<HEADLINE>Steady rise in number of flu cases in Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093919</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Steady rise
in number of
flu cases in
Scotland
ON a population basis the incidence of flu in Scotland is more than double that
in the rest of the UK, figures released yesterday revealed.
They indicate there were more than 15,000 new cases at the end of last week,
compared with 77,000 in England and Wales, where the latest wave was said to
have surprised doctors.
The figures are based on returns from ``spotter'' GP practices sent to the
Royal College of Practitioners' monitoring unit and, in Scotland, to the
Scottish Centre for Infection and Environmental Health at Ruchill Hospital.
Dr Ahilya Noone, at the centre, said yesterday: ``Our spotter practices showed
that were 295 cases per 100,000 population at the end of last week, compared
with 139 overall for England and Wales.
``That has come as no surprise - our data had already been showing a steady
increase over the past few weeks.''
The surge in the North of England was most marked, from 58 cases per 100,000
the previous week to 120 last week. North of the Border, however, the climb has
been steady - from 109 three weeks ago, 223 the following week, and 295 last
week.
In England that would qualify comfortably as an epidemic. A spokesman for the
college's monitoring unit in Birmingham said that was reached around the
200-250 per 100,000 mark. But Dr Noone said: ``There is no real definition for
epidemic.''
Although the prolonged summer might have been expected to delay the onset of
this year's wave, Dr Noone pointed out that last year's outbreak did not peak
until January.
``But it doesn't follow that this year's will go on increasing until then,''
she added.
In fact, this year's probably has more in common with the 1993-94 outbreak.
Both were variants of Influenza A, and the strains currently prominent are
largely covered by the vaccination programme for the vulnerable which was
already being promoted by the end of September.
The vaccines cover strains analogous to A/Johannesburg, A/Singapore and
B/Beijing and are targeted at people with asthma, chronic bronchitis, diabetes,
shortness of breath, heart trouble, kidney failure or other serious medical
conditions.
People taking steroids or cancer treatments are also targeted, as are patients
in residential or long-stay homes where rapid spread could occur, but
immunisation of fit, healthy adults is not recommended by the Scottish Office
Health Department.
The main symptoms of flu are fever, headache, aching limbs, coughing, sneezing,
and a runny nose.
Treating the symptoms is the best that can be done for those who catch flu -
that means staying home and resting (and keeping it to yourself) and taking hot
drinks and painkillers. But beware of accidental overdose of paracetamol or
aspirin through different preparations containing these drugs.
q Meningitis cases in Scotland are substantially lower this year than last,
notwithstanding the recent high-profile outbreaks here and in England. Dr Sarah
O'Brien, a consultant epidemiologist at SCIEH, said there had been 149
meningococcal infections so far this year compared with 173 at the same point
last year. ``They tend not to follow any particular pattern, although they tend
to be more numerous in winter. We normally expect to see a number of unlinked
cases,'' said Dr O'Brien.
</TEXT>
