<HEADLINE>Fraud tops  police list of season  priorities</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093920</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VIOLENT crime as well as cheque and credit card frauds are to be specifically
targeted under Operation Holly, an initiative being launched next week by the
Lothian and Borders force.
The officer leading the operation, Detective Chief Inspector Watson McAteer,
said yesterday they estimated that at its peak as many as 100,000 shoppers a
day would converge on Edinburgh city centre.
``That in itself is bound to attract the criminal to the capital,'' said the
officer. ``This year we have already laid plans for cheque and credit card
fraud crime to be one of our top priorities. Crimes of violence such as robbery
will be our other priority.''
He said both young and elderly people had been targeted before by criminals
during this period because they were unable to put up much resistance.
``It is therefore our objective to target the robbers with plain clothes
officers mingling with shoppers on the streets.''
He said the prevention initiative would also continue into the hours of
darkness to give more protection to revellers attending late night Christmas
functions.
Detectives from a number of areas including Serious Crime Squad and Fraud Squad
will be supported by a team of specially selected uniformed officers .
</TEXT>
