<HEADLINE>Engineering a bargain offer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Conroy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093922</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS Diary has the bargain of the year for small and medium-sized
engineering companies who yearn for the skills of a highly qualified engineer
but can't afford the extra cost.
Lanarkshire Development Agency and Scottish Design have teamed up in an attempt
to ensure the skills of engineers made redundant as the result of Rolls-Royce's
decision to close its aero design division in East Kilbride are not lost to
Scottish industry.
It is hoped that the project, which is already being supported by Rolls-Royce,
will also be funded by Strathclyde European Partnership. The aim is for 25
former RR engineers to be placed with small and medium-sized firms in
Strathclyde for a year. The engineers will be paid a salary of #15,000, with
the companies involved only having to meet 50% of this.
David Robson, business manager of Scottish Design, told Business Diary: ``Such
world-class experience can make a significant impact on local companies who are
competing in a global market place. We are excited about the chance to help so
many firms take on these skills, and we want to hear from interested companies
as soon as possible.''
The engineers involved have already completed a 10-week training programme to
prepare them for working in smaller companies and are available to start in
January. They include senior mechanical design engineers, project managers,
technical authors, IT systems specialists, engineering managers, design
draughtsmen and engineering technicians.
If your company is interested in this initiative, contact David Robson at
Scottish Design on 0141 221 6121.
Edinburgh has
incentive edge
SCOTLAND does not just beat the Irish when it comes to the inward investment of
computer companies. It also has an edge in attracting lucrative hotel business.
Stephen Carter, general manager of the five-star Caledonian Hotel in Edinburgh,
recently returned from the Incentive Travel and Meetings Exhibition in Chicago
which is attended by top hotels from around the world.
He brought back with him a #250,000 incentive travel package from an American
life assurance association, having beat the Irish contingent for the business.
Hail to the new
chamber chief
CONGRATULATIONS to W Stewart McKay who has been elected by the Ayrshire Chamber
of Commerce to succeed Richard Cole-Hamilton as president.
He will be only the second president of the Ayrshire Chamber since it was
formed in 1992 by the two separate chambers in the area coming together.
The new president was South-west of Scotland and Cumbria manager of the
Clydesdale Bank before setting up the Wisdom Associates business consultancy
earlier this year.
Transmitting a
property idea
THE boom in mobile phones is bringing in its wake another property boom
according to chartered surveying firm DM Hall.
The autumn edition of its Landscape newsletter aimed at the farming community
contains the following snippet of news: ``As the mobile phone business
continues to grow, transmitter sites are in ever-increasing demand. These can
be quite profitable for the owner of the modest amount of land required - like
a site in Fife where we achieved a rental of #5500 a year.''
DM Hall's surveyors are welcome to come and see my garden any time.
Espionage at
big breakfast
THERE was a spy in the camp when KPMG Tax Advisers held its Big Budget
Breakfast in the Glasgow Moat House Hotel on Wednesday, thanks to Business
Diary.
Sitting among the 200 guests listening to KPMG tax partner Joy Travers and her
colleagues give their breakdown of the Budget proposals was a Coopers &amp; Lybrand
staff member. The mole had gained access to the event by being one of the first
10 Business Diary readers to give the correct answer - Norman Lamont - to the
question - Who was the last Scots-born Chancellor? - which we set last week.
The entry arrived at the KPMG offices via a fax from the person's home, but
when the accountancy firm checked further it was discovered the entrant was a
Coopers &amp; Lybrand employee.
Ian Spinney of KPMG joked: ``We were rather flattered that Coopers &amp; Lybrand
needed to come to us for tax advice!'' The immediate response to this from an
insider at Coopers &amp; Lybrand was: ``Perhaps it was a bit of freelance
industrial espionage by one of our staff, but we are told the mission drew a
blank.''
Away from the cloak and dagger goings on, Joy Travers sat down to breakfast
with John Paterson, the fundraising director of The Princess Royal Trust for
Carers, and presented the charity with a cheque for #200.
</TEXT>
