<TEXT>
FEARS are increasing that Government proposals for implementing the EU
agreement on the protection of animals during transport could decimate the
Scottish livestock sector.
In a heated debate at the Scottish NFU's Ayr area executive, president John
Scott from Ballantrae said that if the proposals went through it would not only
severely damage the auction system but also add enormously to both farmers' and
hauliers' costs.
``Make no mistake this is possibly the biggest single threat faced by the
Scottish livestock industry,'' warned Mr Scott.
He claimed the new rules were ``self-defeating'', creating more stress and
suffering for animals instead of less.
``Multiple loading and off-loading of newly-weaned calves or sheep will simply
cause more welfare and health problems,'' he said.
``We should be pressing for a relaxation of this directive exempting the whole
of Scotland from some of these proposals which are damaging to animals and
farmers' interests alike.''
Alan Parker, from Lochwinnoch, called on the union to enlist the help of the
SSPCA, as much of what was being proposed was simply ``downright cruel'',
adding ``it pays no regard to livestock management or the welfare of animals
and is seriously flawed''.
Henry Murdoch, from Dalrymple, said the sad thing was that the directive had
been drawn up by people who had no knowledge of the livestock industry. Changes
being proposed to journey times, feeding etc were just ``plain daft''. He
added: ``It's time qualified people had a say in these matters.
``I think there is a hidden agenda in all this. There are people out there who
want to make it impossible for livestock farmers to function.''
Area vice-president Adam Train, from Tarbolton, said the total impractability
of the directive had to be stressed to the Scottish Office who he believed
would be ``supportive'' of farmers' concerns.
A resolution from the area to union HQ will point out that the proposals pay
little regard to livestock management or welfare and calls on the Government to
take practical advice from hauliers, veterinary officials and farmers.
Following another lengthy debate on the possible introduction to the UK of US
beef treated with hormal-growth promoters, the area agreed to back the Meat and
Livestock Commission view that the use of such products should continue to be
banned here and across the rest of Europe.
Mr Scott said that under the GATT agreement there was no way hormone-produced
US beef could be kept out of Europe. The issue for UK farmers was that while
there was obvious commercial advantages to be gained by hormone use, the view
of consumers on the matter was ``paramount''.
The area's livestock convenor Ian Kerr, from Newmilns, said the less said about
the matter the better. ``If we make too much an issue of this the public will
not be able to distinguish between US beef and home-produced beef free of such
promoters.
Alan Parker said the welfarists should be looking at the US feed lots where
hundreds of animals stood shoulder to shoulder. ``It's high time we in Scotland
stressed the significance of the natural product produced here and set industry
standards for Scotch quality beef,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heseltine tells of how he was offered deputy leader post</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL Heseltine was informally offered the post of John Major's deputy three
weeks before the Tory leadership election during which the appointment was
announced, the deputy Prime Minister has disclosed.
He told colleagues to vote for Mr Major after he had told the Prime Minister
that ``I am not going to be involved in this process.''
Casting new light on John Major's path to victory in the leadership battle,
which ended with his re-election in a straight fight with John Redwood, Mr
Heseltine said - in an interview in the Times today - the idea of his promotion
came up in a late-night Commons chat with Mr Major.
``There was no agreement,'' he said. ``It came up as a thought to be discussed.
It was left on the table, so to speak . . . I think it was quite obvious that I
was going to become his number two.''
The plan was confirmed by Mr Major on the morning of polling, he said.
However, asked whether the advance move had been intended to get his support in
good time, Mr Heseltine said such a ``Machiavellian interpretation'' had not
occurred to him.
He said that between the two conversations about his promotion, Mr Major had
told of his idea, which ``had been in his mind for some time . . . to lance the
boil'' over the leadership question.
``He asked my view. I said, after a moment's reflection, that I thought it was
a very sensible thing to do. That was it.''
Explaining why he was so firm in telling his supporters to vote for John Major,
he said: ``I do not believe in deceit.
``If I say to John Major's face I am not going to be involved in this process I
am not the sort of person who then goes round the House of Commons saying well,
I may have said this to the Prime Minister but don't take a blind bit of notice
- you go and sort it out. I would not do that.''
He added that he and Mr Major would never be ``prised apart'' by the
``pressures of politics or by the scrutiny of the media''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Centre opens its doors to the homeless</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093926</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HOMELESS project designed to provide high quality accommodation for up to 39
young people who might otherwise be forced to sleep on the streets of Glasgow
was opened in the south side of the city yesterday.
The James Shields project will provide a sanctuary for young people aged
between 18 and 25 for stays as long as two years.
Named after the city's last Lord Provost, the project was officially opened by
members of Glasgow City Council who have leased the converted Abbotsford
Chalmers Free Church building on Pollokshaws Road. They were joined by
representatives from the Bridge of Weir-based charity Quarriers who will run
the centre and provide support for residents.
According to the project manager, Ms Nicola Hanley, homeless young people will
be referred to the centre by the council's housing department and have their
rent paid for by the DSS. ``The project will have a bias towards female
residents as there's not a lot of suitable accommodation. People will be able
to live here independently but the support workers will help some to acquire
the skills to live on their own and eventually move out to their own
tenancies.''
One of the project's new residents, Ms Yvonne Donnelly, from the Possil area of
Glasgow, described the sequence of events which had led her to seek shelter at
the project.
The 21-year-old told how she had been working at Butlins for five months before
returning to Glasgow to live with her mother. ``We had an argument and she
threw me out. When I was away I was used to my own freedom but when I came back
my mum was telling what to do and asking me where I was going all the time.''
Ideally Ms Donnelly said she would like to get her own house with her boyfriend
of three months who is currently in hospital but who has also been living in
hostel accommodation. But having just moved into her own flat in the centre a
few days ago she said was impressed with the standard of the accommodation.
``It's really nice in here. You couldn't ask for a better place. And it's
clean.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Detective warned  prisoner not to inform, court told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093927</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DETECTIVE accused of corruption visited a man in police custody to make sure
he did not inform on a drug dealer and his associate, a court heard yesterday.
James Reid claimed that Constable Neil Cooper came to his cell to tell him not
to implicate Ronald Cormack and Mr Ian Smith over a break-in.
He said Mr Cooper, who was not involved in investigating the case, told him to
stick to a different story because the officers interviewing him would believe
it.
Reid, 23, of the Gallowgate, Aberdeen, claimed Mr Cooper said Cormack and Mr
Smith had phoned to ensure Reid was being looked after.
Mr Cooper, 36, of Springdale Crescent, Bieldside, Aberdeen, denies attempting
to defeat the ends of justice by failing fully to report the break-in and
informing Mr Smith that Reid had not implicated either him or Cormack.
He also denies a further charge of attempting to defeat the ends of justice and
a charge of corruption.
The High Court in Aberdeen heard that Reid was arrested in the city's Polmuir
Road, in December 1991, on suspicion that he had stolen a mobile phone.
He had been sitting in a car as a look-out for Cormack and Mr Smith, known as
Fat Billy, who were allegedly breaking into the Inn at the Park hotel nearby.
The court has heard that Cormack is serving a 15-year sentence for drugs and
firearms offences.
Reid said that when he was taken into custody he told police officers he had
been planning a lone break-in at a shop nearby.
Asked by Advocate-depute Alan Turnbull what Mr Cooper had said to him when he
paid a visit to the cells, Reid replied: ``To stick to the same story.''
Reid said Mr Cooper told him the police believed the story about the shop
break-in.
He added: ``He just said Fat Billy and Ronald Cormack had got in touch with him
and asked him to see how I was doing.''
Asked by Mr Turnbull if he was surprised by this, Reid replied: ``In a way,
yes.''
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
