<HEADLINE>TALES FROM THE ROOM AT THE TOP</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joanna Trollope</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra past lives</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093928</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n THE stories that formed the most powerful mythology of my childhood came not
from Greece or Rome or the Arabian Nights, but from Glasgow. Glasgow was where
my grandmother (1897) and my mother (1919) were born. It contained the house
and nursery of their childhoods which shaped their imaginations for the rest of
their lives, and which produced stories and images which coloured the later
(and by contrast, we felt, dull) childhoods of my sister, my brother and
myself. Glasgow, we came to believe, was it.
My great-grandfather, James Hedderwick, was a successful Glasgow stockbroker
and also a city father. His portrait hangs in the boardroom of the Royal
Infirmary in tribute to his chairing the committee that organised and paid for
the hospital's great rebuilding programme at the turn of the century. His first
wife having died in childbirth, he brought home to Glasgow in 1887 a
Gloucestershire girl, known locally as ``the Rose of Rodborough,'' and
installed her in No 2 Clairmont Gardens. It was in the top-floor nurseries of
that house that the Glasgow stories began.
They were stories of life in a prosperous Edwardian household, of bowling hoops
in Kelvingrove Park, of watching the city Art Gallery go up, of peering through
the nursery banisters at well-dressed dinner guests crossing the chequered hall
floor far below. They were stories of games, plays and parties, of books and
pictures, while my grandmother's generation merged inexorably into my mother's,
linked by a reluctance to leave that safe and richly imaginative world behind
as well as by the abiding presence of my grandmother's nursery nurse.
They were, above all, stories of a vanished kind of childhood where ritual and
order prevailed, where the child was oddly both monarch and subject at once,
and where the outside world lived, quite definitely, beyond the nursery windows.
</TEXT>
