<DOCNO>GH951202-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Expert offers knot evidence in murder case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093929</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORENSIC scientist gagged himself in a witness box yesterday to demonstrate
how a man - accused of murdering his wife - could have deliberately tied
himself up.
Gordon Wardell was found bound and gagged in the living room of his home after
the murder of his wife last year.
He watched from the dock at Oxford Crown Court as Roger Ide wrapped a piece of
sheet around his neck, tied it, and lifted it over his mouth to show how easily
Mr Wardell could have fooled the police.
Mr Ide had no problems talking through the gag, similar to the one found on the
accused, who denies murdering his wife Carol last September.
He claims she was killed by raiders who stole money from the Nuneaton branch of
the Woolwich Building Society where she worked.
Mr Wardell said the same gang gagged and bound him in their home in Bonneville
Close, Meriden, near Nuneaton, Warkwickshire.
However, Mr Ide - an expert in knots - told the court how easy it may have been
for Wardell to tie himself up. He explained how a strip of material used for Mr
Wardell's gag had been torn off a sheet found in the couple's garage.
When asked by prosecutor Richard Wakerley, QC, if the gag could have stopped
someone shouting, Mr Ide replied: ``It would not have been very effective at
all.'' ''
If a person wanted to silence another, they would put an object in their mouth
and then tape it, Mr Ide explained.
Mr Wardell was found gagged and bound to a metal bin stand with his knees
almost bent double across the main pole of the stand. It was Mr Ide's belief
that Mr Wardle would not have been found this way.
When Mr Wakerley asked if it was possible to tie oneself up that way Mr Ide
said: ``Not in a convincing way, with your hands tied behind your back.''
A police officer, posing as Mr Wardell, was shown stripped to his
underwear,tying himself up to the same metal bin stand in the couple's living
room.
The case was adjourned.
</TEXT>
