<DOCNO>GH951202-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kvaerner deal rejected</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093930</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at the Kvaerner Govan shipyard have rejected a 6.15% pay offer over two
years - raising fears of possible industrial action.
However, a union source predicted last night that the dispute at the Clydeside
yard would not come to that.
It is understood that union representatives are seeking a rise equivalent to
1.5% above an estimated inflation rate of 3.5% for the first year of a deal.
Management confirmed that the workers had rejected the offer, and said further
discussions would be held with full-time union officials on Monday.
It is understood that the dismissed offer to 1400 workers was for a 3.27%
increase in year one and a 2.85% increase the following year, and a promise
that this would be reviewed if inflation, based on the retail price index,
climbed above 3.5% before next November.
It had also been proposed that a 15-minute tea break would be moved back two
hours, beginning at 7.30am instead of 9.30am, and staff would be expected to
give up three days' floating holidays to equalise holidays awarded to manual
workers.
The company also proposed to make #100 bonus payments to each of the 1200
permanent workers and pro-rata payments to about 200 temporary workers, based
on service, and suggested this could be paid into their wages before Christmas
if the deal was accepted.
Management also indicated its desire to give job guarantees to the workforce
for the next 12 months, if enough work could be secured.
Mr David Cooper, shop stewards' convener at the yard, would not be drawn on the
possibility of industrial action last night, saying: ``The yard is working
normally and negotiations are continuing.''
Kvaerner Govan is awaiting confirmation of twoorders which would secure the
1200 permanent jobs at the yard until 1998.
</TEXT>
