<DOCNO>GH951202-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leah's father pays tribute to `his pretty little ship'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE father of tragic ecstasy teenager Leah Betts paid tribute to his ``pretty
little ship'' at her funeral yesterday.
Leah collapsed and died following her 18th birthday party after taking a single
tablet of the drug.
Yesterday her retired policeman father Paul spoke of the torment and heartbreak
of coming to terms with his daughter's death.
In his address to the congregation which packed into the family's parish
church, Christ Church, Latchingdon, Essex, he told the mourners, many of whom
were grieving teenage friends of Leah, how he saw his daughter as a ship and
himself as the captain.
In the analogy to Leah, based on the family's favourite pastime of sailing, he
said how the captain ``thought he had prepared the little ship for anything
that the sea could throw at it and it could communicate as and when needed''.
``He trusted it with all his heart and believed that wherever it went it would
return safely.
``One day,'' he said, ``the little ship was to enter uncharted waters,
unbeknown to its captain.
``The evening started calmly with a gentle glow in the sky, and the little ship
was decked out in all its splendour with a soft wind filling the sails, but it
was not long before the little ship was in a full-blown storm.''
Choking back tears, Mr Betts went on: ``All of a sudden a gigantic wave lifted
the little ship into the air and tossed it on to jagged rocks.''
He said his little ship had been lost for ever but he spoke proudly of how his
daughter's donation of her organs had brought life to six others.
Leah's brother, William, also spoke movingly of his sister as a ``beautiful
rose which stood out from all the other flowers''.
The 11-year-old said: ``The lovely rose grew too close to a weed which started
to wrap around it and as it struggled to get free the weed became too tight and
the rose died.''
In his sermon, the Rev Dr Don Gordon described Leah as ``a loving, lovable and
lovely girl''.
He spoke of her enthusiasm for life, her plans to study for A-levels and go on
to become a teacher.
Leah's father and her step-mother, Janet, had used Leah's death to bring home
the message of the evil of drugs, he said, and had saved in turn many other
young lives.
He said: ``Could it be that in 10 or 15 years observers will look back and say
`That was the turning point, that was a historic situation'.''
Many people from the local community gathered outside the church, listening as
music from Leah's favourite band Oasis was relayed on speakers.
At the end of the service her coffin was led out to Whitney Houston's I Will
Always Love You.
Leah was buried at Great Burstead cemetery alongside her mother, Dorothy, who
died in 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two charges admitted Leeson  jailed for six years</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER futures trader Nick Leeson was sentenced this morning to six-and-a-half
years for his part in the #860m collapse of Barings Bank.
The time Leeson has already spent in a German jail will be subtracted from the
time he has to serve in Singapore.
In court yesterday he admitted two charges connected with the spectacular
failure of Britain's oldest merchant bank.
He was charged with cheating Barings' auditors, Coopers and Lybrand, by telling
them that he had enough money to cover his trading activities.
He was also charged with deceiving Simex, the Singapore International Monetary
Exchange, and persuading it to release more than #76m.
He had already served nearly nine months in the German jail while awaiting
extradition to Singapore. As a consequence, his sentence was backdated to March
2, 1995.
He was sentenced by Judge Richard Magnus, who said: ``The accused was in a
position of trust. He had used that position to trade his honesty and
integrity. The sentence must be sufficiently substantial to indicate the
gravity of the offense to the public.''
He added: ``The facts speak of the criminal enterprise of the accused. The
facts conclusively support the two charges.''
Leeson was expressionless as the sentence was passed.
He was convicted yesterday after pleading guilty to the two charges of
cheating, and the prosecution dropped the remaining nine charges of fraud and
forgery.
Leeson was sentenced to six years for misreporting details about the status of
around #300m in Barings contracts on Febuary 1. That meant Simex released money
to Barings that it should not have.
He received an additional six months for forging documents to deceive Coopers
and Lybrand to believe Barings had received $78m from the New York firm Spear,
Leeds and Kellogg in February.
Prosecutor Lawrence Ang portrayed Leeson as a young trader who used lies and
deceit and resorted to cut-and-paste forgery to conceal losses from regulators.
Leeson, who managed futures trading operations in Singapore, bet that Japan's
stock market would rise. When it slumped after the Kobe earthquake, he doubled
his bets in an attempt to recoup his losses. After he completely wiped out
Barings' cash reserves, Leeson left Singapore.
In pleading for a lenient sentence, defense lawyer John Koh called Leeson's
gambles the ``misguided acts of a dynamic, but in the final analysis,
insufficiently experienced trader.''
Mr Koh also blamed Leeson's chiefs in London for not controlling his
activities. Leeson was in charge of trading as well as keeping his own books,
in effect policing himself.
He noted that Leeson was a first time offender; that he did not personally
profit from the deals; that no substantial loss was caused to investors or to
Singapore's reputation; and that he returned voluntarily to face trial.
Mr Koh, yesterday handed prosecutor Lawrence Ang a Midland Bank cheque for
#50,464 and pledged that the remainder of the #70,000 prosecution costs would
be paid soon.
Leeson had to borrow against his interest in London properties owned by his
wife to do so, Mr Koh said.
Mr Koh told the court that Leeson was sorry, and ``contrary to speculation,
there are no secret profits. Our client has no assets''.
Proceeds from a #450,000 book deal Leeson made for his memoirs ``will go to the
agent, the ghostwriter, English and German lawyers and Singapore counsel,'' he
said.
Any other likelihood of Leeson profiting from his notoriety was remote, because
a writ had been served on him in Britain to strip him of possible gains.
``Any Hollywood movie is
highly improbable,'' he added in a reference to reports about a possible
Hollywood film about the Barings collapse featuring Hugh Grant, star of Four
Weddings and a Funeral.
Leeson's wife, Lisa, meanwhile, was keeping out of the limelight back in
Britain.
Providing a glimpse into the trauma that Leeson suffered during the Barings
debacle, Mr Koh revealed yesterday that she had suffered a miscarriage at the
end of             January.
Speculation is rife in Singapore that Leeson may have struck a deal involving
him detailing to investigators the role played by Barings executives in the
bank's collapse.
The island state's Commercial Affairs Department is believed to be particularly
interested in the role of Mr Peter Norris, Barings' former head of investment
banking in London; Mr James Bax, Leeson's boss in Singapore; and Mr Simon
Jones, director of Baring Futures Singapore.
However, back in Britain, a spokesman for the Serious Fraud Office emphasisied
that it had not uncovered any evidence of criminal actions by London-based
Barings staff.
He reiterated the SFO's consistently expressed view that Singapore was the most
appropriate jurisdiction for Leeson's prosecution. But the SFO continued to
take a keen interest in developments in Singapore.
Mr Denis MacShane, Labour MP for Rotherham and a writer on derivatives who
campaigned for Leeson to be tried in Britain, expressed disappointment about
the way the case had been handled.
He said: ``This confirms what we always feared, that Leeson back in Singapore
would not have to face rigorous examination to tell the whole truth in public
about the collapse of Barings and the involvement of executives in London in
its collapse.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Remember the dark</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CARL MacDOUGALL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE LIARS' CLUB
Mary Karr
Picador, #14.99. LEECHFIELD was voted one of the 10 ugliest places on earth.
There is a small east Texan town and a cancer blackspot to rival Chernobyl and
Bhopal. It is situated on the swampy rim of the Gulf of Mexico, and is home to
an oil refinery and its workers.
The Liars' Club was a handful of oil workers who met in the American Legion Bar
to drink salted beer, play dominoes, shoot pool and tell lies. Mary Karr's
father was undisputed champion.
This is a shrewdly conducted memoir. Karr often seems overawed by her material
and continually stresses its veracity, usually after another fantastic
revelation which causes one to reflect upon on the title and the fact that she
was allowed to sit in on some of the fabling sessions.
Karr is a Professor of Creative Writing and Literature at Syracuse University
and has constructed her memoir like a novel. Pictures are continually blurred;
half memories, little more than snapshots, beginnings of incidents arrive
without reason as though the whole was too painful to recall, as though the
entire memory had been misplaced.
Or she traces the lies, tries to deconstruct the stories and diminish their
power, taking one of her father's myths and tracing the truth, or using it to
take her into a memory of her own, until the two become confused. ``I've plumb
forgot where I am, for an instant,'' she confesses at one point. ``Which is how
a good lie should take you. At the same time, I'm more where I was inside
myself than before Daddy started talking, which is how lies can tell you the
truth.''
She says little, other than by implication, about a family or society which
needs to lie to itself. Her father's lies, she says, were a fence, built
between him and the other men, `` . . . put up to keep them from knowing him
better''.
And as the narrative vacillates between truth and fiction, the techniques are
entirely fictional, using the opening sequence - ``a single instant surrounded
by dark'' - as a recurring theme which dominates the narrative. It is a memory
that took 30 years to unfreeze.
Mary is seven and her sister Lecia is nine. They are alone in the house with
the local sheriff and family doctor. The doctor kneels before her on a mattress
on the bare floor, gently pulling at the hem of her favourite nightgown. ``Show
me the marks,'' he says.
Their mother is drunk and missing. Their father is working at the oil refinery.
Lecia is pretending to sleep. Mary is trying to pinch her awake; something she
does continually throughout the book which becomes a story of untangling this
single memory.
When first published in America, The Liars' Club sold by word of mouth alone.
It is now shifting 10,000 copies a week in the States and a big movie deal has
been made.
It isn't hard to see why. It is the perfect testimony to America's therapy
culture, where the tribulations of someone worse off than yourself are a source
of inspiration and comfort, where a happy ending comes with the genre. It
shines light into dark corners, rattles skeletons and gives hope to those who
need to help themselves and are reliant upon inspirational pieces written by
someone telling you what to do rather than share an experience. It is the real
thing, the perfect antidote to inspirational works that are plotted like
mystery novels, where all will be well when you finish the book.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Liver Birds set for fresh take-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALLAN LAING Entertainment Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093935</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LOT of water has run over the Mersey Tunnel since Sandra and Beryl gave up
the lease on their Liverpool flat and went their separate ways almost 20 years
ago. But now television writer Carla Lane is planning to bring them back
together with a new series of The Liver Birds.
Ms Lane, more concerned with animal welfare than comedy scripts these days,
confirmed yesterday she had written seven new episodes of the series she
created. But she will only go ahead if all the original cast agree to take
part. Provided they do, then rehearsals will begin early in the New Year.
The Liver Birds, one of the most successful sitcoms of the Seventies, starred
Nerys Hughes and Polly James as the two fun-loving Scouse flatmates with a
carefree lifestyle and outrageous fashion sense.
The new series will pick up two decades on. According to Ms Lane, one of the
girls will have lived an exciting life while the other will have been caught up
with domestic responsibilities. However, she would not reveal which one was
which.
After the original series, Nerys Hughes, now aged 53, went on to star in a
number of television dramas. Ms James, now 54, carved herself a successful
career on the stage and has only rarely been involved in television work.
Ms Lane, who went on to write award-winning sitcoms like Bread and Butterflies,
is convinced that the Liver Birds will work second time around.
``After meeting them I felt quite excited and thought it was a good idea after
all so I agreed,'' Ms Lane said. ``Writing the scripts was easy because I know
the characters so well. The real worry for me is that the original series was
glitzy fun and they dressed in ridiculous fashions so it has stayed in people's
memory that way.
``It's very hard to take two women in their 50s and make them like that. Now
they have responsibilities and we will see how they are coping. As a writer I
have matured since then and I'm hoping people will be pleasantly surprised. I
feel pleased and I think it will work,'' Ms Lane said.
q Daytime television presenters Richard Madeley and Judy Finnigan are moving
their long-running This Morning programme to London from Liverpool, it was
announced yesterday.
The husband-and-wife team said they had become frustrated at the refusal of
some international stars to travel north for interviews.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth to decide soon on Loch Lomond laws</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN, Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093936</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE clearest hint yet that the long-delayed Loch Lomond by-laws will be
ratified by the end of the year was given yesterday by Scottish Secretary
Michael Forsyth during a short visit to the area.
On a grey, chilly morning, with the loch totally free of screaming power boats,
water ski craft and jet skis, Mr Forsyth said it would take ``pretty powerful
arguments'' to convince him to overturn the view taken by the local authorities
that the by-laws were necessary to cut down on bad behaviour and conflict
between loch users.
He sidestepped the question put to him by The Herald on whether or not he
favoured a joint board - which would carry planning powers, its own budgets and
staff - over the current joint committee made up from the three new unitary
authorities bordering the loch which leaves the future running of the area
essentially unchanged.
He also refused to be drawn on whether he thought fast water sport was
ultimately a sustainable activity at a beauty spot.
Mr Forsyth took the opportunity to emphasise that yesterday's consultation
exercise was very much in line with his announcement on the previous day of
greater power for local authorities. However, he may yet amend the by-law
proposals to meet objections put forward by the Scottish Sports Council which
have been the cause of the delays.
As he disembarked from the Loch Lomond Park Authority's patrol boat at Luss,
the Scottish Secretary said he had to take the by-laws decision soon so he had
taken the opportunity to see exactly what the implications were.
``Yesterday I talked about the importance I attach to the devolving of power,
and with that responsibility, down to local government and to give local
authorities more freedom to formulate by-laws. This has been trivialised by
some of my opponents but it is an important issue of civic life,'' he said.
By-laws could be used to stop drinking in the open in towns and cities, he
said, admitting that the Scottish Office had taken a restrictive view in the
past.
``I think it is a matter for individual councils and I want to see an extension
of the freedom of local authorities in this area. Today what is under
consideration is the use of by-laws to ensure a speed limit inside a cordon
around the shore line to allow people to practise such sports as swimming,
canoeing, sailing or fishing and to limit the use of high-powered speed boats
where there would be safety or environmental considerations and conflicts with
other users.
``It is my intention to make a decision before the end of the year and I would
need to have some pretty powerful arguments to make me overturn the views which
have been taken by local authorities who are, after all, the democratically
elected bodies with responsibility for this area.''
He said that he considered Loch Lomond to be a very special place, not just
because his constituency boundary ran through its centre but because it was
important to Scotland and had great natural beauty and environmental importance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Margaret, 106, enjoys the simple lifestyle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093937</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT the grand old age of 106, Margaret Duncan knows exactly how to hook a man.
Glasgow's oldest citizen, born when Victoria was Queen and the Eiffel Tower was
just being built, had the city's Lord Provost and comedian Andy Cameron dancing
attendance at her birthday party yesterday.
As Lord Provost Tommy Dingwall handed over a set of silver teaspoons, a case of
wine and a tartan shawl, she joked: ``I think you must think I'm getting
married again.'' That would make husband number three for Margaret, who has
already outlived two spouses.
Her first husband, whom she married at 45, was an ``elderly man'' of 66. Her
second was a 67-year-old ``toyboy'', whom she wed for companionship when she
was 72.
But the fragile lady with the big laugh suffered heartbreak as a young woman.
Her first love, Harry Glover from Shettleston, was killed in the First World
War when she was 22.
These days Margaret, who still regrets she did not have children, is rarely
separated from her new male companion - her budgie Harvey.
Much has changed in her life since she was born in Glasgow's East End, the
youngest of four children.
Times in Britain, under the government of Lord Salisbury, were hard. But
Margaret has fond memories of her childhood, in the days when trams ran through
Glasgow and the River Clyde was booming with industry.
She said: ``When I was a girl you didn't have the television, but we were quite
happy without it because we all got round the piano at night and sang.''
She has not lost her taste for the simple things. Yesterday she prepared to
celebrate with a lunch of her favourite Scotch broth, followed by silverside
and butter beans.
And afterwards, there was no doubt about a sing song: her favourite is the old
music hall song, Who's your lady friend?
</TEXT>
