<DOCID>GH951202-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Troubled Monklands council wins award</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONKLANDS District Council - the subject of a ``jobs for the boys'' inquiry -
revealed yesterday it had won a prestigious award for commitment to the
training and development of its workers.
The award comes a week after the Government inquiry into allegations that
councillors on the Lanarkshire authority used their powers to get family and
friends jobs on the workforce.
During the inquiry headed by Mr William Nimmo-Smith, QC, evidence was heard
from witnesses that senior members of the Labour controlled council issued
green application forms to show they were backing individual applicants for
jobs.
Mr Nimmo-Smith will make his findings known to Secretary of State, Mr Michael
Forsyth, later this month. If he finds councillors have failed in their
statutory duty in hiring staff, then Mr Forsyth may take legal action against
certain councillors.
Several allegations surrounding the jobs claims centred on those employed in
the housing department.
But yesterday the council's housing department announced it had become the
first in Scotland to win the Investors In People Award - a nationally
recognised standard aimed at raising the level of commitment to training and
development among employers.
Monklands Housing, which administers the letting of 21,000 houses, shows its
long-term commitment to its 260 workers through new staffing structures,
intensive on-going training courses and a more effective communications
strategy, a council spokeswoman said.
Housing convener, Councillor Betty Leitch, a witness at the inquiry who said
her two relatives got their council jobs on their own merit, praised the
housing office.
She said: ``The housing department's success follows two years of intensive
work towards achieving the certification and we are delighted to be the first
local authority to attain it.''
</TEXT>
