<DOCNO>GH951202-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mother admits child neglect</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER left a child unrestrained in the back of her car while she drove under
the influence of alcohol or drugs, a court heard yesterday.
The woman, 31, of Forres, Moray, who cannot be named for legal reasons, was
reported after she stopped her car to ask a passer-by for directions in Elgin
last June.
She yesterday admitted a total of four charges, including neglect, in Elgin
Sheriff Court.
Fiscal James MacKay said the woman refused on two occasions to supply police
with a specimen of her breath for testing.
``Police became concerned about the accused's fitness to look after the girl
after the doctor found her to an extent to be under the influence of alcohol
and marginally not fit to be in charge of the child,'' Mr MacKay said.
``The child was released into the care of a family friend.''
He invited Sheriff Noel McPartlin to refer the case to the Children's Panel.
The woman's agent, Mr Alastair Russell, said: ``During the early part of this
year she faced circumstances which placed her under great strain and anguish
and she felt the woman (from whom she had asked directions) had contributed to
that anguish.''
Mr Russell said the accused had drunk two cans of cider.
Sheriff McPartlin deferred sentence until later this month for social inquiry
and community service reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court detains man on siege charges</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 33-year-old man appeared in court yesterday accused of threatening to shoot
policemen during a siege at a house in Glasgow on Thursday night. Mr Brian
Campbell, of Tormusk Road, Castlemilk, did not enter a plea and was detained
for inquiries.
Witnesses sought
POLICE are seeking witnesses to an attack on an 85-year-old woman in Scott
Street, Perth, at 4.40pm on Thursday. The elderly woman suffered a broken hip
and was seriously ill in hospital yesterday. The attacker, a young man who
stole her handbag, was confronted by a passer-by and ran off towards Perth High
Street.
Cannabis fine
A WOMAN was yesterday fined #500 in Dingwall Sheriff Court for drug offences.
Heather Newsome, 33, of Langlands Terrace, Kyle of Lochalsh, had admitted
cultivation and possession of cannabis.
Doctor impostor
A FORMER hospital attendant who dressed as a doctor and went on a stealing
spree was yesterday warned he faced jail. Gavin MacKenzie, 47, of Glen Court,
Inverness, admitted 11 offences at Raigmore Hospital in Inverness between
September 1994 and June 1995 but pleaded not guilty to 20 other charges. The
sheriff deferred sentence.
Last sighting
A MAN, 69, found beaten to death in his South Yorkshire home was last seen
alive on Wednesday night, police said yesterday. Widower Maurice Hoyle died of
head injuries sustained in an apparently motiveless attack.
Soccer hearing
THE hearing of match-fixing allegations against football players John Fashanu,
Bruce Grobbelaar and Hans Segers was adjourned yesterday until January 3.
Chester recovering
ENTERTAINER Charlie Chester has been moved to Nunnery Fields Hospital,
Canterbury, for rehabilitation after a stroke last week. A BBC radio spokesman
said doctors were hopeful of improvement.
Escapee warning
A PSYCHIATRIC prisoner who has escaped could become dangerous in certain
circumstances, the Scottish Office warned yesterday. Robert Moor, 52, who
escaped from Dykebar Hospital in Paisley, was acquitted of murder on the
grounds of insanity in 1971.
Youth flees
A JUVENILE detainee, known as the ``Pyjama Boy'' since his first institutional
escape at the age of 11, has escaped again. The 14-year-old was sent to a
children's home on the edge of Dartmoor last week on counts of burglary,
dangerous driving and car theft.
</TEXT>
