<HEADLINE>Radio station sacks head of news</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093942</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Radio
station
sacks head
of news
MANAGEMENT at a Scottish radio station yesterday sacked one of their top
executives.
But the head of news with Aberdeen-based Northsound has contacted his lawyers
and yesterday vowed to fight his dismissal.
Mr Jonathan Moore was suspended earlier this week and yesterday was dismissed
from the station, which sponsors Aberdeen FC.
A spokesman for the company said: ``We can confirm that Mr Moore's contract has
been terminated. It is an internal matter.''
Mr Moore had been head of news at Northsound for the past two years. He joined
the station after spells at Dundee-based Radio Tay and Edinburgh-based Radio
Forth.
All three stations are part of the Scottish Radio Holdings group which also
owns Radio Clyde in Glasgow.
Scottish Radio Holdings insiders said Mr Moore was sacked after completing a
freelance contract for PR Consultants Scotland.
Later Dundee-born Mr Moore, 29, issued a statement which said: ``I can confirm
that I was dismissed by Northsound Radio for alleged breach of contract. I
strongly deny this and I am meeting my lawyers next week when we will discuss
an application to an Industrial Tribunual for unfair dismissal.''
Mr John MacDonald, the Aberdeen director of Shandwick Scotland, the public
relations company which was until recently known as PR Consultants Scotland,
said yesterday: ``I can confirm that John Moore, of Northsound, has recently
done work for us on a freelance basis, as indeed have other personnel at the
radio station.''
He added: ``However, I am not prepared to discuss money figures in this
context.''
A legal battle now seems imminent at the station which is already involved in a
wrangle over rights to cover football matches involving Aberdeen ... the team
it sponsors.
Rival station Scot FM, whose broadcast area does not cover Aberdeen, has an
exclusive radio contract to cover Scottish Football League matches in Scotland.
Northsound has reported the situation to the Office of Fair Trading because it
believes BBC Radio Scotland has a monopoly in its area because it has a
separate public sector contract which allows it to broadcast league matches.
</TEXT>
