<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Judge's ruling shocks painter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NORTH Sea oil rig painter who claimed he had suffered psychiatric injuries
from watching colleagues die in the Piper Alpha disaster yesterday lost his bid
for #200,000 damages.
Mr William Hegarty, 43, of Bonhill, Alexandria, was aboard the 23,000 tonne
support vessel MSV Tharos which tried to pick up survivors and aid the stricken
platform as it was destroyed by a series of explosions on July 6, 1988,
resulting in 167 fatalities.
Mr Hegarty said he would be appealing against the decision.
He told the High Court in London his life had been in danger at the time and
said he had since suffered post traumatic stress syndrome and depression.
Mr Justice Popplewell in his judgment said Mr Hegarty was a man of ``ordinary
fortitude'' who was genuinely in fear of his life. But he dismissed the action
``with regret'', saying Mr Hegarty's life had never been in real danger.
Last night Mr Hegarty said: ``It was a shock. I expected to win. I thought the
legal system was fair.''
Mr Hegarty said he had not worked since the disaster and added: ``I still
suffer from post traumatic stress disorder. I haven't slept properly for
seven-and-a-half years. I can't sleep without medication. I still dream about
it and it will not go away.''
Mr Hegarty claimed a huge fireball engulfed the support vessel, which he said
had moved to within 25 metres of Piper Alpha. ``The company owed me a duty of
care and I think they broke that rule.''
Mr Hegarty, who has a wife and four children, said he had fallen deeply into
debt since he stopped working and his lifestyle had completely changed.
His claim for personal injury and consequential loss, was brought under common
law and under regulations of the Off-Shore Installations Operational Safety
Regulations 1976.
Mr Justice Popplewell said: ``There were a number or risks resulting from this
fire but I am quite unable to conclude that anything that happened that night
was `likely to endanger' Mr Hegarty's safety or health. Accordingly, with
regret, I must dismiss this action.''
He ruled that the Piper owners, E. E Caledonia Ltd, formerly Occidental
Petroleum (Caledonia) Ltd, had owed Mr Hegarty no ``duty of care''. He noted
that the Tharos could never have been within 25 metres of Piper Alpha and the
only damage to the vessel was blistering of paint.
He said: ``It was undoubtedly a catastrophe of the highest order, it was
shocking, frightening and devastating, not only for those on Piper Alpha but
those on Tharos who had to watch the horrendous unfolding of events without
being able to contribute materially to the welfare of those on Piper.
``Mr Hegarty was present for about two hours before he was evacuated.''
The judge said he had been shown photographs and a film of the disaster, but
they ``did not start to convey the horror of that night. However, they do not
show a fireball either approaching Tharos or engulfing it''.
The judge said he had heard evidence from others who witnessed the disaster and
from the Tharos's skipper, Captain Alistair Letty.
He said he accepted Captain Letty's evidence that the fireball had, at no time,
actually reached Tharos.
</TEXT>
