<DOCNO>GH951202-000182</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000182</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Family hears that man found dead in doctor's surgery `could have died at any time.'  Patient beyond aid, inquiry told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093944</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE death of an elderly man found lying on the toilet floor at his GP's surgery
cannot be attributed to the time it took to find him, a fatal accident inquiry
was told yesterday.
John Ross, aged 86, died eight days after being found unconscious on the floor
of the Muiredge Surgery in Buckhaven. He had lain there for 30 hours before
being discovered. The Fatal Accident Inquiry at Kirkcaldy Sheriff Court heard
that the former docker suffered from two life-threatening conditions which
could not have been treated, even if they had occurred in hospital.
Mr Ross disappeared on August 1 after leaving his home in Sea Road, Methil to
collect a prescription for his wife.
Mr Ross' son Harry, expressed shock and dismay that his father had lain
undiscovered for so long.
When his father failed to return home, the inquiry heard, Harry Ross went to
the surgery to collect his mother's prescription, unaware his father was lying
in the toilets. He claimed receptionists had told him his father had not been
to the surgery that day.
Dr Peter Walker, a pathologist, reported that he could not separate the
unrelated major stroke and lung-damaging blood clots which either singly or
together killed Mr Ross and expressed ``surprise'' that the deceased had had no
symptoms of ill health.
The post mortem examination revealed that Mr Ross had suffered a series of
embolisms - blood clots - in the month prior to his death.
Dr Walker told Sheriff Gail Patrick that Mr Ross suffered from the type of
arterial disease common in the elderly, caused by an accumulation of deposits
associated with fatty foods.
The arteries at the base of his brain were ``severely diseased'' which caused a
``major'' stroke for which there was no adequate treatment.
Mr Ross had also suffered thrombosis in his legs resulting in blocked arteries
causing lung damage and he had suffered a further episode just prior to his
death in Kirkcaldy's Victoria Hospital.
Questioned by depute fiscal Christine Baillie, he said there was no connection
between the stroke and the embolisms, adding that he believed Mr Ross's
collapse in the toilets was the start of the stroke.
Asked by Miss Baillie if immediate discovery would have made any difference to
the prognosis, Dr Walker said: ``I feel none at all,'' as, facing two
potentially and factually life-threatening conditions, neither of which would
benefit from primary treatment, Mr Ross ``could have died at anytime''.
Questioned by Ross family lawyer, David Ritchie the pathologist agreed it was
possible Mr Ross had collapsed as the result of the embolism.
Asked by Mr Ritchie if it was possible the stress of that could have brought on
the stroke, Dr Walker said: ``Not in my opinion,'' but added that it was at
least ``theoretically possible.''
Asked if he would accept the fact that lying for 30 hours in the toilet
possibly led to Mr Ross's early death, Dr Walker said: ``No. I find it
surprising he lived as long as he did.''
Responding to questions from lawyer Susan Craig, representing the Muiredge
Practice, Dr Walker expressed the view that had Mr Ross suffered the embolism
at the surgery he would not have been unconscious but would have died.
Ms Craig asked, ``So if he had collapsed with the embolism, they would have
found a dead body?'' Dr Walker replied: ``Yes.''
He also told her that if Mr Ross had survived an embolism and been admitted to
hospital he did not think doctors could have predicted a stroke and that in any
case there was ``no primary or adequate treatment for either of these killers.''
The inquiry heard from practice doctor Swapan Mukherjee that Mr Ross, who
suffered from osteo-arthirits and some prostate trouble, did not regularly
visit his GP.
He added that he and his colleagues were ``devasted'' when Mr Ross was found on
the evening of August 2 and it was realised that neither checks by practice
staff nor cleaners had discovered him earlier. Receptionist Mary Wilson told
the inquiry that she had failed to check the cubicles in the toilet before
locking up.
Dr Mukherjee revealed that under verbal procedures in force prior to the
incident the rooms were to be checked prior to closure to ensure the lights
were off and there was no one in them.
He told Miss Baillie that as a result of the incident, and recognising the
inadequacy of the measures, a new written checking procedure had been
introduced which included checking the toilets four times a day. Surgery staff
on duty on the day in question, he noted, had been disciplined.
The inquiry continues on December 19.
</TEXT>
