<DOCNO>GH951202-000183</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000183</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Perjury trial halted as accused collapses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093945</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PERJURY trial was halted at Stranraer Sheriff Court yesterday after the
accused collapsed in the dock and had to be taken to hospital.
The jury had taken its place and Sheriff Robert Dickson was taking the bench
when Mrs Jill Thorley fell to the floor screaming and moaning.
As jurors were taken from the court police officers attended the woman, who
appeared to be having breathing difficulties, before paramedics and a local
doctor arrived to examine her. She was taken by ambulance to the Garrick
Hospital in Stranraer and has been detained for observation.
Mrs Thorley, 51, of Knocknar, Monreith, Port William, pleads not guilty to
charges of perjury and attempting to pervert the course of justice.
It is alleged that on August 18, 1994, at Stranraer Sheriff Court, having been
sworn in as a witness to give evidence at a Fatal Accident Inquiry
investigating the death of Daniel Dailly Lowe, a patient at Hillcrest
retirement home, Wigtown, she said that her son Robert David Thorley was the
sleep-in member of staff at the home on February 6, 1994, and that the level of
staff was sufficient to take it within the guidelines of the social work
department, the truth being as she well knew that Robert David Thorley was not
sleeping in the home and the only member of staff was Marie Blackley.
She further denies that between February 6 and August 17, 1994, she induced
Robert David Thorley and Marie Blackley to give false information to the
police, procurator-fiscal Francis Walkingshaw and to give false evidence at the
FAI at Stranraer Sheriff Court and to pretend that they had been on duty at the
home on February 6 when Daniel Lowe left the home and this she did with intent
to deceive the authorities over the staffing levels.
Sheriff Dickson formally adjourned the case and said that he would await
further medical information on Mrs Thorley's condition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000184</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000184</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New Year changes to pistol club rules</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093946</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW rules governing approved rifle and pistol clubs will come into effect from
January 1 following a report by an independent committee which advises the Home
Secretary and the Scottish Office.
In future, members, prospective members and guests must sign a declaration
stating that they are not prohibited from possessing a firearm.
The concept of ``novice'' membership is to be abolished, because in the past,
members could attend clubs for basic training - but not shoot - which led to
confusion.
Probationary membership, which allows a newcomer to be individually trained in
safe practice, and to shoot under the supervision of experienced club members
remains, but the minimum period of probation has been reduced to three months.
By making the changes the Firearms Consultative Committee has addressed a
number of concerns expressed by police and rifle and pistol clubs.
Advocate Mr Kevin Drummond, who served on the committee, yesterday said: ``The
new rules are the result of careful examination of the criteria.
``I am confident this revisal will be welcomed by the police, and the shooting
community.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000185</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000185</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Downsized racers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Fergus Wyllie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093947</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Don't even think about taking your child
to the slopes in an old anorak and jeans, says Fergus Wyllie.  Today's
fashion-smart kids won't get out of the car-park without thermal insulation and
avalanche reflectors
TO say that children's ski clothing is a growing industry is a bit like saying
that Alberto Tomba gets to the bottom of the hill quickly.
More and more manufacturers are producing not only jackets, trousers, and suits
specially designed for youngsters, but also scaled-down versions of the latest
adult gear, in hi-tech, waterproof, wind-resistant, thermally-insulated,
all-singing, all-dancing material.
It has to look right or you can bet your bottom dollar that junior will not
even consider putting his or her arms inside it. Style and quality clothing is
not cheap, especially considering how quickly the youngster will grow out of
it, but it is important that your cherished offspring does not turn into an ice
lolly while braving the arctic conditions on Scottish slopes for hours on end.
There is a flourishing trade in second-hand children's ski wear for this reason.
One example of very smart scaled-down adult gear is Killy's Mougli jacket and
Picasso trousers as worn by Neil Watters, 11, a member of a race training class
at Glasgow Ski Centre in Bellahouston Park.
Both the matt-finish jacket and trousers are made with Entrant G11 waterproof
and breathable fabric and have all the necessary press-studs, zippers, hood,
and flaps to keep bad weather at bay. The jacket, which has a Recco avalanche
reflector and detector, costs #150 and the trousers #80.
Six-year-old Gail Ross is wearing Nevica's Sonic jacket, also with the
avalanche reflector and detector, and Zebedee trousers. They are waterproof and
breathable and cost #100 and #56.
Chuck Roast clothing from New England in the United States is relatively new to
Scotland and combines bright, attractive colours with good performance. Ladi
Smrcek, 10, is wearing a Teflon-coated waterproof jacket (#60) and Polartec
Snow Pants (#24) while Gabriella Flynn models the Snow Pants and Kennebec
fleece (#36), again made from Polartec fabric which is very lightweight, has
good insulation and breathing qualities, and is claimed to be ``non-bobbling''
after machine-washing. Chuck Roast is available from Tiso shops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000186</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000186</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The hills are alive</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Fergus Wyllie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Map,Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093948</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Fergus Wyllie examines the growing confidence in Scots resorts
THIS summer has been a season of growth for Scottish ski areas. Glenshee, which
rather cheekily adopted the title of Britain's ``Trois Vallees'', has gained a
fourth valley by merging with Glencoe.
However, the development which will be of most immediate benefit to skiers is
at Nevis Range where a new chair and tow have opened up extra runs on the
North-east face of Aonach Mor.
The Great Glen chair, from the Snowgoose restaurant to the base of the Nid
ridge, and the Rob Roy T-bar, taking skiers 385m up the ridge, are part of a
#750,000 scheme which includes a chairlift ``over the back'' in Coire Dubh to
be erected next summer.
This year's piste map shows two black and five red runs in the corrie starting
at the Nid ridge. They will not be groomed or snow-fenced but the entrances
will be marked with poles on the ridge. Nevis Range emphasises they may not
always be open, particularly in icy conditions, when the entrances will be
roped off. The ski patrol will be extra vigilant here and will confiscate the
lift pass of any skier who ducks under the ropes of a closed run.
A line of poles will be placed at the bottom of the runs leading back to the
chair and tow so that skiers do not end up halfway to Spean Bridge in poor
visibility. A large cornice often forms along the ridge but it is hoped to keep
the entrances open by grooming and blasting. Eight staff have been on a course
to learn the dangerous art of moving snow with explosives.
Although this development will be very attractive to intermediate and advanced
skiers, the people who will benefit most from the new tow and chair will be
beginners. The green runs beside the restaurant are only reliable in good
winters, whereas the area at the base of the Nid ridge serviced by the chair
and tow has much better snowholding.
The chair, which will be both walk-on walk-off and ski-on ski-off, will also
fill a gap in the progression of beginners at Nevis Range, where the
development has created seven jobs. Until now, learners have started on the
rope tow, moved to the Lochy and Linnhe pomas beside the restaurant, and made
the big jump to the more formidable Alpha poma, taking them on to blue runs if
the snow cover was poor. Now the Great Glen chair will carry them to and from
easy green and blue runs at the base of the Nid ridge.
A new snack bar, Cameron's Tea Hut, has been built there but unfortunately,
like the popular eaterie at the bottom of the Goose run, it will have no
toilets. It seems they cannot be provided due to environmental considerations.
I would have thought the environment might suffer considerably if skiers cannot
be bothered to return to the toilets at the restaurant.
Nevis Range, where a lift pass increases to #17 for an adult and #11 for a
junior (under 18), is opening a snowboard hire shop at the base station with 20
``trays'' at #15.50 a day.
Further south, the most immediate effect of the merger between the Glenshee
Chairlift Company and the White Corries at Glencoe is that the western area
will now open seven days a week, making it a very attractive mid-week prospect
to Central Belt skiers.
The pistes should also be in better condition thanks to overnight grooming by a
#130,000 machine bought with the help of Lochaber Enterprise. Moguls will be
left on one or two runs, however, and the chairlift company stresses that
traditional, hairy Glencoe skiers ``will be able to enjoy what they have always
enjoyed''.
More snow fences have been put on the Plateau to improve snowholding and extend
the length of the season by avoiding that painful walk from the access chair to
the Cliffhanger chair and lower T-bar when the poma track is broken.
A 350-yard trainer tow has been installed parallel to the Plateau poma at
Glencoe to increase the beginners' area.
An adult day lift pass at Glencoe, where 14 winter jobs have been created,
costs #14.50. Sales of a joint season ticket covering Glencoe and Glenshee at a
bargain #210 ceased at the end of October with slightly fewer than 100 sold.
However, canny skiers can buy a book of five-day passes usable at either area
for #60 until December 31.
The Glenshee Chairlift Company, which now effectively runs both areas, resisted
the temptation to market its two areas as Scotland's ``Four Valleys'' and went
for the slogan, Ski Scotland's Super G's (sic). Shame about the apostrophe but
at least it tried to be imaginative.
Snowboarding is big everywhere but especially in Glenshee where the chairlift
company will have 200 boards for hire this season at #12 a day (#17 with soft
boots). It is also opening its own school, the Glenshee Snowboard Academy. It
is not known whether naughty pupils will be spanked, belted, or given lines.
Grampian Enterprise has helped with #100,000 spent on environmental
improvements, such as car park surfacing, grassing, paving, and fencing at
Glenshee, where an adult day lift pass costs #16 this season.
However, the chairlift company's main concern during the summer was its #1.3m
Glen Golf Course in Alyth. It plans to erect the clubhouse next year and open
for business in spring 1997.
The Cairngorm Chairlift Company is also starting its own snowboard school. This
is a new departure as all the ski schools on the hill are independently run. It
has 50 boards for rent at #15 a day and there are literally hundreds of hire
boards available in shops around Aviemore.
Obviously, the company's main efforts have concentrated on getting planning
permission and EU funding for the #15m development plan, which includes a
funicular railway. It received a setback recently when the Cairngorms
Partnership board declared that outstanding issues needed to be resolved before
it could support the project.
The chairlift company's chief executive, Mr Tim Whittome, said that some of the
concerns had now been resolved but that there had been ``shifting of
goalposts'' over objections to the scheme.
Unfortunately, a September deadline for EU Objective One money had been missed
and the company was working towards having planning permission and its own
financial package in place to meet the next one in March. Mr Whittome said that
the earliest construction could start was 1997 with the new uplift open in 1998
and the buildings complete by the end of 1999.
Despite all these difficulties, the chairlift company continues to work at
improving its product, especially customer care. This area, in which training
started last year, will no doubt be improved by the appointment of former Marks
&amp; Spencer executive Anne Angus as general manager.
A high-season, day lift ticket at Cairngorm increases to #17 (child #11.30) and
a morning-only ticket has been introduced at #12. Skiers will pay the full
price but can obtain a #5 refund before a certain time.
Over at the Lecht, they are also gearing up for more and more boarders. A
snowboard park with jumps, walls, and its own tow will be made between the
Eagle and Grouse runs. Unfortunately, a half-pipe is not possible because the
Lecht does not normally have enough snow to build one, and the winds howling
off the Cairngorms would just fill it up with snow every night.
The ski centre has ordered more boards, taking the number for hire up to 44,
and there will be a full-time boarding instructor. Last season, the area had 30
ski instructors teaching mainly beginners at weekends and expects to increase
that number this winter.
There is a new building housing the ski school and a larger shop, run by the
Ski Snow Shop of Aberdeen, selling gloves, hats, goggles, and clothing.
Out on the white stuff, a second, larger piste grooming machine has been
purchased which will improve snow quality, particularly in bad conditions.
One day's full area lift pass costs #11 for an adult and #8 for a child with
ski hire #10 and #7. A combined lift pass and ski hire ticket is available
midweek only for #16 (December and January) and #18 (February and March).
</TEXT>
