<HEADLINE>Dock ain't big enough for case of revolvers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093949</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NINE accused, all members of the Scottish League of Gunfighters, had to stand
in the jury boxes at Dundee Sheriff Court yesterday because the dock was not
big enough to contain them all.
They are charged with possessing smooth bore revolvers capable of chambering
and firing .38 calibre cartridges, which had been converted from replica guns
designed to fire blanks, and are also accused of possessing prohibited weapons
without the authority of the Scottish Secretary.
The offences are alleged to have happened in the Scotsman bar in Gellatly
Street, Dundee.
The nine deny the charges.
They are Mr William Townsley, 36, of Tarvett Mill, Cupar; Mr John Cargill, 60,
of Fleming Gardens West, Dundee; Mr Munro Crichton, 51, of Sharps Court,
Dundee; Mr Patrick Welsh, 52, Edzell Court, Dundee; Mr John Martin, 49, of
Baluinie Street, Dundee; Mr Charles Menzies, 37, of East Ingliston Farm
Cottages, by Forfar; Mr Alexander McKenzie, 66, c/o Harris Terrace, Dundee; Mr
Thomas Lindsay, 51, of Carlungie, Carnoustie; and Mr George Yeaman, 53, of
Upper Dalgairn, Cupar.
Trial was set for March 6 .
</TEXT>
