<HEADLINE>A degree? I don't believe it, says actor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093950</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A degree?
I don't
believe it,
says actor
BELIEVE it or not, Scottish actor Richard Wilson, best known for his role as
irascible pensioner Victor Meldrew, yesterday became an honorary doctor of
Glasgow Caledonian University.
Proposing him for the doctorate, Professor Gordon Dickson, dean of health, said
Mr Wilson had ``committed himself to his profession and achieved excellence in
it'', frequently undertaking ``unsung work'' and offering support to young
aspiring actors.
Meanwhile, the new Principal of Glasgow University yesterday insisted that the
description of ``ivory towers'' no longer applied to British higher education.
In his first address to a graduation ceremony, Professor Graeme Davies said of
that sobriquet: ``Nothing could be further from the truth of the current
situation.''
However, he added: ``For our universities to be able to continue to make the
contribution of which they are capable, and upon which much of the economic and
cultural success of the future will depend, it is important for Government to
ensure that their ability to respond is not jeopardised.''
Professor Davies accepted that universities had to give a high priority to
wealth creation, and cited the work done to help fish farming in Scotland, a
sector which now employs more people than steel and coal production.
``They (universities) are vibrant, exciting and rewarding communities which
have increasingly developed partnerships and networks that penetrate deep into
the commercial, industrial and financial sectors.''
q LABOUR leader Tony Blair yesterday criticised Government policy on higher
education after being awarded an honorary degree.
Mr Blair, who was made an honorary doctor of civil law by Northumbria
University, later told a news conference that virtually every university in the
country was unhappy about the way it was being treated.
``There are difficulties over funding and would be under any government. But I
think it is essential we find a system that is fairer and allows as many young
people through university as possible.''
