<HEADLINE>Sour about sales policy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E Dundas, Christopher Sims, Angus Gawn</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<FLAG>personal finance letters</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093952</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q.In a recent newspaper article several leading financial advisers were quoted
as saying that due to Equitable Life's secretive stance in not revealing
information on its cash reserves they could not recommend the company. It also
quoted Money Management magazine as reporting that Equitable Life had a low
free-asset ratio.
The company countered this criticism by arguing that it didn't publish its
reserves to avoid misleading comparisons and by suggesting that independent
advisers might be sour over its policy not to pay commission on selling
pensions.
I have in the past made regular single premium payments to my Equitable pension
policy and had intended to do so in the future. However, in the light of the
criticism made by the advisers I wonder if there is significant cause for
concern.
n.Financial advisers are clearly not going to recommend a non-commission paying
life office and there is no reason under the ``best advice'' rules why they
should because they have not out-performed commission-paying offices, though
Equitable Life is frequently in the top 10.
As you indicate, Equitable does not agree with the financial strength tables
published by Money Management and other magazines because there is a no
standardised way of compiling them. Within the official parameters, a company
can calculate its free-asset ratio, which - because it measures the ratio of
surplus assets to liabilities - is considered a key measure, in a variety of
ways, some more flattering than others.
Instead, Equitable points to outside opinion on its financial strength, notably
its ``AA excellent'' rating awarded by Standard &amp; Poor's, the rating agency,
which is only just below the highest AAA category, and the recommendation by
the Government Actuary that it may be used to run pension plans for local
authorities and other public sector bodies. Equitable also has a strong track
record on its payouts on with-profits policies.
All insurance companies are closely monitored by the Department of Trade and
Industry, and the chance of even a small company going bust is remote. However,
a relatively poor financial position could act as a constraint on its
investment performance and, therefore, the returns a with-profits policyholder
would obtain.
q.I am 48 years of age and would like to retire at 55. My husband and I are
members of our relevant company pension schemes. We have a mixed bag of shares
and our mortgage is paid off.
In the light of the enclosed estimate from my employer, should I purchase added
years or is this not financially viable? We have followed your advice over the
years in the purchase of both unit and investment trusts. I have enclosed
details of our portfolio and would be grateful if you could advise us on
whether any changes are recommended.
n.Assuming your scheme provides a pension of one-sixtieth of final salary for
each year of service, paying the maximum contribution for added years would be
worth an extra 10% of salary on your pension if you continued working until 60.
However, retiring at 55 would greatly reduce the pension purchased and it is
probably not worth doing because you would get a better return by saving the
extra contributions you would have made. As for your portfolio, it seems quite
well-balanced and no obvious changes are called for.
q.I am almost 50 and planning for retirement. I've been making AVCs (#80 per
month) for five years into a pension plan with Albany Life. At this rate it has
been calculated I should be able to retire within the next 10 years on half my
present #25,000 salary. By that time my mortgage will have been paid off.
However, I should like to ensure I'm comfortable in retirement by investing
more now. My thought was to increase my pension contributions but I've been
told there is a risk of ``overfunding''. Could you explain? If this is not a
tax-efficient way to build a nest egg how could it best be done?
n.The maximum that those in a company pension scheme are allowed to contribute
to their main scheme and AVCs is 15% of earnings. The employer's contributions
are on top of this. You are presently contributing 3.8% so unless your payments
into the main scheme are exceptionally high it would appear you have quite a
lot of leeway. Typically, the employee's contribution is 6% to 7% of gross
earnings.
Overfunding results when the AVC, combined with the main company scheme, would
provide benefits which exceed the maximum allowable two-thirds of final salary.
The overfunded portion is returned after a tax charge of 35% for standard rate
taxpayers. This is to offset the initial tax relief on premiums. People who
have been with one employer for many years may already qualify for nearly the
maximum pension. If this is the case overfunding is a real risk. However, this
does not appear to be so in your case.
q.I am 58 years old, work as a professional and have various investments but
not a PEP. We are in the process of buying a flat for our son. It will be in
his name but we are taking out a mortgage for about #50,000. This will also be
in his name, but as he has no income the repayments will be made by us and the
possible rent from other students who will take a room. I will act as guarantor.
The building society, Bradford &amp; Bingley, is looking for security for the loan
and will accept a PEP in my name. Our financial adviser has suggested three
companies, Ivory &amp; Sime, M&amp;G Compound Growth PEP and HSBC Flexipep. He is
leaning towards Ivory &amp; Sime and I would appreciate your advice.
n.All these fund managers are respected names in the industry and it is really
impossible to predict which might give the best performance over the timescale
of a mortgage. However, expenses have an important bearing on performance over
the long term, so it is probably advisable to go for the one with the lowest.
But have you thought of simply having a repayment mortgage, possibly with
enhanced repayments so it is repaid in less than the usual 20 to 25 years?
q.Can you tell me how inheritance tax is levied on husband and wife? Is it now
like income tax where independent taxation applies, or is it assessed on the
joint estate?
n.Inheritance tax (IHT) is levied separately on husband and wife so each can
have an estate of up to #154,000 without any IHT worries. In addition, anything
passing from one spouse to the other by lifetime gift or on death is exempt.
But if one spouse leaves his or her estate to the other there will be IHT
payable on the second death if the joint estate is more than #154,000.
Passing the estate, or at least enough to use the #154,000 allowance, direct to
the next generation is a sensible tax move but care must be taken to ensure
this does not leave the surviving spouse with insufficient income or capital to
live comfortably.
With effect from April 6, the exempt amount will be increased to #200,000 for
each spouse.
q.I bought a new house six months ago but have recently had to resell it due to
difficulty in selling my present home in the depressed market. I had to take
out a bridging loan but have had a claim for tax relief on this refused. The
tax office says that in my circumstances the interest paid on the loan is not
allowable. Am I not right in saying bridging loan interest is allowable in
addition to relief for mortgage payments?
n.Tax relief is usually available for interest paid on bridging finance up to
#30,000 in addition to any relief given for existing mortgage interest on the
old house. Relief for bridging loan interest is available for up to a year to
enable the existing house to be sold, and this time limit can be extended by
the Inland Revenue if it considers it reasonable to do so.
However, the relief is only available provided that within the 12 month or
extended period the new house is occupied as your main residence. It is likely
that if you never sold your old home you did not take up residence in the new
one and it, therefore, never became your main residence. If this is the case,
the Revenue's decision is correct.
