<HEADLINE>Salmond looks to association of states in Britain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093953</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAN INDEPENDENT Scotland should set up an Association of States of the British
Isles, Scottish National Party leader Alex Salmond said yesterday.
The association would identify areas of common concern and interest with
England, Wales, Northern Ireland, the Irish Republic, the Isle of Man and the
Channel Islands.
It would be based loosely on the Nordic Council and other similar groupings of
nations in Europe and would allow joint action, where appropriate, on issues
before the European Union and other international bodies, Mr Salmond said.
He was speaking to reporters after visiting the Council of Ministers in
Brussels, where he claimed Scotland was excluded from full participation
because of British interests.
He complained that at a recent fisheries council Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth, who enjoys full Cabinet rank, had sat silently during the meeting
while the talking was done by a junior representing English interests.
``This is what it has come to,'' he said. ``There was a time a few years ago
when the very thought would have been laughed at.''
Later, Mr Salmond met the EU's social affairs commissioner, Padraig Flynn, for
talks on the Social Chapter of the Maastricht treaty.
Mr Salmond said that under the Labour-Liberal Democrat proposals for a Scottish
parliament the Scots still would be unable to sign up for the chapter because
Westminster retained a veto. The same would apply under Mr Forsyth's proposals
for the Scottish Grand Committee.
``Only the parliament of an independent Scotland can take that decision and
thus fulfill the clear wish of the Scottish people, who are good Europeans but
are treated as an offshore outpost of Europe under the present arrangement,''
he said.
His proposals for an association of states is an updated version of a policy
which the SNP advanced in the 1970s. It was designed to show that an
independent Scotland would not be cast adrift politically and economically.
</TEXT>
