<HEADLINE>#9m cuts at Save the Children</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093954</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of Britain's largest and best-known charities yesterday announced swingeing
#9m cuts in children's projects.
Save the Children, whose president is the Princess Royal, blamed a ``difficult
operating environment'' for the dramatic cutbacks - which amount to 10% of the
total budget.
The National Lottery had been a ``significant pressure'', a charity spokesman
added.
The move will lead to job losses and project closures, including programmes in
the UK such as family centres and schemes for young people leaving care.
It is the second funding crisis for the charity, which has 80 UK projects and
programmes for children in more than 50 countries. Last year it announced it
was slashing #30m from its budget over four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
