<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000194</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000194</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Racers' cash  on the slide</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andi Robertson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093956</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Andi Robertson
bemoans the parlous
state of ski finance
EVEN for a nation which spawns legions of wannabe McCoists, Hastings and
McColgans, there should be a path to let the rarer youngsters who dream of
becoming the next Tomba or Zurbriggen reach their potential.
So contends the British Ski Federation who are charged with the task of
overseeing the perilous route from first slalom gates raced, through to
Olympic, World Cup or World Championship selection.
Since moving north under the aegis of a new regime five years ago, competitive
skiing's British governing body - based in a converted registrar's office in
East Calder, West Lothian - seem to have laid these foundations.
With a new set-up of international coaching in place which actually achieved
continuity over three or four years, British ski racing had a financial
timebomb planted in its midst around a year ago with the news that the Sports
Council was planning massive cuts to its contribution to the BSF's budget. In
fact the projection promised a cut from #305,000 to just #120,000 over the
period between the 1994 Lillehammer Olympics and the season of the 1998 games
in Nagano.
It may well be a return to this painful, pedantic refrain - ``money please for
Britain's hard-up, hard-done-by ski racers'',-but the current demoralising
effect is a shock wave which soon reaches the retail operators, many of whom
invest in supporting young talent, financing coaching, and running and funding
race leagues or championships.
Each will concede that there is little direct return from sponsorship (least of
all in the sale of race equipment which is almost universally discounted for
the young competitors), but they insist that the need for a high-profile
successful British team is an essential component of their marketing mix.
``In general we get tremendous support for our athletes from the retail trade,
from British manufacturers and distributors - and the unfortunate fact is that
we are becoming more reliant on them,'' reflects British Ski Federation Chief
Executive Mike Jardine.
Rob Farrell of retailers Nevisport, who are an equipment supplier to the
British team and for two years have supported one of the KPMG Scottish Ski
Team's brightest hopes, Derek McMillan, with equipment echoes the BSF viewpoint.
``Take youngsters such as Derek - it's now a massive commitment for parents to
fund a ski racing career. For many that drive is only going to be killed if
there's no prospect of external funding ever really taking over and subsidising
their costs when they reach national team level,'' Farrell says.
While they continue to fight the Sports Council's plans there are signs of a
substantial restructuring of UK coaching and the Home Nations and British
teams, as concessions, according to Jardine, ``to the seemingly ever-changing
justifications of the council for their cuts''.
The BSF has been thrown a lifeline from the industry in the form of a
management contract to run the Snowsports &amp; Outdoor Leisure Trade Exhibition -
skiing and snowboarding's biggest annual trade show, to be held in March at
Manchester's G-Mex.
The federation has already had to lay off administrative staff. The revenue
generated will allow it to maintain its current level of international coaching
staff and continue a programme that sees more British team skiers Europa Cup
qualified than before and more British skiers racing abroad than before and,
after the postponement of last year's Alpine World Championships, the daunting
prospect of two World Championships in consecutive years followed by the 1998
Olympics.
But without funding to send full teams to each then there is little light at
the end of the tunnel for British ski racing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000195</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000195</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bid to have daughter sterilised</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN, Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER is asking a judge to allow her 32-year-old daughter, who is severely
mentally handicapped, to be sterilised.
However, a curator appointed to look after the interests of the daughter is
opposing the application.
Lord MacLean was told at the Court of Session that the daughter attends an
adult training centre from Monday to Friday and lives at home in Edinburgh at
weekends.
The mother maintains her daughter is vulnerable to sexual advances, that her
life in the community involves contact with the opposite sex and that, to an
extent, she can travel around Edinburgh on her own.
According to the mother the daughter has always been popular with the opposite
sex and might be coerced into sexual activity without being aware of the
possible consequences.
She fears that if her daughter becomes pregnant she would be unable to cope
mentally with the pregnancy or with caring for the baby.
The daughter has been on the pill from the age of 15, but the mother is arguing
that it is impracticable and medically risky for her to continue with
contraception indefinitely.
She says sterilisation is the safest way of meeting her daughter's needs.
The mother also wants Lord MacLean to appoint her a tutor to her daughter with
powers to decide, for example, with whom she is to associate, whether she
should be allowed to engage in social activities and to consent to surgical
sterilisation.
The curator accepts that the mother should be appointed as tutor to her
daughter but does not accept that the daughter should be sterilised.
She argues that sterilisation is unjustified because the woman does not at
present engage in sexual intercourse. She says her oral contraception is
well-controlled and that the alternative to that would be a serious of regular
injections or an implant to prevent a pregnancy.
Lord MacLean is expected to issue a written decision later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000196</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000196</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tanker drivers keep look-out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093958</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tanker drivers from The Cheese Company's Lockerbie creamery are working with
police to keep an eye on farms in the early hours of the morning when they are
collecting milk.
The move follows the theft of 48 trailers worth more than #125,000 from the
Dumfries and Galloway countryside this year. The tanker drivers have also been
asked by the police to hand out crime prevention leaflets.
</TEXT>
