<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000197</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000197</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>From the Queen to Hello!</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093959</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Eric Thorburn is
photographer to the great and the good, and Clare Henry
reveals that he loves every minute of it
AS a boy in Govan, Eric Thorburn liked model-making. Soon his hobby extended to
suspending wooden airplanes with catgut in the back garden. ``Then I decided to
immortalise them via my dad's camera. That's how I discovered I liked
photography.''
Currently the best kent name in Scottish photography, with a list of clients as
long as your arm, from the Queen to Scottish Power, Distillers, Carstairs
Hospital, Newsweek and Hello!, he has just finished one of his most enjoyable
assignments ever: taking all 45 artist members of the 134-year-old Royal
Glasgow Institute of the Fine Arts.
``I just loved it. Fabulous. I only knew about five of them, people like David
Donaldson and Sandy Goudie - the rest were all new to me. It was terrific
working with artists. Ask them to lie on the floor surrounded by canvases and
they didn't blink an eye. You can't do that with royalty or managing
directors.''
Personality is all-important here. Thorburn has an engaging enthusiasm which
encourages a rapport with his sitters. Portraiture depends upon eye contact.
There are no short cuts. ``I enjoy the buzz; thrive on it.''
Thorburn took his artists in their studios - so I decide to turn the tables on
him and visit him in his studio, an old coach house at the bottom of his
garden, originally converted for his grandmother. Here in the curved, coved,
ground floor studio he did all the posed shots for Scottish Ballet and many of
his magazine and newspaper fashion pages. ``The dancers came on the train with
their costumes and we took the pictures here under powerful lights. Models
posed with the wind machine! But I got totally, utterly bored with posed
fashion photography. Nowadays I'm more often out and about on location.''
He almost missed his treasured RGI project. The phone call came out of the blue
and Thorburn turned the commission down. Luckily his wife Liz came to the
rescue, and immediately persuaded him to change his mind, ``A good thing too.
It's been such a lot of fun!''
They went to Arran to capture Jack Knox in his converted garage studio
overlooking the beach or riding his bike, to Hampshire to see William Crosbie
at home, to Elie to take Geoff Squires leaning on his splendid balcony, to
Clydebank for Tom McKendrick and to Lincolnshire to photograph Barbara Balmer.
They visited Dundee and Arbroath for Alberto Morrocco and Bill Littlejohn and
drove all over Britain at speed to pin down reclusive artists in their gardens
or gregarious folk in Glasgow and Edinburgh.
One especially memorable trip was to Bellochantuy in Argyll where Bill Wright
creates his beautiful grainy waterscapes on the beach. ``I love the look of him
- his beard, his sailor's cap. However I wasn't getting it right. Then I saw
these huge 12ft rocks, like giant pebbles, and got him walking between them.
It's my favourite black and white shot.''
The original plan, brilliantly conceived by Barclay Lennie, RGI treasurer and
gallery owner, was for all black and white portraits. ``People seem to think
they are more `artistic' than colour,'' says Thorburn. ``I don't agree. I feel
it's an insult to photograph colourful painters in monochrome. So we
compromised: four colour shots plus one black and white each. The exception is
Mary Armour. She said she wanted all colour, so I made an exception. After all
she's the honorary president; she's the boss.''
When he left school Thorburn was apprenticed to photographer Stephen Orr. ``I
was thrown in at the deep end: society weddings, clan chiefs etc. I also met
Olivier and Chagall. We did pictures for the personality page of the Glasgow
Bulletin.''
Then he started up on his own. ``I was dead lucky again. I found premises at
385 Sauchiehall Street - but there was a big difference between assisting Orr
and doing it on your own. But a business gets its own momentum. We don't
advertise, we don't have brochures or portfolios.''
With Thorburn's client list you don't need to. Thirty years on he's still
snapping the great and good: 18 years with Scottish Opera taking every single
production, seven years with Scottish Power covering Torness, Hunterston,
Inverkip and more, Pitlochry Theatre, Scottish Field (more than 200 front
covers), Highland and Islands Development Board (``a dream of a brief for 15
years - to cover Caithness, Sutherland, Orkney and Shetland as, when, and how I
wanted to. But then they sold their library of my pictures. It's a sore
point.'')
The list goes on with Scottish Ballet, all 60 of United Distillers properties
from Wick to Edinburgh, Scottish Tourist Board, Glaxo, the Royal Scottish
Academy of Music and Drama - plus many royals.
Thorburn did the official portrait of the Queen in Holyrood's Throne Room with
the crown jewels for Edinburgh Castle; also the official portrait of the Queen
Mother at Clarence House for the RSAMD. ``I've taken all the Royals several
times, including Diana, but the Queen Mother is a favourite. She's a wonderful
lady.'' Thorburn once took all the Scottish dukes in their castles too.
Celebrities include Michael Caine, Sean Connery (used three times life size in
Moscow); Leonard Bernstein (``great profile''); Benno Schotz (the last pictures
taken just before his death, looking very smart in a bow tie), Alex Gibson,
Jackie Stewart and Rudolf Nureyev. Thorburn's shot of Pavarotti drinking from a
huge quaich of whisky at the banquet following his Glasgow concert, has been
used around the world.
The Nureyev pictures involved a memorable trip with editor Roddy Martine. ``I
flew direct to Paris from Jura where I'd been fishing with Lord Astor. It was
first class and champagne all the way. Nureyev was in a great mood and even
agreed to pose outside despite the rain.''
Thorburn rarely exhibits his work. ``It's not worth it. I might do five or six
prints to get a perfect image but the difference is so slight, the average
person doesn't notice. Most of my work is for reproduction. It drives me crazy
when they alter the essential composition by trimming - but that's life.''
At least he has control of his RGI artists exhibition and has made the most of
dramatic, often memorable compositions: a nude Sandy Goudie raining poppies,
(``he put as much into these shots as I did''); Crosbie in dense shadow, Eli
Lamb and her litho stones, MacInnes and Low with haloes. Many shots play on the
double mirror reflection. ``I've learned an enormous amount from these
artists.''
Thorburn's studio walls are a mini-Thorburn picture gallery: oyster catchers
against the Speyside sun (his daughter's favourite), Parkhead squalor, Hill
House splendour, Pavarotti, his children, the Queen. Current projects include
photos for David Donaldson's book and Mackintosh architecture for the 1996
exhibition catalogue.
His son Paul is already in the trade, taking shots of Mel Gibson and friends at
the Braveheart première for the new In! magazine.
I left him as he and Liz rushed off to take belly dancers in Edinburgh. ``Every
day is different for a photographer. I love it!''
n Thorburn's exhibition, PRIVATE VIEW, is on the ground floor at the MacLellan
Galleries today 10am-5pm; tomorrow 11am-5pm. Admission free.
Picture: JEFF MITCHELL
</TEXT>
</DOC>
