<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Young people unite to go `shopping' for peace</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Peace delegates: Michael McKeever, 17, from Cumbernauld, Nicola Barn, 17, from
Dunfermline, Murray Gibson, 17, Falkirk, and Katie Keith, 17, from Portlethen,
pictured here with Elaine C Smith, were among 120 Scottish young people who
attended a Peace Market at the City Chambers, Glasgow, yesterday. Various
stalls competed with each other to ``sell'' their views on peace issues such as
Bosnia, poverty and racism. In the afternoon Bernard Ponsonby chaired a
Question Time with a panel of Scottish politicians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000199</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000199</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Viscount admits possession of an imitation firearm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093961</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VISCOUNT Pollington, who last year found his sister dead of a drugs overdose,
yesterday admitted possessing an imitation gun with intent to cause fear when
he appeared at the Old Bailey.
He also admitted affray in a Chelsea branch of the Winerack off-licence.
Pollington, 36, the heir to the Earl of Mexborough, was remanded on bail until
January for medical and other reports to be prepared.
Judge James Rant varied his bail conditions to allow him to leave his home in
Hasler Street, Chelsea, to spend Christmas with his family on their estate in
Yorkshire.
The facts of the case were not opened in court and Pollington was not referred
to by his title.
He was charged in the name of John Andrew Bruce Pollington by the clerk. He
answered only to confirm his name and to respond to three charges. He pleaded
guilty to possessing a firearm with intent to cause fear of violence in July
this year. The offence happened in a Chelsea pub.
He denied stealing a packet of cigarettes from Winerack in August this year,
but admitted affray by using or threatening unlawful violence causing a
reasonable person to fear for their safety at the shop on the same date.
Pollington, an international yachtsman, discovered his sister, Lady Alethea
Savile, dead of a drugs overdose at her Chelsea home in September last year.
He later told an inquest his sister had told him on many occasions that she
intended to take her own life.
She took the overdose after her parents cut off her allowance to try to wean
her from drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000200</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000200</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Whisky goes to your head</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>westminster diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975093962</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scotch whisky industry is, quite rightly, congratulating itself on securing
a 27p reduction on a bottle in the Budget, but the Diary has found another use
for the product.
According to the Earl of Gowrie, a small application of Scotch (externally) to
the head is just the thing for treating head lice. The fascinating information
comes from Lords exchanges on the matter the other day, but not everyone was
convinced.
Lord De Freyne: ``My Lords, considering what has been said about this problem,
does my noble friend agree that whisky is bad for the head?''
Health Minister Baroness Cumberlege: ``I have heard of vinegar being used as
shampoo, but never whisky. I thought Lord Gowrie was providing a rather quirky
solution to a quirky problem.''
Lady Saltoun of Abernethy: ``My Lords, if whisky does the trick, would not
surgical spirit do it just as well, but much cheaper?''
Baroness Cumberlege: ``My Lords, I think these are a lot of lousy suggestions.''
Incidentally, who was that man in the Red Lion pub in Whitehall on Tuesday
night sinking a pint with a couple of his press officers? Yes, it was Kenneth
Clarke, who raised his glass to the assembled company, and declared: ``Cheers -
and no price rise.''
Time to be off?
STAYING in the Lords, peers are also debating plans to change us all on to
Western European Time, a variation on the theme put forward recently by Tory MP
John Butterfill in his Private Member's Bill.
All sorts of fuss the other day about the tilt of the globe and the east-west
element, which apparently means that the real time in Glasgow is 45 minutes
behind the real time in London.
Lord Howie of Troon: ``That 45 minutes is quite substantial, especially on a
Glasgow morning in January or February. I have been there often at that time
and I know that it is a dismal experience. It is not a happy time. It is cold,
miserable and dank and it is also dangerous.'' Better off in Troon, then.
Rural London
WE ARE fascinated by information from the Scottish Office about the grants
available for dry-stone walling works in Scotland - 70% for dyking works on
inbye and hill land and for the provision of dykes to exclude livestock, and
grants of up to 50% for works which improve the attractiveness of the landscape.
The only puzzling thing is why all this information came in the form of a
written reply to Joan Ruddock, Labour MP for Lewisham Deptford in the heart of
south-east London.
Wrong scent
IT'S AMAZING what a presidential visit can do. Mr Clinton's trip to Belfast has
prompted the Northern Ireland Office to go ``live'' on the Internet. You can
now get a general introductory background on Northern Ireland, notes on the
economy, industrial development, employment, tourism and so on.
Another little footnote to Mr Clinton's visit concerns the very attractive
floral display that was set up in the Royal Gallery the other day in
preparation for Mr Clinton's address to representatives from both Houses of
Parliament. The whole thing had to be removed and replaced with pot plants
because, it was discovered at the last minute, Mr Clinton has an allergy which
can be set off by flowers.
Returning fire
NICE to be popular. Dover Tory MP David Shaw, the man who pursued the Monklands
affair until he was blue in the face, is now being targeted by Labour. A group
of MPs headed by Clydesdale's Jimmy Hood have tabled a Commons motion noting Mr
Shaw's interest in other MPs' constituencies and inviting MPs to press the
Government on issues that concern the people of Dover, ``who are obviously
being neglected.''
Slow starter?
WHO was that sound asleep in the Commons Press Gallery the other day? Could it
have been Sheila Gunn, formerly of the Times, recently recruited to add spark
to Conservative Central Office's relations with the media?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000201</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000201</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour well ahead over women MPs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093963</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR women MPs are set to hugely outnumber their Tory counterparts after the
next election, Labour said yesterday.
So far, the party has selected 102 women to fight seats, compared with the
Tories' nine.
Thirty of Labour's prospective parliamentary candidates will have been MPs in
the current Parliament, and 39 are in the most winnable seats.
The Tories have selected three would-be women MPs in seats where Tory MPs are
standing down.
Labour currently has 39 women MPs, and none intends to stand down at the next
election.
The Tories have 20 women MPs, but Dame Elaine Kellett-Bowman, MP for Lancaster,
and Dame Jill Knight, MP for Birmingham Edgbaston, have already announced they
are standing down.
Ms Tessa Jowell, Shadow Minister for Women, said: ``Currently just nine per
cent of MPs are women, and while Labour is poised for a substantial boost in
its representation of women in Parliament, the Tories seem to be doing their
best to keep aspiring women out.''
Tory vice-chairwoman Dame Angela Rumbold has urged her party to do more to
increase its number of women MPs, amid fears there could only be one new woman
on the Conservative benches after the next election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000202</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000202</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wonderful, wonderful</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975093964</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alison Kerr  visits Copenhagen, a city of many
parts, and relaxes in a cafe society which
appears to be at peace with itself
COPENHAGEN is a city of cities. As such, its character is difficult to define,
and its geography even harder to grasp. There's an old town, a new town, and
even a free state within one of them (which one, I'm not sure). It's all very
confusing - especially if you only have a couple of days there. Where most
cities normally get by on one or two main squares, Copenhagen has nine: the
walk from the Town Hall to the Royal Theatre, along the world's longest
shopping precinct - the Stroget - takes you through at least three. Similarly,
there are three artificial lakes, and various canals; and a whole host of
castles - from Rosenborg Castle (completed in 1633) through to late
eighteenth-century Amalienborg Palace (the current royal family's residence).
The first striking feature of Copenhagen particularly, and Denmark generally,
is the phenomenal number of people whose chosen mode of transport is the
bicycle. In the course of the 15-minute bus journey from Copenhagen's slick
airport to its central railway station, I counted 33 cyclists - from the
left-hand window alone. That's at least two cyclists a minute. This
predeliction for pedalling is not just a result of Denmark's admirable concern
for the environment, but also because cars are so expensive to buy and run.
After the bikes, the thing that you might notice is the distinct lack of style
of the Dane on the street. Whereas Paris is chic and London is street-wise,
Copenhagen - in terms of fashion anyway - is pedestrian precincts behind: this
is not a city that compulsive clothes buyers should target for a shopping
spree. Rather, what Copenhagen excels at are beautifully designed household
objects to be found in boutiques on the Stroget; in the department stores and
in the lower-budget, trendier shops of the studenty Latin Quarter - an area
which provides the ideal antidote to some of the tack and tat displayed on the
main commercial streets.
The emphasis on all things nice for the home is very much part of the Danish
psyche. A custom that is regularly referred to in all the guide books is the
untranslatable hygge. Less of a practice and more of an ambience, hygge sums up
the cosy, congenial atmosphere of a meal at a friend's house: good food, plenty
of drink and a meticulously and thoughtfully laid-out table. It's particularly
associated with the winter months, when social activity switches, for the most
part, from the outdoor entertainment (on the streets and in the Tivoli Gardens)
and cafe culture to indoors events like theatre, formal concerts and dinners,
which usually take the form of huge buffets (specialities include dishes with
spiced meat, pickles, and a wide range of fish).
In the early autumn the city was still buzzing by night: people promenading the
pedestrian area and indulging in the city's healthy cafe life. On the Saturday
of my visit, the Danish Royal Opera was performing Carmen in the Royal Theatre
(also home to the Royal Ballet) and an American trio was delighting the packed
Copenhagen Jazz House. Everybody walks, or pedals, in this city - reckoned to
be one of the safest in Europe - and if you're staying in the centre of town,
it's unlikely that you'd need to take a bus or a taxi to go anywhere.
The only way to see Copenhagen is by foot. And, if you follow the suggested
walking routes in the city council's handy guide Copenhagen in One Day, it's
easy to see how the Danes work up an appetite for their buffets and smorrebrod
(open sandwiches). A favourite Sunday walk of locals is along the Langelinie
(``the long line'') - a stretch of pier with two attractions worth stopping
for. One is the Gefion Fountain - a huge affair with an imposing statue of a
manly-looking goddess beating the hell out of four oxen with a whip. Garrison
Keillor, in a series of essays called We Are Not Married, says of this
impressive sight: ``Most Americans walk past this magnificent fountain and
hardly see it because they are intent on finding the famous mermaid statue
which they know from their map to be nearby, and which they imagine to be as
big as the Statue of Liberty, but which turns out to be a small, sad, damp
person in the midst of a personality crisis.''
True, size-wise she is a bit disappointing, but the Little Mermaid (from Hans
Christian Andersen's fairy tale) is a lovely sight all the same, and one which
has become symbolic of the city: miniature versions sell in all the tourist
shops. Andersen (1805-1875) was, of course, one of Copenhagen's most famous
sons. His statue sits just beyond the Town Hall Square, on Hans Christian
Andersen Boulevard, and the city's tourist office has been named after the
title of one of the songs from the Hollywood musical of his life - Wonderful
Copenhagen.
Copenhagen is an architectural treasure trove. Only three skyscrapers (one of
them being my hotel, the Radisson SAS Royal Hotel) impinge on its skyline -
which has little changed over the past century. The proliferation of
Renaissance-style buildings (like the Stock Exchange) was the work of Dutch
architects brought to Denmark by King Christian IV. Paris was the inspiration
for the King's New Square, and presumably the Royal Theatre which bears a
considerable resemblance to the French capital's opera house. Houses are
painted in warm colours - ochre, yellow, gold, terracotta. Of the many
different styles of church spires in Copenhagen, the most awesome is the green
copper spire of Our Saviour's Church - Scandinavia's oldest baroque church. The
gorgeous mint green of the spire contrasts beautifully with the golden
staircase which is wrapped around it, and which leads to the golden globe
perched on the very top.
Our Saviour's Church is just around the corner from an area that's not referred
to in any of the tourist books. In fact, it's not even acknowledged on any of
the maps of Copenhagen. Christiania is a ``free state'' within Denmark. In the
1960s, hippies in their masses moved into a disused military base and set up
home there. Despite various attempts by the city to reclaim the property, the
squat has grown over the years, and is now tolerated by the government.
Christiania has its own venue (holds 2000) for rock concerts (The Levellers
were soon to appear there), its own restaurants, and its own authorities, to
whom anyone wishing to join the existing 2000 residents has to apply.
Understandably, Christiania is a mecca for New a
n British Midland operates daily flights from both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000203</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000203</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>6000 jobless to go on `workfare' scheme</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975093965</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WORKFARE-style ``Project Work'' scheme for up to 6000 long-term unemployed
people was launched by the Government yesterday. Under it, people between 18
and 50 who have been jobless for more than two years will have to attend a work
experience programme or lose benefit.
Education and Employment Secretary Gillian Shephard announced that Ministers
have decided to press ahead with the scheme following a trial project in
Norfolk.
Mrs Shephard said the Government would now be setting up two pilot schemes in
April to deal with ``the recalcitrant few'' who did not want to go back to work.
After Mrs Shephard's announcement at the Tory women's conference in London, the
Prime Minister said: ``The majority genuinely seeking work will find this a
lifeline. But those who refuse to take the offer of work experience will lose
some or all of their benefit.''
Mrs Shephard said the scheme would require ``some activity, some effort'' from
the unemployed group affected. ``It's called paying for what you get - making
some effort in return for help given.''
Placement would last up to six months, comprising three months of training and
three months' work experience. The type of work offered could include painting
and decorating, construction and gardening.
People who refused or dropped out would lose two weeks benefit at first. The
second time it happened the person could lose a month's benefit and a third
drop out could lead to total loss of benefit. Hardship cases, where dependent
children were involved, probably would retain about 60% of benefit.
Mr Major said the Government would look with interest to see if Labour
supported the project. Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown recently produced a
similar idea for cutting the benefit of young people who were unwilling to join
any of four types of education or training projects.
Shadow Education and Employment Secretary David Blunkett said the Government
scheme offered no real opportunity or choice, and the cost of the scheme, at
between #10m, contrasted with Labour's billion-pound package to tackle
long-term youth unemploymen funded through the windfall tax.
Liberal Democrat spokesman Don Foster said it was ``a small step in the right
direction''. It would be far better to use benefit payments as a way of giving
in-work training with the chance of a real job at the end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000204</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000204</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Improved resources may be cell death solution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975094002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE deputy governor of a prison where two teenage girls hanged themselves
within four days said yesterday that more staff and money could prevent cell
suicides.
William Low, second in command at Cornton Vale, Scotland's only women's prison,
spoke out on the last day until January of the inquiry into the deaths at the
jail.
Kelly Holland, from Hamilton and Arlene Elliot, from Partick, both 17, were
found hanged in their cells in Cornton Vale in June.
Mr Low reviewed the Cornton Vale regime following the deaths but told the
inquiry he was satisfied the system was reasonable.
But he admitted that nursing staff who screened prisoners for warning signs of
suicide were sometimes under so much pressure they did not have time to read
the girls' medical notes.
He said: ``The regime is satisfactory in terms of what we can provide, but
given enough money I'd like if possible to provide a more therapeutic regime.
He said counselling and enabling staff to spend more time with prisoners would
make the inmates think better of themselves, and less likely to contemplate
suicide.
It would be more effective than providing special anti-hanging cells.
So-called Aberdeen cells, designed to be ligature-proof so there was nowhere
for prisoners to attach a noose, would cost up to #50,000 each at Cornton Vale,
he claimed.
Mr Low said the jail was currently looking at various options for change, but
would not reach a decision until after the outcome of the fatal accident
inquiry.
Asked whether it was possible to eliminate all risk of suicide in prisons, Mr
Low replied: ``I'd like to, but I don't know if that's physically possible.''
Earlier, a senior prison officer described how he had spent 45 minutes talking
to Arlene Elliot the night before she died.
Residental supervisor Derek MacLeod said the officers had been extra vigilant
after Kelly's death three days earlier, and he decided to talk to a number of
girls.
He said he had no concerns at all about Arlene, and if he had, he could have
put her on strict suicide supervision.
Mr MacLeod said he was the first to arrive in Arlene's cell on the evening she
died, after hearing another prisoner screaming for help.
He told the inquiry at Stirling Sheriff Court that while other officers
administered heart massage and the kiss of life, he tried three times ito
contact a nurse.
Arlene's mother, Roseanne McKay sat with her head in her hands on the public
benches as Mr MacLeod gave his evidence.
The inquiry will continue on January 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000205</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000205</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McIntyre plans to put athletics career back on track</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Doug Gillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975094003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE athletics jury which has already condemned 30-year-old Lynne McIntyre as
one of sport's under-achievers may yet have to reconsider.
Twelve years after she was the youngest Olympic 1500 metres finalist, at 19,
the City of Glasgow woman hopes to return and win selection for Atlanta in the
same event. Why not? She has overturned a catalogue of disasters, any one of
which would have buried a person of lesser moral fibre.
In 1984, McIntyre was eleventh in Los Angeles. A week later she set a British
junior 800m record (2min. 01.11sec.) which still stands. Were it not for South
African Zola Budd's passport of convenience, she would also hold the 1500m mark.
Charting the rise and demise of the former Lynne McDougall is simple, but
behind the statistics - as many Scottish senior outdoor titles as Commonwealth
champions Liz McColgan and Yvonne Murray combined - and the belief that she can
run faster after a 12-year absence, lies a saga of triumph against emotional
and physical adversity.
The death of her coach, and then her father; painful injury; surgery; and then
divorce - all while earning an honours degree and a distinction in a
post-graduate Masters - conspired against her.
Budd and McIntyre, the two youngest in that 1984 team, exchanged little
conversation, with Budd a cloistered pawn in a newspaper circulation war.
However, McIntyre, dismissing two Commonwealth final appearances as incidental,
hopes to have the last word.
Just months after her seventeenth birthday, belying her frail physique, she won
the 1982 Scottish senior 1500m title, setting a senior native record. It
survived a week, broken by future Commonwealth 10,000m champion Murray, one
year her senior.
Two years later McIntyre won the national senior cross-country title with
Murray second. And when McIntyre won the 1986 Scottish 1500m title, the older
McColgan - later that year to become Commonwealth 10k senior champion - was
runner-up. In 1989 she set a Scottish championship 1500m record which still
stands, and the future European and world finalist, Alison Wyeth, was runner-up
when McIntyre won the UK 1500m title.
But perhaps none of this should have surprised. In the winter of '76, she had
given a clue by running future Olympic 400m finalist Linsey Macdonald a close
second in the Scottish under-13 cross-country championships.
A few months ago, despite having kept in modest shape - enough to pick up what,
by her own standards, were soft Scottish track and cross-country titles in the
interim - McIntyre was contemplating final retirement.
Instead, after her flickering enthusiasm had been kept alight by Gerry Barnes
and Bill Parker, she returned to John Anderson, the man who had stepped in to
steer her to Olympic success following the death of much-loved Glasgow coach,
Ronnie Kane.
Anderson, a far better mentor than histrionic Gladiator referee performances
might suggest, refused to help her unless she was serious. ``I told him I was
back because I felt I'd never fulfilled my potential,'' she said.
``If I could achieve that at 19, physiologically immature, I know I can run
faster now. I got a poor degree at Strathclyde (she dismisses a second-class
honours in psychology) and don't want to look back on my athletics in the same
way. Perhaps I can do as well in athletics, second time around, as did in my
Masters.''
It was perhaps no coincidence that she sought out Anderson within days of her
former husband remarrying. ``It took me three years to sort out my life after
our marriage broke up,'' she said. ``I felt ineffectual - as if I could not
control my life. It was hard working out where I went from there. But women, I
think, do better than men in that situation, because they confront themselves.
We internalise it, while men just carry on.''
Listening, one understands why, at 21, she counselled drug addicts and
alcoholics full time, and why, now, she co-ordinates the Glasgow Healthy City
project which attempts to address the problem of urban regeneration by
combating unemployement, poverty, and deprivation. She realises winning Olympic
gold might be easier than changing government attitudes.
The elfin face is remarkably unchanged since 1984, I observe. ``Surprising,
considering I enjoy a Glenmorangie - with a dash of water - and a good dry
white wine,'' she said with a laugh. Then, heresy: ``There's more to life than
athletics.''
Perhaps that truth reveals why she might just succeed in turning back the clock.
Unlike most top athletes, she puts something back. Responding to an initiative
by fellow 800m internationalist Carol Sharp, McIntyre will help present a
Puma-backed conference next weekend at Jordanhill College, Glasgow, which will
attempt to reverse the pattern which sees Murray as the only Scot, Sharp and
McIntyre apart, to have broken 2-03 for two laps in more than a decade. Perhaps
en route to Atlanta, Lynne will retrace her footsteps and show the way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000206</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000206</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>B of S completes takeover BANKING</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>99</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975094039</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANK of Scotland yesterday revealed it was confident of offloading 49% of the
Bank of Western Australia, hours after announcing completion of the #439m
purchase of its entire share capital.
When Bank of Scotland first announced the acquisition on September 20, industry
analysts believed it might ultimately be left with more than 51% of the
Australian bank.
This concern was a consequence of the public offer price implied by Bank of
Scotland's proviso that it would float 49% subject to it realising a minimum
price of #202m.
This was considered to be on the expensive side.
However, Bank of Scotland general manager Robin Browning said yesterday that
the flotation looked likely to succeed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000207</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000207</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ELECTRONICS Prestwick Holdings shares tumble</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>99</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975094040</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES in printed circuit board manufacturer Prestwick Holdings, having already
been slashed from the 50p-plus level they reached in September, yesterday
tumbled another 4p to 35p.
The latest 10% plunge in the Ayr-based company's market capitalisation followed
comments by outgoing executive chairman Archie Coulson at the company's annual
meeting.
Mr Coulson said first-half results were not likely to meet the company's
original expectations. He blamed delays in the installation of new equipment,
part of a major expansion drive by Prestwick, as well as associated staff
dislocation and recruitment and training costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000208</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000208</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Key dates in the Barings  collapse</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>chronology</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975094050</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE saga of how a ``barrow boy'' from Watford sank Britain's oldest merchant
bank and shook financial markets around the world:
q August, 1994 - Internal auditors warn Barings executives of ``significant
general risk'' that derivatives trader Nick Leeson in Singapore could override
controls.
q January 26, 1995 - Kobe earthquake jeopardises Leeson's contracts as Japan's
Nikkei Index falls rather than rises in aftermath of the earthquake.
q Wednesday, February 22 - Leeson last seen at Singapore office.
q Thursday, February 23 - Bank's senior executives in London are told the
contracts expose it to catastrophic losses.
q Sunday, February 26 - Bank of England announces Barings will go into
administration.
q Monday, February 27 - Sterling plunges to record low against German mark.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke announces inquiry into collapse. Singapore's fraud
squad receives complaint from Baring Futures Singapore branch, where Leeson
made his ruinous ``derivatives'' bets.
q Tuesday, February 28 - Leesons book flight in Borneo to Frankfurt intending
to return to Britain.
q Thursday, March 2 - Police and world's media waiting at Frankfurt airport as
Leeson's plane touches down. Couple are detained and Leeson held in prison on
forgery charge pending court appearance. Lisa Leeson released and flies back to
Britain. Dutch banking giant ING group offers to buy the collapsed bank for #1,
and meet its liabilities provided there are no more hidden debts.
q March 6 - Dutch group ING buys Barings.
q April 26 - Formal request for extradition made by Singapore.
q July 18 - Bank of England report into crash blames Leeson and management
blunders.
q July 19 - Lisa delivers husband's letter to John Major pleading for help; he
admits causing collapse and offers to plead guilty to seven charges if tried in
Britain.
q August 30 - Serious Fraud Office begins six-day interrogation of Leeson.
q September 11 - Interview with Sir David Frost broadcast. Leeson admits
responsibility for crash but claims Bank of England mismanagement doubled
losses.
q September 13 - SFO confirms it will not seek trial in Britain.
q October 17 - Singapore report into collapse blames Barings executives and
accuses two managers of trying to cover up Leeson's losses.
q October 29 - Leeson abandons fight against extradition to Singapore and
apologises for doubting he would get a fair trial.
q November 14 - German Government approves extradition.
q November 17 - Leeson says goodbye to family and in-laws in special four-hour
prison visit.
q November 23 - Leeson is flown back to Singapore. Held in custody overnight at
the offices of the Commercial Affairs Department, Singapore's financial police.
q November 24 - Leeson is remanded to a Singapore prison after being charged
with 11 offences relating to Barings' collapse.
q December 1 - Leeson found guilty of two charges of cheating relating to the
bank's collapse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000209</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000209</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dynasty was once a great power in Europe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>chronology</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975094053</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BARINGS was described in 1818 by French statesman Duc de Richelieu as the sixth
great power in Europe, alongside England, France, Russia, Austria and Prussia.
q The first Baring, Johann, arrived in Britain in 1717 from Bremen in northern
Germany.
q Two of his sons, John and Francis, started the bank in London in 1762.
q Baring credit re-opened trade with the United States after the American War
of Independence and helped finance Britain's wars against Napoleon.
q The Barings invested heavily in land to hedge against disaster should the
bank fail. When Francis died in 1810 he had just #68,000 in the bank but
#400,000 in land holdings.
q The so-called Baring Crisis of 1890 rocked the City. It was sparked by a
default on Argentinian loans worth about #250 million in today's terms.
q Edward Baring, Lord Revelstoke - who had a gambling instinct - had to sell
houses, paintings and furniture to pay off his debts and his wife was said to
have died of shame.
q But the bank survived as the dynastic family rallied around.
q In 1969, control was passed to a charity which held the share capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000210</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000210</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man who broke the bank</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975094059</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICK LEESON's deal with the Singapore authorities may not mean that others
involved in the Barings scandal will walk away scot-free, but the fact he was
not cross-examined in court meant that he would not be publicly naming names.
What happened next depended on whether the Singapore authorities, as Finance
Minister Richard Hu indicated in October they intended to, pursue charges
against those Barings executives alleged to have taken part in a cover up.
Leeson's immediate staff in Singapore are unlikely to interest the Singapore
authorities. They are more interested in the man he reported to in London, Mr
Peter Norris, and the two regional bosses, Mr James Bax and Mr Simon Jones.
Singapore's official report into the Barings debacle, published in October,
said other Barings officials had concealed Leeson's unauthorised trades and
that there was ``a strong inference that key individuals of the Barings group
management were grossly negligent, or wilfully blind and reckless with the
truth''.
After the collapse in February, Barings was bought by the Dutch financial
conglomerate, ING, and, while most of the 2000 Barings staff in London were
kept on, 21 of the senior staff were either sacked or resigned. The ING
decision was clearly taken on the basis of what it found when it took over. The
Singapore report found the fall of Barings Futures to have been caused by
``institutional incompetence, a lack of understanding of the future business
among senior executives, and a total failure of internal controls''. Some of
those who left voluntarily, or were dismissed, must have borne some
responsibilty for that situation.
The two names which crop up repeatedly are those of 40-year-old Mr Norris, who
was head of the investment banking arm, and now lives in Hertfordshire, and
42-year-old Mr James Bax, who was south east Asia regional manager, and still
lives in Singapore. The auditors, Price Waterhouse, in their report to the
Singapore authorities, alleged the two men had ignored warning signs, provided
Leeson with more and more money for his losing bets, and later tried to cover
up his losses.
They were said to have played down a #50m discrepancy in Leeson's books,
discovered by the auditors in January, which would have served as a warning
that things were going wrong. There were other warning signs about that time
which were also ignored, including two from Simex, the Singapore International
Monetary Exchange.
The Bank of England, whose Board of Banking Supervision published its report on
the affair in July, is examining whether it was misled by Mr Norris in the
account he furnished of the events leading to the collapse. There are
discrepancies between what he told the Bank, and what is contained in the
Singapore inspectors' report, and he has discussed them with the Bank's
investigators, Mr Brian Quinn, head of banking supervision, and Mr Ian West,
head of special investigations.
Although criticised by the Board of Banking Supervision report published for
failing to prevent the collapse, it is only in the Singapore report Mr Norris
is accused of participating in a cover up. Mr Bax has not been interviewed by
the Bank officials. He has, however, been interviewed by the CAD, as has Mr
Simon Jones, operations manager for the region when Leeson was dealing. The
Singapore report also named Mr Anthony Hawes, the group treasurer, as having
been involved in the concealment.
Mr Norris has dismissed the Singapore conclusions as having no basis in fact,
and, to be fair, the report's conclusion that there was a cover up appears
based on conflicting testimony from former Barings executives, rather than
conclusive proof. The man who might be able to furnish that proof is Mr Leeson.
Since he is not now going to undergo cross examination in public about his
crimes, if no further action is taken by the Singpore authorities, that may be
the last to be heard. While what has happened is clearly in Mr Leeson's
interests, from the point of view of the British investors, who trusted
Barings, as well the matter of public trust in the Bank of England's ability to
supervise the activities of such banks, it is bad news.
Other Barings executives criticised by the Board of Banking Supervision for
their part in the affair include Mr Ron Baker, head of the financial products
group, was found to have no real understanding of the nature of Baring Futures
Singapore and to have failed to familiarise himself with what Mr Leeson was
doing, and the former Bank supervisor, Mr Chris Thompson. Although the
chairman, Mr Peter Baring, and the deputy chairman, Mr Andrew Tickey, emerged
relatively unscathed, they, too, had to take responsibilty for the fact that
senior management was so ill-informed.
Mr Leeson's lawyers have all along claimed he was being made a scapegoat for
``a wide circle of people''. This magic circle may well, because of the deal,
simply vanish. It is no longer operating, its members are no longer working for
Barings, and the supervisory authorities have learned the lessons of the
Barings affair.
Mr Bax and Mr Jones have so far not commented on either report, but in a letter
to the Singapore Times in March, claimed that Mr Leeson reported directly to
London.
The Serious Fraud Office said last night it had not uncovered any evidence of
criminal actions by London-based Barings staff, but it would be taking a keen
interest in developments in Singapore. The SFO investigation into Barings would
be reactivated in the event that information were to come to light which
warranted it pursuing any actions in Britain, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000211</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000211</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Downfall of a plasterer's son</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975094061</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICK LEESON had the world in his hands - but let it slip through his fingers.
The boy who went from a Watford council estate to dealing in hundreds of
millions of pounds, sent world markets crashing.
His actions reverberated around the globe as his bosses at Barings Bank, in
London, tried to disassociate themselves from his activities.
Leeson, 28, is the only son of a plasterer. His mother died ten years ago and
Bill Leeson took charge of Nick, his younger brother and two sisters.
At school, Nick was a prefect, a good footballer but not too bright
academically. He failed his maths A-level and left Parmiter's School with two
poor passes in French and History.
Like many of the school's old boys, he went to work in the world of banking.
His first job was as a clerk at Coutts.
Three years later, he switched to the merchant bank Morgan Stanley, where he
made his mark as a dealer in futures. Within five years, he was being
head-hunted by Baring Brothers.
As the whizz-kidd went from strength to strength, he met and married Lisa Sims,
who worked at the bank as a secretary.
Soon they were living a luxury lifestyle in Singapore - but hardly had time to
enjoy it.
Lisa, 27, stood loyally by her husband and was by his side as they fled
Singapore only to be stopped in Germany. She returned to Singapore with him
when he was finally extradited. Leeson had been pale and drawn as he was
arrested in Germany. But his return to Singapore last week was more relaxed.
He sipped gin and tonic on the plane and smiled as he made his first court
appearance on arrival.
Now he will have time to contemplate how the couple will be able to pick up the
pieces of their life on his release.
Lisa was staying out of the limelight with friends yesterday - and was ``not
too bad'' under the circumstances, her father, Mr Alec Sims, said.
He said he did not know if Mrs Leeson, a part-time waitress, had any plans to
fly to Singapore.
A spokeswoman at the Elizabeth Tea Rooms, in Pudding Lane, Maidstone, where Mrs
Leeson works, said she was not expected in and could not say where she was.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000212</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000212</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gambling on the future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975094064</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRADING in derivatives involves gambling with the chance of making mountains of
money - and the risk of losing spectacularly.
They are ``derived'' from the underlying price of other investments, including
futures, which involve betting on future prices.
A certain amount of money is invested in the hope that the value of a
commodity, currency, shares or bonds will rise.
If it does, your bonus for making your company truckloads of money is assured.
If not, it can mean financial oblivion.
The particular attraction of derivatives comes from the fact that only a small
down-payment is needed to stand a chance of hitting the big time.
Leeson lost Barings hundreds of millions of pounds by gambling on a contract
linked to share prices on Tokyo's Nikkei index.
The multi-billion pound global derivatives business came about when
stockbrokers were dreaming up new ways of increasing business in the late 1980s
after the world stock market crash of 1987.
Derivatives are very highly geared - each pound of investment can carry #20 of
risk or more. And they are complex - many bank directors are said not to
understand what the young dealers in their employ are doing.
Many City observers say that futures markets have been in business longer than
traditional stock markets, which is trade based on the current price of shares.
It is thought that trading in rice futures in Japan began centuries ago and
many believe they can play a useful role.
Commodity futures, for example, allow a farmer to fix the price for his crops
in advance.
Those in favour of derivatives say they can help offset risk in an increasingly
volatile market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951202-000213</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951202-000213</DOCID>
<DATE>951202</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Radical chic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andi Robertson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975094066</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OVER the course of a dozen years, Edinburgh-born skier John Vaitkus has slowly
become one of skiing's more familiar faces. Captured in spectacular action for
the pages of ski magazines and videos across the world, his profile is
instantly recognisable. His neat, technically precise skiing mixes control with
absurd dynamics and at 37 he remains in demand as one of an elite breed of
international skier.
Paradoxically for all his globe-spanning exposure to ski enthusiasts of all
standards, he remains almost entirely anonymous. Vaitkus has lived in Chamonix
for more than 10 years and has the unmatched snowfields, challenging couloirs
and cornices as his daily ``office'' routine, making his living as one of
Europe's leading ski models.
It's a remarkable existence and a success story which has outlasted the
hundreds of pretty-boy rich-kid Europeans, Antipodeans and Americans who
gravitate to photographic meccas such as Chamonix for a post-ski racing
pre-college rite of passage - if they're lucky earning beer money and perhaps a
few glossy enlargements of a once-in-a-lifetime leap.
``Over the past few years it has become crazy out here. There are kids who are
prepared to fling themselves off anything without a second thought just to get
themselves on to film. It's amazing that, as yet, there's been no real tragedy,
but it's waiting to happen,'' says Vaitkus, who has worked with most of
Europe's top photographers, but now chooses only to work mostly as a close-knit
team, with those who sympathise with his working methods and ethics.
``It's come to the stage where photographers demand more and more, not because
they've shot it all perfectly before, but because they want to make up for
their technical shortcomings by getting kids to do bigger more radical jumps
and that's stupid.''
Vaitkus points to the exploits of the mohawk-styled American stunt skier Glen
Plake and Scott Schmidt; and also producer Greg Stump whose enormous video
sales have made them ski-household names. Their exploits become simply
run-of-the-mill, swelling this lemming-like exodus to the mountains to jump
higher and further in pursuit of celluloid glory.
His stock in trade has been stills and video work in advertisements and
promotions for leading worldwide manufacturers such as Salomon and Tenson,
while in the UK one of the most comprehensive annual collections of Vaitkus in
action is featured in the retail chain Ellis Brigham's weighty, glossy
mail-order bible The White Book in which he has starred for a number of years.
The world recession in the ski market coupled with the fast-growing influx of
do-it-for-nothing thrill seekers has made it all the tougher. He reflects that
five years ago a mere 20 days of work early in the season was more than enough
to keep body and soul intact for the year. Now now he is increasingly being
forced to exploit other avenues in paragliding and climbing.
Those who hire him rank him among only a handful of successful, totally
dedicated European ski-action models. While his contemporaries have almost
universally Alpine or Scandinavian backgrounds, born in the mountains,
Vaitkus's enduring passion for the sport started on the dry-slope matting of
Hillend as one of the first Edinburgh comprehensive school kids taught to ski
as part of the curriculum.
He too may have served his apprenticeship on the race circuits in the winter,
but he also bummed in the summer skiing resorts, living in a beaten-up Renault
6 for three months just to ski every day.
His teenage potential was rewarded as one of the first recipients of the Boyd
Anderson scholarship, which was awarded by the benefactor who granted much of
the land Hillend is sited on. It was for less privileged kids who needed to get
racing and training on snow. He went on to become a respected coach to British
Alpine Racing Clubs but gave up when, he says, he really felt he couldn't look
British children in the eye and tell them they really could go on to win World
Cups.
``Racing's a vital background for what I do now. It requires at least
centimetre if not millimetre precision every time, just as it's needed when you
make a turn for a top photographer who expects you to keep the skis' logos
perfectly framed - even when you're dropping in on a big cornice -- so I guess
all those wet nights at Hillend must be worth something now!''
Most of all he feels the new crop of bone-headed daredevils are simply missing
the point, trading only on the freefalling seconds of big air - not that he
doesn't still yearn for the same regular adrenalin fix and will take the
scariest of drops in his stride, but his is a craft which has been honed
through winter and summer months in Chamonix.
``Now I always know the risks exactly, intuitively. I'll have flown the slopes
through the summer paragliding, or climbed them, and know the likely conditions
for any given weather pattern. We set out to minimise the risks. I want to do
this for a lifetime, not to have to give it up tomorrow. What most of these
kids are losing out on is the whole mountain experience.''
Vaitkus has turned director, teaming up with fellow skier Roger Lambert and
Swedish cameraman Lars Pykto to make their second film over a six-week period
last spring. The Long Way Down records an inspirational descent from a 4000m
peak above Chamonix dropping 6000ft of vertical, down through the tree line
towards the valley floor.
Avoiding the cliches of endless cliff jumps and wipeouts, it concentrates
instead on stunning scenery and dangerous descents in areas never skied before.
With a budget of around #15,000 it reputedly challenges even the multi-million
dollar productions of Warren Miller.
At one point in shooting Vaitkus dropped on to a 45-degree untouched face only
to find the six inches of new snow slide away from underneath him to reveal a
sheer wall of glacial blue ice.
``My first thought was that my only means of survival, my ice axe, was on my
pack but fortunately I had brand new skis on and the razor sharp edges gripped
until I managed to get my pack off and sort myself out.''
In the immediate future the trio will be skiing to earn their keep but looking
for funding for their next film project. A job which, says Vaitkus, is a much
more daunting mountain to conquer
.
